<html>
<head>
<title>The DeSilver Membership Program</title>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<img src="/graphics/abouthdr.gif">
<center><h2>THE DeSILVER SOCIETY</h2></center>

The ACLU has established a new society to honor those who support our civil liberties work 
through estate and charitable financial plan.  It is named after ACLU founding member Albert 
DeSilver (1888-1924), the first person to leave the ACLU a financial legacy.  Continuing a 
75-year tradition of giving for the future of civil liberties, hundreds of supporters are 
now recognized as charter members of The DeSilver Society.
<P>
Harrison DeSilver, an architect and the oldest son of Albert, recently visited the national 
office to reminisce about his father, who descended from conservative businesspeople, and 
mother Margaret, the daughter of Quakers. "My father was a superstar," said Harrison. "I 
don't know how he got interested in civil liberties -- my mother almost certainly influenced 
him."
<P>
A New Yorker and the product of Ivy League schools, Albert volunteered with the National 
Civil Liberties Bureau while practicing law.  But in 1918, he left his prestigious firm to 
engage in civil liberties work full time.  When the Bureau became the ACLU, Albert was its 
first associate director and largest financial contributor until his untimely, accidental 
death.  Margaret continued her husband's generosity and served on the national ACLU board 
for many years.
<P>
Harrison inherited his parents' social awareness, registering as a conscientious objector in 
World War II and working with Roger Baldwin on the ACLU's National Committee on Conscientious 
Objectors.
<P>
The ACLU is grateful that Albert, whom his son described as having "very high 
standards," set the standard for stewardship of our nation's constitutional heritage -- now 
recognized through The DeSilver Society.
<P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
