<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Jeff & Jon Pyle Story</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<CENTER><H2>ACLU Clients - Jeff and Jon Pyle</H2></CENTER>
<font size=4>
<img src="/graphics/pyle.jpg" align=left><blockquote> Jeff and Jon Pyle are from South Hadley, Massachusetts.  In May of 1993
they sued their high school in federal court over the censorship of message
T-shirts.
<P>
The case started when Jeff wore a T-shirt to gym class which read, "Coed
Naked Band -- Do It To the Rhythm."  Halfway through the class his gym
</blockquote><br clear=all>
teacher told him he would not be allowed to wear the shirt again because it
created an "emotionally unhealthy environment" in her class.  When he wore it
again to assert his First Amendment right to freedom of expression, he was
sent to the office for insubordination.
<P>
Jeff appealed the charge to the school committee, which responded by
introducing the most restrictive dress code in the state of Massachusetts.
The code banned all messages which the committee found to be "obscene, lewd
or vulgar," any message which "demean[ed]" individuals or groups on the basis
of race, sex, color, national origin or sexual orientation, and messages
which advertised alcohol, tobacco, or illegal drugs. 
<P>
Jeff argued before the committee that the proposed code was
unconstitutional under the First and Fourteenth Amendments, but to no avail.
The committee passed it.  When Jeff realized that the school committee would
not take his arguments seriously he and his brother sued in federal court. 
 <P>
During this time, the Pyle brothers wore several other T-shirts to
school to protest the censorship and test out the new code.  Jon was allowed
to wear a shirt reading, "Coed Naked Gerbils -- Some People Will Censor
Anything."  But he was sent home for wearing a shirt saying, "See Dick Drink,
See Dick Drive, See Dick Die, Don't Be a Dick."  Jeff wore a shirt which had
a picture of two men kissing on it and the words "Read My Lips." No one
objected.  But he was thrown out of school for wearing a shirt reading "Coed
Naked Civil Liberties -- Do It To the Amendments."  
<P>
In court, the Pyles persuaded the judge to overturn the part of the
dress code banning all "demeaning" messages.  This was the first time a "hate
speech" code had been struck down at the high school level.  But the judge
upheld the part of the code banning "lewd, profane or vulgar" speech, saying
that school committees, as elected officials, reflect the moral fiber of
their community and can decide what is and is not "vulgar" for other people's
children.
<P>
The Pyles, like Justice Harlan, believe that "one man's vulgarity is
another's lyric," and that school officials have no business censoring
whatever they find offensive.  They appealed the unfavorable part of the
district court's decision to the Court of Appeals for the First Circuit.  But
the First Circuit, instead of deciding the case, certified a question to the
Supreme Judicial Court of Massachusetts asking for an interpretation of a
Massachusetts state law which protects student free expression.
<P>
The Supreme Court of Massachusetts must decide if under the law,
T-shirts which could reasonably be considered vulgar," but which cause no
disruption or disorder can be banned in schools.  This is where the case is now.</font>
<P>

</blockquote>    


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
