<HEAD>
<TITLE>08/11/96: Visions of Liberty, #6</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<P>August 11, 1996</P>
<H2>Memo to Congress: The Constitution Will Still be Standing When You Return</H2>
<P>As those of you who have read my last column know, &quot;Visions of Liberty&quot;
went on a brief hiatus in July while I was on vacation.  But as I said in that
column, you can't take a vacation from the fight for freedom.  </P>
<P>That's a point I always make to the ACLU national staff in my annual
vacation memo that's become something of a tradition. In it, I tell them,
half-jokingly, &quot;If the Constitution's not standing when I get back, I'll
know who to blame.&quot;  </P>
<P>But what Congress has wrought in the days before breaking for its own summer
recess is no joke: the House passed the Defense of Marriage Act, which would
deny recognition of marriages between same-sex couples; and English-Only
legislation that will legitimize and encourage discrimination against Americans
not fluent in English; both Houses signed off on a health care bill that
includes provisions destructive of our medical privacy.  There was also a bill,
which for the moment we defeated, that would have expanded the already

unprecedented scope of federal wiretapping authority.  (We expect a revival of
the wiretapping legislation when Congress gets back to business as usual after
Labor Day.)  </P>
<P>Who, indeed, is to blame for all this unconstitutional,  unprincipled
legislation?  Some of it is old-fashioned special- interest politics.  The
medical privacy legislation, for example, was passed without much public
awareness and in effect catered to the interests of companies who make money by
buying and selling personal information.  But most of the legislation violating
important civil liberties principles reflected election-year politics, the
frenzied and unprincipled attempt by politicians to pander to the fears,
resentments and prejudices of the majority.</P>
<P>James Madison, one of the fathers of the Bill of Rights, recognized this
special danger to liberty.  In a democracy, he argued, the ultimate source of
power lies with the majority of the people.  Therefore, the invasion of
individual rights, he thought, was likely to come not from a legislature that
was out of step with its constituents, but from a legislature acting in accord
with the majority.  </P>
<P>Madison was a skeptic, and with good reason.  He had seen &quot;overbearing
majorities&quot; in every state violate their own state bills of rights.  In his
home state of Virginia, he saw the Virginia Declaration of Rights &quot;violated
in every instance where it has been opposed to a popular current.&quot; </P>
<P>In fact, initially Madison didn't have much faith in the Bill of Rights to
restrain the tyranny of a majority in a democracy, and for that reason was not
in favor of adding a Bill of Rights to the Constitution.  It was Thomas
Jefferson, writing from Paris, who convinced Madison with this argument: once
established, a bill of rights would provide the legal basis for an independent
judiciary to strike down majoritarian excesses by ruling unconstitutional any
legislative or executive act that violated individual rights as defined in the
Constitution.</P>
<P>Madison came to understand that, if enforced by the courts,  the Bill of
Rights would be more than a &quot;parchment barrier;&quot; it would become an &quot;impenetrable
bulwark&quot; against every assumption of unconstitutional power by either
Congress or the President, even if committed in response to majority opinion.  
</P>
<P>So why, you might ask, is the ACLU fighting so hard against these myriad
unconstitutional proposals when we have this impenetrable bulwark to keep the
government from violating our rights?  Why not just go to court?  </P>
<P>Well, we do.  Last spring, for example, after Congress passed and the
President signed a law imposing censorship on the Internet, we went into court
and got the law struck down.  But that doesn't always work.  Too often, when
constitutional rights are at stake, the courts reflect popular sentiments
instead of curbing them: in 1857, for example, slavery was held by the U.S.
Supreme Court to be constitutionally acceptable.  Similar examples are plentiful
throughout our history.  </P>
<P>The fact is, once laws that violate civil liberties are in place, it can be
extraordinarily difficult and sometimes impossible to persuade a court to strike
them down.  Jefferson was right in principle, but Madison turns out to have been
prescient: too often the Bill of Rights has proved to be merely a parchment
barrier.  During moments of frenzy or fear, it is not hard for politicians to
manipulate citizens.</P>
<P>The continuing push for expanded federal wiretapping is one example of how
constitutional principles can get washed away in a &quot;popular current.&quot; 
Spurred by the recent tragedies of the TWA Flight 800 explosion and the bombing
at the Atlanta Olympics, President Clinton quickly revived legislation, rejected
by Congress earlier this year, calling for expansion of the FBI's wiretapping
authority. </P>
<P>Hard to go against public sentiment on that one, right?  Who in his right
mind would speak out against this law if it will help catch terrorists? </P>
<P>The problem is, this law won't do anything more to help us catch terrorists,
but will do a lot to make innocent people less free.</P>
<P>The FBI already has all the authority it needs to investigate these heinous
crimes.  Current law allows the FBI to obtain wiretaps for a host of crimes,
including arson, bombs, nuclear weapons, assassinations, hostage-taking, and
other crimes that place people in danger of death or physical injury.  If these
acts don't constitute terrorism, what does?</P>
<P>Moreover, for crimes that threaten national security or place people in
imminent physical danger, the FBI is allowed to wiretap for 48 hours without a
warrant.  And they can even obtain court orders to allow them to tap multiple
phones not belonging to the suspect if they can show that the suspect is
probably using the phones to avoid the tap.  These are called &quot;roving
wiretaps&quot; and they are especially dangerous because they target phones
primarily used by innocent people.  That is why the FBI is required under
current law to obtain a warrant for these kinds of taps.  And courts virtually
never deny warrants.  Since 1988, no application for a criminal wiretapping
warrant has been denied.  What more does the FBI want or need?    </P>
<P>What the FBI wanted -- and what the proposed legislation would have given
them -- was the expanded discretion to place these dangerous roving wiretaps
without having to convince a court that they were necessary to prevent a suspect
from thwarting the tap.  </P>
<P>Requiring exacting court scrutiny, as the current law does, is important in
light of the FBI's sorry history of illegitimately tapping innocent people.  But
bombs have exploded and people have been killed.  We are all fearful, and the
FBI, pandering to those fears, saw its chance to dilute the scope of court
supervision over its wiretapping authority.</P>
<P>The irony is that wiretapping isn't very effective against random terrorist
acts.  In fact, the government doesn't use it much.  Out of 9,553 electronic
surveillance applications filed by federal and state authorities in the past ten
years, only 19 -- less than 0.02% -- were for arson, bombing or firearms. 
Seventy percent of all wiretaps are for narcotics investigations and another 18
percent are for illegal gambling and racketeering.   The protection of liberty
-- always vulnerable -- requires something more than faith in the decent
intentions and benevolent instincts of public officials or a concerned majority.
 In the words of the historian Leonard Levy, liberty requires that &quot;the
state must be bitted and bridled by a Bill of Rights...its protections not to be
the playthings of momentary majorities or of those in power.&quot;</P>
<P>So, I've got another memo I'm thinking about right now, a memo to the
members of the 104th Congress: The Constitution will still be standing when you
return.  And the ACLU will still be standing behind it. </P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union<BR>Photo by Bob
Adelman</I></H6></CENTER></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
