<P>

<DL>

<font color="#0000FF"><center><h1>Legal Research</h1></center>
</font><P><P>
<hr>
<b><a href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/supct.table.html">Decisions of the U.S. Supreme Court</a></b> 
<P>Based at Cornell University, the Decisions of the U.S. Supreme Court owes its status as one of the most useful Internet sites to the fact that it quickly and reliably transfers Court-provided decisions into an Internet-friendly form (often within hours of release).  Under Project Hermes, this partnership with the Court has led to a fully searchable archive of Supreme Court decisions dating back to 1990, with selected cases from before that time.  Cornell has recently added analysis of the more significant decisions of the New York Court of Appeals.  
<P><center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center><P>

<b>United States Court of Appeals</a></b>
<P>Most of the United States Court of Appeals now have their own web sites, generally maintained by Emory University, Villanova University, or the University of Texas.   There is a uniform look and feel across the board, as all of the  Appeals sites list decisions by date and party names and utilize similar graphics.  <a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/FEDCTS/">Emory University</a> has also created a clickable map that links to each of the Courts.  
<p><DL><DD>
<li><a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/fedcircuit">Federal Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.ll.georgetown.edu/Fed-Ct/cadc.html">D.C. Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.ljextra.com/public/daily/XD1ca.html">First Circuit</a> (not an official site)
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.pace.edu/legal/us-legal/judiciary/second-circuit.html">Second Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.vill.edu/Fed-Ct/ca03.html">Third Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/4circuit/index.html">Fourth Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.utexas.edu/us5th/us5th.html">Fifth Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/6circuit">Sixth Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/7circuit/index.html">Seventh Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.wulaw.wustl.edu/8th.cir/">Eighth Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.vill.edu/Fed-Ct/ca09.html">Ninth Circuit</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/10circuit/index.html">Tenth Circuti</a>
<br><li><a href="http://www.law.emory.edu/11circuit/index.html">Eleventh Circuit</a>
</DL>
