<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Visions of Liberty, A Weekly Cyber-Column by Ira Glasser</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<H2>No Vacation for Civil Liberties</H2><IMG
SRC="/graphics/lib.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" BORDER="0" WIDTH="318" HEIGHT="227">
<P>The summer of 1996 may be the brightest yet for the lesbian and gay rights
movement, and for women as well.  In May, a 6-3 majority of the Supreme Court
invalidated Amendment 2, a ballot measure that would have prohibited all legal
protections against discrimination based on sexual orientation.  And this week
the Supreme Court voted 7-1 to overturn the Virginia Military Institute's policy
of excluding all women, declaring that Virginia's daughters must be served as
well as her sons.  	</P>
<P>With these two historic decisions, it may seem safe to entrust our rights to
the Supreme Court.  Maybe now all those people out there fighting for justice
can just turn off their phones and fax machines, put away their protest banners,
and enjoy a well-deserved vacation.  I, for one, will be away from the office
for a little while, putting this column on a brief hiatus.  But the ACLU office
will keep humming.  After all, you  can't take a vacation from the fight for
freedom. 	 	</P>
<P>As any student of American history will tell you, the Supreme Court has
rarely been in the vanguard of protecting our civil liberties.  Indeed, for most
of its history, instead of challenging prevailing stereotypes, the Supreme Court
relied on them to uphold restrictions on people's rights.    	</P>
<P>The 1857 Dred Scott decision was a tragic case in point.  Six Justices used
the case brought by Scott, a freed slave from Missouri, to uphold the
constitutionality of Southern slavery and advance the notion that blacks were
inferior.  	</P>
<P>In language that offends our contemporary sensibilities, Chief Justice Roger
Taney wrote that blacks are &quot;a subordinate and inferior class of beings&quot;
who were &quot;unfit to associate with the white race.&quot;  The Constitution
not only provided no relief, according to Taney, it permanently excluded blacks
from national citizenship and established them legally as less than human. 
Blacks therefore had &quot;no rights which the white man was bound to respect.&quot;
    	</P>
<P>It would take a bloody Civil War to put African Americans on the road to
full equality.  But even after the 13th, 14th and 15th Amendments were adopted
in the period immediately following the war, legally ending slavery and
guaranteeing equal rights, the nation soon entered into a 100-year reign of
terror against black Americans with the full support and complicity of the
Supreme Court.  	</P>
<P>In the end, it was the civil-rights movement itself that forced the Court
and other institutions of power to apply the Bill of Rights equally.  Only after
years of boycotts, picket lines, demonstrations, and only after thousands of
beatings, arrests and jailings, did the Supreme Court do its duty and begin to
fulfill its obligations under the Constitution.  	</P>
<P>Women's rights, at first, fared just as badly.  In 1873, for example, the
Court denied an Illinois woman, Myra Bradwell, a license to practice law. Women
were not suited to practice law, the Court said.  Again, the language is
astonishing by today's standards: &quot;Man is, or should be, woman's protector
and defender,&quot; wrote Justice Joseph Bradley.  A woman's &quot;natural and
proper timidity and delicacy&quot; makes her unfit for civil life, he added in
denying her entrance into the bar.  (Sounds a lot like the arguments the
Virginia Military Institute made against admitting women!)  	</P>
<P>Then, in 1971, nearly a century later, the Supreme Court dramatically
departed from its unbroken tradition of upholding sex distinctions in the law. 
An Idaho law gave men preference over women in deciding who should be the
administrator of an estate.  Sally Reed, represented by Ruth Bader Ginsberg, now
a Justice of the Supreme Court but then the Director of the ACLU's brand-new 
Women's Rights Project, challenged the law and the Court struck it down --
unanimously.  But this came after much struggle, and more than 50 years after
women won the right to vote.  And it came in the midst of a new feminist
movement that challenged the most entrenched stereotypes about women's &quot;proper&quot;
role in American society.  	</P>
<P>History serves as a painful reminder for those of us fighting for gay
rights, or women's rights, or any kind of civil rights, who might now be tempted
to rest on our laurels and rely on the Supreme Court to decide fairly the
struggles brought to its door.   Remember that only 10 years ago, in its very
first gay rights ruling, the Court upheld Georgia's sodomy statute in a decision
that relied on the &quot;ancient roots&quot; of &quot;Judeo-Christian moral and
ethical standards&quot; to justify the government's place in our bedrooms.  That
decision has never been overruled.  And in the past several years, the Court has
retreated from its commitment to equality for black Americans by rendering
decisions in the areas of voting rights and affirmative action that turn back 
the clock.  	</P>
<P>It is always profoundly gratifying when decisions like Amendment 2 or VMI
let a little more light, a little more liberty, into our lives. But history has
taught us, perhaps too well, that we cannot depend on the nine Justices alone to
safeguard our constitutional rights.      	</P>
<P>This Supreme Court term will be winding up in the next day or so.  But the
struggle for civil liberties will continue.  I'll be back in this space next
month with more from the frontlines. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union<BR> Illustration by
Irina Lubenskaya -- Photo by Bob Adelman </I></H6></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
