<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>08/18/96: Visions of Liberty, #7</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<P>August 18, 1996</P>
<H2>Election Year Politics</H2><IMG SRC="/graphics/vis818.gif">
<P>A few days ago, a friend and devoted supporter of civil liberties asked me
why he should make an extra contribution to the ACLU now when it seems more
important to contribute to the electoral defeat of zealous opponents of civil
liberties, like Senator Jesse Helms.</P>
<P>Indeed, he added, after watching the Republican convention, he was persuaded
that nothing would protect civil liberties more than defeating Bob Dole.  So he
was inclined to contribute his money toward that end, rather than give it to the
ACLU.</P>
<P>Well, I watched the Republican convention, too.  More importantly, I read
the Republican platform.  It was a nightmare for civil liberties.  It favored a
constitutional amendment that would destroy religious liberty by allowing the
government to impose someone else's prayers on your children.  It favored a
constitutional amendment to take away the guarantee of citizenship for children
born in this country to parents here on temporary visas or whose visas had
expired or who had entered without visas.  It favored a constitutional amendment
 to allow the government to imprison people for using the American flag to
express dissent.  And it favored yet another constitutional amendment to outlaw
abortions under all circumstances, including rape and incest.  It also expressed
enduring hostility to civil rights for gay men and lesbians.  And it opposed all
affirmative action remedies for racial and gender discrimination.  Not a pretty
picture.</P>
<P>But the Democrats are no civil liberties bargain, either.  Clinton has sold
out the rights of needy children by his willingness to sign a welfare bill
reminiscent of the English Poor Laws at the dawn of industrialization.  Then, as
now, structural changes in the economy left many without jobs.  Then, as now,
government decided to force the unemployed to work by making their lives and
their children's lives as wretched as possible, in the vain hope that they would
then have no choice but to work.  But there weren't enough jobs, and the only
result was an unprecedented increase in sustained misery.  The same result is
likely now.</P>
<P>Clinton has also supported expanded wiretapping, the erosion of federal
courts' authority to review the constitutionality of state trials, the expansion
of the death penalty, and curfew laws that would make being a young a crime even
if teenagers were out at a concert with their parents' permission.</P>
<P>Clinton also signed a law subsequently ruled unconstitutional by a
three-judge federal court, that imposed broad censorship on the Internet, with
heavy criminal penalties for posting material on the net that would be perfectly
legal to print in a book, newspaper or magazine.  When asked by an ACLU staff 
member why the Clinton Administration was being so hostile to civil liberties, a
presidential adviser admitted it was &quot;good politics.&quot;</P>
<P>So, this is what we face:  a Republican party that has been captured by
religious zealots and the forces of intolerance and a Democratic president who
seems only too willing to abandon civil liberties principles in order to get
elected.</P>
<P>As a result, civil liberties are caught in a political crossfire.  The plain
truth is that many of our most fundamental freedoms will continue to be in
danger no matter how the elections come out in November because both parties are
locked in a competition to see who can sacrifice more liberties.</P>
<P>None of this is especially new.  The people who founded this country and
wrote the Bill of rights knew that even in a democracy liberty would be 
threatened by momentary passions, misguided fears and the readiness of
politicians to pander to these forces.  That is why they created a legal system
to bridle majoritarian excesses.</P>
<P>But the legal system our founders created depends on citizens willing to
stand of for their rights -- no matter which party is in office -- and it
requires organizations to support these citizens when they do stand up -- to
represent them in court and to fight for them in Congress and in the forums of
public opinion.</P>
<P>For 76 years, the ACLU has been doing that.  We never support or oppose any
electoral candidate because we know that no matter who is in office, we will
sooner or later have to sue them to enforce the Bill of Rights.  That doesn't
mean one candidate wouldn't be better for civil liberties than another.  It
means that the outcome of the struggle to defend the Bill of Rights for all
Americans depends more on citizens and on organizations like the ACLU than on
elected officials.</P>
<P>Denizens of the Internet know this because a few months ago, a
Republican-controlled Congress passed a law censoring the Internet and a
Democratic president signed it.  When it comes to protecting freedom of speech
in this new medium, neither party proved reliable.  Instead, the censorship law
was struck down by citizens who stepped forward to resist it and by the ACLU,
which represented those citizens.</P>
<P>And that's why I told my friend to support the candidate of his choice but
to continue supporting the ACLU as well -- especially in an election year when
politicians have a tendency to sacrifice any liberty if they think it will help
them get elected.</P>
<P>As our entire history demonstrates, liberty depends not on those who oppose
it or sell it out when it becomes inconvenient, but on those willing to fight
for it and provide support for those who defend it.</P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union<BR>Illustration by
Irina Lubenskaya -- Photo by Bob Adelman</I></H6></CENTER></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
