<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> The ACLU on Violence Chip </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/libraryhdr.gif">
<CENTER><H1>Violence Chip</H1></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><EM>"Why Does the ACLU Oppose the V-Chip Legislation<BR> 
Currently Pending In Congress?"</EM></CENTER>

<STRONG>BACKGROUND</STRONG><BR>
Culminating a protracted campaign against TV violence, both Houses of
Congress have passed legislation requiring that new televisions be equipped
with the so-called v-chip -- a computerized chip capable of detecting program
ratings and blocking adversely rated programs from view.  The v-chip
provisions appear in each House's version of the telecommunications bill. The
Senate bill orders the television industry to "voluntarily" establish within
one year a rating system for violence and "other objectionable content."  If
the industry fails to comply, the legislation authorizes the President to
appoint a  federal ratings agency.  The House version would establish a
government advisory committee to set guidelines for the rating of
"programming that contains sexual, violent, or other indecent material about
which parents should be informed before it is displayed to children." 
 <P>
The legislation is now headed for conference committee to resolve differences
in the House and Senate bills. The ACLU will actively lobby against its
passage.
<P>
<STRONG>IN BRIEF</STRONG>
<BR>
<UL>
<LI> A media ratings system mandated by the government under threat of the
formation of a federal rating agency should private industry fail is not a
"voluntary" system.  It is a form of censorship clearly forbidden by the
First Amendment.  
<P>
<LI> The courts have repeatedly held that depictions of violence in books and
films are protected by the First Amendment from government regulation or
restriction.  The government may not even prohibit speech that advocates the
use of force or violence unless it is intended to incite or produce such
action and is likely to do so.  
<P>
<LI>Although its supporters claim the v-chip gives parents control over their
children's viewing habits, in fact it will function as a governmental
usurpation of parental control.  Under the legislation, it is the government
(either directly or by coercing private industry), and not the parents, that
will determine how programs will be rated.  If a parent activates the v-chip,
all programs with a "violent" rating will be blocked.  What kind of violence
will be censored?  Football games?  War movies?  News reports?  
<P>
<LI> Various devices that enable parents to control their children's TV watching
without any government involvement or interference are already on the market.
These include a channel  "lockbox" for cable TV, built-in channel guards that
allow parents to block certain channels for specified periods of time, and
new products such as The TeleCommander and the TV Guardian that allow parents
to choose what their children will be able to watch on TV.  The v-chip is
therefore unnecessary.
</ul>
<STRONG>ACLU POLICY</STRONG><BR>
Protection of the rights enshrined in the First Amendment is part of the
ACLU's "common law."  The organization has historically opposed laws or
practices that restrict, in any way, freedom of the press and freedom of
expression.  This includes media depictions of violence.
<P>
<STRONG>ARGUMENTS, FACTS, QUOTES</STRONG><BR>
TV violence has been blamed for various social ills since 1952, when
Congress held its first hearings on the subject.  Four decades and many
studies later, a causal relationship between exposure to violent imagery and
violent behavior has still not been proven.  In 1972, the Surgeon General
issued a report on Television and Social Behavior.  The report noted only a
"preliminary and tentative indication" of a causal relation and said:
<P>
  "The effect is small compared with many other possible causes, such as
parental attitudes or knowledge of and experience with the real violence of
our society...evidence does not warrant the conclusion that televised
violence has a uniformly adverse effect...or an adverse effect on the
majority of children."
<P>
Subsequent research findings are just as "tentative," and distract attention
from the real causes of crime and violence:  poverty, inadequate educational
and job opportunities, domestic abuse.
<P>
Although the Supreme Court has not yet ruled on the TV violence issue, its
1968 decision in Interstate Circuit v. Dallas is relevant.  In that decision
the Court struck down as unconstitutionally vague an ordinance authorizing
the classification of certain films as "not suitable for young persons" where
the standard was defined as:  "describing or portraying brutality, criminal
violence or depravity in such a manner as to...incite or encourage crime or
delinquency on the part of young persons."  Other federal courts have ruled
that laws regulating "excessive violence" on TV are unconstitutionally vague
because they fail to put anyone on notice of what exactly is banned.
<P>
A uniform TV rating system is unworkable.  In some major markets, viewers
will soon be able to choose from 100 different channels, representing about
2,400 hours of programming each day.  Both telecommunication bills give
private industry one year to come with a "voluntary" rating system, but given
the massive volume of programs and the fact that TV offerings constantly
change, it is unlikely the industry would be able to meet the deadline.  A
huge government bureaucracy with the power to preview, rate and block TV
programs will be the inevitable result of the v-chip legislation.
<P>
<STRONG>RESOURCES</STRONG><BR>
<a href="http://www.aclu.org/news/n022996b.html">February 29, 1996 - ACLU Expresses Concerns on TV Rating Scheme; Says
         "Voluntary" System is Government-Backed Censorship 
 </a> <br>

<P>
<a href="pbp14.html">Briefing Paper #14:  "Artistic Freedom." </a>
 <P>
<P>
</blockquote> 



<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
