<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>09/01/96: Visions of Liberty, #9</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<P>September 1, 1996</P>
<H2>Translating Liberties: Letter from Russia</H2>
<P>The ACLU normally doesn't become involved in civil liberties cases abroad,
unless an American citizen or the U.S. government is involved.  But on a recent
trip to Russia to attend a human rights meeting there, I learned of a case that
should be of interest to the entire community of people concerned about
fundamental rights.</P>
<P>I was in Russia -- St. Petersburg, to be specific -- to help evaluate a
project of a civil liberties group there called Citizens Watch.  The project
included the publication, in Russian, of ACLU handbooks on various rights.  We
had agreed to be the American partner in the project, and the first publication
they undertook was to translate and publish the ACLU's &quot;Your Right to
Government Information.&quot;  It was strange to see our handbook in the
Cyrillic alphabet, but thrilling to know that our efforts here were being used
there as a model.  </P>
<P>In any event, while sitting in the offices of Citizens Watch shortly after I
arrived, still groggy from crossing several time zones without much sleep, their
fax machine began to whir and out of it came a bulletin about their latest case.
 </P>
<P>The case involves a retired Russian naval officer named Alexander Nikitin,
who contracted with the Bellona Foundation, a Norwegian environmental group, to
prepare a public report on the potential hazard posed by Russian radioactive
waste dumping at sea.</P>
<P>There was nothing secret about this work.  Nikitin worked openly, and he
utilized material previously published and available.  The report itself was
prepared by the Bellona Foundation for a meeting in Moscow last April; and the
text of the report was published in three languages and posted on the Internet. 
It has now led to a joint project between Russia and Norway on utilizing nuclear
waste.</P>
<P>Despite this completely open process, Nikitin has been charged with treason
by the Russian government and imprisoned without a trial since early February. 
According to his wife, who saw him on August 21st, his health and physical
condition has badly deteriorated in recent weeks, indicating mistreatment or at
least negligence with respect to the conditions of his detention.</P>
<P>The pre-trial detention itself has now been extended until October 8th,
which would be eight months after Nikitin was arrested.</P>
<P>The case against Nikitin seems utterly without any foundation.  The treason
charge is based on an accusation that he gave the Bellona Foundation secret data
on the dumping of Russian radioactive waste at sea, yet the practice had
previously been detailed in a publicly available report by President Boris
Yeltsin's own ecological adviser.  Both Nikitin and the Bellona Foundation
insist that all the information provided in the report was taken from publicly
available sources.  Furthermore, all the information in the report is strictly
related to environmental conditions and threats to human life and health.  Such
information cannot be classified as secret under Article 7 of the Russian Law on
State Secrets.</P>
<P>The role of the Federal Security Bureau (FSB) in this case is especially
ominous.  The FSB is the successor agency to the old Soviet KGB, the secret
police which for decades functioned as an engine of political repression in a

lawless state.</P>
<P>The FSB subjected Nikitin to surveillance from the first days of his work
with the Bellona Foundation.  They therefore had every opportunity to impede the
delivery of information to Bellona if their purpose was to prevent the
transmission of legitimate state secrets.  Instead, they permitted the delivery
of the draft report and then embarked upon creating a fabricated espionage case.</P>
<P>The charge against Nikitin is based on an investigation by military experts
appointed by the prosecutor.  They concluded that six of the eight chapters of
the Bellona report contained state secrets.  But they conceded that they had
failed to investigate whether the so-called secrets had in fact been derived
from publicly available sources.  Nikitin's lawyer, Yuri Schmidt, in applying
for a re-examination of this question, attached copies of previously published
articles and books upon which Nikitin relied.  The investigatory authorities
were forced to concede that their initial conclusion, classifying the data used
in the report as secret, was hardly correct.  But the second investigation has
been similarly unresponsive to the question of public sources, and meanwhile
Nikitin remains in prison.</P>
<P>Procedurally, Nikitin's rights have been grossly violated.  He was initially
refused counsel of his choice and instead assigned a lawyer employed by the
policy agency that arrested him.  The lawyer of his choice was denied security
clearance and then asked to submit to wiretaps and mail surveillance as a
condition of representing Nikitin.  Eventually, this was overturned by Russia's
new Constitutional Court, but in the meantime the defendant was effectively
excluded from the legal proceedings.  The two-month extension of Nikitin's
pre-trial detention was granted on August 6th, ostensibly to allow more time to
reinvestigate the question of whether he relied solely upon public sources.  But
as of August 18th, no investigative acts involving Nikitin have taken place. 
And the appeal of his extended detention, required by Russian law to be
considered by the court within four days, has gone unaddressed for over two
weeks.</P>
<P>Substantively, Nikitin appears to have been arrested and detained without
trial for perfectly legal activities.  According to Boris Pustintsev, a longtime
human rights activist in St. Petersburg, if Nikitin is convicted, &quot;any
Russian citizen collaborating in any way with a foreign organization or company
could find himself in danger.&quot;  This case, Pustintsev believes, &quot;brings
us back to the totalitarian Soviet times.&quot;</P>
<P>Russia has a new Constitution, he says, which is not being enforced, and has
joined the Council of Europe and signed all existing international agreements on
human rights, which are in this case being ignored.  He believes that the
pressure of international public opinion can make a difference.</P>
<P>So does Amnesty International, which has called for Nikitin's immediate
release and urged all human rights activists to make their views known to
Russian officials.  For further information about where and to whom to write,
you can e-mail Amnesty International, United States Section at
<A HREF="mailto:admin-us@aiusa.usa.com">admin-us@aiusa.usa.com</A> or visit
their main web page at <A HREF="http://www.amnesty.org/">www.amnesty.org</A>.</P>
<P>The case itself illustrates the problems civil liberties advocates face in a
place like Russia.  There are no traditions of governance through law, no
traditions of independent courts enforcing laws against government excess, no
traditions of organizations outside of government acting as a restraint on
government.  There are few journalists who are familiar with the law or whose
beat includes the world of law.  And citizens generally are unaware of what
their rights are, of how to enforce their rights, or of what their rights could
be. </P>
<P>In a situation like this, organizations like the ACLU act not only as a
source of information but also as a beacon of hope and possibility to the
relative handful of heroes who struggle with few resources and at significant
personal risk to bring fundamental rights to their country.  </P>

<P>The outcome of the Nikitin case may well become a pivotal moment in that
ongoing struggle.  Certainly, that is how the activists I met in St. Petersburg
felt.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union<BR>Photo by Bob
Adelman</I></H6></CENTER></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
