</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>
EXECUTIVE SUMMARY OF THE HOUSE TERRORISM BILL, H.R. 2768
</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote><img src="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<p>	
<b>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY OF THE HOUSE TERRORISM BILL, H.R. 2768</b>
<p>
February 9, 1996  
<p>
This is an Executive Summary of the ACLU's objections to H.R. 2768, the "Effective Death Penalty Antiterrorism Act of 1995."  The House Judiciary Committee approved a similar bill on June 20 despite bi-partisan opposition from four Republicans and eight Democrats: Bob Barr (R-GA), Steve Chabot (R-OH), Bob Inglis (R-SC), F. James Sensenbrenner, Jr. (R-WI), Xavier Becerra (D-CA), John Bryant (D-TX), John Conyers, Jr. (D-MI), Jerrold Nadler (D-NY), Robert Scott (D-VA), Patricia Schroeder (D-CO), Jose Serrano (D-NY), and Melvin Watt (D-NC).  H.R. 2768 represents an agreement, following the Judiciary Committees  vote,  between Bob Barr and Henry Hyde.  It  is scheduled to be considered by the full House of Representatives on March 11.  The ACLU urges members of the House to oppose the bill for reasons stated below:
<p>
In Brief:  H.R. 2768 will ultimately have its greatest impact on American citizens who will suffer grave invasions of privacy in the name of national security.  Coming to the House floor in the wake of hearings on Waco and Ruby Ridge, the bill marks a dramatic expansion in the power of federal law enforcement.  The bill contains no provision for law enforcement accountability, but includes provisions about habeas corpus that will virtually strip the federal courts of their ability to remedy law enforcement abuse that results in unconstitutional incarceration.  The bill will have a chilling effect on domestic groups who are critical of U.S. foreign policies.  It will give the Executive the authority to blacklist certain groups by designating them terrorist organizations.  It will prevent Americans from inviting dissenting voices from other nations to speak or to visit the United States.  It will allow the deportation of individuals without giving them the opportunity to know why they are being deported.  It will give expanded powers to the FBI to obtain personal phone and travel records without a criminal predicate.  It will invite more illegal law enforcement wiretaps.  
<p>
<b>1.  Broad Terrorism Definition Risks Selective Prosecution</b>
<p>
H.R. 2768 defines "terrorism" as state and federal law crimes such as kidnaping, killing, serious assaults, and illegal property damage that creates a substantial risk of serious bodily injury when such crimes: (I) involve conduct in both the United States and abroad; (ii) meet a jurisdictional base; and (iii) are certified by the Attorney General as "terrorism" because the crime is calculated to retaliate against the government, or influence government conduct by intimidation or coercion, and is a violation of one of a number of federal criminal statutes.  Under this broad definition, virtually every serious crime involving conduct both within and outside of the United States is a federal crime of "terrorism" when the Attorney General says it is.  The "terrorism" label triggers severe penalties.  Despite efforts to narrow the definition of terrorism, this provision raises a substantial risk of arbitrary and discriminatory application because so much conduct (already a crime under federal or state law) triggers application of the section, and because the political motivation of the actor is presumed by the Attorney General, not found by a judge or jury.  The Attorney Generals certification is not subject to review by a court, and may be influenced by political considerations and pressures.
<p>
<b>2.  More Illegal Wiretaps and Less Judicial Control Will  Threaten Privacy	</b>
<p>
H.R. 2768 would dramatically reduce privacy rights in the United States because it would invite significantly more illegal law enforcement wiretaps with less judicial control, resulting in a significant increase in the number of entirely innocent conversations intercepted by law enforcement officials.  Already, too many innocent conversations -- nearly two million in 1994 alone -- are intercepted by federal and local law enforcement wiretaps.  In fact, every time a wiretap or other form of electronic surveillance is placed, nearly 1,800 innocent conversations are intercepted.  The FBI already has authority to conduct a wiretap to prevent the crimes which the public associates with terrorism.  The bill would strip judges of the power to order the FBI to periodically justify continuation of the wiretap.  It would also authorize courtroom use of evidence gathered in an illegal wiretap when law enforcement officers acted illegally, but in "good faith."  The Supreme Court has recognized that barring from court the fruits of an illegal search (such as a wiretap) is the only effective means of deterring such illegal searches.
<p>
<b>3.  Expansion of Counterintelligence and Terrorism Investigations Threatens Privacy</b>
<p>
The FBI would be handed additional access in counterintelligence investigations to complete records about the airline flights people in the U.S. have taken, the cars they have rented, and the hotels in which they have stayed, all without evidence establishing probable cause that such a person has been involved in criminal activity.  It could obtain this information merely by secretly (in an ex parte proceeding) showing a judge that it wanted the information for a foreign intelligence investigation and that there are facts giving reason to believe that the person to whom the records pertain is a "foreign power" or an agent of a foreign power engaged in "international terrorism" or "clandestine intelligence activities" that may involve a violation of federal criminal law.  It would also be given access, without any judicial intervention at all, to a persons name, address and local and long distance toll billing records merely by writing a letter to a phone company certifying that the information is "relevant" to an international terrorism investigation.
<p>
<b>4.  The Executive Would Decide Which Foreign Organizations Americans Could Support</b>
<p>
The bill would give the Secretary of State the authority to make criminal the provision of "material support" for the legal, non-violent, even charitable activity of foreign organizations the Secretary of State designates as "terrorist."  Because current law already prohibits the giving of material support for terrorist activities, the new law would prohibit material support for legal activities of organizations the Secretary of State disfavors for political reasons.  Had this bill been law a few years ago, it would have been illegal for human rights groups, relief organizations, and church-related groups to go to Central America and provide anything but medicine and religious materials through any organization the Secretary of State, for political reasons, declared a "terrorist" organization.  In addition, the bill would remove the statutory proscription on FBI investigation of First Amendment activities when the FBI is investigating support for "terrorist" activities.
<p>
<b>5.  Secret Evidence Would Be Used In Deportation Proceedings</b>
<p>
The bill would permit the government to deport aliens based on evidence kept secret from the alien, in violation of the alien's right to due process.  Secret evidence, in the form of classified information, could be used to deport any alien, whether a permanent resident or a visitor, accused of terrorism.  The bill would even effectively prohibit permanent resident aliens from choosing the lawyer who would review the secret evidence on their behalf because their choice would be limited to a handful of lawyers approved by the court.  The right to choose one's own attorney is a fundamental due process right.
<p>
<b>6.  Foreign Dissidents Would Be Barred From the United States</b>
<p>
The bill would prevent Americans from inviting controversial foreigners who dissent from government policies to visit the United States to speak because it would bar members of designated "terrorist" organizations from entering the country.  Current law already bars from the United States aliens who have, or might, engage in terrorist activity.  The bill is not aimed at these individuals.  Instead, the bill would bar members of groups selected by the Executive for foreign policy reasons.  Those groups most likely to be designated are the groups that dissent from U.S. foreign policy, or oppose the governing party of a U.S. ally.  Even those members who oppose violence, and have risked their lives to oppose those who would commit violent acts, would be barred if regarded as members of an organization designated by the Secretary of State.  They would be barred even absent any evidence giving reason to believe that they had, or would after entry, engage in any terrorist activity at all.  This provision of the bill would resurrect in principle the McCarthy-era McCarran-Walter Act.
<p>
<b>7.  Federal Courts Would Virtually Lose The Power To Correct Unconstitutional Incarceration</b>
<p>
The bill would require federal courts to ignore unconstitutional state court convictions and sentences unless the state court decision, though wrong as a constitutional matter, was "unreasonably" wrong.  The risk that innocent persons would be held in prison in violation of the constitution --or even executed--would increase dramatically because the bill imposes unreasonably short time limits for filing a claim for habeas corpus relief, limits almost all petitioners to one only round of federal review, and requires that the petitioner meet an extremely high "clear and convincing" burden of proof in order to secure relief.  For the first time, a time limit would be placed on the exercise of an important constitutional right:  "use it now or lose it" might be appropriate for vacation time, but not for prison time, particularly for a death-row prisoner when a life is at stake.
<p>
<b>8.  Aliens Are Equated With Terrorists</b>
<p>
Much of the bill has nothing to do with terrorism and everything to do with immigrant-bashing.  The FBI's investigation of the Oklahoma City bombing suggests that aliens had nothing to do with the bombing.  Nonetheless, this bill, touted as a response to the bombing, purports to strip aliens who are alleged to have entered without inspection by INS of their constitutional right to due process in deportation proceedings, open to the probing eyes of law enforcement immigration files submitted on a confidential basis, bar from the United States aliens who arrive without adequate travel documents and could not prove, in the airport upon arrival, a "credible" fear of persecution in their homeland, and render deportable long-time legal permanent residents convicted of minor crimes, even if they are the sole supporters of their family members who are U.S. citizen children.  The Oklahoma City bombing should not be used as an excuse to bash aliens or to enact restrictive immigration laws.
<p>
<b>CONCLUSION</b>
<p>
The ACLU opposes H.R. 2768 and urges members of the House to oppose the bill.  A detailed analysis of the bill is available from the ACLU.  For additional information, please contact Gregory T. Nojeim, Legislative Counsel, at the ACLU (202) 544-1681.
<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
