<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Report: Court Stripping: Congress Undermines the Power of the
Judiciary</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">&quot;COURT STRIPPING&quot;</H1>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">CONGRESS UNDERMINES THE POWER OF THE JUDICIARY</H1>
<H2>An ACLU Special Report<BR>June 1996</H2>
<HR>
<H1>COURT STRIPPING: Congress' Campaign to Undermine the Power of the Judiciary</H1>
<P>After withstanding more than 200 years of recurrent attacks by the two other
branches of government,  the federal judiciary took a series of debilitating
blows this Spring when Congress passed a series of restrictions on the
independence, scope and power of the nation's federal courts.  They are:</P>
<UL>
<LI> The Prison Reform Litigation Act (enacted April 1996);
</LI>
<LI> Restrictions on the Legal Services Corporation (adopted April 1996);
</LI>
<LI> The Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act (enacted April 1996);
</LI>
<LI> Immigration legislation (approved by both Houses of Congress and now
pending in a Senate- House conference committee).
</LI></UL>
<P>These restrictions slam the courthouse door on   society's most vulnerable
members. And, by stripping the federal courts of a wide range of procedural and
substantive powers, they threaten what James Madison called &quot;an
impenetrable bulwark&quot; of American liberty:  a system of independent courts
with the power to strike down as unconstitutional all legislative or executive
acts that violate the Bill of Rights.</P>
<P>Ever since the Supreme Court established its role as the final arbiter of
constitutional rights in <I>Marbury v. Madison</I> in 1803, both the executive
and legislative branches have attempted to encroach upon the judiciary's
independence.   In fact, the current court stripping effort is unusual only in
that it has  succeeded where others have failed.</P>
<P>The impact of these Congressional actions is already being felt. Taking
advantage of the new Prison Litigation Reform Act, which weakens federal court
oversight of unconstitutional prison conditions, the District of Columbia filed
a brief on May 17th with the D.C. Court of Appeals arguing that an extensive
remedial plan ordered by a Federal District Judge be dismantled.  The plan
remedied unconstitutional conditions for women inmates at three D.C.
correctional institutions, including rampant sexual harassment and sub-standard
health care.</P>
<P>And on June 3rd, the U.S. Supreme Court heard oral arguments in <I>Felker
v. Turpin</I>, a death penalty case from Georgia, and the first constitutional
test of the new restrictions on federal habeas corpus contained in the
Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act. </P>
<P>We issue this special report out of our grave concern that an independent
judiciary, which our nation's founders deemed essential to our constitutional
form of government, and which one eminent  scholar has called, &quot;America's
most distinctive contribution to constitutionalism (1) is now in jeopardy. </P>
<P>And we call upon both the Department of Justice, and on and Congress, 
particularly Members of the Judiciary Committees of  both Houses, to live up to
their responsibility to ensure that the federal judiciary is able to fulfill its
role as protector of constitutional rights -- a responsibility that they have,
in recent months, abdicated.</P>
<H2>The Courts Under Attack</H2>
<P>Although the federal courts have long been a target of politicians of every
stripe, a series of public and unusually vituperative attacks on individual
judges and on the federal bench as an institution has served as cover for
Congress' unprecedented power grab. In this highly politicized election year,
the federal judiciary emerged in the early pre-election campaign period as a
scapegoat for crime and a range of other social ills.</P>
<P>In February,  candidate Pat Buchanan called federal judges &quot;little
dictators in black robes,&quot; and advocated an end to life tenure on the
federal bench. The fire was fueled when Judge Harold Baer, a federal district
judge from New York, threw out evidence which he decided had been illegally
seized in a highly publicized drug case.  Amid a chorus of demands for Judge
Baer's resignation or impeachment,  Senator Bob Dole charged that one of &quot;the
root causes of the crime explosion&quot; was &quot;liberal&quot; judges
appointed by President Clinton. Dole went on to attack the American Bar
Association's role in evaluating judicial nominees, calling the ABA &quot;nothing
more than another blatantly partisan liberal advocacy group.&quot;  The Clinton
Administration responded with its own list of Reagan and Bush appointees who
have made decisions that it said could be deemed &quot;pro- defendant&quot;.
</P>
<P>All this  created a climate in which justice became politicized and judges
intimidated. And, as this special report demonstrates, it enabled Members of
Congress with an anti-civil liberties agenda to push through a series of laws
and restrictions that will have long lasting and profound consequences for the
independence and integrity of the federal courts.</P>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>THE TROUBLESOME  &quot;EXCEPTIONS CLAUSE&quot;  </H2>
<P><B> </B>In 1981, Justice Potter Stewart, discussing his retirement,
answered a reporter's question about various proposals then pending in Congress
to strip the Supreme Court of jurisdiction over certain categories of cases. &quot;There
is nothing new about having such bills in Congress,&quot; Justice Stewart said. 
&quot;I think there have been such bills in Congress ever since I've been here,
in fact long before that.&quot;  But, Justice Potter went on to say that &quot;if
any such bills were enacted, it would present immediately very difficult
Constitutional questions.&quot;</P>
<P>The Constitutional questions Justice Potter referred to revolve around the
meaning of the Exceptions Clause under Article III of the Constitution.  </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;In all Cases affecting Ambassadors, other Public Ministers and
consuls, and those in which  a State shall be Party, the Supreme Court shall
have original Jurisdiction.  In all the other   Cases before mentioned, the
Supreme Court shall have appellate Jurisdiction, both as to Law  and Fact,<I>with
such Exceptions, and under such Regulations as the Congress shall  make.</I>&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>In a friend-of-the-court brief filed with the Supreme Court in<I>  Felker
v. Turpin</I>, we observe that, &quot;The extent to which this almost casually
adopted, last minute addition to Article III was meant to leave the role of the
Supreme Court as the ultimate arbiter of the Constitution at the whim of the
national legislature has been hotly debated by constitutional scholars for many
years.&quot;    </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H1>THE PRISON LITIGATION REFORM ACT:  Stripping the Courts Power to Reform
Prisons</H1>
<P>The Prison Litigation Reform Act (PLRA) was swept into law as a virtual
footnote to the appropriations bill. It strips the federal courts of much of
their power to correct even the most egregious  prison conditions.   It does
this  by altering the basic rules which have always governed prison reform
litigation:</P>
<P><B>&#183; The PLRA makes it impossible to settle prison cases by consent
decree, and jeopardizes virtually every existing consent decree. </B>  </P>
<P>Many prison lawsuits are resolved by consent decree:  prison officials agree
to make changes in unconstitutional prison conditions, before trial and without
acknowledging any guilt.  The federal trial court then monitors the decree to
ensure full compliance within a reasonable amount of time.   This is the most
effective, efficient, and inexpensive method of achieving meaningful prison
reform.   It is clear from past experience that without the threat of court
intervention, state prison systems drag their feet and unconstitutional

conditions persist.</P>
<P>The new law forces prison officials to admit that they violated inmates'
constitutional rights before they can enter into a consent decree, opening
themselves up to personal liability.  The inevitable result is that most prison
litigation will now go to trial -- a hugely expensive and time consuming
proposition. Furthermore, existing consent decrees can be challenged under PLRA
as well, potentially sending every one of the cases upon which those decrees are
based back to court.   The magnitude of this change will be enormous since
two-thirds of the country's state prison systems have one or more facility
currently operating under a court order. </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>Inevitably, most prison litigation will now go to trial -- a hugely
expensive and time consuming proposition.</H3></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>&#183; The PLRA  limits the lifespan  of any  court judgment or consent
decree resulting from prison reform litigation to two years.  </B></P>
<P>History has shown that two years is an unreasonably short period of time in
which to effect meaningful change in the way a prison is run or to cure
seriously  substandard conditions<B>.</B>  Even if  no remedial action is taken
and conditions remain exactly as they were, the PLRA lets the government  off
the hook after two years, unless the court holds a new trial and finds that
conditions still fall short of what the Constitution requires.  In the same
vein, preliminary injunctions, which are issued in emergency cases sometimes
involving life and death situations,  have been given a 90-day shelf life unless
a trial is held and permanent relief granted during that time.  </P>
<P>In addition, the PLRA severely limits the longstanding practice and 
authority of the federal courts to assign Special Masters to oversee the reform
process. Still another provision drastically limits  attorneys' fee awards,
defunding lawyers who now handle prison cases, and discouraging others from
doing so in the future. </P>
<P>Politicians hostile to prison reform have long accused federal judges of
meddling in the day- to-day running of corrections institutions and entertaining
frivolous lawsuits initiated by inmates and their advocates.   But as Justice
William F. Brennan has observed, &quot;Judicial opinions in this area do not
make pleasant reading&quot; (concurrence in<I> Rhodes v. Chapman</I>, 1981).  
All of the deplorable conditions described below were remedied as a result of
prison reform litigation, followed by  federal court oversight.  The PLRA places
every one of the consent decrees in immediate jeopardy.(2)</P>
<P><B>Rape and sexual abuse</B> </P>
<UL>
<LI>In Washington D.C., prison guards sexually assaulted female prisoners on a
routine basis. One officer raped a prisoner while she was sick in the infirmary.
</LI>
<LI>In Georgia, dozens of women inmates were forced to have sex with prison
guards, maintenance workers and a prison chaplain. Many become pregnant and were
then pressured into having abortions.
</LI>
<LI>In Louisiana, female prisoners were forced to have sex with prison staff,
and with male inmates brought in by prison guards. 
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Physical abuse</B> </P>
<UL>

<LI>In a California prison, prisoners in restraints were severely beaten by
guards. They were kicked, hit with batons, and burned with scalding water. 
Their heads were bashed, their teeth knocked out, their jaws fractured and their
limbs broken.
</LI>
<LI>In Idaho, a 17-year-old boy in jail for failing to pay $73 in traffic fines
was tortured for 14 hours and finally murdered in his cell by other prisoners.
</LI>
<LI>In South Carolina, several suicidal juvenile inmates were transferred to

the state mental hospital where, naked or in paper gowns, their hands and feet
were bound to a bed and they were forcibly injected with psychotropic drugs.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Squalid conditions and lack of medical care</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>In the U.S. Virgin Islands, one-man cells infested with rats housed four or
five prisoners. Mattresses on the floor were soaked by overflowing toilets, and
the drinking water was contaminated with sewage.
</LI>
<LI>In Pennsylvania, prison officials failed to implement basic tuberculosis
prevention procedures despite warnings by the Commissioner of Health.  As a
result of a federal court order, over 450 prisoners infected with TB were
identified in a single prison.
</LI>
<LI>In California, female prisoners received almost no pre-natal care and one
prisoner gave birth on the floor of the jail without medical assistance three
hours after telling prison staff that she was in active labor.
</LI></UL>
<HR>
<H1>THE ANTITERRORISM AND EFFECTIVE DEATH PENALTY ACT: Crippling Federal Habeas
Corpus</H1>
<P>Tucked away in the recently enacted anti-terrorism legislation is a
provision that will not combat terrorism, but will destroy what Alexander
Hamilton once described as the greatest liberty of all:  the Writ of Habeas
Corpus.  &quot;The Great Writ&quot; has been  a central part of the American
system of justice since Congress passed the first Judiciary Act in 1789.  After
the Civil War, the Habeas Corpus Act of 1867 extended the right to the states. 
Under the law, convicted offenders serving state sentences have the right to
challenge the constitutionality of their conviction and sentence in federal
court.   For more than forty years, the U.S. Supreme Court has repeatedly held
that federal courts are <I>required</I> to exercise independent judgment of
state prisoners' constitutional claims.  Now, in the name of fighting terrorism,
the federal courts have been stripped of their traditional power to assure that
state criminal convictions and sentences are constitutional.(3)</P>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H1>FROM THE ACLU'S BRIEF</H1>
<P>in <B><I>Felker v. Turpin, </I>urging the Court to not to reach the
Exceptions Clause issue, or to find the Anti-Terrorism and Effective Death
Penalty Act unconstitutional</B></P>
<P>&quot;The question of whether, and to what extent, Congress can limit this
Court's appellate jurisdiction by invoking the Exceptions Clause has
implications that extend far beyond the narrow context of successive habeas
petitions.  In the early 1980s, literally scores of bills were introduced in
Congress to strip this Court (and often the lower federal courts, as well) of
jurisdiction to hear cases involving school prayer, school busing, and abortion.
 Fifteen years ago Congress wisely stepped back from the precipice by defeating
each of these assaults on the Court's jurisdiction.  But given the current
political climate, there is every reason to believe that these or similar bills
would be resurrected were this Court to adopt a view of the Exceptions Clause
that left Congress free to impose whatever limitations it chose on this Court's
appellate jurisdiction.</P>
<P>&quot;What may be conceivable in theory would be devastating in practice to
the real world system of checks and balances that has enabled our constitutional
system to function for 200 years.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<P>&#183;<B> Federal courts are now required to defer to state court decisions
even when those decisions are clearly wrong.</B>  </P>
<P>Under the new law, the federal judiciary cannot grant a writ of habeas
corpus unless a state court decision upholding the prisoner's conviction is &quot;unreasonably&quot;
wrong, or flatly contradicts clearly established Supreme Court rulings.  This
heightened standard makes it all but impossible for federal judges to review the
evidence and come to their own independent conclusions.  It elevates process
over results:    a person  convicted because of constitutional error, such as
the failure to disclose evidence establishing innocence, may well be foreclosed
from federal habeas relief as long as the state court allowed him to present his
arguments, even if the state court came to the wrong conclusion.  As one
prominent expert on habeas law said, &quot;It will be easier for a camel to pass
through the eye of a needle than for a constitutional claim to get into federal

court in habeas.&quot;</P>
<P>The law's title, &quot;The Antiterrorism and <I> Effective Death Penalty</I>
Act,&quot; is chillingly apropos.   More than 40 percent of state-imposed death
sentences reviewed by federal appellate courts since the reinstatement of the
death penalty have contained reversible constitutional  errors.  Since 1973,
fifty-four people sentenced to death have been released from prison after
evidence of their innocence was uncovered.  Many of these miscarriages of
justice were avoided because of the availability of federal habeas review.  They
include cases in which defendants were victims of racism at trial, received
inadequate legal counsel, or were found guilty because the prosecution withheld
exculpatory  evidence.  Many, if not most, of these cases, would be unreviewable
under the new law.</P>
<P>&#183;<B> Prisoners are given an unreasonably short time limit for filing
federal habeas petitions.</B></P>
<P><B> </B>For the first time, a statute of limitations has been imposed on
the filing of habeas corpus petitions.  The new law limits the time span for
filing a habeas petition to one year from the time the conviction became final. 
If the state provides counsel for any post-conviction proceeding, however,  then
a state prisoner sentenced to death will have only six months to file a
petition. These time limits are exceptionally harsh and difficult to meet.  Six
months is not enough time for even the most diligent and skilled attorney to
reinvestigate the legal and factual issues involved in a death penalty case.  
</P>
<P>Had the Effective Death Penalty and Public Safety Act been the law of the
land in the past, Shabaka Waglini, Ricardo Guerra and Henry Drake, all innocent
men,  would not be alive today:</P>
<H2>Lives Saved by Habeas Corpus</H2>
<UL>
<LI><B>Shabaka Waglini</B> was convicted of first degree murder in 1974 and
sentenced to death in Florida. He came within 13 hours of execution when a
federal court granted his habeas corpus petition and ordered a new trial. It was
found that the prosecutor concealed FBI evidence proving that the fatal bullet
could not have come from Waglini's gun; allowed the only witness against Waglini
to lie in exchange for lenient treatment in another case; and misled the jury in
closing arguments. Waglini was ultimately released after spending 14 years on
death row for a crime he did not commit. 
</LI>
<LI><B>Ricardo Guerra</B> was convicted of murder by a Texas court and
sentenced to die in 1982. Every state court affirmed the conviction. But in
1993, in a federal habeas review, the court found that the prosecutor threatened
and intimidated witnesses, most of whom were children who spoke little English;
failed to disclose evidence that proved Guerra innocent; and knowingly presented
false evidence to the jury. The judge said that the prosecutors' &quot;misconduct
was designed to obtain a conviction and another 'notch in their guns' despite
the overwhelming evidence that (another man) was the killer and the lack of
evidence pointing to Guerra.&quot; 
</LI>
<LI><B>Henry Drake</B> was convicted of murder and sentenced to death in
Georgia in 1976.  The actual murderer, who was the star prosecution witness at
Drake's trial, admitted his guilt in an affidavit which he gave to his own
lawyer.  The lawyer was ethically bound by the attorney-client privilege not to
reveal the information.  Finally, after the real murderer died in 1982, the
lawyer made the evidence available to Drake, and he was released from prison. 
Under the new law's time limits, Henry Drake would have been foreclosed from
federal habeas review, and he would, in all likelihood, have been executed.  
</LI></UL>
<HR>
<H1>NEW LEGAL SERVICES RESTRICTIONS</H1>
<P>The recently adopted appropriations bill not only slashes the funding for
the Legal Services Corporation (LSC) by a devastating one-third, but contains
crippling restrictions that effectively prevent the federal courts from
addressing and remedying constitutional violations of the rights of  poor
Americans.   </P>
<P>For more than two decades, the LSC has delivered quality legal services to
poor people throughout the U.S. who would otherwise have no access to justice. 
LSC-funded lawyers represent the poor, including the elderly and the disabled, 
in matters involving  health care, disability benefits,  domestic violence,
divorce, child abuse, neglect and custody, housing and employment.   LSC-funded
backup centers provided technical assistance and legal expertise.  Other
LSC-funded offices specialize in providing assistance to migrant workers, Native
Americans and other  groups historically excluded from the legal system.  But
Congress has carved out sweeping categories of cases that LSC may no longer
bring, even with non-LSC funds.</P>
<P>&#183;<B> The LSC may no longer  bring class action lawsuits or participate

in litigation to &quot;reform&quot; the welfare system.</B></P>
<P>The class action lawsuit, an enormously useful procedural device for
addressing and remedying systemic violations affecting large numbers of people,
gathers together all the claims of &quot;similarly situated individuals&quot; so
that they can be tried in a single lawsuit.  Without the class action, it would
have been virtually impossible for the federal courts to desegregate the South's
public schools, or to remedy the horrific conditions that existed in state-run
mental institutions throughout the country.  But today, the class action is
effectively off-limits to the needy.  The new regulations prohibit LSC-funded
attorneys from bringing class action suits, from participating in litigation to
&quot;reform&quot; the welfare system, or from challenging any existing welfare
law.</P>
<P>Had these regulations been in place before, the following small but typical
sampling of class action lawsuits could not have been brought and won by LSC
lawyers:</P>
<UL>
<LI><B>On behalf of disabled people:</B>  In 1983, LSC lawyers brought a
successful class action lawsuit on behalf of tens of thousands of disabled
people who had been improperly denied disability benefits by the Social Security
Administration.  The court found that some members of the class had already died
or suffered further illness as a result of the government's actions.  Without a
class action, only those relatively few disabled recipients able to retain
lawyers could have won the restoration of their benefits.  The rest would have
been out in the cold.
</LI>
<LI><B>On behalf of former homeowners:  </B>In the early 1990s, LSC assisted
Georgia homeowners who had lost their homes because their lending institution
had engaged in fraudulent and deceptive practices.  A class action was brought,
and more than 20,000 defrauded customers were eventually compensated for their
losses.
</LI>
<LI><B>On behalf of poor children:</B>  In the early 1970s, schools were
closed in California wine country so that students could help harvest the
grapes.  The country welfare officials said that all AFDC (Aid to Dependent
Children) recipients ten years old or over had to work in the fields or lose
their benefits.  Families, including children, were forced to work in fields
with no toilets and unsanitary drinking water.  LSC brought a successful class
action and stopped the county from violating state child labor and AFDC laws.
</LI>
<LI><B>On behalf of the elderly:</B>  In the early 1990s, thousands of elderly
people were  cut off from Illinois' Community Care Program, which provides home
and community- based services to those who would otherwise require nursing home
care, without notice or a hearing.  LSC brought a class action and won a
settlement reinstating all those who had been improperly removed from the
program, and establishing due process standards.
</LI></UL>
<HR>
<H1>THE ANTITERRORISM LAW AND PENDING IMMIGRATION LEGISLATION:  No Due Process
for Immigrants</H1>
<P>The anti-terrorism law, and immigration legislation that is currently
pending in conference, contain significant court stripping provisions which
compromise the due process rights of all  immigrants, including long-term
permanent residents, regardless of the strength of their legal claims.</P>
<P><B>&#183; The legislation eliminates due process safeguards for allegedly
undocumented aliens, including political refugees </B></P>
<P>One extreme court stripping provision, originally included in the House's
immigration proposal, was tacked onto the new anti-terrorism law and enacted in
April.  It radically changes the immigration adjudication process by shielding
decisions made by Immigration and Naturalization Service employees from any
administrative or judicial review.  Anyone arriving in the U.S. without proper
documentation, or anyone already in the U.S. who is believed to have crossed the
border without presenting proper documentation, <I>even if such a person has
been residing in this country for many years, </I>can be &quot;summarily
excluded,&quot; i.e., instantly deported, to his or her country of origin.  </P>
<P>The new law will have its most devastating impact on legitimate refugees
forced to flee their country without valid travel documents.  Upon arrival, they
will have to persuade an INS official  that they have a legitimate fear of
persecution  on account of their political opinion, race, religion, national
origin, or membership in a particular social group.  Should they fail to
convince the INS in the airport, immediately upon arrival, that they can prove
their asylum case, they will no longer have the right to a hearing before an
immigration judge or the right to  federal judicial review.  Instead of a
federal judge being the final arbiter of a political asylum claim -- a decision
that may be of life or death proportions -- that responsibility now resides with
the INS.  There is no appeal.  The equivalent in a criminal case would be having
the police and prosecutor determine guilt or innocence at the scene of the
crime, instead of leaving this determination to a judge or a jury at a hearing.</P>
<H2>Tragedy Averted</H2>
<P>Had summary exclusion been the law of the land in December 1994, Fauziya
Kasinga might have been returned to Togo:</P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Fauziya Kasinga</B> is a young woman who fled her homeland in order to
escape genital mutilation, a traditional practice in portions of Africa and the
Middle East, and arrived in the U.S. with fraudulent papers necessary for her
escape.   After languishing in an INS detention facility for more than a year
while her political asylum claim was pending, Ms. Kasinga was released only
after her story was made public.  Her claim is being considered by the Board of 
Immigration Appeals and if it is rejected, she will have the right to federal
court review.  But if the new law had been in place, it is more than likely that
she would have been excluded immediately upon her arrival in this country and
sent back to Togo.   Genital mutilation has only recently been asserted as
grounds for refugee status, and the law in this area is still evolving.  Would
the INS employee who initially interviewed her have made the right decision?
</LI></UL>
<P><B>&#183; The pending immigration bill  strips from the federal courts the
power to make remedial orders to correct large scale constitutional violations
of immigrants' rights</B></P>
<P>The House version of the pending legislation eliminates all &quot;pattern
and practice&quot; class action challenges to immigration policies and
practices.  This litigation tool has made it possible  for the federal courts to
address and remedy serious INS abuses against classes of immigrants, including
coercive arrest and deportation practices; abominable conditions of detention;
and discrimination against Haitians, Salvadorans and other nationalities. 
Robbed of the ability to entertain pattern and practice lawsuits, it will be
almost impossible for the federal judiciary to  rein in an agency that is
notoriously overworked, inefficient and often discriminatory.  </P>
<H2>Corrupt Asylum Process Reformed</H2>
<H4>If the pending legislation passes, this kind of litigation will become a
thing of the past</H4>
<UL>
<LI><I>American Baptist Churches v. Thornburgh</I> is the name of a class
action lawsuit brought by the ACLU and other groups in 1985.   It charged the
INS with systematic discrimination against political refugees from El Salvador
and Guatemala. Though they faced clear persecution and even death at home, where
ferocious civil wars were raging, these refugees were routinely denied political
asylum because the American government supported the repressive Salvadoran and
Guatemalan regimes. Nicaraguans, on the other hand, were just as routinely
granted asylum because of U.S. opposition to the ruling Sandinistas.  A 1990
settlement  ruled that foreign policy considerations could not be the
determining factor in asylum decisions, and ordered  new hearings for many of
the 240,000 Salvadorans and Guatemalans in the U.S.  This single, pattern and
practice lawsuit brought about the reform of the entire asylum process.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>&#183; Federal courts are precluded from reviewing certain deportation
orders</B></P>
<P>The Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act, which was enacted in
April, prohibits any court from reviewing a final order of deportation entered
against a long-time legal permanent resident if the immigrant has committed even
a minor criminal offense (one for which the sentence that could have been
imposed is one year of imprisonment).  This means that such minor, nonviolent
offenses as theft of cable TV services , for example, deprives a legal permanent
resident of <I>any</I> opportunity to challenge the lawfulness of his
deportation.</P>
<P>The Senate version of the pending immigration bill contains an even broader
provision that prohibits judicial review of <I>any</I> denial of discretionary
relief by an immigration judge.  That means that if the immigration judge abuses
his discretion, no court may review the decision.</P>
<P> <B>&#183; The pending immigration bill places insuperable procedural
obstacles in the path of aliens seeking judicial review of INS decisions  </B></P>
<UL>
<LI>The Senate version says that aliens have a right to legal counsel only so
long as it does not &quot;unreasonably delay&quot; the proceedings. Currently,
new arrivals have at least 14 days to secure an attorney before an
administrative hearing can be held. The House version reduces the time to ten
days; the Senate version to only three.
</LI>
<LI>Both Senate and House bills would delete a statutory requirement that
notices of deportation grounds be written in both English and Spanish.  As a
result, even if an alien is entitled to a hearing to assert his or her legal
rights, they will in effect forfeit their right because they do not understand
the charging document.
</LI>
<LI>Under current law, when an alien files a petition for judicial review, any
deportation order against that alien is automatically stayed until the court
renders a decision.    Under the Senate bill, the stay is no longer automatic;
the alien must affirmatively seek a stay of deportation from the INS or from the
court.  This greatly increases the likelihood that aliens with good legal claims
will be deported before a court can even consider them.
</LI></UL>
<H1>CONCLUSION</H1>
<P>An independent federal judiciary is essential to preserve and enforce
fundamental rights.  This does not mean that the courts or individual judges
should be immune from popular or academic criticism.  But by disabling the
federal courts in advance from executing their constitutionally mandated duty
and responsibility to safeguard individual rights, Congress  threatens the
delicate balance between majoritarian rule and respect for the rights of
individuals.  The first victims of court stripping -- immigrants, prisoners, the
poor -- will not be the last.  The most unpopular and vulnerable members of
society are all too often the first targets of government repression.  But once
the federal courthouse door has been slammed shut to one group, it won't be long
before others are similarly excluded.  </P>
<P>The only question is, who will be next?  </P>
<HR>
<H2>NOTES:</H2>
<P>(1) Gerald Gunther, &quot;Judicial Review,<I>&quot; Encyclopedia of the
American Constitution</I>, (Macmillan, 1986) p. 1054</P>
<P>(2) These examples come from the case files of the ACLU's National Prison
Project.</P>
<P>(3) Since state judges, unlike their federal counterparts, face re-election
in order to keep their jobs, they are vulnerable to public pressure and passing
passions.  Thus, they cannot always be relied upon to protect defendants'
constitutional rights against the wrath of a frightened public.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
