<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
Gay and Lesbian Rights
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/gay.gif">
</CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The following sites provide comprehensive or unique resources relating to
the work of the ACLU in this issue area.  While some of these sites are operated
by organizations that work frequently in coalition with the ACLU, the sites may
also include materials on positions we do not share. 
</P>
<P>To report a broken or relocated link, or to suggest a site for inclusion on
this page, use the feedback button at the bottom of this page. </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/rbline.gif" WIDTH="100%">
<P>
<B><A HREF="http://www.hrcusa.org/">Human Rights Campaign</A></B>  <BR>This
site allows you to lobby your senators and representatives, and to  immediately
send them a message.  The battles that are being fought regarding  lesbian/gay
lesgislation and litigation are chronicled throughout the HRC site, with the HRC
link page containing approximately 55 links, many of them political in nature.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://www.cyberspaces.com/outproud/">!OutProud!, The National
Coalition for Gay, Lesbian &amp; Bisexual Youth</A></B>  <BR>The !OutProud!
site deals with lesbian and gay issues as they pertain to young people.  The
site offers a wide range of resources for youth and educators, and is also home
to QueerAmerica, a resource which allows the user to locate organizations in
their area.  The list of links to approximately 65 other lesbian/gay sites
focusses on youth-related organizations and publications, with a listing of
college groups that are on the Web.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://www.ngltf.org/main.html">National Gay and Lesbian Task
Force</A></B>  <BR>NGLTF, an organization which &quot;seeks to build the
political strength of the lesbian and gay rights movement at the grassroots
level,&quot; has put its press releases and position papers online.  There is
also information on upcoming events.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
 
<B><A HREF="http://www.glaad.org/">Gay &amp; Lesbian Alliance Against
Defamation</A></B>  <BR>GLAAD's web site serves to further its goal of fighting
&quot;the defamation of lesbians and gays and their enforced invisibility in the
popular culture.&quot; The site defines the goals, the victories and the battles
being waged by GLAAD, with regional chapters reporting on events in their areas.

</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
 
<B><A HREF="http://www.glstn.org/freedom/">The Gay, Lesbian, and Straight
Teachers Network</A></B>  <BR>GLSTN fights homophobia in schools around the
country.  Various informational and educational brochures can be downloaded from
this site.  
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
 
<B><A HREF="http://www.datalounge.com/hsupports/">Hollywood Supports</A></B> 
<BR>This organization was &quot;launched in the fall of 1991 by leading
entertainment industry figures  to counter workplace fear and discrimination
based on HIV status and sexual orientation,&quot; with   the prime objective of
ensuring &quot;a safe working environment free of stigma, fear and bigotry.&quot;
In addition to the organizational information, users can also find sections on
the seminars that  Hollywood Supports offers.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
 
<B><A HREF="http://now.org/now/issues/lgbi/lgbi.html">NOW and Lesbian Rights</A></B>
 <BR>This page is part of the the <A HREF="http://now.org/now/home.html">National
Organization of  Women's</A> web site.  NOW's policies on lesbian rights are
defined; there is also  a short narrative on the history of NOW and lesbian
rights.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
 
<B><A HREF="http://www.contrib.andrew.cmu.edu/~nifty/lglv.html">The League of
Gay and Lesbian Voters PA</A></B>  <BR>This &quot;non-partisan organization
focusing on issues of special concern to the lesbigay community in Pennsylvania&quot;
utilizes its web site to further  its primary activities of voter registration,
and the education of voters/legislators/candidates.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
 
<B><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/gaylaw/">The National Journal of Sexual
Orientation Law</A></B>  <BR>This publication, with the primary purpose of
disseminating &quot;information and ideas about law and sexual orientation in an
efficient and timely manner,&quot; also tries to provide information distinct
from recent &quot;articles on sexual orientation in traditional law reviews.&quot;</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P><B><A
HREF="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/user/scotts/ftp/bulgarians/mainpage.html">&quot;We
can always call them Bulgarians&quot;</A></B>
<BR>This is a page done by Scott Safier of Carnegie Mellon University.  The
site pulls together many articles  dealing with everything from religion,
politics and the law, to explaining the hanky codes and giving the history of
the  rainbow flag.  There are approximatly 40 links, including organizations,
publications and individuals sites.</P> 
