<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>06/16/96: Visions of Liberty, The Fire This Time</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<H1>The Fire This Time</H1>
<P>Like a nightmare from my childhood, the stories and photos about black
churches burning throughout the deep South make me shiver with fear, evoking
memories of a time when terror against people of color was a routine feature of
Southern life and an essential ingredient of a system of racial subjugation.</P>
<P>Why now, after all these years, has this nightmare sprung to life again?
Jesse Jackson offers an answer.  &quot;It seems that the blue suits are engaging
in anti-civil rights propaganda and legislation in Congress, and the black robes
are handing out restrictive rulings in the courts, and the white sheets are
doing the burning,&quot; Jackson said.  &quot;There is a kinship among these
things.&quot;</P>
<P>Is there?  Not literally, perhaps.  Certainly, the criminals who set fire to
black churches did not conspire with the leaders of Congress who have proposed a
bill to end affirmative action remedies, nor with those Supreme Court justices
who have decided voting rights cases in a way that will lead to a purge of black
legislators -- just this week the Court declared unconstitutional four more
majority black districts.</P>
<P>But there may indeed be a kinship nonetheless.</P>
<P>Back in 1963, on the day after four young black girls in Birmingham, Alabama
were killed when a bomb exploded in their church during Sunday services, a young
lawyer named Charles Morgan, Jr. made a similar point.  The blame, he said, did
not fall only on those who planted the bombs, but also upon the &quot;good
people&quot; of Birmingham, who by their silence and their acceptance of the
subjugation of blacks had created a climate in which the bomb throwers felt
justified.  The good people violated no law but they did commit a crime of

another kind: it was called complicity.</P>
<P>As Morgan was right in 1963, so Jackson is right today.  There is a kinship
among these things, and it is our obligation to explore it.</P>
<P>For fifteen years now, many of our political leaders have called for an end
to remedies for racial discrimination.  In the face of overwhelming evidence of
suffocating racial disparities, politicians have declared the disease of racism
cured, and the playing field level.  Any remaining racial differences -- in
employment, in housing, in education, in political representation, in prison
populations -- must be the fault of blacks themselves, they have implied,
because they could not possibly be attributable any longer to the enduring
effects of racial subjugation.</P>
<P>These relentless lies have poisoned the moral air in America.  They have
defused the passion to remedy the effects of racism and instead encouraged
resentment against its victims.  And the Supreme Court, which from 1954 on had
played such an important role in setting the nation's moral tone, today echoes
the politicians' lies by steadily eroding the ability of black candidates to
find equal opportunity at the ballot box.</P>
<P>Those who breathe this poisoned air -- who are too young to have breathed
any other air -- direct their anger and their resentment not against racism but
against its victims.  And a few of them, demented to be sure, act out that
resentment and somehow come to feel comfortable enough to burn black churches.</P>
<P>Yes, there is a kinship among these things and it is a kinship we had better
address.  For this is not the first time we have seen such kinship in America. 
After the Civil War, unprecedented and sweeping civil rights legislation was
passed to guarantee equal rights regardless of race and to prohibit racial
discrimination in voting, public accommodations and the criminal justice system.
 In addition, Congress set up special economic programs and facilitated a
massive voter registration effort.  By 1867, there were -- incredibly -- 735,000
blacks and 635,000 whites registered to vote in the ten states of the Old South.
 It appeared as if a remarkable reconstruction might take place.</P>
<P>And then it crumbled.  Angry white groups willing to use terror and violence
became widespread.  Throughout the South, Republicans committed to ending the
enduring effects of slavery were gradually replaced by Democrats committed to
the subjugation of blacks.  And after the 1874 elections, Congress was also
transformed:  a 110-vote Republican majority became a 60-vote Democratic
majority.  Two years later, in order to win the presidency, the Republican
candidate, Rutherford B. Hayes, agreed to renounce the use of federal power to
protect the rights of Southern blacks.  And in 1873 the Supreme Court joined the
retreat by interpreting the newly-minted Fourteenth Amendment to allow states
the authority to decide which rights their citizens should have.</P>
<P>Once the definition and enforcement of civil rights were left to state and
local governments, blacks were once again at the mercy of their oppressors.</P>
<P>Nearly a hundred years of violent terror followed, relieved only by the
civil rights movement of the sixties and the consequent resolve of Congress and
the courts to address again the persistent effects of centuries of racial
subjugation.</P>
<P>It is no exaggeration to say that the political and judicial retreat during
the 1870s paved the way for the Ku Klux Klan's long reign of terror.  So, too,
it is legitimate to suggest that the burning of black churches today is related
to the current political and judicial retreat: &quot;There is a kinship among
these things.&quot;</P>
<P>Consider, too, General Colin Powell -- certainly no radical -- who recently
commented upon the retreat from affirmative action remedies by saying that &quot;the
progress achieved over the past generation must be continued if we wish to bless
future generations....  We must fight misguided government efforts to shut it
all down.&quot;</P>
<P>Either that, or more nightmares.</P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
