<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>08/25/96: Visions of Liberty, #8</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I>
<P>August 25, 1996
<H2>More Reefer Madness
</H2><P>	Even though I've been in the "business" of protecting civil liberties
against the abuses of government for almost 30 years (I joined the staff
of the New York Civil Liberties Union in 1967!), I am still amazed at how
often public policies that affect the lives of millions of people, sometimes
very adversely, are based on pure myth.  There are hundreds of examples:
<P>	Myth:	Poor women have babies so that they can increase their monthly
welfare checks.
<P>	Political solution:  Pass "family cap" laws that deny additional benefits
to any additional children.
<P>	The truth:  There is no evidence that women have more children in order
to get more money from the government, no evidence that punishing women (and
their children) will, 	in fact, deter them from having more babies, and anyway,
women on welfare have fewer children than women who are not on welfare.	
<P>	Myth:  We are experiencing an "unprecedented crime wave" caused by a
"ticking time bomb" of "superpredator" juveniles hell bent on killing, maiming
and robbing us.
<P>	Political solution:  We must protect ourselves by getting rid of the
juvenile justice system which "coddles" young criminals, and lock them up
for longer periods of time in adult prisons.
<P>	The truth:  Juvenile crime levels are lower than they were in 1980, juveniles
commit only a handful of the violent crimes in this country (13%), and recent
studies show that locking young offenders up with adults leads to higher,
not lower re-arrest rates.
<P>	But the granddaddy of all myths has to be the myth of reefer madness.
 For the past 70- plus years, the government has tried, over and over again,
to convince us that marijuana must remain illegal because it poses an
unacceptable danger to the health and well-being of the nation.  Marijuana
kills brain cells; it causes formerly happy and industrious children to become
alienated, under-achieving teenagers; it's the gateway drug to cocaine, heroin,
and terrible, mind-bending drugs that underground chemists haven't even thought
of yet.  And to those parents who, based on their own youthful experimentation,
don't think marijuana is such a big deal, the government warns that the pot
they smoked in the 60's and 70's is nothing like the weed their kids are
smoking today.  It's ten, twenty, one hundred times more potent, we are told.
<P>	This week, marijuana became a campaign issue.  The Department of Health
and Human Resources released the results of its annual National Household
Drug Survey and evidently recent marijuana use among teens in on the rise,
from 5.3%  in 1992, to 10.9% in 1995.
<P>	The responses were predictable.  Administration officials wrung their
hands, "admitted" they had not done enough to fight teenage drug use, and
promised to do more -- much more.  Bob Dole blamed President Clinton for
this "national tragedy" and promised he would "make the drug war priority
No. 1 again."  In the meantime, Congress is waiting in the wings with more
anti- drug bills, as if we don't have enough repressive and ineffective laws
on the books already.
<P>	The truth may not matter to our political leaders, especially in an election
year.  But it should matter to the rest of us.  It should matter that, contrary
to what both Clinton and Dole are saying, the government's war on marijuana
has never been more vigorous.  Since 1992, when Clinton first took office,
there have been more than 1 million marijuana arrests, mostly for possession
-- the most marijuana arrests of any administration ever.  This Administration
has aggressively opposed legalizing marijuana for medical purposes, even
though the idea enjoys broad popular support.  It has pumped vast sums of
money into interdiction and eradication efforts, and supported such anti-civil
liberties measures as civil forfeiture and mandatory minimum sentencing laws.
 
<P>	Dole's accusation that Clinton has not done enough, and Clinton's mea
culpa, are fradulent -- a political sideshow.
<P>	And so, it turns out, are the scarey things the candidates say about
marijuana.  In November, the Lindesmith Center, a drug policy think tank
in New York, is publishing a new, 55- page book called "Marijuana Myths,
Marijuana Facts" by two scholars, John P. Morgan, M.D. and sociologist Lynn
Zimmer.   Morgan and Zimmer have painstakingly reviewed all of the scientific
literature about marijuana, and their book pokes huge holes in eighteen separate
marijuana myths.  For example:
<P>	Myth:  Marijuana is much more potent now than it used to be.
<P>	The truth:  In 1993, the last year for which figures were available,
the average percentage of THC (the active ingredient in marijuana) in
government-seized marijuana was 3.32 percent.  In 1975, samples of marijuana
tested by a large independent laboratory ranged in THC content from 2 to
5 percent, with some as high as 14%.
<P>	Myth:  Marijuana causes brain damage.
<P>	The truth:  This claim is based on a 20-year-old study in which two rhesus
monkeys were exposed to continuous massive doses of THC -- up to 200 times
the psychoactive dose for humans.  It has never been replicated, and there
is no evidence anywhere that marijuana users suffer brain damage.
<P>	Myth:  Marijuana is a "gateway" to the use of harder drugs.
<P>	The Truth:  It's true that most users of heroin, LSD and cocaine have
used marijuana (and alcohol, and tobacco).  But the vast majority of marijuana
users never use any other illegal drug.  In fact, as marijuana use increased
in the 60's and 70's, heroin use markedly declined.
<P>The truth?  Marijuana is a rather benign drug that isn't addictive and
causes no significant harm to even to long term users.  And kids know it,
even though more of them have been exposed to drug education programs than
at any other time in U.S. history.  
<P>	Why should we care if the government is lying to us about marijuana?
 
<P>	Because the lie sets the stage for a chain of  destructive events that
tear away at our most fundemental liberties.  It is used to justify criminal
prohibition and to lock people up for unconcionably long sentences for using
the "wrong" drug.  The lie is used to justify the seizure of people's homes,
cars and other personal property.  It is used to deny sick people legal access
to a drug which has recognized medicinal value.  And, of course, it is used
to get politicians elected.
<P>	So, as the election campaign heats up, be prepared for a major escalation
in anti-marijuana rhetoric and remember that most, if not all, of what is
said is pure bunk.
<P><CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER>
<H6><CENTER><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union<BR>Photo
by Bob
Adelman</I></CENTER>
</H6></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
