<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Visions of Liberty #17: Scapegoating Immigrants -- Again</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<P>November 17, 1996</P>
<H2>SCAPEGOATING IMMIGRANTS -- AGAIN</H2>
<P>Between 1890 and 1924, millions of people came to America from Eastern and
Southern Europe in search of a better life economically and a freer life
politically.  Most of them found what they sought, after much struggle and hard
work, or lived to see their children find it.  Today, tens of millions of
American citizens, perhaps even approaching a majority, are descendants of those
immigrants.  And so much of what we now regard as uniquely American -- our
music, our art, our theater, our films, our literature, our science, our Nobel
Prizes and our business success stories -- were produced by those immigrants and
their children and grandchildren.</P>
<P>But back in the 1920s, the majority didn't see it that way.  Immigrants from
Eastern and Southern Europe were seen as alien races -- yes, races -- and a
threat to what it meant to be American.  Many were said to be criminals seeking
to feed off hardworking Americans.  Almost no one saw the achievements that lay
ahead.</P>
<P>The government reflected this prejudice.  Between 1910 and 1920, the Palmer
Raids (named after U.S. Attorney General Mitchell Palmer) were responsible for
the deportation of thousands of immigrants -- seized suddenly from their beds or
jobs and deported without hearings, based on little more than prejudice and fear
of people who looked and sounded different.  And in 1924, Congress passed and
the President signed the National Origins Quota Act of 1924, which by design and
operation virtually eliminated immigration from Eastern and Southern Europe.</P>
<P>The conceded purpose of the Act was to preserve the racial and ethnic makeup
of the United States as it had existed in 1890.  There was no attempt to deny
this purpose or to sugarcoat it.  The day the Act became law, The New York Times
announced it with the following headline:  &quot;Chief aim . . . is to preserve
racial type as it exists here today.&quot;</P>
<P>The Act accomplished its goals by setting annual immigration quotas for each
country based on the percentage of the American population from that country in
the 1890 census.  The result in effect limited future immigration to people from
Northwestern Europe.  Not until 1965 -- in the midst of the civil rights
movement -- was a new immigration law passed that overturned the 1924 Act.</P>
<P>The 1924 Act passed because people were blinded by their prejudice and could
not see the richness and productivity that the early 20th century immigrants
would bring to American life and culture.  Racism prevailed, and the
Constitution was ignored.  People were denied entry based on their national
origin and those that were here were subjected to illegal treatment and
deportation without recourse to the courts.</P>
<P>Today, we are in the midst of another wave of anti-immigrant hysteria. 
Though today's prejudices are more subtle than the explicit racism of the 1920s,
many of the arguments heard now are similar to the ones that prevailed then:
that new immigrants are not as industrious as the old immigrants; that they are
not assimilating as well; that they will change the essential character of the
country; that they are coming in overwhelming numbers (actually, as a percentage
of the population, there are far fewer immigrants today than there were then);
that they are often criminals; and that they are unjustly benefitting from the
country's generosity.  At a time of unsettling and rapid social change mixed
with economic uncertainty and fear for the future, such arguments find receptive
ears, then as now.</P>
<P>Although we hear much talk about illegal immigrants, only about 150,000
immigrants actually enter the United States illegally each year.  Given the huge
perimeter of our national borders and the size of our population, that is not an
overwhelming amount, and the problem, if it is a problem, does not justify the
political hysteria it has generated.  But what really reveals the animus of our
elected officials in Washington are the laws they have recently passed that
punish and violate the rights of legal immigrants and their families, including
the children who have been born here and are, therefore, citizens.  Consider
three laws passed this year:</P>
<P>1.  The Anti-Terrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act was passed by
Congress and signed by President Clinton this past April.  This law was
ballyhooed by leaders of both parties as a response to the Oklahoma City bombing
in 1995.  But much of this law had absolutely nothing to do with combatting
terrorism, a fact consciously kept from the public.</P>
<P>For example, this law included a provision that imposed mandatory detention
and deportation on longtime permanent legal residents if they had been convicted
of any drug offense at any time in the past.  This included convictions for
simple possession of marijuana (except in very small amounts).  Thus, a person
who may have arrived here legally as a child many years ago, married a citizen
and who has several citizen children, and who has worked and paid taxes for 20
years, can be summarily arrested, detained and deported for a marijuana
possession bust 25 years ago.  Moreover, all this can be done without any
opportunity to challenge the deportation in court because the law conveniently
included a provision eliminating the right to judicial review.  People have
already been caught in this web of cruelty.  What this sort of law has to do
with combatting terrorism, or reducing illegal immigration, we have not been
told.  Perhaps those of you who are Republicans ought to ask Mr. Dole and Mr.
Gingrich why they pushed this law through Congress, and those of you who are
Democrats might want to ask Mr. Clinton why he signed it.</P>
<P>2.  The Welfare Reform Act was passed and signed by President Clinton this
past September.  It categorically eliminated both Supplemental Social Security
Income and Aid to Families for Dependent Children for all legal permanent
residents.  Under this law, an estimated 500,000 elderly and disabled
immigrants, who entered the country legally, never violated any law or
immigration requirement, who worked for years and paid taxes, contributed to the
economy and in every respect played by the rules, will now have their essential,
life-sustaining benefits taken away.  Not content with this piece of designer
cruelty, the new law also authorizes the states to enact local laws denying
state-funded benefits to legal permanent residents.</P>
<P>Again, you might want to ask the politicians you voted for why they would
want to do such things in your name.</P>
<P>3.  Finally, the Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act
was buried in a comprehensive budget bill and enacted on September 30 with
little public attention and virtually no public debate.  Yet this Act amounts to
one of the most sweeping revisions of the law governing the powers of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) to determine admissions,
deportations and detention.  This law not only reiterated the authority to
deport longtime legal residents for minor crimes, it also restricted
humanitarian relief and virtually eliminated the opportunity to apply for asylum
for persons arriving here without papers (a common and understandable phenomenon
when one flees a persecutorial government).  Worst of all, this bill enacted
unprecedented restrictions on the power of federal courts to review the legality
of individual deportation orders, to issue injunctions against illegal INS
policies or practices and to determine the constitutionality of INS actions. 
Aside from what this law does to legal immigrants, it represents an attack upon
the rule of law itself and the principle of independent courts.</P>
<P>Were the politicians you voted for acting in your interest when they enacted
such a law?</P>
<P>Immigration policies during the 1920s are now universally regarded as a
descent into hysteria, prejudice, unconstitutionality and cruelty.  The
politicians responsible for those policies and practices are a blot on
fundamental American principles of fairness and equality under the law. 
Someday, someday soon I hope, today's politicians will be similarly seen by the
majority of American citizens.</P>
<HR>
<P><A HREF="vision16.html">Previous installment of Visions of Liberty</A></P>
<P><A HREF="visionid.html">Visions of Liberty Column Index
</A></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
