<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Visions of Liberty #18: REFLECTIONS ON SKIN COLOR AND THE PERSISTENCE OF
RACIAL DISADVANTAGE</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<P>December 8, 1996</P>
<H2>HOW LONG?  VERY LONG: REFLECTIONS ON SKIN COLOR AND THE PERSISTENCE OF
RACIAL DISADVANTAGE</H2>
<P>Last month, the voters of California approved an initiative ending all forms
of affirmative action.  A few weeks later, a coalition of civil rights groups,
including the American Civil Liberties Union, obtained a preliminary injunction
in federal court blocking the implementation of the ban.  At this writing, the
case is still pending and its ultimate disposition unknown.  Meanwhile, the
debate over the persistence of racial disadvantage and the need to remedy it
continues.</P>
<P>Those who support at least some forms of affirmative action do so because
they believe that drastic remedies are still required to provide equal
opportunity and to overcome the substantial disadvantage, including outright
prejudice, still suffered by Americans of darker skin color.</P>
<P>Those who oppose all forms of affirmative action do so because they believe
that such remedies are no longer required, that the playing field is now level
and that disadvantages based on skin color, created and embedded in our laws and
customs for over two centuries, have been largely eliminated during the past
four decades.  This attitude was best reflected in a poll of delegates to the
Republican convention in San Diego last summer, which revealed that 60 percent
of those delegates believed that equal opportunity was now a fact and that civil
rights laws prohibiting racial discrimination in employment, education and
housing were no longer necessary and could be safely repealed.</P>
<P>Who is right?</P>
<P>Certainly, much progress has been made in the last forty years.  The
formalities of racial bias have been eliminated.  Jim Crow laws have been
abolished.  Segregation is no longer legally permitted, and civil rights laws,
enforced by the courts, have in fact opened up avenues of access to jobs,
education and housing that were unimaginable back in the fifties.</P>
<P>But it is also true that many of those avenues of opportunity remain narrow
and constricted, available in fact only to the relatively few.  The persistence
of prejudice based on skin color remains and, even beyond outright prejudice,
the profound disadvantages created by centuries of slavery, terror and legalized
subjugation have proved to be more difficult to erase than many of us imagined
during the hopeful sixties.</P>
<P>Redemption for two hundred years of social sins will, it appears, require
more than forty years and more than the abolition of formal inequality, which
was the great accomplishment of the civil rights movement of the fifties and
sixties.</P>
<P>What does the evidence tell us?</P>
<UL>
<LI> In November, shortly after Californians voted to end affirmative action
remedies, a tape recording of an executive meeting at Texaco revealed senior
managers engaged in crude and overtly racist conversations regarding their black
employees.  What was remarkable about this tape recording was that it became
publicly available and was widely reported.   Was the Texaco incident
aberrational?  Almost certainly not.  There is ample reason to believe that
similar &quot;private&quot; conversations take place unrecorded and unrevealed
throughout corporate America.  Indeed, at about the same time, similar attitudes
and conversations were revealed to have taken place at the Shell Oil Company. 
These attitudes and the persistence of bias they reflect, help explain why so
many blacks employed by such companies are repeatedly passed over for promotion
and advancement, despite excellent work records.  Bias does, in fact, persist,
though it is less obvious and open than it was 40 years ago.
</LI>
<LI> During the same period, two articles appeared in medical journals
documenting the severe health disadvantages suffered by American blacks.  The
first, in the October issue of the American Journal of Public Health, studied
blood pressure differences between 4,000 black and white young adults in four
cities.  It has long been known that blacks generally are more susceptible to
high blood pressure, a silent and deadly disease, but this new study suggested
that at least some African-American blood pressure problems are related to the
stress caused by discrimination rather than to diet or genetic factors. 
Although this study is more suggestive than definitive, it is consistent with
other, similar studies.
</LI></UL>
<P>The second recent study was published by The New England Journal of
Medicine, one of the oldest and most respected journals in the field.  This
study found dramatic differences in life expectancy.  Fifteen-year-old
African-American boys in Harlem, for example, have less chance of reaching the
age of 45 than white boys do of reaching 65.  And a survey of mortality rates
for men and women between 15 and 64 in 16 different regions found excessive
numbers of premature deaths among blacks as compared to whites.  Even when death
due to homicide and AIDS, both of which occur disproportionately among blacks,
are removed, there was still a &quot;tremendous excess of premature mortality&quot;
among blacks, according to the lead researcher.</P>
<P>The leading causes of such premature deaths is cardiovascular disease and,

secondarily, cancer.  Persistent and severe stress related to the circumstances
of life in what Kenneth Clark once called the dark ghettos of our inner cities,
was suggested by the lead researcher as an explanation.  Inadequate and late

treatment of disease, once it develops, compounds the problem.  The result is
early disability and death, leaving dependents adrift and in trouble.  And so
the cycle continues.</P>
<P>These findings, combined with the often invisible persistence of bias,
require a remedial policy response if we mean finally to have justice, fairness
and equal opportunity in this country.  What we did to African-Americans for
more than two centuries has not yet yielded to the remedies invented and
implemented in recent decades.  More is required.  Yet less seems to be the
order of the day.</P>
<P>Poor people are being cut off from minimal income support without any
serious effort being made to create jobs, train people to perform them and
provide day care to make it possible for them to take jobs.  And the movement to
abolish civil rights remedies for discrimination is growing, despite the
evidence provided by the Texaco and Shell Oil revelations.</P>
<P>The civil rights movement of the sixties depended on the courage of
African-Americans who organized resistance to racial disadvantages and upon
whites of good will who were morally committed to redemptive remedies.</P>
<P>We need that combination again, badly.</P>
<HR>
