<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Visions of Liberty #19: Which Morality? Freedom versus Authority</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0Gold (Macintosh; I; PPC)"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" HEIGHT="54" WIDTH="572" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
</P>
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<P>December 15, 1996</P>
<H2>Which Morality? Freedom versus Authority</H2>
<P>Today, a struggle between two competing visions of morality is taking place
in America -- one based on freedom, the other on authoritarianism.  A recent
edition of The New York Times carried two articles that, when read together, are
poignant and graphic reminders of just how different these moral compasses are.
 </P>
<P>The first, entitled &quot;Love at the Top ...&quot;, told the sweet story of
a late-in-life love affair between Nelson Mandela, the president of South
Africa, and Gra&ccedil;a Machel, the widow of President Samora M. Machel of
Mozambique.  &quot;I thought that part of my life was over&quot;, said Mrs.
Machel, &quot;and here I am in love.&quot;  </P>
<P>The couple, however, does not plan to marry.  They will spend two weeks a
month together, but continue their life work:  Mandela in South Africa, creating
a society based on democracy, justice and racial reconciliation to South Africa,
and Machel in Mozambique, heading a U.N. study on the impact of war on children.
 The decision not to marry, said Mandela, was hers.  &quot;I like being called
Mrs. Machel,&quot; she has said.  &quot;It is my way of keeping my husband
alive.&quot;</P>
<P>Some would consider living together without benefit of marriage an immoral
act.  But in my view, Mandela and Machel's central roles in establishing civic
virtue in their troubled lands is what defines their morality, not the decisions
they make in the context of their personal life together.</P>
<P>The second article appeared just a few pages later. Entitled &quot;Stoning
of Afghan Adulterers,&quot; the story told of two people in Afghanistan who,
like Mr. Mandela and Mrs. Machel, were in love, living together, and unmarried. 
When they were discovered by the ruling Taliban religious movement, they were
arrested and publicly stoned  to death.  The story was not pretty:  the man and
woman were buried vertically up to their chests and then people threw  stones at
their heads from close range until they were dead.   According to the article,

one died in ten minutes; the other suffered for considerably longer.</P>
<P>The authorities were chillingly unapologetic about the incident.  Mohammed
Wali, the Muslim cleric who led the investigation that resulted in the stoning,
said: &quot;When I see this kind of thing, I am very happy, because it means
that the rule of Islam is being implemented.&quot;  Mullah Mohammed Hassan, one
of the most powerful clerics in Afghanistan, said that the threat of severe
punishment would end sinful activities like homosexuality just as it had ended
adultery in the village where the offending couple were murdered. If Mandela and
Machel had been living in Afghanistan, would they too have been stoned to death?
 Very possibly.</P>
<P>How should public morality be defined?  By the degree of democracy, fairness
and racial justice  reflected in the laws and processes of a government?  Or by
the intensely personal, consensual behavior of individuals?  </P>
<P>In theocracies like Afghanistan, public morality has nothing to do with
democracy or the protection of personal freedom.  Instead, it is defined by the
extent to which personal behavior conforms to a rigidly imposed religious code. 
 And transgressors are severely punished if caught. </P>
<P>In America, the Constitution protects, or should protect, such personal
decisions from government interference or punishment. In America, public
morality means what it now means in South Africa:  democracy, freedom, justice
and fairness.  Freedom means that the state may not enforce my personal
standards on you.  And religious freedom means that the beliefs of some may not
be imposed through law on others who do not share them. </P>
<P>Unfortunately, this vision of morality based on freedom is not shared by
everyone in America.   We have our share of merchants of virtue, bent on forcing
their beliefs on everyone else.  Take Jesse Helms.  He is sponsoring a
constitutional amendment to restore government-sponsored prayers in public
schools because he thinks it will enhance his authoritarian brand of public
morality.  </P>
<P>During the 1950s, of course,  many states did impose daily prayers in public
schools, and the states that did so the most were in the deep South.  In
Mississippi, a larger proportion of schoolchildren were praying every day than
in any other state.  Was Mississippi a moral state in those days?  </P>
<P>I don't think so.  Racial segregation and subjugation were enforced, often
by brutal, state-sanctioned violence and terror.  This was the state where
14-year old Emmett Till was lynched for looking at a white woman; where three
civil rights workers -- James Chaney, Andrew Goodman and Michael Schwerner --
were murdered by a sheriff  and buried in a ditch because they helped black
citizens register to vote.  And Mississippi was the state where James Meredith
was shot because he was the first black to attend the University of Mississippi.</P>
<P>Jesse Helms preaches from the Senate floor about public morality.  But in
the early 1960s, when Helms was a disc jockey in North Carolina, he regularly
attacked the lunch counter sit-ins that were the vanguard of the civil rights
movement.  The movement for racial justice was the greatest moral struggle of
this generation.  But where was Senator Helms in that moral struggle?  And who
is he to preach to us now about morality?</P>
<P>If the 1950s were years of public immorality, the 1960s changed much of
that.  Racial segregation was vanquished, at least formally.  The seeds of
women's equality were planted.  The First Amendment triumphed over McCarthyism. 
And, in 1969, the gay rights movement was born.  The 1960s were, in fact, years
of moral redemption. Those who never lifted a finger to oppose the public
immorality of the 1950s do not have the moral standing today to tell us how to
live our lives.</P>
<P>As between South Africa and Afghanistan, I'll take South Africa -- and the
vision of morality reflected in the American Bill of Rights.</P>
<HR>
