<DOCHDR>
http://www.aclu.org:80/library/vision14.html 204.243.96.55 19970213122909 text/html 7265
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 12:27:56 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 18-Oct-96 21:49:16 GMT
Content-length: 7080
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>10/20/96: Visions of Liberty, #14</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>
<P>October 20, 1996</P>
<H1>Two Nations, One Justice </H1>
<P>On October 11, Magnus Malan, South Africa's former Minister of Defense and
15 co-defendants were found not guilty of murder by the presiding judge.  They
were accused of plotting to arm and train the assassination squad that attacked
the home of an African National Congress member in 1987 and killed 13 people,
most of them women and children. </P>
<P>Following the acquittal, President Nelson Mandela said he &quot;fully
accepted&quot; the judgment of the court.  If South Africa wished to build a
democracy, Mr. Mandela said, &quot;then we must respect the institutions of
government, and the judiciary is a very important arm of government.&quot;</P>
<P>This defense by Mr. Mandela of the independence of the courts stands in
sharp contrast to the sniping at judges which has become the bipartisan
political sport of the moment in America.  </P>
<P>Last spring, President Clinton attacked a federal trial judge in New York
for a ruling he had made on a motion involving the legality of a search; Bob
Dole soon joined in the fun.  Weeks later, New York's Mayor Giuliani and
Governor Pataki attacked a state court judge who had made a decision that they
didn't like.</P>
<P>Nelson Mandela had more reason than most to find the acquittal of Malan and
his co-defendants excruciating.  After all, he spent most of his adult life in
prison at the hands of the apartheid regime and was the head of the African
National Congress, whose sympathizers were slaughtered in that incident. </P>
<P>President Mandela's searing personal experiences might understandably have
led him to attack the court when he learned that his tormentors had been
acquitted.  But as a man of principle, he rose above that impulse and defended
the importance of independent courts in a democracy.</P>
<P>I wish I could say the same of political leadership here in the United
States, where the idea of independent courts was established when America was
invented over 200 years ago.  But at the same time that we are witnessing the
profoundly moving birth and evolution of democracy in South Africa, we are also
witnessing unprecedented attacks on the 205-year-old tradition of independence,

scope and power of America's federal courts -- the bedrock of our constitutional

form of government. </P>
<P>In 1996 alone, Congress passed, and President Clinton signed, a series of
laws that reduced or eliminated the ability of federal courts to remedy
violations of legal rights. </P>
<P>The first of these was swept into law as a virtual footnote to a huge
appropriations bill, the so-called Prison Litigation Reform Act.  The Act
stripped the federal courts of much of their power to correct even the most
egregious prison conditions and prohibited prison officials from settling
lawsuits by agreeing to make changes in unconstitutional prison conditions.
There was so little opposition to the Act that it never went through hearings or
faced separate votes in either the House or the Senate. </P>
<P>That action set the stage for the crippling of the &quot;Great Writ of
Liberty,&quot; the right of habeas corpus.  This ancient procedure, first
established in England in the 17th Century and later included in Article I,
Section 9 of the American Constitution, was designed to allow people convicted
in state courts to seek federal court review of the constitutionality of their
convictions.</P>
<P>Under the new law, federal courts are required to defer to state court
decisions <I>even when those decisions are clearly wrong</I>. And all too
often, they are.  Since 1973, 54 people sentenced to death have been released
from prison after evidence of their innocence was uncovered.  None of these 54
people would be alive today if they didn't have the right to habeas corpus
review.   </P>
<P>President Clinton also signed several laws that bar or dilute judicial
review in cases involving immigrants, including long-term legal residents and
political refugees, and undocumented aliens fleeing persecution and seeking
asylum.</P>
<P>Had these laws been in effect in 1994, for example, a young woman fleeing
genital mutilation in Togo and seeking asylum here could have been deported --
to face torture -- without independent court review of an immigration employee's
denial of her claim of asylum.</P>
<P>And just hours after the new immigration law went into effect, Attorney
General Janet Reno was in court, attempting to use wording in the law to dismiss
major class-action lawsuits by thousands of undocumented immigrants who say they
were wrongly disqualified from a 1980's-era INS amnesty program. </P>
<P>Another new law strips Legal Services lawyers who receive any federal
funding of their authority to represent poor people in cases involving abortion,
immigration and prisoners' rights, even if they use private funds.  The law also
explicitly bars Legal Services lawyers from challenging the constitutionality of
any aspect of the new welfare law.  Thus, those directly injured by the welfare
bill are in effect banned from challenging its constitutionality.</P>
<P>Because this interference with the independence of the courts targets
unpopular and politically powerless groups -- immigrants, prisoners, welfare
recipients and the poor and disabled -- few cared when these laws were enacted.</P>
<P>But it is important for us all to understand that what Congress and the
President did to our society's most vulnerable can be done to the rest of us. 
If the right to challenge constitutional violations can be removed from anyone,
it can be removed from everyone.</P>
<P>As Judge Learned Hand, one of the leading American judges of the 20th
Century, known for his judicial restraint, once said: &quot;Liberty lies in the
hearts of men and women.  When it dies there, no Constitution, no law, no court
can save it.&quot;</P>
<P>Nelson Mandela kept liberty in his heart when he was confined on Robbins
Island by a repressive government regime, and he kept it in his heart when the
judiciary of his own democratic government acquitted some of his oppressors.</P>
<P>These two countries, the United States and South Africa, today share common
ideals of a democratic nation founded on principles of justice for all.  But as
one nation comes into being, the other seems to be allowing serious erosions in
one of democracy's most important features -- access to independent courts.</P>
<P><A HREF="vision13.html">Previous installment of Visions of Liberty</A></P>
<P><A HREF="visionid.html">Visions of Liberty Column Index</A></P>
