<HEAD>
   <TITLE>10/13/96: Visions of Liberty, #13</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0Gold (Macintosh; I; PPC)">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif"  ALIGN=BOTTOM> </P>

<P><I>by Ira Glasser, ACLU Executive Director</I></P>

<P>October 13, 1996</P>

<H3>ENDING DEMOCRACY AS WE KNEW IT: A RADICAL PROPOSAL FROM CLINTON AND
DOLE</H3>

<P>The current presidential and vice presidential debates, and the exclusion
of Ross Perot and his vice presidential candidate from those debates, brings
other campaigns to mind, and sets me to wondering what is becoming of our
democracy.</P>

<P>In 1968, the two leading candidates for president were Richard Nixon
and Hubert Humphrey. But there was a third candidate that year named George
Wallace, who charged that there wasn't &quot;a dime's worth of difference&quot;
between Nixon and Humphrey. He may or may not have been right, but millions
of Americans agreed with him. Wallace, a longtime governor of Alabama and
a major political figure, wanted the chance to convince other Americans.
After all, isn't that what elections in a democracy are all about?</P>

<P>Not everyone thought so. When Wallace came to New York City and tried
to rent Shea Stadium for a political rally, Mayor John Lindsay barred him
from doing so, because his views were not shared by most New Yorkers. The
First Amendment guaranteed Wallace the right to speak, but Mayor Lindsay
arranged things so that not many would hear him.</P>

<P>The New York Civil Liberties Union thought that was unconstitutional,
and sued in Wallace's behalf. We won, and Wallace got to speak in Shea
Stadium. He got a lot of votes that year, including some in New York, but
he didn't persuade enough people and finished a poor third in the election.</P>

<P>Still, his ideas received a wide hearing, which is one of the purposes
of an election in a democracy. Elections are not only a vehicle for choosing
our temporary leaders; they are also an important vehicle for conducting
great public debates about policies and practices that affect our lives.
Although such debates take place at all times, it is during election periods
that those debates are most focused and when citizens pay the most attention.</P>

<P>Often, ideas voiced by candidates who don't initially attract enough
adherents are able to triumph in subsequent elections. That is why it is
important to allow many views to compete during an election campaign and
not limit the debate to those views that happen to be dominant at the time.
In Wallace's case, his views eventually formed the basis of Nixon's famous
Southern Strategy, which transformed politics in this country by delivering
the South to the Republicans, something thought to be impossible 30 years
ago.</P>

<P>In similar fashion, the many unsuccessful presidential campaigns of
the Socialist Norman Thomas gave voice to many programmatic ideas that
found their way into the New Deal programs of Franklin Delano Roosevelt
and, in some cases -- social security, for instance -- into the unalterable
fabric of American life.</P>

<P>And in 1948, the arguments of four candidates -- Harry Truman, Thomas
E. Dewey, Henry Wallace and Strom Thurmond -- foreshadowed major developments
in today's political landscape even though neither Wallace nor Thurmond
stood much chance of winning at the time.</P>

<P>Below the presidential level, the rise of the Conservative Party about
a quarter-century ago and its willingness to run candidates to the right
of the Republican Party attracted enough adherents over time to transform
the Republican Party into its conservative image, even though Conservative
Party candidates virtually never won elections.</P>

<P>All of this comes to mind when I consider the implications of excluding
Ross Perot from the presidential debates. Mr. Perot has the right to speak,
and the money to buy microphones. But the two major candidates and their
political parties, aided and abetted by the Federal Election Commission
and the Internal Revenue Service, have conspired to keep Perot away from
his most relevant audience. Perot, like third-party candidates before him,
thinks there isn't that much difference between Clinton and Dole. On many
issues, he is right.</P>

<P>Clinton and Dole have much the same policy on drugs -- not a dime's
worth of difference there. And they represent much the same policy on crime
control, the death penalty, immigration policy, welfare policy and foreign
policy. I am not suggesting that despite these essential similarities,
there are not good reasons to choose one candidate over the other. (Abortion
rights and tax policy provide two examples where there are sharp differences,
for example). But I am suggesting that these two candidates essentially
agree on many important issues and that elections ought to provide the
opportunity for alternative ideas to surface and be discussed.</P>

<P>If alternative ideas are not given a fair opportunity to compete, how
can citizens make up their minds and determine for themselves what policies
are in their best interests?</P>

<P>Now I do not know if Ross Perot has anything different to offer on these
important issues. But that, of course, is the point. </P>

<P>Yes, the two leading candidates are free to decide that they want to
debate each other without the discomfort of confronting other viewpoints.
They have a right to do that. But they don't have a right to do it with
public funds or with the active complicity of government agencies. And
that is exactly what has happened.</P>

<P>Under our campaign finance laws, corporations are forbidden from making
financial contributions to federal campaigns. But the Federal Election
Commission -- a government agency -- has granted an exemption from this
prohibition and allowed electoral debates to be financed by tax- exempt
not-for-profit organizations that conduct debates in a nonpartisan manner.</P>

<P>So the Democrats and Republicans got together and created such a not-for-profit
corporation called the Commission on Presidential Debates. They applied
to the Internal Revenue Service for a tax-exemption, claiming to be a nonpartisan
voter education organization, and the IRS granted it. Then, bypassing the
normal ban on corporate contributions to federal election campaigns, they
successfully solicited corporate contributions to finance the debates.
Moreover, these corporate contributions were now tax-deductible, which
meant that all American citizens helped pay for them. </P>

<P>The key rationale for this end run around the campaign finance law is
that the Commission on Presidential Debates is nonpartisan. But it isn't.
It's bipartisan. Nonpartisan means the absence of any favoritism to any
candidate. Bipartisan means favoritism to two candidates at the expense
of all others. This distinction -- an important one -- is the basis of
Perot's lawsuit against the Commission on Presidential Debates.</P>

<P>The basis on which the Commission has excluded Perot is a dangerous
one. It would be legitimate, in my view, for the Commission to say that
only bona fide candidates will be included in the debate. Who is a bona
fide candidate would be determined by reasonable, objective criteria. For
example, only candidates who have satisfied the ballot requirements in
all 50 states would be included. This would eliminate truly fringe candidates
and require that the price of admission was a viable candidacy nationwide.
But that is not what the Commission has done. If that criterion were used,
then Perot would have been included and the Commission would have been
operating in the nonpartisan way it said it would when it applied to the
IRS.</P>

<P>Instead, the Commission excluded Perot on the ground that he had no
reasonable chance to win. This is a curious criterion in a democracy. It
means that people with different ideas that have not yet gained wide support
will be denied the opportunity to gain that support by being denied access
to the relevant audience. Applied years ago, it would have excluded all
minor-party candidates and robbed America of many policies they first voiced
and which only later gained wide acceptance. In fact, the two leading candidates
have conspired to rig the debate in order to insure their dominance and
have falsely claimed to be nonpartisan in order to gain access to money
to which they are not by law entitled.</P>

<P>Utilizing the same criterion applied to Perot -- the polls show he can't
win so let's not allow Americans to listen to him -- we might as well exclude
Dole too. After all, the polls show he can't win either. Should Clinton,
therefore, be allowed to exclude Dole and speak alone? Similarly, should
Lyndon Johnson have been allowed to exclude Barry Goldwater? Could Richard
Nixon have excluded George McGovern? Could Ronald Reagan have excluded
Walter Mondale? Why bother with debate when the polls have settled the
issue?</P>

<P>This, of course, is the opposite of democracy. Americans would in fact
be outraged if government agencies gave favored status to only one leading
candidate. We would say we were becoming a one-party state. We should be
equally upset at the prospect of becoming a two-party state, where only
those who currently wield power are allowed to speak broadly.</P>

<P>There is more at stake here than who wins the next election.</P>

<P><A HREF="/library/visionid.html">Visions of Liberty Column Index</A></P>

