<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>09/22/96: Visions of Liberty, #12</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>by Ira Glasser, Executive Director, American Civil Liberties Union</I>
</P>
<P>September 22, 1996</P>
<H2>A Tale of Two Centuries</H2>
<P>A few months ago, a Republican-dominated Congress combined with a Democratic
president to fulfill a 1992 campaign promise &quot;to end welfare as we know it.&quot;
 The opponents of this legislation bitterly attacked it.  Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, a nationally-recognized expert on social welfare policy, denounced the
new law in especially strong terms:  &quot;...we are doing mad things.  The
premise of this legislation is that the behavior of certain adults can be
changed by making the lives of their children as wretched as possible....  We
are putting those children at risk with absolutely no evidence that this radical
idea has even the slightest chance of success.&quot;</P>
<P>But those who supported the law claimed that it would help poor people. 
Poor people, they argued, had been weakened by the habits of dependency, had
lost their incentive to work and had become uncompetitive in  the labor market. 
The welfare system itself, it was argued, had become a cause of poverty.  Remove
the crutches of public support and the lame will learn how to walk again.  They
will regain the incentive to work, restore their own vitality and with it the
nation's economic strength.  </P>
<P>Those who opposed this legislation were all for the idea that most welfare
recipients who are able to work would be better off if they had decent jobs. 
But they do not believe that enough decent jobs exist.  They point out that
large economic changes have occurred that have basically created surplus labor
that the American economy no longer needs.  (Moreover, even to the extent that
such jobs are available, women with dependent children would require both job
training and child care in order to be able to take available jobs; however,
neither job training nor child care is provided by the new law.)  </P>
<P>New technological developments have created growing needs for highly
skilled, highly educated workers.  At the same time, the sharp decline of
manufacturing jobs has reduced the need for workers with less education and few
skills.  This trend has been accelerated by the expansion of a global economy
across national borders, as manufacturers increasingly seek lower labor costs by
shifting their plants to underdeveloped countries.  Thus, for example, the boom
in expensive sneakers has been fueled by American manufacturers shifting their
operations to underdeveloped Asian economies where they can increase their
profit margins by utilizing workers who can be paid a fraction of what it would
cost to pay American workers.</P>
<P>These trends have created huge wage disparities in America between highly
educated and less educated Americans.  In 1979, for example, young white males
with at least a college education earned, on the average, 30 percent more than
young, white males with only a high school education.  By 1989, that gap had
dramatically widened to 79 percent, while the cost of housing, education and
medical care soared.  The result has been a steep decline in the standard of
living for many less educated Americans because the American economy no longer
has a need for what they are qualified to do.</P>
<P>Even for those families who have managed to keep up, they have done so only
because of the combined wages of husband and wife.  A dominant economic reality
today is that for many families two wage earners are now required to earn what
not too long ago one could earn, in terms of purchasing power.</P>
<P>Few Americans blame themselves for these changes in the American economy. 
They know something has gone wrong, and they know it isn't their fault:  they
are working as hard as they can, but seem to be falling further and further
behind.  And for the first time since the end of World War II, public opinion
polls a couple of years ago showed that a majority of Americans had become
pessimistic and believed that their children would be worse off economically
than their parents.</P>
<P>Welfare recipients suffer even more from these structural economic changes. 
They generally are the least educated and have the fewest skills.  The evidence
shows pretty clearly that even for those welfare recipients who are able to work
-- and most are children and the women who care for them -- the jobs they are
qualified to do are few and declining, and not very well paid.  </P>
<P>So how will cutting off welfare for such people help?  Without assuring that
there are enough decent jobs actually available, cutting off welfare will do
little except increase misery and attendant social pathologies.  That's why
Senator Moynihan denounced the welfare bill in such strong terms.</P>
<P>Moynihan is an established scholar in the field and he knows that something
very much like what we are experiencing now happened in England two centuries
ago, at the dawn of industrialization.  </P>
<P>During most of the 18th century, nearly all English citizens were
agricultural workers dependent on wages.  But there was also a welfare system. 
People were entitled to relief if they were temporarily unemployed, or if they
were old, disabled, infirm or orphaned.</P>

<P>Although like the modern American welfare system, the English system was
often inadequate, it kept the economic and social life of rural villages fairly
stable and intact.  But toward the end of the 18th century, in the years just
before the beginning of Queen Victoria's long reign, something began to happen
that shattered the stability of this system.  Poverty -- what they then called
pauperism -- began to rise steeply.  Moreover, much of it seemed to be
permanent, that is, a surplus of labor for which the market had no need became a
permanent feature of the economic landscape.  Ironically, this was accompanied
by a national rise in trade, what today we might call economic growth.  So while
the economy was growing as a whole, a large portion of the population was
excluded from that growth.  These developments were unprecedented, and due to
major changes in the political economy - including the dawn of the industrial
age -- that few could see or understand at the time.</P>
<P>The traditional English relief system began to crack under pressures it was
not designed to absorb.  As unemployment increased and became more permanent,
poverty became very expensive to relieve.  Not understanding the macro-economic
forces that were causing these dislocations, they began to attribute the problem
-- as we have today -- to the welfare system itself.  Local governments were
given increased responsibility to find work for the able-bodied, but then as now
there was little work to be found for those whose skills and labor the market no
longer required.  </P>
<P>At first, the cost of welfare went up, but then the cost became politically
unbearable, and subsistence subsidies were cut.  Between 1815 and 1834, poor law
expenditures decreased precipitously -- about 30 percent per capita and 50
percent as a percentage of national income.  The minimum level of subsistence --
not generous to begin with in 1795 -- declined to levels that assured misery.</P>
<P>The industrialization of rural England brought further economic
dislocations.  The power loom replaced handweaving and forever changed the
economy of English villages.  Manufacturing shifted to large-scale factories,
leaving entire cottage industries permanently destroyed, and the people who had
earned a living from them permanently unemployed.  A relief system intended
temporarily to help the unlucky working poor become transformed into a system
that permanently maintained the dependency of those whom the economy no longer
needed.  Demoralization among the poor became widespread, and the poor
themselves became a social problem.  Then, as now, some people began to imagine

that relief programs themselves were  the problem, and that if they were ended,
the poor would raise themselves up.  </P>
<P>At the turn of the 19th century, Thomas Malthus, the most blunt opponent of
government support for the poor, argued that the only way to solve the problem
of the dependent poor was to abolish government relief programs.  Malthus
opposed public relief programs because he believed, like some in Congress today,
they did no good and merely debilitated those they intended to help.  His
solution was to abolish such support entirely.  If all relief were denied,
Malthus argued, nature would take its course.  Some perhaps would die, but those
who survived would be stronger; they would learn virtue; independence,
self-reliance, sexual restraint, what some today are calling Victorian morals.</P>
<P>As it turned out, an undiluted dose of Malthusian medicine proved too harsh
then, as it has now.  But Malthus created the framework for debate, and set the
stage for other unbelievably harsh proposals, which seemed reasonable by
comparison.  Thus did a shift occur, as it has today, toward public immorality,
the capacity of decent, personally virtuous citizens who believe themselves to
be concerned about others to support policies that are incredibly cruel,
coercive, callous and shameful, all the while using the language of personal
morality and private virtue.</P>
<P>Malthus was followed by Jeremy Bentham, who opposed the complete abolition
of relief.  He was, perhaps, the first advocate of workfare in a world that no
longer seemed able to provide real jobs.  He proposed to build 500 large
workhouses, systematically distributed so that no one would be far from one. 
People would be assigned geographically; infants would be branded at birth to
assure proper assignment.  Everyone would work, even the blind. Child labor was
an integral part of his plan.  </P>
<P>Bentham's master plan was also eventually rejected by Parliament, but like
Malthus' proposal, it moved the center of debate and rendered acceptable what
might otherwise have been seen as unacceptable.  Bentham's central idea
survived:  relief should be available but the conditions of relief should be
made so horrible, so humiliating, so punitive, so harsh that no one short of
starvation would choose to be a recipient.  In 1834, the new Poor Law was
passed, essentially reflecting this idea.</P>
<P>There would be no entitlement to relief.  Support would be provided only in
exchange for work.  But since no real jobs were available to the poor (that,
after all, was the problem), workhouses would be established and people who
chose public support would have to enter the workhouse, a place deliberately
designed to impose shame and stigma.  </P>
<P>As many have pointed out, no English legislation was ever so hated.  Those
who had no choice but to enter the world of the workhouse were in effect

banished form civil society and forced to exchange all dignity and independence
for the means of support.  Those who refused such a bargain and chose to be
independent, were forced to make their way in a world that had no use for them. 
Where once they had been degraded by their dependency on public support, now
they were degraded even more by the illusion of independence.  They were forced
to be responsible for themselves at a moment in time when for them that was not
possible.</P>
<P>Independence and social abandonment in a political economy that could not
absorb their surplus labor and had less and less need for their skills resulted
not in any moral uplifting or fresh incentive to work but rather in severe
suffering, misery and degradation -- not only of the able-bodied adult worker,
but also and depravedly of children, old people and the disabled.  This is the
world chronicled in Charles Dickens' novels.</P>
<P>Are there lessons in all this for America in 1996?  It has, of course,
become fashionable lately to celebrate Victorian values, to applaud the English
Poor Law that, as Gertrude Himmelfarb has written, &quot;would promote the moral
as well as the material well-being of the recipients of relief by providing
incentives to go off relief rather than remain on, and by encouraging those
virtues of self-reliance, self-respect and self-discipline that would transform
paupers into self-supporting workers.&quot;  What Himmelfarb doesn't tell us is
what exactly those incentives to avoid relief were, and what misery they
produced.  Nor does she tell us that they were spectacularly unsuccessful in
transforming paupers into self-supporting workers because the fundamental
problem was not a lack of individual virtue or self- respect or self-reliance
but rather an epic change in the political economy that made adequate wage-based
support virtually impossible for large numbers of people.</P>
<P>Eventually, pauperism in England declined.  But it was not because paupers
became, as individuals, more virtuous.  It was because economic expansion raised
real wages by 50 percent between 1850 and 1885, and by another 40 percent
between 1885 and 1900.  Poverty was reduced by the same thing that had expanded
it: large economic forces.  What transformed paupers into self- supporting
workers was not institutionalized cruelty, Malthusian jungle economics or moral
lectures from Queen Victoria.  What reduced poverty was the greater availability
of real jobs at decent wages.  </P>
<P>The problem of poverty during a time of economic dislocation and transition
is what to do in the meantime, and how to help those who are left out.  This
cannot be accomplished through moral exhortations from people who do not need to
worry about paying their rent, and it is despicable -- yes, shameful, to use a
good Victorian word -- to repeat the failed experiment of designed cruelty as an

incentive to force people into a labor market that has no use for them.</P>
<P>The problem we face today is not &quot;welfare&quot; nor the immorality of
individuals who are poor and unemployed.  The problem we face is the political
economy, now as in 1834.  The notion that we can save those left out of the
economy by abandoning them is truly perverse.  It is also immoral, for those who
care about values.</P>
<P><A HREF="/library/visionid.html">Visions of Liberty Index</A></P>
<P></P>
