<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>09/15/96: Visions of Liberty, #11</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/vision.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P><I>Guest Columnist, Loren Siegel, ACLU Public Education Director</I>
</P>
<P>September 15, 1996
</P>
<H2>Reflections on Lethal Injection</H2>
<P>There is a new occupation in New York State for which the faint of heart
need not apply.  It's called &quot;execution technician.&quot;  This is the
person who will mix and administer the toxic combination of drugs necessary to
carry out execution by lethal injection.  The position is still vacant, since
New York State only reinstated capital punishment last year and its death row is
still untenanted.  But eventually, unless the state's highest court declares the
statute unconstitutional, someone is going to have to fill those shoes.</P>
<P>Since January 1996, 30 human beings have been executed in this country, 26
of them by lethal injection.  At this rate, 1996 will be the peak year for
executions since 1976, when the Supreme Court's decision in <I>Gregg v. Georgia</I>
reinstated the death penalty after a four year hiatus.  It's almost as though
the availability of this no-fuss, no-mess method of extermination is driving the
dramatic escalation in the number of people put to death.  In 1982 there were
only 2 executions nationwide.  By 1993, there were 38.  And by 1995, the number
had spiked to 56.</P>
<P>Lethal injection has become the method of choice for executioner states 
because it  is perceived as a painless, hygienic medical procedure.  No more
contorted limbs, popped out eyeballs or scorched flesh from an excess of
electric current  (n.b. that electrocution was believed to be far more humane
than hanging when it was introduced in 1890).  As one of its first proponents
once put it, &quot;Being a former farmer and horse raiser, I know what it's like
to try to eliminate an injured horse by shooting him.  Now you call the
veterinarian and the vet gives it a shot and the horse goes to sleep -- that's
it.&quot;  (Gov. Ronald Reagan, 1973).</P>
<P>But is that really &quot;it&quot;?  Of course no one has lived to tell the
tale, but lethal injection, while much kinder to the onlookers, is clearly not a
painless experience for the person to whom it is being administered.  In fact,
electrocution is much faster and less painful than lethal injection, and
beheading is less painful still.  So, if we were really concerned about the
condemned person's comfort level, we would be bringing back the guillotine.</P>
<P>Here's how lethal injection works.  First you are strapped down on a gurney,
arms extended and wrists bound in place.  Then the execution technician (who
cannot be a doctor or a nurse because the AMA's Code of Ethics forbids medical
professionals from participating in executions) inserts the intravenous line
into your arm (but only after swabbing the arm with alcohol -- to prevent
infection...)  Sometimes the needle is inserted only after lengthy and painful
probing to find a viable vein.  Then sodium pentothal is injected to render you
unconscious.  Then pancuronium bromide and potassium chloride are introduced
into your vein, the first to paralyze your diaphragm and stop your breathing,
and the second to cause your heart to stop beating.</P>
<P>Sometimes things go wrong.  In Texas, there have been a number of botched
executions since lethal injection was introduced.  In one, it took 24 minutes to
kill a man, after the tube attached to the needle in his arm leaked and sprayed
toxic chemicals in the direction of witnesses.  In another, the initial dose of
chemicals was too weak, causing the &quot;patient&quot; to choke and heave for
several minutes before death came.</P>
<P>Why am I going into such gruesome detail?  Because there are more than 3,000
human beings on death row today, and if we are going to condemn most of them to
death by lethal injection, we ought to at least know what it is we are
perpetrating.  Also because I, like Justice Thurgood Marshall, have enough faith
in the American people to believe, as he did, that &quot;fully informed of the
purposes of the death penalty and its liabilities&quot; they will &quot;reject
it as morally unacceptable.&quot;</P>
<P>Obviously, we abolitionists have an uphill struggle ahead of  us.  Support
for capital punishment has never been stronger.  According to a 1995 Gallup
poll, 77% of Americans favor the death penalty for murder, and only 13% oppose
it (the rest are undecided).   This is in spite of the fact that the public
knows, or should know, that the death penalty is not a deterrent, that it is
applied disproportionately to poor people, that it is applied in a racially
discriminatory way, and that sometimes innocent people are mistakenly executed. 
These facts have been reported in the media many many times. </P>
<P>So, what do Americans need in order to be, in the words of Justice Marshall,
&quot;fully informed&quot; about the death penalty?   Perhaps they need to see
the consequences of their support.  Forty years ago Albert Camus, the French
writer, philosopher and abolitionist, published his essay<I> Reflections on the
Guillotine.</I>  In it, he argued passionately that executions ought to be made
public:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;[Society] must show the executioner's hands each time and force
everyone to look at them -- the over-delicate citizens and all those who had any
responsibility in bringing the executioner into being.  Otherwise, society
admits that it kills without knowing what it is saying or doing.&quot;  </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>What would happen if instead of being performed in secrecy, every single
execution were televised live during prime time, including the botched up ones? 
  Would support for the death penalty  drop off?  You bet it would.  If people
found the sanitized Hollywood version of lethal injection shown in <I>Dead Man
Walking</I> distressing, they will find a real live execution absolutely gut
wrenching.  And maybe that's what it will take. </P>
<P><A HREF="/library/visionid.html">Visions of Liberty Index</A></P>
<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A></CENTER>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER"><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union<BR>Photo
by Bob Adelman</I></H6></BLOCKQUOTE></BODY></HTML>
