<DOCHDR>
http://www.aclu.org:80/library/resource3.html 204.243.96.55 19970213114519 text/html 14346
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 11:44:08 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:52:24 GMT
Content-length: 14158
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>
Internet Research Tools</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<blockquote>

<IMG SRC="/graphics/libraryhdr.gif"><P><P>
<P>
<DL>
<font color="#0000FF"><center><h1>Internet Research Tools</h1></center>
</font><P><P>
A number of sites have been created to help Internet users take advantage of 
resources unique to the on-line world.  Some sites, ranging from listings of available 
electronic versions of books and magazines to information on newsgroups, 
attempt to index and explain the sometimes confusing array of Internet resources by focusing on one particular type of resource.
<P>
Other resources attempt to catalog as many Internet sites as possible, irregardless of subject matter.  Known as 'search engines,' these resources vary in their thoroughness of coverage, speed of query return, and detail of results. 
<P>
 Below, the ACLU has attempted to make sense of the rapidly growing array of Internet research tools.  If you know of a particularly helpful resource that you think should be included in this listing, be sure to use our <a href="http://www.aclu.org/feedback.html">feedback form</a> to let us know.
<P>
<center></blockquote></dl><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="100%"></cente

<DL><blockquote><P>
<font color="#0000FF"><h2>Internet Search Engines</h2></center></font>
</font><P><P>
<hr>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/search.html">Yahoo</A>
<P>
<DD>
Stanford students David Filo and Jerry Yang's Yet Another

Hierarchical Officious Oracle search engine has grown into the

most popular source for quick, topic-oriented searching. Its hierarchical

organization (basically a huge collection of subject-organized

links) makes it easy to discover related resources, while the

fact that a human being categorizes each new entry cuts down on

the number of irrelevent retrievals. 

<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</A>
<P>
<DD>
Containing over 5 million web pages, this robot-generated

search utility ranks each document returned, showing the search

term in context. Its popularity means that it is sometimes hard

to get into.
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.altavista.digital.com/">Alta Vista</A>
<P>
<DD>
Alta Vista is a creation of  Digital Equipment Corporation and hit the web in December 1995.

This search engine gives access to all 8 billion words found in over 16 million Web pages.

It also has a  full-text index of over 13,000 news groups updated in real-time. 
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.cs.washington.edu/research/projects/ai/metacrawler/www/">MetaCrawler Searching</A>
<P>
<DD>
This collection of search utilities allows the user to search

five of the more popular search engines at once. It is faster

than most other meta-engines, but does not allow the user to choose

which specific engines to search. 
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.opentext.com:8080/omw.html">Open Text</A>
<p>
<DD>
An extremely sophisticated commercial search engine that is

currently free, Open Text searches the contents of web pages.

It allows users the option of viewing search terms in context,

and following up an especially good match by looking for similar

pages.
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www2.infoseek.com/">Infoseek</A>
<P>
<DD>
Billing itself as "the most powerful and popular" way to search the Web, this fre section of Infoseek's site sometimes takes quite a while to load.  For a fee, you can search newsgroups, newswires, and more.
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.intbc.com/sleuth/">The Internet Sleuth</a>
<P>
<DD>
This site allows users to search over 650 databases in categories such as computers, 
social sciences, government, and news.  Its creators have also standardized each
databases' search forms, making it easy to search a variety of databases quickly.
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.mckinley.com/">Magellan</A>
<P>
<DD>
This  search engine ranks many of the 
sites it stores with a four-star system, and attempts to assess the material available on each site.    
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<a href="http://inktomi.berkeley.edu/">Inktomi</a>
<P><DD>
Claiming to be the largest and fastest database, this search engine 
with the funny name rarely returns a busy message.
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.cs.colostate.edu/~dreiling/smartform.html">SavvySearch</A>
<P>
<DD>
Another meta-engine, this one allows users to choose the number

(but not the name) of search engines to query, and the type of information

to return. However, only the hyperlinked title is displayed.

<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.albany.net/~wcross/all1srch.html">All in One</A>
<P>
<DD>
Over one-hundred form-based search engines have been collected

into this mega-search engine. Categories include: World Wide Web,

Software, People News/Weather, Publications/Literature, Desk References,

and Other Interesting Searches/Services.
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html">WWWW</A>
<P>
<DD>
The World Wide Web Worm is a robot that searches citation

hypertext, citation addresses (URL), HTML titles, and HTML addresses.
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.einet.net/">EINet Galaxy</A>
<P>
<DD>
Derived from the content of Galaxy pages, this full-text index

mainly covers the Web and specially-designated 'gopher jewels.'

<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://web.nexor.co.uk/public/aliweb/search/doc/form.html">ALIWEB</A>
<P>
<DD>
This unique engine searches descriptive forms filled out by

people who choose to register with ALIWEB.  Its database, therefore, is relatively small, but records tend to be more complete. 

<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.town.hall.org/Harvest/brokers/www-home-pages/query.html">Harvest Broker</A>
<P>
<DD>
Over 45,000 home pages are indexed by this broker, which

uses the WAISserver search engine. 
<P>
<DT>
<P>
<a name="gopher">
</blockquote><IMG SRC="/graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<blockquote>
<P>
<font color="#0000FF"><center><H2>Gopherspace</H2></center></font>
<DL>
<DT>
<P>

Gopher servers are text-based sites organized in outline form;

many are in the process of being replaced by web sites. However,

gopher sites often provide lengthy and unfilitered documents,

making them a good place to look for comprehensive information

on a topic.  The name is either: 1) a reference to the nickname

of the University of Minnesota, where the concept was first developed;

or 2) a variation on the slang term 'go-fer,' as in 'go for some

coffee.'
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<DT>
<br>
<P>
<A HREF="http://hoohoo.ncsa.uiuc.edu/archie.html">Archie</A>
<P>
<DD>
The Archie system searches a database of files available via

anonymous File Transfer Protocol (ftp). Search terms are not subject-oriented;

they are file name-oriented. Thus, a search for 'liberty' will

only pull up those sites with file names containing the word 'liberty'.

  This site contains a form-based interface that allows the user

to choose the number of hits returned, the type of search performed,

and the country-location of the server used. 

<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>
<A HREF="gopher://veronica.sunet.se:2347/7">Veronica</A>
<P>
<DD>
The Very Easy Rodent Oriented Net-wide Index to Computerized

Archives (Veronica) system searches keywords in gopher document

titles, allowing queries of approximately 5,000 gopher servers,

with about 3,000 World Wide Web servers and around 1,000 telnet

servers also covered.  The 

<A HREF="gopher://gopher.scs.unr.edu/11/veronica">University of Nevada at Reno</A>

provides an index of Veronica servers.  Unfortunately, servers are often busy and 

therefore unavailable.
<P>
<DT>
<center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif" width="50%"></center>
<P>

<A HREF="gopher://gopher.utah.edu:3000/7">Jughead</A></H2>
<P>
<DD>
The jughead system (Jonzy's Universal Gopher Hierarchy Excavation

And Display) is closely related to Veronica; however, it performs

a more comprehensive search of only the information that is on

one particular gopher site.  A list of jughead servers is available

at the <A HREF="gopher://gopher.utah.edu:70/11/Other%20Gophers">University of Utah</A>.
<P>
</DL>


</blockquote><IMG SRC="/graphics/redline.gif" width="100%">
<P>
<font color="#0000FF"><center><h2>Specific Internet Resources</h2></center></font>
<P>
<blockquote>
<hr>
<A HREF="gopher://gopher.lib.ncsu.edu:3001/7" >Alex</A>
<DD>
A search engine for electronic versions of books and other textual material.
<P>
<DT>
<A HREF="http://www.columbia.edu/~svl2/bartlett/">Bartlett's Familiar Quotations</A><DD>This section of Columbia University's Project Bartelby allows for key-word queries of the famous text. <P><DT><A HREF="http://jg.cso.uiuc.edu/PG/">Project Gutenberg</A>
<DD>
A major effort to create on-line versions of classic books.
<P>
<DT>
<A HREF="http://ipl.sils.umich.edu/">IPL The Internet Public Library</A>
<DD>
The University of Michigan's project recreating the look and feel of a 
library, including an on-line librarian.
<P>
<DT>
<A HREF="http://www.cis.ohio-state.edu/hypertext/faq/usenet/" >List of USENET FAQs</A>
<DD>
Ohio State's searchable collection of Frequently Asked Questions, drawn from 
thousands of newsgroups.
<P>
<DT>
<A HREF="http://scwww.ucs.indiana.edu/mlarchive/>Search for Mailing Lists</a>
<DD>
Indiana University's database of close to 13,000 mailing lists, searchable by key word. 


<P>
<DT>
<A HREF="http://www.gallup.com/index.html">Gallup Poll</A>
<DD>
Access to the Gallup Organization's monthly newsletters, containing polls and
 anlysis.
<P>
<DT>
<A HREF="http://galaxy.einet.net/GJ/general-ref.html">General Reference Resources</A>
<DD>
Einet Galaxy's list of twenty-some reference volumes available on the Internet.
<P>
<DT>

<A HREF="telnet://library.ncsu.edu">NCSU Libraries Information System</a>
<DD>
There are a number of valuable resources available through this telnet site created 
by the Triangle Research Libraries Network (Duke, North Carolina State,  and the 
University of North Carolina.  Item #1 on the main menu allows for searches of 
the respective school library catalogs (options #1-3), and government documents(#4).  
<P>
Option #5, Other Library Catalogs, allows users access to a listing that is 
alphabetical by name (#1, Hytelnet) or by state (#2, LIBS).  Hytelnet is designed 
to help keep track of the libraries that are accessible via telnet.  It can also 
be used via its <a href="http://www.cc.ukans.edu/hytelnet_html/START.TXT.html">web site</a>.
Users choose commands and move the cursor around the screen by using the arrow keys.  Hitting 
return while on the Library catalogs line brings you to various menus where you can 
choose the geographic location of libraries to look for.  Once you decide on a particular
library to visit, Hytelnet gives you information on how to login and exit, then 
asks if you want to be connected.  Once you do, you leave Hytelnet and enter that 
particular library's on-line catalog system.  When you exit, you return directly to 
Hytelnet. 
<P>
 Aside from library catalog systems, Hytelnet also indexes some Other resources 
avalable via Telnet.  Subcategories include databases and bibliographies, distributed 
file servers (gopher/WAIS/WWW), and Fee-based Services.    
 
        

Choosing item #2 on the main menu, Journal Articles Indexes, and then option #1, UnCover, brings you (after a short wait and 
a screen where you identify the type of terminal you are using) to a menu presenting 
the CARL Corporation's "shopping list of databases."  This database is also available independently,
by telnetting to <A HREF="telnet://database.carl.org">telnet://database.carl.org</a>.   The Uncover database, option #1,
 indexes journals and their table of contents, adding citations on 
a daily basis.  The user-friendly interface allows you to search by key word, 

or specific journal title; for a fee, fax copies of articles can be obtained.  
<P>The 
Journal Graphics database, option #7, indexes television and radio transcripts and can be 
searched by key word or name.  Actual copies of the transcripts are available for 
a fee.  Also under option #7 is the British Library Document Supply Centre, which in 
addition to indexing 54,000 current journals also contains articles from 170,000 journals that 
have ceased publications; hard copies of articles are available for a fee.  Also 
under option #7 is the Federal Domestic Assistance Catalog.  Typing in key words pulls 
up extremely detailed information on over 1300 government programs that provide 
grants, loans, and technical assistance.  Full contact information is provided for 
each program.  Finally, under option #7 there is an interesting service named 
KnowledgeOne that promises, for a fee, to answer any question or request for information.
<P>
<P></DL>
</blockquote>
<p><center><IMG SRC="/graphics/redline.gif" width="100%"></center>
<br>
