<HEAD><TITLE>
ACLU Abolitionist (A NEWSLETTER ON THE NATIONWIDE STRUGGLE AGAINST THE DEATH PENALTY) - January 1996 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img src="/graphics/death.gif">
</center>
<P>
<blockquote>
<h2>HABEAS CORPUS AT RISK</h2>
<p>
Congress continues to threaten the Writ of Habeas Corpus.  
The Senate terrorism bill, passed in June by a vote of 91-8, 
included a provision that would make it virtually impossible 
for a federal court to correct a constitutionally erroneous state 
court decision.  It could do so only if the state court's decision 
was "unreasonably wrong."
<p>
The House proposal on terrorism originally did not contain a 
habeas corpus measure.  A later "compromise" version contains 
one  similar to that passed by the Senate.
<p>
The House leadership threatened to bring this new terrorism + 
habeas bill (HR 2768, "The "Effective Death Penalty and 
Antiterrorism Act of 1995") up for a vote just before the Christmas 
recess.  However, opposition to the inclusion of the habeas 
provisions, and problems on the part of conservative Republican 
freshmen denied the leadership the margin of votes needed to
bring the bill to the floor for a vote.  We are now told that the House 
leadership will seek a vote on this bill sometime in late January or 
early February. 
  <p>
The Congressional leadership machinations make it difficult to keep 
track of the content and numerical identification of this legislation.  
On December 19, a joint letter expressing opposition to HR 2703 
(the predecessor of HR 2768) was sent to House Speaker Gingrich 
and Minority Leader Gephardt by the ACLU, the Citizens Committee 
for the Right to Keep and Bear Arms, the Gun Owners of America, 
the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, the Second 
Amendment Foundation and Ross and Green.  
<p>
In part the letter stated "The Federal courts must remain open and 
able to review the legality of convictions and sentences to ensure
that when the government seeks the liberty or life of an individual, 
it acts within the law. ... [This measure] would prevent the federal 
courts from performing their essential function of assuring that 
convictions and sentences comport with the basic requirements 
 of the United States Constitution.  [It] would too greatly hamper 
 the federal courts in carrying out that function, among other things 
by requiring extraordinary deference to constitutionally erroneous 
state court decisions and imposing arbitrarily rigid time limits on 
the filing of habeas petitions for the first time in the nation's history."
<p>

A very useful article by Leslie Hagin, of the National Association of 
Criminal Defense Lawyers, discussing habeas "reform" legislation
appeared in the December 15, 1995 issue of Gun Week.  
<p>
Abolitionists and others opposed to the evisceration of federal 
habeas corpus relief must express their opposition to the inclusion
of limitations on habeas in the already draconian terrorism bill.  
They must urge Representatives not to give in to pressure to pass
a terrorism bill, especially one that includes habeas "reform."  
Details and arguments are discussed in the last two issues of The
ACLU Abolitionist.  Call Travia for a copy of the joint letter sent to 
House leaders, for ACLU's analysis of the Terrorism Act, or a copy 
of the Gun Week article.  You can also get these documents from 
ACLU's Constitution Hall on AOL. 
<p>
--- <i>Diann Rust Tierney</i>
<P><center><a href="abol196.html">Newsletter Index</a></center>
<p>
</blockquote>
<br>
