<HEAD><TITLE>
ACLU Abolitionist (A NEWSLETTER ON THE NATIONWIDE STRUGGLE AGAINST THE DEATH PENALTY) - January 1996 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img src="/graphics/death.gif">
</center>
<P>
<blockquote><h2>POST-CONVICTION DEFENDER ORGANIZATIONS </h2>
<P>
The almost-inevitable closing of the Post-Conviction Defender Organizations, 
formerly known as Death Penalty Resource Centers, has been delayed by 
the federal budget debate.  The legislation defunding the 20 PCDOs was 
part of the Commerce, Justice, State and Judiciary Appropriations bill which 
President Clinton vetoed December 19.     
<P>
In 20 states, Post Conviction Defense Organizations (PCDOs) conduct the 
appeals of indigent death-sentenced prisoners. PCDOs represent some 
defendants, train lawyers in the critically important and arcane details of 
providing effective appeals in capital cases, assist in finding expert 
consultants, and enable networking among advocates for appellants on 
death row.  
<P>
In fiscal year 1995 PCDOs received $19.8 million in federal funds.  As 
discussed above, the precise details regarding the date on which funding 
will end depends on current negotiations surrounding the budget and the 
appropriations bill funding the judiciary.  The Florida and Tennessee PCDOs 
have already closed their doors.  The future of the other 18 centers is 
uncertain.  It is expected that Congress will provide funds for a six month 
phase-out period.
<P>
--- <i>Hunter Labovitz</i>
<P><center><a href="abol196.html">Newsletter Index</a></center>
<p>
</blockquote>
<br>
