<HEAD><TITLE>
ACLU Abolitionist (A NEWSLETTER ON THE NATIONWIDE STRUGGLE AGAINST THE DEATH PENALTY) - January 1996 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img src="/graphics/death.gif">
</center>
<P>
<blockquote><h2> CONVERSATION WITH AN ABOLITIONIST</h2>
<p>
In the 1960's she was a philosopher, an activist in the fight for civil
rights and against the war in Viet Nam.  In the early 70's DENISE 
Le BOEUF settled in New Orleans were she got a chance to reflect, 
pursue other interests and to travel.
<p>
Work in civil rights had sensitized her to issues of criminal justice, and 
in time, feeling this was the most concrete way to help, she entered 
Tulane's School of Law.  There, she soon got a chance to test her resolve, 
for Tulane has an active law clinic:  Denise was a member of a team, led 
by the clinic's director, which defended two persons charged with homicide.
<p>
After graduation she clerked for a judge on the Louisiana Supreme Court -- 
and had to argue her very first capital appeal to that same bench!  Her 
first post-conviction case came in 1989, working with the Loyola Death 
Penalty Resource Center in New Orleans.  In 1992, she joined the 
Center's staff.  Denny also is a valuable member of the Advisory Board 
of the Capital Punishment Project.  
<p>
Based on her first-hand experiences with its victims, Denny is increasingly 
convinced that the death penalty machine is fueled by problems of poverty, 
race and civil rights, compounded by child abuse and the use of drugs.  
Many aspects of her work with death row inmates are gut-wrenching, 
but they are also uplifting, for the courage and moral fiber of many of her 
clients and their families are inspiring.  
<p>
"I'm very lucky to have a job that enables me to work for a cause I strongly 
believe in, and in the course of which I meet so many inspiring people" 
says Denny.  "The defense, even of those who committed a heinous 
crime is not a personal dilemma.  Many of my clients have done terrible 
things; most were so profoundly disabled by problems of mental health 
or family history that they cannot function in society.  But some overcame 
such a situation.  One of our clients, for instance, was a drug user who 
committed armed robbery (his co-defendant was the actual killer).  During 
13 years on Louisiana's death row he was a friend of almost all those
executed there during that time.  In the process he's become a fine human 
being."  But this surely is not the way to rehabilitate someone! 
<p>
Representation of a death row inmate is all-involving.  There's too much to 
do, with too little help, and uneven and undependable resources.  Denny's 
opponent, the State of Louisiana, has infinitely more resources - 
investigative, forensic, scientific and mental health experts, researchers, 
etc.  However, some help is available for the community of dedicated 
volunteers, e.g., experts willing to work at reduced rate, and fellow 
attorneys with whom to consult.  Many more volunteers are needed, 
she says, from paralegal, counselors, mitigation investigators, to people 
willing to do office work and raise funds. 
<p>
"The loss of funds for Resource Centers is a catastrophe for those on death 
row.  Many now have no lawyer - period!  Defense lawyers are trying to fill 
the gap as best they can.  Most states have some, but inadequate funding 
for direct appeals to state courts.  But for state post-conviction petitions,
lawyers representing death row inmates have to scramble for funds.  The 
struggle for funds, the lack of professional coordination, the loss of pooled
resources for expertise is incredibly wasteful.  It will end up significantly
increasing the costs and decreasing the efficiency of the death machine.  
<p>
How best to work for Abolition?  "My clients' inability to function in
society is almost always a result of child abuse.  Drug and alcohol 
abuse is common, it's an attempt to self-medicate their agony.  Often 
it's also a precipitating factor for the crime.  The root problem of child 
abuse is compounded by the drug use, and by the problems of our society, 
such as unemployment, violence, fear, racism, vengefulness, etc.  To a 
large extent these are compounded by the death penalty itself."
<p>
"We must improve our abolitionist message, and our way to put it across.  
We must address the sensible people in our society, those who care 
about fairness.  Somehow we must bypass the din of politicians with a 
vested interest in the death penalty.  Abolition is a civil and
constitutional rights issue, strongly tied to issues of poverty, prejudice 
and race.  The ACLU must treat it as such, and give it center stage."  
<P><center><a href="abol196.html">Newsletter Index</a></center>
<p>
</blockquote>
<br>
