<HEAD><TITLE>
ACLU Abolitionist (A NEWSLETTER ON THE NATIONWIDE STRUGGLE AGAINST THE DEATH PENALTY) - January 1996 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img src="/graphics/death.gif">
</center>
<P>
<blockquote>
<h2>THE DEATH PENALTY IN THE STATES</h2>
<p>
A search of the Congressional Quarterly data base, which tracks legislation 
in 50 states showed that 151 bills relating to the death penalty were 
submitted to state legislatures.  Seventeen were submitted in TN alone, 
13 in NY and 8 in IL.  In most instances duplicate bills were simultaneously 
submitted in both houses.  Bill duplication in the same chamber makes it 
obvious that some legislators are playing to the grandstands.  
<p>
The bills embody a variety of tactics to enlarge the reach of the death
penalty and speed executions.  Several affiliates informed us how the 
death penalty fared in their state: 
<p><blockquote>
<b>AR: </b> A bill that would require that death sentences be carried out by 
electrocution rather than lethal injection was withdrawn.  "Thank goodness 
the legislature only meets every other year!" says Rita Spellinger.
<p>
<b>CA: </b> According to Francisco Lobaco, The legislature provided that, in March 
1996, California voters will be asked to approve two capital punishment 
measures.  One applies the death penalty to murder in the course of a 
drive-by shooting, carjacking, or the killing of a juror.  In addition, death
penalty-related legislation introduced in the last session will again be 
considered in 1996.  They include death penalty sentencing for murder 
of a social worker or child abuse worker engaged in the performance of 
their duties; one setting time limits for appeals from a death sentence.  
"I expect to see many more death penalty related bills next year" says 
Francisco.   
<p>

<b>FL:</b>  An act was passed which defines a "career criminal" (someone 
convicted three times of certain crimes), and mandates various convictions, 
including the death penalty).  Death penalty-related bills (6 in the senate,
4 in the House) have been pre-filed for the 1996 session.  They would 
reform the Habeas Corpus petition process and add aggravating factors.  
Larry Helm Spalding says the Affiliate is monitoring and/or lobbying on 
these and related crime bills.  
<p>
<b>IL:</b>  Seven death penalty bills were filed (1 in the Senate, 6 in the House).
Mary Dixon  advises that all were sent to the Rules committees- 
presumably to resurrected in the next session.
<p>
<b>LA:</b>  A bill imposing the death penalty for rape of a victim under 12 became 
law in June.  A bill providing the time within which the state's supreme
court must decide a case where the death penalty has been imposed, and one 
providing the death penalty for rape of a victim over 65 will be on the next 
legislative calendar.
<p>
<b>MA:</b>  Abolitionists defeated yet another attempt to bring back the death 
penalty in MA.  The Affiliate was a pivotal part of the 20-member coalition 
that conducted a well-organized  grassroots and lobbying campaign.  
Norma Shapiro says the coalition found concerned allies, among 
religious organizations, lawyers (the Bar Association, the National 
Lawyers Guild), the MA criminal defense lawyers, sociologists, 
criminologists, Mds, etc.  
<p>
The MA coalition developed excellent lobbying materials, such as fact 
sheets based on conditions in Massachusetts, an excellent abolitionist 
booklet prepared by Chief Justice Hennessey (Retired), and made good 
use of a new poll by Northeastern University on the death penalty views 
of Massachusetts citizens.  The poll had found that few legislators or the 
public knew that the state has a provision for a sentence of life in prison 
without possibility of parole (LWOP).  [Call Travia for the above materials.]
<p>

The coalition's successful strategy principally targeted newly-elected 
legislators, and those who were uncommitted, and addressed the 
specific concerns of each.    
<p>
Norma notes that the abolitionist margin of victory dwindled from 16 
(last time) to 10.  Since 5 open seats will be filled this November, she is 
understandably cautious about claiming victory in advance on indubitable 
future attempts to revive the capital punishment statutes in Massachusetts.
<p>

<b>MN:</b>  The state abolished the death penalty in 1911; its last execution was 
in 1906.  The first week in December, the state Judiciary Committee held 
a hearing on a proposal to put the death penalty on the ballot in 1996. 
MN CLU's Kathleen Milner and other abolitionists helped plan the hearing.  
Former Mississippi prison warden Donald Cabana was among those who
testified in opposition to the death penalty.  Acording to a 1992 survey by 
the University of Minnesota, 70% of Minnesotans polled favor LWOP plus 
restitution of prison wages to a victim's family, to a sentence of death.  
<p>
During its 1995 session, the Minnesota House voted 96-37 against a crime 
bill amendment that would have reinstated the death penalty.  Recognizing 
that pro-death penalty forces are likely to try again, the abolitionist
coalition plans to work on a public education program aimed at raising 
opposition to the death penalty.  
<p>
<b>NY:</b>  The state's DP law took effect September 1. It applies to those
convicted of murdering a police officer, a prison guard or a judge, serial 
killing, murder committed with other felonies, like rape, and slaying by 
terrorists. The Act established a "Capital Defender Office" (CDO).  
Funded at $3.2 million this year, it conducts capital murder defenses in 
primary trials and state court appeals.  
<p>
By the end of October 31, 1995, the CDO had been notified of 102 murder 
cases that potentially qualify for the death sentence.  Of these, it has
taken on 8 cases; 7 were referred to outside lawyers.  The other 87 
accused may not face death:  the Bronx District Attorney appended notes 
to the 22 murder cases he referred to the CDO, stating he would not seek 
capital punishment because of his opposition thereto.  And in Manhattan, 
D.A. Morgenthau appointed a commission to help him make a decision on 
such a prosecution.  Thus, those who commit murder are death-eligible in 
one N.Y. county, not in another, starkly illustrating the capriciousness of 
death penalty yet again.
<p>
The N.Y. Times (12/14/95) reported that N.Y. Attorney General Dennis Vacco 
(who, at the time was in need of some good press) called for changing the 
law to render subject to execution someone caught with the raw materials 
for a nuclear bomb (ingredients yet to be determined!) -- a solution in
search of a problem?    
<p>
<b>TX:</b>  A bill mandating that a prosecutor must seek the death penalty for 
someone convicted of "an act of terror" passed the Senate unanimously, 
but did not pass the House, perhaps because it was submitted late in the 
session.  As did similar bills in several other states, the bill referred to
the Oklahoma City bombing.  According to Susan Maldonado, the TX 
legislature meets for 180 days every two years.  Thus the bill may be 
re-introduced in 1997.
</blockquote><P><center><a href="abol196.html">Newsletter Index</a></center>
<p>
</blockquote>
<br>
