<HEAD><TITLE>
ACLU Abolitionist (A NEWSLETTER ON THE NATIONWIDE STRUGGLE AGAINST THE DEATH PENALTY) - January 1996 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img src="/graphics/death.gif">
</center>
<P>
<blockquote><h2>PROJECT ACTIVITIES</h2>
<p>
    The Project receives many letters requesting information or help from 
Death Row inmates.  The increasing population of death row and the 
de-funding of the PCDOs has increased the number of such letters.  
Most concern legal representation, the legal system, or conditions of 
imprisonment.  Some come from prisoners; some are forwarded from 
other organizations.  This year we received and answered more than 200.  
Some are answered by the Project's Legal Fellow, Hunter Labovitz.  Most 
do not require a technical legal answer, and are answered by Bob Vandivier.  
<p>
The Project tries to respond in timely fashion to each letter, drawing on 
regional legal resources as indicated, and to tailor the response to the 
individual request.  While the Project cannot provide legal representation, 
it often is able to learn enough through local inquiries to reassure the 
prisoner that his/her legal representation is doing what reasonably can 
be expected.  When the Project's inquiries suggest otherwise, 
sometimes our inquiry stimulates attention on the part of local resources. 
<p>
Readers are encouraged to help us keep track:  Please let us know of 
changes in requests for legal assistance in your state.
Bob Vandivier
<p>
  RESTORATIVE JUSTICE:  During the past year the Project's Phyllis 
Turner laid the basis for a conference that will discuss how victim 
restoration may impact criminal sentencing.  Several polls show that the 
possibility of making restoration to a victim's family on the part of a 
defendant decreases support for capital punishment.  In the long term 
this approach might enhance alternatives to death sentencing.  Despite 
Phyllis' departure (see below), ACLU will continue to participate in this 
project.  
<p>
     It is painful to announce that two colleagues are leaving the Project 
for greener fields!  Hunter Labovitz has accepted a position as staff 
attorney in Florida's Office of the Capital Collateral Representative (CCR).
<p>
This state-funded office provides direct representation in state and federal 
post-conviction proceedings to persons sentenced to death in Florida.  
We'll sorely miss Hunter's legal skills, his enthusiasm, his idealism, 
and his unflagging energy in the pursuit of civil rights in general, and 
abolitionist goals in particular.  We'll miss him, but our sense of loss is 
mitigated by the knowledge that his talents will be used to help the 
many Florida Death Row prisoners who so sorely need help.
<p>
Phyllis Turner has left us for a position with the National Organization for 
Victim Assistance.  Phyllis is a long-standing advocate of offender 
rehabilitation, and of victims' rights.  Her strong convictions, her 
enthusiasm, and her unexcelled networking abilities will be of great use 
to NOVA.  In her new position Phyllis will also continue her involvement 
with aspects of Restorative Justice relating to capital punishment.  We'll 
miss you, Phyllis!
<p>
There is good news as well:  Theresa Fuentas, a law student at George 
Washington University National Law Center has joined the Project as a 
part-time volunteer.  Before entering law school Theresa worked on civil 
liberties issues in New Jersey.  For us, Theresa will research and write 
on several issues relating to capital punishment.  
<P><center><a href="abol196.html">Newsletter Index</a></center>
<p>
</blockquote>
<br>
