 <HEAD><TITLE>
ACLU Abolitionist (A NEWSLETTER ON THE NATIONWIDE STRUGGLE AGAINST THE DEATH PENALTY) - January 1996 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img src="/graphics/death.gif">
</center>
<P>
<blockquote>
<h2>FACTS AND SOURCES</h2>
  <p>
     Dick Dieter has done it again!  His Death Penalty Information Center 
has published yet another wonderful report.  A 35-page report with 93 
references,  With Justice for Few; The Growing Crisis in Death Penalty 
Representation spells out the reasons for the assertion that "[f]ar too
often, people are given the death penalty not for committing the worst 
crimes, but for having the worst lawyers."  With the increasing use of the 
death penalty,reduced opportunities of appeals, and severely reduced 
support for PCDOs this problem is becoming ever more acute.  DPIC's 
Justice for Few report provides timely and valuable ammunition.
  <p>
     Crime and Justice Policy Preferences, reports on a survey of
legislators' attitudes conducted by students of the College of 
Justice of Northeastern University.  Conducted in part to inform 
legislators considering reinstatement of the death penalty in 
Massachusetts, the students analyzed the legislators' thinking about 
the purposes of criminal punishment and appropriate punishment for 
first degree murder, including capital punishment and its alternatives. 
These were compared with those of Massachusetts citizens  (a 
different report).   The 115 legislators who participated in the survey 
represent a 58% participation rate.  Almost all felt that the seriousness 
of the crime and the offender's prior record should determine the severity of
the punishment.   74% of citizens and 45% of the legislators favored the
death penalty (i.e., they accepted, but did not necessarily favor it).
Legislators, like citizens, prefer Life in Prison without Parole (LWOP) to 
the death penalty.  When restitution is added, their support for capital 
punishment drops further from 37% to 26% of legislators (and from 
38% to 23% of citizens).
  <p>
Policy Preferences is an excellent and useful analysis of well-researched 
material.  For a copy, please call Travia.
  <p>
     Circumstantial Evidence by Pete Earley; published by Bantam Books, 
N.Y.; 1995.  describes Walter McMillian's road to Alabama's death row -- 
and his ultimate vindication with the help of Bryan Stevenson and the 
Alabama Resource Center.  Largely by-passed by the civil rights 
struggles of the early 60's, Monroeville was the setting for Harper 
Lee's To Kill a Mockingbird, a fictional tale of
black-defendant-accused-of-murdering-female-white-teenager.
Mr. McMillian's ordeal bears an uncanny resemblance to the fictional tale.  
Monroeville is a town where whites see no race problem at all.  
African-Americans, facing racism every day, know better.  The racism that 
caused Mr. McMillian's conviction despite his innocence, was fueled by a 
vengeful erstwhile white lover, corrupt officials, who manufactured evidence 
and witness' statements, withheld evidence, and refused to give credence to 
the testimony of Mr. McMillian's friends and relatives who said he was at a 
party at his home at the time of the murder.  The racism is shown almost 
incidentally, but it's unmistakable.  Circumstantial Evidence is one of the
best books showing that racism fuels the machine of death, and the 
terrible possibility of killing the innocent.  Earley is an excellent writer;
this book reads like a murder mystery.  Each person is alive, and unique.  
Give it to acquaintances who need convincing that the death penalty must 
be abandoned.
  <p>
       The Death Penalty in the Nineties, An Examination of the Modern 
System of Capital Punishment, by Welsh S White, The University of 
ichigan Press, Ann Arbor, MI, 1987, 1991.  223 pp.  Provides an updated 
overview of the Supreme Court in the post-Furman era.  Many topics of 
importance to abolitionists are discussed.  Among these: miscarriage 
of justice; the continued racism; plea bargaining, the penalty phase of 
capital trials; defendants who elect execution; and the "death-qualified" 
jury.
  <p>
The author says the present system of capital punishment does not meet 
"reasonable standards of fairness," but presents information to enable 
readers to form their own judgment.
  <p>
An extensive critical review of this book was written by Deborah W. Denno 
(83 Crim. L. & Criminology 437 (Summer, 1992)).  After citing several more 
positive reviews, and stating that "White's scholarship and experience are 
unassailable," she provides a critique that includes an informative and 
provocative "fill in" and update.  For example, Ms. Denno expands on, and 
adds thoughtful analysis to White's treatment of the Supreme Court's 
"twisting" and reversal of the "death is different" doctrine. 
  <p>                                                                       
                                                        --- <i>Robert Vandivier</i>
<P><center><a href="abol196.html">Newsletter Index</a></center>
<p>
</blockquote>
<br>
