   <HEAD><TITLE>
ACLU Abolitionist (A NEWSLETTER ON THE NATIONWIDE STRUGGLE AGAINST THE DEATH PENALTY) - January 1996 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img src="/graphics/death.gif">
</center>
<P>
<blockquote>
  <h2>DEAD MAN WALKING</h2>
<P>
The movie, adapted from the book by abolitionist Sister Helen Prejean, 
has opened in Los Angeles and New York, and may be coming to a 
theater near you very soon.  The film's subject is likely to increase the 
public's focus on the death penalty, and thus provides an opportunity to 
do some public education on the need for abolition.  We've discussed 
how best to do this, and have developed some ideas:
<P>
       Arrange a pre- or post-movie discussion of the death penalty -- a
nearby library or restaurant might be the perfect spot.
<P>
      Arrange to have literature on the death penalty available for
distribution before and/or after the movie.  Live volunteers would probably 
be most effective, but even an "un-manned" literature table will do if need 
be.  
<P>
        When the movie is released on video, arrange for community showings 
and a discussion of the movie.  Have literature available, of course. 
<P>
      Review the movie for smaller, local or community papers and encourage 
people seeking more information to contact you or the Project.
<P>
      Comment on the movie in internet chat room conversations, alt. act. 
newsrooms, etc.  (We'll soon have something on ACLU's Constitution Hall 
on AOL).
<P>
We'd love to have some feedback from you to share with our readers in the 
next issue of the Abolitionist.  Let us know what you did,  and how it turned
out.  And of course, if you need materials, call Travia.  We have copies of
the briefing paper on the death penalty, the Double Justice video, and fact
sheets on innocence, and on general statistics.
<P><center><a href="abol196.html">Newsletter Index</a></center>
<p>
</blockquote>
<br>
