                        <H3>ACLU Cyber-Liberties Update</H3>
                        <H3>Wednesday, January 8, 1997 </H3>
					   
<HR>
<B>CONTENTS:</B> 
<UL>
<LI> <A HREF="#crypto">Encryption Decision Overturns Clinton Rules</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#sd">South Dakota Governor Blocks e-mail, ACLU Responds</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#cybersitter">CYBERsitter blocks Peacefire.org</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#fla">ACLU of Florida looks at Library Use of Blocking Software</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#oecd">OECD Expert Group Finalizes Cryptography Guidelines</A>
<LI><A HREF="#about"> Cyber-Liberties Update Information (Revised January 8, 1997)</A>
</UL>
<HR> 
<H3><A NAME="crypto">Encryption Decision Overturns Clinton Rules</A></H3>

<P>
	Adding what the Los Angeles Times called a "new twist to the battle over
government restrictions on data-scrambling technology," a federal judge has
ruled that government regulations barring the export of encryption software
are an unconstitutional violation of free speech.
</P>

<P>
	Ruling in favor of Daniel Bernstein, an Illinois math professor who attempted to publish his encryption codes on the Internet, U.S. District Judge Marilyn Hall Patel in San Francisco recently struck down the government regulations as a "paradigm of standardless discretion" that failed to protect First Amendment rights. 
</P>

<P>
	While saying it is still analyzing the Bernstein decision, the ACLU welcomed it as "extraordinarily important for its holding that computer source code is protected speech and for the Judge's willingness to look beyond the
government's claim that export controls were justified by 'national security.'"
</P>

<P>
	In its report on the decision, the Washington Post said that encryption software -- which allows people to turn their telephone conversations and data into virtually uncrackable code -- has been at the heart of one of the hardest-fought technology controversies for the Clinton administration. Despite protests from the computer industry, the government restricts its export on the grounds that it could aid criminals and terrorists.
</P>

<P>
	The government is likely to appeal the Bernstein decision to the Federal Court of Appeals and, if it does, the ACLU said that it would once again file a friend-of-the-court brief on Bernstein's behalf. The ACLU has already appeared as a friend-of-the-court in a parallel case, Karn v. US, which will be argued early next year in the Federal Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
</P>

<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="sd">South Dakota Governor Blocks E-Mail Petitions</A></H3>
</P>

<P>
	The American Civil Liberties Union is poised to take action against the state of South Dakota,  charging that it violated the U.S. Constitution when it blocked e-mail from an Internet Service Provider (ISP) whose customer was sending mass mailings.
</P>

<P>
	The controversy arose early in December when a Michigan woman found that the petitions she was e-mailing to officials in South Dakota were being bounced back to her.  The reason her petitions were blocked, said the press secretary for Governor Bill Janklow of South Dakota, was that they were protesting phantom legislation that had never been proposed.
</P>

<P>
	The woman, Linda LeMonde, is an American Indian activist who became alarmed about what she thought was a proposal to prohibit Native American ceremonies on state forest land in South Dakota and to limit the number of American Indians who could assemble at gatherings.  According to the Governor's office, no such legislation was under consideration.
</P>

<P>
	But when South Dakota blocked all e-mail coming from Technology Dimensions because a customer of the ISP was forwarding mass e-mail petitions to government employees, it violated the Constitution, ACLU attorney Ann Beeson told C/Net News.  
</P>

<P>
	"We believe that South Dakota's efforts to restrict e-mail access to government officials is a violation of the First Amendment and citizens' rights to petition their government," she said.
</P>

<P>
	In a December 18 letter to Governor Janklow, the ACLU strongly urged the Governor to lift the block and provide full access to all citizens seeking to communicate by e-mail.  
</P>

<P>
	According to the letter, the e-mail block, "if accurately reported, implicate[s] both the right to free speech and the right to petition the government."   The letter was signed by ACLU national staff attorneys Ann Beeson and Steve Pevar. 
</P>

<P>
	Jim Soyer, spokesman for Governor Janklow, defended the state's move, telling C/Net News that government employees were being flooded with petitions filled with inaccuracies.  
</P>

<P>
	But in its letter, the ACLU pointed out that such a block is content-based discrimination: "As the [Supreme] Court has repeatedly held, the government may not censor speech solely because it believes the speech to be inaccurate," the ACLU noted. 
</P>

<P>
	According to Beeson, to date the ACLU has received no meaningful response from the Governor's office and legal action is still an option.    
</P>

<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="cybersitter"> CYBERsitter blocks Peacefire.org</A></H3>
</P>

<P>
	Commercially available blocking software is designed to prevent access to web sites that are deemed inappropriate, but just what is inappropriate? Bennett Haselton, a student at Vanderbilt University who also runs the Peacefire.org web site, installed a copy of CYBERsitter, and was surprised at some of the sites it blocked. CYBERsitter blocked, among other sites, the National Organization for Women, and all web pages on large ISP's such as Echo and the WELL. When Bennett complained, CYBERsitter blocked his site as well. 

</P>	
<P>
	Peacefire.org is a civil liberties membership organization for young people. They are now blocked by CYBERsitter presumably because Bennett brought them so much negative publicity. 
</P>

<P>
	CYBERsitter will not release a list of the sites it blocks, and just recently it released a revised version of the guidelines it follows in deciding what to censor. The guideline are vague enough that CYBERsitter can essentially censor whatever it wants. While as a private company CYBERsitter can block what it chooses, the ACLU believes it should provide clear information about what it blocks and why, so consumers can make informed decisions about whether to use the product.
</P>

<P>
	Bennett is continuing to bring publicity to these issues. He, and Peacefire, will be plaintiffs in the ACLU's upcoming challenge to the New York State version of the CDA. His web site can be found at http://www.peacefire.org
</P>

<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="fla"> ACLU of Florida looks at Library Use of Blocking Software</A></H3>
</P>

<P>
	In another incident regarding blocking software and its application, the ACLU of Florida is looking into complaints against the Orange County, Florida, Library system. The Library system has about 70 terminals that have web access. The library administrators were concerned because the terminals were used, among other things, to view pornography.
</P>

<P>
	In an attempt to deal with this situation the library installed a web blocking program called WebSense on their machines. Unlike CYBERsitter, WebSense is designed for corporate, rather than home use. Also unlike CYBERsitter, WebSense divides the sites it filters into 28 broad categories, and allows the person controlling the program to decide which categories to block. But the library does not allow adult patrons, or minors with parental permission, to modify or switch off the program while surfing the web.
</P>

<P>
	The ACLU does not object to the use of blocking software on public library terminals, as long as the software can be turned off at adult patrons' request.
</P>

<P>
	Andy Kayton, Legal Director of the ACLU of FLorida, has been in touch with the library in the hopes of resolving the situation. However if the library refuses to give citizens uncensored access to the internet, litigation is an option, he said.
</P>

<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="OECD"> OECD Expert Group Finalizes Cryptography Guidelines</A></H3>
</P>

<P>
	An Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) expert group, created to draft cryptography guidelines has finished its work. The guidelines focus on eight principles for cryptography policy: 
<UL>
		<LI> Trust in cryptographic methods 
		<LI> Choice of cryptographic methods 
		<LI> Market driven development of cryptographic methods 
		<LI> Standards for cryptographic methods 
		<LI> Protection of privacy and personal data 
		<LI> Lawful access
		<LI> Liability 
		<LI> International co-operation
</UL>
	These guidelines will be forwarded to the Council of the OECD in spring 1997 for approval as a formal Recommendation of the OECD. GILC and the ACLU held a conference in Paris in September during the OECD group's gathering which contributed to a favorable climate for the guidelines.
</P>

<P>
	The OECD press release on the guidelines can be found at <A HREF="http://www.oecd.org/news_and_events/release/nw96119a.htm">http://www.oecd.org/news_and_events/release/nw96119a.htm</A>
</P>

<P>
