	<LI> <A HREF="#EO">White House Issues New Executive Order on Cryptography</A>
	<LI> <A HREF="#about"> About the Cyber-Liberties Update (Unchanged since 9/17/96)</A>
</UL>


<HR>
 <A NAME="editor"><H3>Note From the Editor</H3></A>

<P>
I am going to be travelling in December, and will be unable to publish a Cyber-Liberties Update on December 11. If there is major breaking news while I am away, Lynn Decker of the ACLU Public Education Department will send email to this list about it. Otherwise, the next Update will be just after Christmas.
</P>

<P>
Once again I would like to encourage all of you to take a look at our New York State Chill Page. It contains information about the New York State version of the CDA, and includes a form where you can tell us how the New York State law is effecting your speech online. It can be found at http://www.aclu.org/action/nychill.html
</P>

<P>
-Lisa Kamm
</P>


<HR>
<A NAME="ga"><H3> Plaintiffs File Reply Brief in Georgia Internet Case</H3></A>

<P>
The Georgia Internet case -- which challenges a Georgia law that bans online
pseudonyms and prohibits certain links on the Web -- is proceeding apace.
On November 26, 1996, Plaintiffs filed reply briefs in response to the
State's earlier briefs.  The State had exhibited a fundamental
misunderstanding of both cyberspace and the First Amendment -- for example,
they argued that casual speech in chat rooms on the Internet was not
protected speech.  Plaintiffs' briefs also explained the fatal flaws in the
State's attempt to radically re-write the statute to apply only to
intentional fraud and deception.
</P>

<P>
To clarify some of the factual disputes about the nature of cyberspace,
Plaintiffs have asked the Court to hold an evidentiary hearing on their
motion for a preliminary injunction against the Georgia Act.  The hearing
would probably be set for early next year.
</P>

<P>
The lawsuit was filed in late September on behalf of 13 plaintiffs,
including the ACLU of Georgia, Electronic Frontiers Georgia, Representative
Mitchell Kaye, and the Electronic Frontier Foundation.  The recent briefs
and other case documents are available at:
</P>

<P>
<A HREF="http://www.aclu.org/issues/cyber/censor/censor.html#georgia">http://www.aclu.org/issues/cyber/censor/censor.html#georgia</A>
<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.efga.org/">http://www.efga.org/</A>
</P>

<P>
For more information, contact Ann Beeson, ACLU, at 212-944-9800 x788, or
Robert Costner, Electronic Frontiers Georgia, at 770-512-8746.
</P>


<HR>

<H3><A NAME="cato"> Cato Study Says Internet Cannot Be Constitutionally Regulated</A></H3>

<P>
In the first study to look beyond the pending ACLU court challenge to censorship on the Internet, the Cato Institute has published a study that examines and rejects as unconstitutional many remaining proposals for government controls on cyberspace.
</P>

<P>
The study, Beyond the Communications Decency Act: Constitutional Lessons of the Internet, was prepared by Solveig Bernstein, assistant director of telecommunications and technology studies at Cato. "No regulation of computer network indecency should pass constitutional scrutiny," Bernstein concludes.
</P>

<P>
The ACLUs National Washington Office welcomed the Cato study, saying that there is already discussion among some members of Congress about legislative attempts to censor the Internet should the Supreme Court strike down the so-called Communications Decency Act.
</P>

<P>
Moments after the CDA was signed by President Clinton last year, the ACLU filed a lawsuit against it in federal district court in Philadelphia. A three-judge panel overturned the law, but the Clinton Justice Department has asked the Supreme Court to review that decision. A decision from the Justices on whether they will review Reno v. ACLU is expected soon.
</P>

<P>
"We must all be wary of future efforts to hijack free-speech supporters into backing new censorship schemes," said Donald Haines, an ACLU Legislative Counsel who works on privacy and Internet regulation. "We need to tell Congress that true friends of the Net are not interested in a "better" way to censor it. We oppose Net censorship because it's wrong and unnecessary." 
</P>

<P>
Specifically, the Cato study rejects as unconstitutional legislation that would ban speech deemed "harmful to minors" and proposals to force content providers to label and rate their sites for content. 
</P>

<P>
"For spontaneous computer speech," Bernstein says, mandatory labeling would be "the equivalent of requiring the labeling of conversations around a backyard barbecue."
</P>

<P>
The Cato report can be found at <A HREF="http://www.cato.org/pubs/pas/pa-262es.html">http://www.cato.org/pubs/pas/pa-262es.html</A>
</P>


<HR>
<H3><A NAME="EO"> White House Issues New Executive Order on Cryptography</A></H3>

<P>
On November 15, the White House released a new Executive Order regulating cryptography exports. The new policy, temporarily relaxing the export restrictions on encryption technology, was first announced by Vice President Al Gore on October 1. It only relaxes the export policy for companies taking steps to make the keys available to the government.
</P>

<P>
This EO moves export determinations on most cryptography products from the State Department to the Commerce Department. While it does not specifically state what Commerce will licence, Gore's earlier announcement indicated that Commerce will allow exports of cryptography products using keys up to 56 bits in length (up from the current 40 bit limit). To get these licenses, companies must agree to work to develop key recovery programs.
</P>

<P>
Key recovery describes an arrangement in which the government can get access to the keys needed to break the encryption. Copies of the keys, or enough information to determine the keys, are stored with the government or with third parties. This means the government can get the keys, and therefore can decrypt any data they protect.
</P>

<P>
Additionally, while authority is being transferred from State to Commerce, the Departments of State, Defense, Energy, Justice  and the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency will have the opportunity to review export licence applications. These agencies, especially Justice, have never been friendly towards cryptography.
</P>

<P>
This new policy is insidious. It creates a great deal of pressure for large technology companies to work towards developing key recovery systems. If they work towards that goal they will be able to produce one version of their software for both domestic and international use. If they are not granted export licenses they will either have to produce different software for the different markets, or eliminate the cryptography functions in their domestic products so they can export them. The EO states that this is all for national security, and to limit the international spread of crypto, but the Commerce department is barred from considering whether the same technology, or crypto technology of an equal strength, is already available overseas, in its normal review process. 
</P>

<P>
At the same time as issuing the new EO, Clinton also designated Ambassador David L. Aaron as the new "Special Envoy for Cryptography." While Congress will not pass key escrow legislation, the establishment of a "crypto czar" is part of the campaign to enshrine key escrow into law through bilateral and multinational treaties.
</P>

<P>
The ACLU opposes this latest Administration policy, and is very concerned about the potential for privacy abuses when the government can access the keys to decrypt protected data.
</P>



<HR>

