			<P>
			<HR>
			<A NAME="note">
				<H3>
					Note From the Editor
				</H3>
			</A>
			</P>
			<P>
			The cyber-liberties section of the ACLU web site has been updated and redesigned. I'd like to encourage all of you to it check out. I will be doing my best to keep it current. It includes an archive of back issues of this Update, and issue pages containing information on various cyber-liberties issues, cases, and activities. It can be found at 
			<A HREF="http://www.aclu.org/issues/cyber/">
				http://www.aclu.org/issues/cyber/
			</A>
			</P>
			<P>
			The NY State CDA Chill page mentioned in the last Cyber-Liberties Update is now on the web. The page has information on the NY State statute, and a form where you can submit information about how your online speech has been affected by the NY State law. The Chill page is located at 
			<A HREF="http://www.aclu.org/action/nychill.html">
				http://www.aclu.org/action/nychill.html
			</A>
			</P>
			<P>
			-Lisa Kamm 
			</P>
			<P>
			<HR>
			<H3>
				<A NAME="cyberpromo">
					Cyberpromo v. AOL
				</A>
			</H3>
			</P>
			<P>
			A District Court in Pennsylvania has ruled that AOL is not a state actor subject to the First Amendment, and therefore can block unsolicited commercial e-mail (spam). 
			</P>
			<P>
			Cyber Promotions, Inc. (Cyberpromo) had been sending literally millions of pieces of unsolicited e-mail to AOL users at their AOL addresses. When AOL began blocking all e-mail sent from Cyberpromo's domains, the company filed suit in the U.S. District Court of the Eastern District of Pennsylvania. Judge Charles Weiner initially issued a temporary restraining order barring AOL from blocking Cyberpromo. 
			</P>
			<P>
			After the issues were briefed Judge Weiner found that there were no disputes over the facts of the case, and issued a summary judgment opinion. He held that AOL is not a state actor, and is not working in conjunction with the government. As a wholly private actor, AOL is not required to open its network to Cyberpromo, and is therefore within its rights to block e-mail from the Cyberpromo's domains. Additionally, Judge Weiner stressed that there are other ways for Cyberpromo to reach the same audience, including through traditional marketing methods such as postal mail, and that this ruling does not close off all means of communication. 
			</P>
			<P>
			Even before the decision, AOL switched gears and created PreferredMail -- a filter that blocks mail from Cyber Promotions and several other sites that regularly send out unsolicited commercial mail. Users can turn off the filter if they want to receive it.
			</P>
			<P>
			Cyberpromo may have lost its First Amendment case, but it hasn't given up yet. The company has now filed a new motion alleging that the PreferredMail filter violates federal anti-trust laws. They have not decided whether to appeal the decision. 
			</P>
			<P>
			<HR>
			<H3>
				<A NAME="webtv">
					Web TV -- A Web Browser or a Munition?
				</A>
			</H3>
			</P>
			<P>
			The latest victim in the U.S. government's push to control encryption technology is Web TV -- a set-top box that allows people to browse the Internet using their TV sets. In order to protect the privacy of the users, and to enable secure online transactions, the boxes encode the information that moves between the users and the Web TV server. 
			</P>
			<P>
			Building in security and privacy is great, but has unfortunately created a problem for the manufacturers. The government classifies strong encryption technology as a munition, and bars its export. The Clinton Administration's latest proposal will allow the export of encryption products with a key up to 56 bits as long as the exporting company agrees to build in "key recovery systems" -- back doors for the government to access encoded data. 
			</P>
			<P>
			Web TV uses a 128 bit key, which is much more secure than the 56 bit keys for which the government will grant export licenses. It may look like a harmless TV adapter, but the Clinton Administration considers it a dangerous munition, and is highly unlikely to grant an export license.
			</P>
			<P>
			The companies that manufacture the set-top boxes had planned to export them to Europe and Japan next year, but are now unlikely to do so. The U.S. cryptography export regulations create strong incentives against incorporating cryptography into products built in the U.S., and may well encourage companies to move overseas to develop products that require security and privacy.
			</P>
			<P>
			<HR>
			<H3>
				<A NAME="japan">
					Japan Tightens Cryptography Export Regulations
				</A>
			</H3>
			</P>
			<P>
			In what could be a major setback for privacy and free speech online, the Japanese government has greatly tightened its export controls on cryptographic products.
			</P>
			<P>
			The U.S. government's longstanding hostility towards cryptography is well known, from its oft aborted clipper proposals, to the current block on the export of Web TV (see story above). 
			</P>
			<P>
			Civil libertarians and others who support the use of cryptography have often thought that the export limitations issue would become moot with regard to international availability of cryptography, although they would continue to create problems for U.S. businesses and block them from participating in foreign markets. 
			</P>
			<P>
			The problem is that now Japan -- at the urging of the U.S. -- is also limiting export of encryption technology. Increased limits overseas make it even more important to work domestically towards a removal of the ban on encryption exports.
			</P>
			<P>
			<HR>
			<H3>
				<A NAME="ga">
					Government's Reply in Georgia
				</A>
			</H3>
			</P>
			<P>
			On November 8, the State of Georgia filed its reply brief in the Internet lawsuit brought by the ACLU, Electronic Frontiers Georgia, and other groups. The suit challenges a law making it a crime to "falsely identify" oneself online, among other things. (see story in the Cyber-Liberties Update from October 3, on the web at http://www.aclu.org/issues/cyber/updates/)
			</P>
			<P>
			The Government's argues that the statute is not as broad as it seems, and merely eliminates intentional fraud and misrepresentation online. But the language in the statute actually goes way beyond eliminating fraud and misrepresentation -- it also bars anonymous use of the internet, or the use of a pseudonym. The language of the statute also would make it illegal to link to a corporate web page using the corporation's logo, whether that use has "intentionally" related to fraud, or not.
			</P>
			<P>
			The ACLU also argues that since the Internet inherently functions across state lines, and is fundamentally interstate commerce, state governments are constitutionally barred from regulating it by the Commerce Clause. Georgia argues that they have the power to regulate criminal activity that affects their citizens within the state borders, and that doing so does not violate the Commerce Clause.
			</P>
			<P>
			Arguments in the case may be scheduled as early as December, but are more likely to happen early next year.
			</P>
			<HR>
			<H3>
				<A NAME="speak">
					ACLU Speaks on Cyber-Liberties
				</A>
			</H3>
			<P>
			November 13, Lisa Kamm, 7:00 - 8:30, "Cyber-liberties and the Elections," Jerome Greene Hall, Room 107, Columbia Law School, New York, NY. 
			</P>
			<P>
			November 18, Barry Steinhardt and Stefan Presser, 4:00 PM, Forum on the CDA at the Yale Law School Auditorium, New Haven, CT. Sponsored by the Yale ACLU Chapter.
			</P>
			<HR>
			<A NAME="about">
