<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>07/29/96: In Congress -- Encryption -- Action on the Burns Bill</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/legishdr.gif">
<P><A
HREF="http://www.aclu.org/cgi-bin/take_action.pl?GetDoc=110&dir=aclu&redirect=http://www.aclu.org/issues/cyber/encryptk.html">Fax
your Senators and support this bill</A></P>
<P>The Senate Commerce Committee, after several postponements, may act shortly
on S. 1726 the PRO-CODE Bill to protect the right of Americans to use encryption
technology to secure their private communications and information.   	</P>
<P>Encryption is a form of speech and is protected by the First Amendment..
American's have the right to speak anonymously and to keep their speech and
private information away from the preying eyes of the government and private
groups and individuals alike.   	</P>
<P>In fact, Cryptography products are the locks and keys of the Information
Age, enabling individuals and businesses to protect sensitive information as it
is transmitted over the Internet. The ability to protect and secure information
is vital to the both the growth of electronic commerce and to the Internet as a
means of mass and democratic communication.  	</P>
<P>The United States Government currently prohibits the export of strong
cryptography. It treats encryption software as an armament to be controlled by
the government. The export ban has discouraged U.S. software companies, who must
 compete in a global market, from including strong cryptography even in products
for the domestic market.   	</P>
<P>Even more ominously, the Clinton Administration has proposed a series of
measures, which began with the infamous Clipper Chip to be built into
communications hardware, that would enable the government to easily obtain the
keys to decrypt private communications.  Clipper II and III are schemes for the
&quot;voluntary escrow&quot; of private keys that would all too quickely turn
into a manditory program.</P>
<P>Senate Bill 1726 Promotion of Commerce On-Line in the Digital Era sponsored
by Senator Burns of Montana (Pro-CODE) Act of 1996, would: 
</P>
<P>- Allow for the unrestricted export of &quot;mass-market&quot; or &quot;public-domain&quot;
encryption programs, including such products as Pretty Good Privacy and popular
World Wide Web browsers. 
</P>
<P>- Require the Secretary of Commerce to allow the unrestricted export of
other encryption technologies if products of similar strength are generally
available outside the United States. 
</P>
<P>- Prohibit the federal government from imposing mandatory key-escrow
encryption policies on the domestic market and limit the authority of the
Secretary of Commerce to set standards for encryption products.   	</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
		<CENTER>
			<SMALL>
				[ 
				<A HREF="../censor/censor.html">
					Censorship
				</A>
				| 
