<HEAD><TITLE>
Cyberliberties
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<img src="/graphics/cyber.gif"></center>
<P>
<blockquote>
<i>"Cyberspace must be free!"</i><p>

The U.S. is in the midst of a communications revolution brought about by the remarkable capabilities of new interactive technologies.  Cyberspace is probably the richest source of creative, diverse, empowering and democratizing communication ever developed.  It is, perhaps, the world's first true "mass media" because it allows anyone with a few simple tools to communicate their ideas to thousands of people at once at practically no cost.
<p>
In the past year, an unprecendented wave of censorship and overzealous law enforcement has swept through the online world.  State and federal legislators proposed and passed legislation to criminalize online speech.  Police raided community bulletin boards and seized entire systems, based on evidence that a minuscule portion of files might be legally obscene.  The privacy rights of online users were threatened by indiscriminate snooping and interference by government and industry in private e-mail.  And California BBS operators were convicted under the community standards of Memphis, Tennessee.
<p>
All the innovation and citizen empowerment inspired by online communications will be lost if civil liberties don't apply in cyberspace.
</blockquote>
<br>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
<H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
