<DOCNO>WT12-B28-147</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA083-000585-B035-171</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.aclu.org:80/about/75th_ann/gay.html 204.243.96.55 19970213130839 text/html 68420
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 13:07:25 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:51:50 GMT
Content-length: 68232
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Substantive Plenary VI:
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><h1>Transcript of Substantive Plenary VI<br>
Rights of Gays and Lesbians</h1></center>
<blockquote>
              MS. FELDBLUM:  It really is the best of
    times and the worst of times for people who care
    about gay and lesbian, bisexual civil rights.  In
    one respect we're in a better position than we have
    been for a very long time.  I have worked on this
    issue fewer years than some of the other people
    that you will hear from.  But even in the last 0
    years that I've worked on this in Washington, I
    feel that there are qualitatively different
   feelings towards working on this issue.  It is, in
   that sense, the best of times.<p>
              And what I will talk about in my piece,
   is where we are going in terms of getting civil
   rights protections, both legislatively and
   judicially, both on the federal level and on state
   and local levels.  And much of the story around
   that is around the best of times.  It is also, in
   some respect the best of times in other areas, such
   as marriage and family.  And Tom Stoddard will be
   talking about the initiatives that have occurred in
   those areas.                                       <p>
              It is also the worst of times.  There
   are new and different obstacles that have now come
   up against people who are striving to achieve these
   rights.  And Matt Coles will talk about some of
     those obstacles that we face in the legal arena,
    things like Amendment  in Colorado.  And Urvashi
    Vaid will talk about how to deal with some of those
    obstacles in an organizational fashion.                                           <p>
               I'm going to start with -- we decided,
    unlike some things, we were going to start with the
    best of times.  Although you will see in each of
    our presentations, we each have an understanding
    and an acknowledgement of this list in each
   respect. <p>
              But I am going to start with the effort
   to achieve civil rights protection on the basis of
   sexual orientation in areas like employment, public
   accommodation, housing, governmental services.  <p>
              Okay, just to sort of lay the ground for
   where we're at -- I know some of this is known, but
   I want to make sure we're all working with the same
   info -- as most of you know, private actor
   discrimination, that is discrimination undertaken
   by private actors, a private employer that fires me
   because I'm a lesbian, a private landlord that
   kicks me out of my apartment because I'm a lesbian,
   a restaurant that kicks me and my lover out of the
   restaurant because we're holding hands, okay?  Any
   discrimination on the part of a private actor is
    not illegal under federal law.  There is no
    redress.  You can't even think of going into court,
    there's no federal law.      <p>
               There are eight states around the
    country that do have laws that prohibit such
    discrimination --                  <p>
               AUDIENCE MEMBER:  Nine.           <p>
               MS. FELDBLUM:  -- nine, that's right.
    I'm sorry, Rhode Island.  Yeah.             <p>
              I forgot.  It's been too long a day, I
   can tell, which is good.  It's like when I used to
   talk about the ADA after it was passed, and I kept
   saying, the bill, the bill.  And I'd have to go:
   It's a law now.  It's a law.<p>
               -- nine states and a number of
   localities.  But clearly, if you don't live in one
   of those nine states or any one of those
   localities, there is no protection.<p>
              If a public actor discriminates against
   me, if a public university that I'm teaching at
   would fire me or public housing, I can
   theoretically go into court under the
   Constitution.  Under the Constitution you get equal
   protection of the laws and I can say this denies me
   the equal protection of the laws.  The key point
    there will be under what standard the court
    evaluates my challenge, whether essentially they
    treat me like an optometrist or they treat me like
    a women or a racial minority. <p>
               In other words, will they have a very
    lenient standard of review -- what's called the
    rational basis standard of review, in which case
    the act of discrimination will probably go
    unchallenged, that is it will be upheld -- or if
   they impose a strict standard of review. <p>
              Now, I will not go into the intricacies
   of those standards of review here.  This is just to
   say that in the judicial arena, which only applies
   against public actors, we, as gay people, have not
   tended to fair very well.  We have tended to get
   the lowest standard of review.  And now that you
   have, through the ACLU's America Online, with the
   ACLU being online, those of you who are
   particularly interested in that issue, there should
   be next week, online, the brief that I wrote on
   behalf of a number of gay groups and women's
   groups, with a lot of input from other people on
   this panel, that dealt specifically with the
   standard of review.  And you should feel free to
   download the whole 30 pages, and Phil Gutis will be
    so excited that he can write more numbers of people
    who are downloading.    <p>
               So, we can get protection through a
    statutory protection for private actors, which is
    the key, and we could get that through a federal
    law in the way that exists on the basis of race,
    gender, religion, disability -- there is now a
    federal law prohibiting such discrimination -- or
    we can get it through state and local laws.<p>
              Here is where I think that we are in the
   best of times, in the sense that the landscape has
   changed significantly, in terms of the effort
   towards getting such laws on the local, state and
   federal level. <p>
              When I started working at the ACLU, I
   was there from '88 to '92.  I was fortunate enough
   to be there at the culmination of the disabilities
   community's efforts to have the civil rights
   community at large understand that disability
   rights were civil rights.  And it was because the
   Leadership Conference on Civil Rights made the
   Americans with Disabilities Act a legislative
   priority that that bill was able to become a law in
   the two years that it took.  There was no doubt
   that it was that coalition effort that made the
     difference. <p>
               I remember saying in 1990, turning to
    Mort Halperin, who was then my boss at the
    Washington office, at an LCCR dinner where they
    were talking about the ADA's passage, and I said:
    "This will never happen for gay men and lesbians.
    We will never be a legislative priority for the
    LCCR, it won't happen."  Because the sense I got
    working with wonderful people in lots of
   organizations, was that they were not happy to make
   lesbian and gay rights a legislative priority.  And
   Mort said to me:  "I think you're wrong.  I think
   they will."     <p>
              And in fact, the landscape changed in
   Washington, D.C. dramatically in the fall of 1991.
   No press release, no major hoopla, but the ground
   moved, because in the fall of 1991 the executive
   committee of the Leadership Conference on Civil
   Rights voted to make a gay and lesbian civil rights
   bill something that the coalition would potentially
   endorse.  I was just a first step.  It was just
   giving the mandate to a drafting group to work on a
   bill, but it was key.  And it was the efforts of
   people like Mort and Ralph Neas and Pat Wright and
   other of our colleagues in the other civil rights
   organizations that made that possible.<p>
               Well, from 1991, from that time until
    now, it took two years to draft the Employment
    Non-Discrimination Act which was introduced in the
    last Congress and was introduced again in this
    Congress.  And the key thing I want to say about
    that bill, in terms of work by a group like the
    ACLU, is the following:  No. , the bill was
    intentionally crafted to be pragmatic.  That is,
   the bill just covers employment.  It doesn't cover
   anything, it just covers employment.  And there
   were compromises that were made in terms of not
   mandating benefits for domestic partners within the
   federal bill, having the relatively broad religious
   exemption, excluding transgender folks from
   coverage under that law.  <p>
              There were changes -- there were
   decisions made in that bill to make it pragmatic.
   However, none of those decisions affected the core
   protection of that bill, which is to say that an
   employer cannot use sexual orientation as a basis
   for employment discrimination, and sexual
   orientation harassment on the job is covered, just
   like gender harassment or racial harassment.  <p>
              Now, the question is, can this bill
     pass?  And this is, in my mind, still within the
    context of this is the best of times.  I believe
    this law can pass.  And I believe that the process
    that will occur in order to make it pass will
    itself be essential toward changing attitudes in
    this country and thereby changing the lives of
    lesbian and gay men in this country.  <p>
               No. , I believe it will pass, because
    there is an effort to make this a bipartisan bill,
   and that was apparent in the introduction of this
   bill just two weeks ago, when it was introduced.
   That Republicans stood up and said: "This is a good
   bill, because no one should be discriminated
   against."  And the fact is that when you look at
   public opinion -- and the ACLU just ran a great ad
   in The New York Times about this -- most Americans
   believe that it's wrong for someone to be denied a
   job just because they're gay.  Now, most of these
   people also think such a law already exists.  But,
   you know, if you can get to the member and say,
   look, public opinions says that they think this is
   okay.       <p>
              But that's not enough.  It's not enough
   to just have the poll, the public opinion poll that
   says people don't think that they should be fired
   from a job just because they're gay, because the
    member is still afraid.  The member of Congress is
    still afraid to vote yes because the 30-second
    spot. <p>
               So I believe that one of the key things
    to make this work is not just from the top down.
    The bill has to exist at the top, so there is
    something to work toward.  But the work comes from
    the bottom, from across the country.  That is,
   No. , the best thing that will make this law pass,
   is if there are more local and state laws that
   prohibit discrimination.  Governor Weld of
   Massachusetts, Governor Whitman from New Jersey
   have both come out in favor of ENDA.  Guess what,
   Massachusetts already has such a law, New Jersey
   already has such a law.  It is much easier for
   someone to come out in support of the federal law
   if there's already a state law.  <p>
              And it is much easier to get a state law
   if you have localities within the state that have
   such a law.  The way to make this law pass on the
   federal level is to build the protections from the
   local level and the state levels.  And what that
   will mean, is that in the 0 to 5 states that we
   will never get such a law -- unfortunately, but we
   will not -- the other 30 states having laws will
    help pass the federal law and then we'll in fact
    have complete protection.<p>
               The second reason why passing state and
    local laws are so important, is not just to create
    the comfort zone for the members of Congress, but
    the process that you go through when you work in a
    coalition on such a bill is key in terms of
    changing attitudes, which is ultimately what we
   need.  A law cannot change people's thoughts.  <p>
              I know that when I worked on the
   Americans with Disabilities Act, I knew nothing
   about disability, really, before I started.  I knew
   stuff about AIDS, that's how I came to it.  But it
   was working on the ADA for two years, where I met
   people with disabilities, that opened my eyes to
   the range of issues affecting disabilities.  The
   same happens when you work in coalition on gay and
   lesbian issues.  I've seen it happen in the last
   three years in Washington.  It absolutely happens
   in every area where there is such a coalition
   effort.  And I believe that the ACLU is a key group
   for, in fact, helping to make those coalitions
   happen on the state and local level.      <p>
              And the third thing, is as you are
  working on the state and local level, the ACLU has
    a great structure for feeding you in toward the
    federal level in terms of phone calls, et cetera.
    But that really is not as important, in my mind, as
    the fact of having the efforts on the state and
    local level.         <p>
               I do believe that ENDA will pass.  And I
    used to be not sure if it would pass in my
    lifetime.  I am positive it will pass in my
   lifetime, and I'm not planning on killing myself,
   so...       <p>
              But the hard part will be whether all
   the other laws that affect public accommodations
   and housing, et cetera, when those will come.  That
   is the good news, I believe the best of times in
   terms of civil rights protections. <p>
              I believe that in terms of the efforts
   in the courts, the one area where it is going
   through the courts at the moment is in the
   military.  That is, in terms of discrimination by
   public employers, which is where constitutional
   challenges could arise, the main discrimination
   occurs in the military, those are the cases that
   are coming to the courts.  We have traditionally
   lost in those areas.  We are no longer consistently
    losing.  In fact, we are wining now as many cases
    as we are losing and many of those cases are
    brought by the ACLU Lesbian and Gay Rights
    Project.            <p>
               [ APPLAUSE ].     <p>
               Let me finally say that besides the
    America Online access -- which I think is
    excellent, in terms of you being able to get input
    here -- you should know that Matt Coles has a book
   coming out by the New Press, specifically on
   working on state and local initiatives, civil
   rights laws.  It's called "Try This At Home."  And
   in terms of general law, Bill Rubinstein, Matt
   Coles' predecessor at the project, has written a
   book called Lesbians, Gay Men And The Law, which is
   a great sourcebook, and I'm sure you can get
   information about that.            <p>
              There really is a lot that we can do.  I
   believe that this is the moment in history, and
   that we are seeing history being made as we live. <p>
              Thank you.                <p>
              [ APPLAUSE ].     <p>
              MR. STODDARD:  Good afternoon.  It's a
   pleasure, a great pleasure to be here among my
   friends and family.           <p>
               Ira Glasser, yesterday morning, invited
    us to take the long view in this year of our 75th
    anniversary, and he was certainly right about
    that.  If the long view is appropriate and helpful
    for us to take as civil libertarians, it is
    especially appropriate and especially moving to
    think about the long view in connection with this
    particular set of issues.  75 years ago there was
    no lesbian and gay rights movement.  There was
   maybe a twinkle in the eyes of a few dozen men and
   women, but that was it.                        <p>
              The modern day lesbian and gay civil
   rights movement is only 6 years old, if one uses
   Stonewall as the marker.  And the advances are,
   frankly, stunning, absolutely stunning, as Chai's
   introductory remarks have already suggested.  <p>
              The ACLU has also come a long way.  I'm
   going to deviate from what I'm supposed to be doing
   for just a moment to say something about that.  But
   if a gay person can't deviate, who can.             <p>
              [ LAUGHTER ].    <p>
              This morning I went into my historical
   file and I found a letter sent by an unnamed
   employee of the American Civil Liberties Union in
   957 to the public relations director of the
    Mattachine Society, which at the time was the most
    visible gay rights organization, dated November
    9th, 957.  It reads as follows.  It's quite
    short.  "Thank you for your letter of November
    st.  We are glad to learn of your interests in
    the Union's work and activity.  While we appreciate
    your kind invitation to address your group, we must
    deline.  The civil liberties aspects of the
    question of sexual deviation is so small that we do
   not devote major attention to this issue.  None of
   our staff is expert in this question and could
   hardly offer your group the kind of intensive
   discussion it would desire and deserves.  The
   meeting might very well begin with a general
   discussion of civil liberties, but the main
   interest of your organization would, in our
   opinion, veer into your special field" -- I love to
   veer -- "where we lack the competency to
   intelligently discuss the issue."               <p>
              Ira Glasser would never write that
   letter.                            <p>
              [ APPLAUSE ].   <p>
              AUDIENCE MEMBER:  Who did?  <p>
              MR. STODDARD:  The ACLU has come a long
   way and we should all take great pride in the
   extraordinary, precedent-setting work of the AIDS
    Project and the Gay and Lesbian Civil Rights
    Project.  This organization is one of the two or
    three leading groups in the country, perhaps even
    the world, on these subjects.  And I, as a civil
    libertarian, am very proud of that.     <p>
               Okay, now I'll do what I'm supposed to
    do.  I'm supposed to talk about family issues.     <p>
               In the seventies, as the modern day
   lesbian civil rights movement was trying to define
   its priorities and begin its work, issues tended to
   be centered on the rights of the individual as an
   individual, which was of course not universal, but
   the emphasis tended to be different, perhaps
   because the movement in those days was especially
   dominated by men.  Issues tended to be civil rights
   protections, generally, statutes analogous to the
   civil rights act of 964, for example, and the
   repeal of sodomy statutes.    <p>
              In the eighties and into the nineties
   the priorities established in the seventies
   shifted, changed in large, moved on to include
   family and lesbians and gay men in the context of
   family.  It's those issues that I'm going to talk
   about for just a moment.  <p>
             Over the past 0 years the lesbian and
    gay rights movement has come to embrace the concept
    of individuals in the general context of their
    families.  Individuals as parents, as children, as
    spousees, as households.  And now there is a
    flowering of work to establish the rights of
    lesbians and gay men, and all people in this
    country -- because, of course, this movement is
    ultimately about the rights of all people -- to be
   part of their own chosen context, to be part of the
   loving and concerned networks in which we all
   operate.             <p>
              I can see at least six different
   categories in which this work proceeds, and this
   is, I think, the most challenging and the most
   difficult of the work into the future.  <p>
              No. 1, marriage, something I'm
   particularly obsessed with.  I'm sorry I'm not here
   to introduce my spouse.  The personal is the
   political, after all.   <p>
              The Supreme Court of Hawaii ruled, two
   years ago, that the denial of a license to two
   women or two men to get married, is presumptively
   violative of the Hawaiian state constitution.  The
   court ruled on the basis of the state's equal
    rights amendment, the gender discrimination portion
    of the state constitution.  The argument being a
    very simple, and I think compelling one, that the
    state should not be able to say to a woman that she
    can only marry a man and not marry a woman, even
    though their relationship has all of the other
    aspects of the close and loving relationship we
    associate with spouses.<p>
               This is a startling and scary
   development.  This is the first court to make such
   a ruling.  The ruling will probably be, to a
   subsequent ruling by the Hawaii Supreme Court,
   stating that the denial of a marriage license to
   two women or two men definitively violates the
  Hawaii State Constitution and therefore, same sex
   couples may, for the first time -- not only in the
   United States, but in the world -- get a marriage
   license.     <p>
              That may sound like a small thing.
   Hawaii is a small state and a distant state,
   although a very wonderful state --      <p>
              [ LAUGHTER ].  <p>
               -- and a state that many people would
   like to visit for all sorts of reasons.  How
   convenient.   <p>
               But here is the legal catch:  In
    general, states are supposed to give regard to the
    legal act of their brother and sister states.  What
    happens if two men get a marriage license in
    Hawaii, then happen to move to Utah, for example, a
    state that comes to mind, and wish to receive the
    recognition for their marriage that traditionally
    Utah gives to marriages from New York or Florida or
    Washington State or anywhere else.  That will
   happen, and it will happen not only in Utah but in
   every state.  Lesbians and gay men will go to
   Hawaii to seek a marriage license.  I don't know
   the residency requirements of Hawaii, but some
   certainly will be able to qualify in some fashion,
   then they'll go back and seek recognition elsewhere
   for personal reasons and also for political
   reasons.   <p>
              And what will happen?  Well, I don't
   know.  This is an issue that the far right will
   really love, really love.  And it will be, it will
   be something that all of you as activists and civil
   libertarians will have to face in some fashion in
   your states.   <p>
              Utah -- actually, I lied a little bit, I
   didn't just choose Utah at random -- the Utah state
     legislature, in anticipation of this development,
    voted just a few weeks ago to declare that marriage
    is a heterosexual institution in Utah and that same
    sex couples, in essence, cannot enter into a
    marriage, as a statement of public policy.      <p>
               The phrase "public policy" is critical
    here, because under the laws of every state,
    although a state is required to give general legal
    effect under the full faith and credit clause of
   the Constitution, to what other states do there is
   an exception for violation of public policy.  And
   if legislatures across the country express their
   view that the public policy of Utah or Idaho
   requires heterosexual marriage to be limited to
   heterosexuals, you've got a problem.  And I don't
   know exactly what's going to happen, but I suspect
   we're going to see referenda and initiatives that
   are more dangerous politically, as well as
   frightening legally, than we've seen with regard to
   civil rights statutes.  This is an issue the far
   right loves. <p>
              There's an irony that should be added as
   a footnote.  There is a certain paradox on the
   issue of marriage.  To the far right, the radical
   right -- I have to remember to keep using the right
     phrases -- to the radical right marriage seems to
    be the most radical and dangerous proposition
    offered up by the lesbian and gay rights movement,
    because in their minds it seems to threaten their
    traditional ideas of family and spouses.        <p>
               Within the gay rights movement the view
    is very much different from that, as you might
    imagine, but in a way that you might not be fully
    aware of.  Many lesbians and gay men say:  "Look,
   marriage has been oppressive, especially not
   tolerant to women.  And the gay rights movement
   should not be seeking to spread out the oppression,
   to share the oppression with new couples."  So what
   is, what seems very radical and dangerous to the
   radical right, people outside of the movement, on
   the other side of it don't like it; seems
   conservative and dangerously traditional to people
   within the lesbian and gay rights movement.  And
   there is a little bit of truth on all sides of this
   I suspect.         <p>
              Okay, there's marriage, that's the
   issue, the large issue looming in the future that
   will be used as an organizing tactic by the radical
   right.                <p>
              No. 2 , domestic partnership.  As an
     alternative to traditional spousal recognition,
    activists throughout the country, some lesbians and
    gays, some not, have offered a new legal form
    called domestic partnership, which is a legal
    species by which a same sex couple or a
    heterosexual couple may register with a
    governmental agency, declaring that they have a
    close and loving relationship, leaving open the
    question of what flows from that.  Many cities
   around the country have now adopted some form of
   domestic partnership, including Los Angeles, San
   Francisco, Seattle, New York, Washington, D.C..
   Here's the problem, though, from a legal
   perspective:  By and large, cities do not have
   jurisdiction over family law and what they do
   doesn't matter very much.       <p>
              What the cities have done is therefore
   almost entirely symbolic, except with regard to the
   employment opportunities and benefits offered by
   the government as employer itself.  But I'll tell
   you, as a domestic partnership, or as a domestic
   partner, I find this legal species, even though
   very limited in effect and mostly symbolic,
   extremely useful.  For example, my spouse's law
   firm just decided to open up the group health plan
     to domestic partners, because the species had been
    created by the City of New York and seemed to have
    a certain legitimacy.  They didn't need to worry
    about fraud, as they might have otherwise, or
   issues of proof.  So domestic partnership can be
    quite valuable.  That's the second new development
    and that will continue to bubble up, particularly
    in the state legislatures.<p>
               The third issue, economic benefits.
   Marriage is desirable for many people because of
   the whole network of benefits that attach to
   spousal relationship.  And some claims have been
   made throughout the country, over the past five
   years, that the state and government in general is
   required to give economic benefits to same sex
   couples, or to domestic partners.  Those claims
   have, by and large failed, but there has been
   enormous progress on this issue through day-to-day,
   nonlegal activism within corporations.  It's a
   reminder to those of us who are lawyers, that
   lawyers aren't the only people who make change.
   It's especially important to remember that within
   the ACLU, I think.                        <p>
              Hundreds of corporations in the United
   States now extend benefits, economic benefits from
    group health care to bereavement leave to same sex
    couples or to domestic partners.  And they've done
    it simply by making economic arguments to
    employers, saying, among other things, it will be
    hard to recruit and get really good candidates of
    all kinds into a particular law firm if there is no
    recognition of these special relationships.  That's
    No. 3, mostly a nonlegal development.         <p>
               No. 4 has to be disputes.  Here is an
   example of where the long view gives us a sense of
   hope.  Approximately half of the states in the
   United States have judicial decisions that stand
   for the proposition that a woman or man may not be
   denied custody rights simply because of his or her
   sexual orientation.         <p>
              When you consider that 30 years ago,
   women in particular who were identified as lesbians
   were routinely denied their parental rights this is
   an extraordinary development.  The argument 30
   years ago was that a lesbian mother, was at the
   very least an unapprehended felon.  Someone who
   wanted to violate the sodomy statutes even if she
   hadn't been convicted.  Those are arguments in at
   least half the states, and in the states that are
   most populous, it can no longer be made.  That's a
    very significant development.  And the Bottoms
    case, of which you probably read in the ACLU
    newsletter, in Virginia, will, I think, ultimately
    be overturned, even in the state of Virginia,
    because the trend is wildly against that idea.   <p>
               No. 5, adoption, foster care.  Very
    quickly, two states specifically prohibit lesbians
    and gay men from serving as adoptive parents,
    Florida, thanks to Anita Bryant, and New Hampshire,
   thanks to Michael Dukakis.  I won't go into the
   long explanation of why Dukakis is connected to the
   developments in New Hampshire, but those two states
   statutorily prohibit lesbians and gay men from
   serving as adoptive parents.  This issue also
   arises in foster care.  The state of Nebraska
   recently adopted a regulation that prohibits the
   state from recommending foster care for a lesbian
   or gay man or lesbian or gay couple.                               <p>
              The Supreme Court of Florida recently
   side stepped the issue of whether the exclusion is
   unconstitutional, but this will be an ACLU issue
   for the future as well, especially as the far right
   moves on the family issues.       <p>
              Lastly, a very interesting new legal
   development of which some of you may not be aware,
    second-parent adoptions.  Traditionally under
    adoption law, when an adoption takes place, the
    natural -- the original parents' parental rights
    are severed.  That is to say, when an adoption
    takes place there can't be an adding onto a
    previous parental relationship.  There has to be
    only one parent or one parental connection.      <p>
               Lesbians and gay men have asserted that
    this is improper and disserves the interest of
   children, and have created a new idea, which is to
   say adding on a second parent's adoptive rights for
   the benefit of the child as well as the parents,
   and states -- courts in a number of states have
   accepted that idea, including two high courts.  The
   high court of New York, which is called the Court
   of Appeals, is about to consider this question
   itself and I'm afraid they may go in the wrong
   direction, believing that adoption under existing
   state statute requires a severing of the previous
   adoptive relationship.  But in the end this trend,
   too, is very vocal.  And it means, in connection
   with all of the other developments I've talked
   about very briefly, that lesbians and gay men will
   be entitled to the full and rich family life that
   all Americans deserve.   <p>
           Thank you.               <p>
               MR. COLES:  Tom and Chai are both
    members of the National Board, which is, I think
    another symbol of how far along this organization
    has come.  Since they're members of the National
    Board, they got to tell you about good things we
    see on the horizon.  Since I work for the national
    staff, I got assigned to tell you about some of the
    bad things that we see on the horizon.   <p>
              I'm going to talk quickly about three
   general areas of things that I think you might see
   happening at the affiliates and give you a couple
   of quick ideas about things that I think that you
   can do about them.<p>
              And the first area is anti-gay ballot
   initiatives.  And I think the specific nature of
   what we're going to see over the next five years is
   going to somewhat depend on what happens in the
   Colorado Amendment  case.  I'm sure everyone here
   knows what Colorado's Amendment  is.  It was an
   amendment to the state constitution that deprived
   every form of government in Colorado from ever
   passing any kind of law that would protect
   lesbians, gay men and bisexuals from any form of
   discrimination.  That law was challenged.  The
    challenge is now in the U.S. Supreme Court, which
    will probably hear arguments sometime in October.
    They will probably decide the case, I think, early
    next year.                            <p>
               If we lose that case, and I think we
    could lose that case, I think it's a fair
    assumption that we will see replications of
    Amendment  in virtually every state that has
    initiative and referendum.  We'll see virtually,
   the effects of the Colorado initiative brought back
   again.                                   <p>
              If we win that case, I think we will
   still see initiatives, maybe not as widely.
   They'll be a little bit different.  They'll be
   designed, I think to try and get past the
   Colorado -- the Supreme Court case, if we win it.
   One form which we've actually already seen crop up
   in a few places.  It's an initiative which just
   says:  The state can pass civil rights laws to
   cover these groups and no others, and then lists a
   group of people who can be protected, and low and
   behold, lesbians, gay men and bisexuals are not on
   the list of people who can be protected.  The
   discrimination is taken off the face of the
   initiative.  They're much harder to challenge
    legally.  It would present a different set of legal
    issues than the Colorado issue.   <p>
               The other thing that I think we may see
    is some of the same issues that Tom was talking
    about, issues about marriage, adoption, foster
    parenting and custody put on the ballot in public
    initiatives, and I think these will generate some
    very tough election campaigns.  I'll talk
    specifically about some of the kinds of devices we
   may see in a minute, but first I want to suggest
   what you can do if you see the potential for an
   anti-gay initiative on the ballot coming down the
   pike.      <p>
              And the first thing to do, and I can't
   emphasize this enough, is to find out what all your
   state or local rules on initiatives and referendums
   are.  They are very complicated.  They differ from
   state to state.  But find out how many signatures
   people need, find out when they have to go in, find
   out what the process for title and summary are,
   find out what kind of challenges are possible.  You
   need to know all that stuff to be able to get
   yourselves armed to figure out what an intelligent
   response to a potential anti-gay ballot initiative
   is.<p>
            And then when you've got yourself armed
    with that, think about the following potential
    tactics.  Think about running an anti-qualification
    campaign, a campaign to try and keep the initiative
    from qualifying for the ballot.  There are a number
    of states and localities where the signature
    requirements are quite high.  In cities in North
    Carolina you've got to get 5 percent of the
    registered voters.  It's very possible to beat
   these things in places where the signature
   requirements are quite high.  And even where
   they're not referendums, an initiative was
   successfully kept off the ballot in Arizona last
   year, I think partly because the Republican party
   thought it would be a bad idea to have another --       <p>
              AUDIENCE MEMBER: They never submitted
   any signatures, because they never got any, zero.  <p>
             MR. COLES:  Well, in any event, I know
   they didn't submit signatures at the end of the
   campaign.  I realize that.  I know that.<p>
              AUDIENCE MEMBER:  They never gathered
   any, either.     <p>
              MR. COLES:  Well, that's news to me,
   they never gathered any, but, okay.   <p>
              AUDIENCE MEMBER:  Right.   <p>
                MR. COLES:  In any event, you can run an
    anti-qualification campaign.  There are a series of
    different ways to do that.  You can run various
    sorts of preelection challenges, especially that
    are keyed into those technical requirements of what
    you need in an initiative.  It's very important, if
    you do that, to be in touch with the political
    people.  How a campaign goes on an initiative, you
    can make a difference in 5 or 6 percent of the
   vote, depending on the way the question is stated
   on the ballot.  And you can very often challenge
   the ballot questions when they are originally
   formulated.  And of course, you can run a campaign
   against the initiative itself.  These things are
   winnable.  If you don't believe me, ask Jack
   Van Valkenburgh from the Idaho affiliate of the
   ACLU.  In a year of a Republican sweep --    <p>
              [ APPLAUSE ].             <p>
               -- an anti gay initiative got beaten  
   in Idaho.  These things are winnable in a political
   campaign.  And the project has put out a briefing
   book that reviews the Colorado experience and makes
   a series of what I think are helpful suggestions
   that we did pass on to the folks in Idaho.  If
   you're looking at this, we can help you with that
  as well.                                <p>
               And finally, don't assume just because
    we've loss the Colorado case, if we have loss it,
    that court challenges post amendment are
    impossible.  Depending on the way the state's law
    works on amendments -- again, thinking of Idaho --
    it may well be possible to bring various kinds of
    post election state law challenges.  So don't think
    any doors are necessarily closed.  <p>
              Secondary, where I think you may see
   things over the next couple years is, somewhat as
   Tom gave you a hint of, in the area of marriage and
   family law.  And I think there are three types of
   things that we'll see.  We'll see anti gay marriage
   legislation, laws saying affirmatively that
   lesbians and gay men cannot get married in a given
   state.  We may see laws prohibiting adoption or
   foster parenting or regulations designed to the
   same effect.  And we may see laws forbidding second
   parent adoptions, that Tom was talking about a
   second ago.     <p>
              Litigation in these areas is difficult,
   very difficult.  These kinds of laws and
   regulations are very, very difficult to challenge
   in court, but never dismiss them out of hand.  If
    you've got one coming up, call us at the project
    and talk to us about it.  Because the way some of
    them have been crafted, because of the way state
    law works in various states, some of them can be
    challenged with litigation.  But you should never
    think of litigation as the first course and,
    indeed, once again there are a number of success
    stories on policies like these that have been
    stopped.   <p>
              The grassroots policy that Tom was
   talking about actually hasn't gone, hasn't taken
   final effect as a rule in Nebraska yet.  And while
   it's not clear to me that it will be stopped, it's
   been slowed down considerably, I think by a very,
   very good combination of providing the state social
   services agency with information that most of the
   assumptions they were basing the policy on were
   wrong.  We provided them a couple of powerful
   examples of why this was not a good idea.  And by
   convincing a number of moderate political people in
  the state that it would be good to oppose it.  And
  at least, I think the jury is still out on how
   Nebraska is going to turn out at this point.  But
   it is possible -- it has been slowed down.  It may
   be stopped.  <p>
         South Dakota also comes to mind.  South
  Dakota, like Utah, had a proposal in the
   legislature to ban lesbian/gay marriage and partly
   with the help of Dorothy Davidson in the Mountain
   States Regional Office, that got defeated.  Now, it
   got defeated with an argument that won't work for
   us forever, because one of the main arguments
   against it was, it's completely unnecessary, people
   already can't get married in South Dakota.  And it
   could prove to be very expensive if challenged.
  Once the Hawaii case comes along, it may be tougher
  to use that argument.  But again, South Dakota
   seemed to me to be an unlikely place to stop that
   under any circumstances.  And it is possible to
   stop them.<p>
              The third area in which I think you may
   see things, and this is a very general area:  I
   think as we see increasing visibility of lesbians
   and gay men and increasing visibility of the
   lesbian and gay movement, we're going to see
  increasing discrimination and we're going to see it
  all across the board.  I think we're going to see
   increasing employment discrimination, we're going
   to see increasing discrimination in housing.  We'll
   see attempts to stop lesbian and gay parades from
    going forward.  We'll see attacks on anti
  discrimination laws where they get passed.  <p>
             What you can do about these things is
  pretty obvious.  But I want to point out two areas
  in which I think there are some things that I think
  you can do that are not completely obvious.  And
  the first thing is this:  If you have a
   discrimination case in a state where you don't have
    a nondiscrimination law, unlike Rhode Island and
   the eight other states, and you don't have
   governmental actors, so that you can bring a
   constitutional claim, don't assume that all is
   necessarily lost.  It may well be necessarily lost,
   but don't assume it.  In various circumstances
   there are some creative things you can do.  If you
   get a case like that cropping up, please call us at
   the project at the national office, we'll take a
   look at it and see if we can think of a way to
   approach it anyway. <p>
              Don't automatically assume that all is
  lost in a nondiscrimination case.   <p>
             And second, particularly if you see
   cases that involve things like parades and
   demonstrations, or more particularly, instances of
   people suffering discrimination because they are
   out of the closet or open, and work for
   governments, let me just pass on to you a word
   about what I am beginning to call regularly, the
   great silver lining case of the last 0 years, and
   that is the Boston parade case. <p>
              There are two things in the Boston
   parade case in this general area that I think
   everyone ought to know.  The first thing, and the
   less important one, but still very significant is,
   the Supreme Court went out of its way in the Boston
  parade case to say that the states and the cities
  have the power under the federal constitution to
   pass anti-discrimination laws that protect lesbians
  and gay men from discrimination.  <p>
              Now, that issue wasn't really in front
   of the Court.  So in some sense it's not, you know,
   the greatest bit of holding that you've ever seen.
   On the other hand, it's pretty strong language from
  the Court and I think if you're in a place where
   you have a local non-discrimination law or a state
  non-discrimination law and you have to defend it,
  this is a powerful tool for defending it that
   people shouldn't overlook.  But even more important
   in that case, the Court said, look:  The gay Irish
   contingent in that parade, by marching behind a
  banner that identified the folks in the parade as
  lesbian and gay, was making a political statement.
 It was making a statement that there are lesbians
  and gay men in the Irish community and that they
 are entitled to equal respect as members of that
  community. <p>
              I think -- now, that's a step short of
   saying that being out of the closet on the job or
   coming out of the closet on the job, if you work
 for a governmental employer, is protected political
  speech, but it comes, I think, very close.  And it
  gives us the powerful tools we need to put together
  that kind of an argument.  So if you've got a case
 that involves people being out and suffering any
   kind of retaliation from the government, think
   about the Boston parade case.  I think it's a
   powerful new tool for us. <p>
              And finally, let me repeat my broken
   record at the biennial, which I've been alluding to
   so far, which is this:  We've got a very able staff
   at the National Lesbian/Gay Rights Project.  Mark
   Elovitz and Ruth Harlow are right at the table up
   here.    <p>
              [ APPLAUSE ].<p>
              The project's been around almost 10
  years.  We've got a lot of experience.  If you've
    got a lesbian or gay issue coming up in your
    affiliate, call us right away.  We can save you a
    lot of time.  We can be very helpful in telling you
    whether there's something to do about this, framing
    how to go forward on it and putting you in touch
    with resources.  Please get in touch with us right
    away.   <p>
               The bottom line is, I think there's
   going to be a lot of action in lesbian and gay
   rights in the next five years.  It's going to be
   the kind of action that takes foresight and
   planning to succeed with, especially the stuff that
   doesn't lend itself well to litigation.  And
   they're going to be tough.  These are going to be
  tough political issues, they're going to be tough
   electoral issues and they're going to be tough
   litigation issues.   <p>
              But tough issues, when it's the right
   thing to do, I mean we're the ACLU, that's what we
   do, right?  <p>
              [ APPLAUSE ].    <p>
              MS. VAID:  Hi, my name is Urvashi Vaid.
   And I'm going to -- I'm playing cleanup hitter
   here.  My job is to talk some about the nonlegal
   opportunities that exist for us to organize and
    fight back against the kind of landscape that Matt
    described.  But before I do that, I want to do my
    presentation in two ways:  Suggest to you a
    conceptual shift that I think is confronting the
    gay movement in particular, and it's confronting
    the progressive movement generally, and then talk
    very practically about some of the work that I
    think affiliates can do.<p>
              In the high-tech world of computers, the
   simulation of events and situations produced from
   computer and video technology is called virtual
   reality, right?  It's most commonly used to train
   airline pilots in flight simulation and by the
   Defense Department to play war games.  Virtual
   reality has, until now, been mostly the fascination
   of cyber junkies like me.  I am one.  I'm coming
   out.      <p>
              [ LAUGHTER ].         <p>
              You didn't know that.   <p>
              The technology of this virtual reality
   should probably be as common as headphones or, you
   know, Sony Walkmans and all that stuff.     <p>
              Well, I think that metaphor aptly
   describes in some way the status of gay people,
  only I call it virtual equality.  The irony of
  gay/lesbian progress is that nearly more than 50
   years of activism -- I do include the Mattachine
    movement as part of the modern movement -- more
    than 50 years of organizing and challenging
    homophobia and sexism has yielded us not freedom,
    but virtual equality.  Virtual equality simulates
    genuine equality, but cannot transcend the
    simulation.      <p>
              In this state gay and lesbian people
   possess some of the trappings of full equality, but
   are denied its full benefits.  We proceed as if we
   enjoy real freedom, real acceptance, as if we've
   won lasting changes to the laws of our nation.  And
  some of us even believe that the simulation of
   equality we have won represents the real thing.
   But the real facts of discrimination, the
   conditions which define gay and lesbian life,
   demonstrate that we have won virtual freedom,
   virtual equal treatment under virtually the same
   laws as straight people.   <p>
              I think that, as Chai pointed out at the
   outset, we're at a contradictory juncture.  On the
   one level our movement has been a staggering, yet
   still controversial success.  And yet we remain
 profoundly stigmatized and still struggling against
   the same crisis that gay and lesbian people have
    faced for the last hundreds of years.  We're still
    struggling against violence, against
    discrimination, against the denial of social
    services by government, in health care access, in
    education.  We're still struggling against
    invisibility within our communities, we're still
    struggling against the prejudice of our families,
   against the ostracism of religion and against the
   prejudice in the workplace.     <p>
              Indeed, a vast majority of our people
   still remain closeted, still remain unwilling to
   acknowledge their sexual orientation.       <p>
              I guess I'm the bummer.  I told you I
   was going to be a bit of a bummer.   <p>
              Gay and lesbian participation in the
   cultural, commercial, political, religious and
   civic leaders of our society is, indeed evident
   everywhere.  But in the eyes of so many of our
   straight peers, gay people are still seen as
   immoral, unnatural, and unhealthy.  Now, perhaps
   this state of affairs is merely the inevitable
   consequence of civil rights progress.  As any
   movement succeeds, vestiges of the old ways
  persist. <p>
              Like the other civil rights movements
   which preceded us, and on which we have consciously
   modeled our goals and strategies, I think the gay
    movement has reached a moment of partial
    fulfillment.  The system has adapted to our
    existence, but it still has not changed in
    fundamental ways and nor have we changed it in
    fundamental ways.  We are freer than we were in the
   forties and sixties, the seventies and eighties,
   but we still have failed to realize true
   recognition as moral, healthy, natural, normal
   human beings, which I think is the goal of our
   movement.  At least I claim it as that.  <p>
              The modern black civil rights movement,
   I think began to face a similar dilemma in the
   early sixties soon after the passage of major
   federal civil rights legislation, like the Civil
   Rights Act of 964 and the Voting Rights Act the
   next year.  Laws were changed, people's lives
   improved, but the economic condition of large
   numbers of African Americans remained the same and
   even deteriorated over the next 30 years.  Racial
   prejudice remained in place, even as its age old
  legal operation was dismantled.   <p>
           The women's liberation movement faced
    this moment in the late seventies as its national
    leadership targeted the ERA.  By the mid eighties
    the effort to pass the ERA had failed, the radical
    grassroots women's movement was splintered into
    warring single-issue factions and the term post
    feminism was more popular than feminist.
    Gender-based discrimination, sexism and violence
    persisted, even as women's participation in all
  aspects of cultural life increased. <p>
              I think today the gay and lesbian, our
   sexual transgender movement is in the middle of a
   similarly decisive moment.  And we can choose in
   this moment to follow the path our predecessors
   have paved of pursuing incremental legal and
   legislative reform, of increasing gay visibility,
   of pressing for fair treatment.  I mean, and I
   think we must continue along this path.  But I want
   to suggest that we have to do more.  And I think
  what we have to do more -- what we have to do is
   reach beyond the civil rights framework of
   mainstream integration, beyond the partial equality
   it delivers and imagine -- and reconnect ourselves
   to the different framework, which is:  Genuine
   social change or liberation.<p>
            I think at this contradictory juncture
   it behooves us to re-examine long held assumptions
   about our politics, our identities, our strategies
    and our social agenda and to define a new and
    broader moral vision as a gay and lesbian
    movement.  In other words, instead of asking the
    question that we have chanted for 50 years, "What
    do we want and when do we want it?"  And answering,
    "Gay rights now."  <p>
              I suggest the time has come for us to
   ask and answer:  What do we represent as gay
   people?  For what vision of society do we fight?
   How does a freedom-based movement differ from a
   rights-based movement and what will it mean for us,
   for our nation and for the world to accept
   homosexuality as morally, politically and socially
   equal to heterosexuality?     <p>
              That's a far more threatening question.
   Indeed, that's the question that our enemies ask.
   That's the truth on which they wage the debate, is
   they say we represent a true danger.  And we say,
   oh, no, we're just like you.<p>
              It doesn't work.  We don't respond to
   their argument.    <p>
              So answering these questions, I think
    requires us to examine the whole idea of
    mainstreaming.  Now, I think that the military
   experience of '93 and '94 revealed the inadequacy
   of our mainstreaming.  In that political loss, even
   though it was a cultural win, because the
    conversation about homosexuality took place at the
    kitchen tables of every -- practically every home,
    because we were in the news every day.  So in that
    sense it's a cultural victory, to be talking about
   homosexuality.  But it was undeniably a political
   loss.  In that political loss our movement learned
   that we had neither overcome the negative cultural
   images of homosexuality held by so many, nor had we
   created a powerful movement that could exert its
   muscle in a major domestic policy battle.  <p>
              Please feel free to disagree.     <p>
              Many of us viewed -- I mean, you're not
   shocked, we've had this argument before.  We've had
   this conversation before.  <p>
              Many of us viewed the fight to lift the
  ban as a logical step in our civil rights
  strategy.  Yet despite the years of groundwork by
   gay and lesbian veterans and many of you who have
   brought lawsuits to challenge the policy, despite
   the political work of people like Tom and Chai and
 activism in the military -- you know, the Campaign
    for Military Service, and despite the huge
    visibility of the issue in the '92 campaign or the
    '93 March on Washington, we ran up against the
    most abject stereotypes of gay men and lesbians.
    You know, when soldiers begin talking about showers
    and foxholes, whatever mainstream legitimacy we had
    assumed, whatever straight tolerance we thought we
    had earned vanished.  <p>
              Arguing this undeniably square issue in
   the language of fairness and civil rights, we were
   brought face-to-face with our essential queerness,
   that which is the most marginalized about us still,
   our sexualities.   <p>
              Indeed, the military fight resulted in
   the reaffirmation, not only of the ban on gay
   people in the military, but it added new
   restrictions to anti-gay codes, which will be, I
   think, declared unconstitutional but -- I mean,
   they have been, but -- and I think that -- I hope,
  I pray they will be upheld.      <p>
              Today someone can be kicked out not just
   for being gay or engaging in gay/lesbian sex, but
   for acting gay, declaring they are gay or for being
   perceived to have done so.  So I think we should
   question whether -- in a conceptual sense --
    whether the civil rights paradigm alone is the best
    vehicle to win genuine gay/lesbian freedom.       <p>
               Now, given this audience, I appreciate
    the heresy of what I am proposing, okay?  So don't
    get me wrong.  I am not arguing that we must
    abandon civil rights.  I am arguing that we must
    supplement it.  Absolutely, we cannot abandon the
    work that we have been doing, it is just beginning
   to incrementally succeed.  But I do not believe
  that that civil rights strategy on its own or the
  strategy of political and legislative mainstreaming
   on its own will result in what I think our goals
   should be, which is the true equality of lesbian
   and gay people in every aspect of life. <p>
              This tension between civil rights
   strategy and social change strategies is an old one
   in the queer movement.  I mean, it's old.  It goes
   back; it goes back.  And it's still going on.  So
   I'm just weighing in in its modern day version.        <p>
             That's the general, conceptual
  paradigmatic shift that I think we ought to
   consider and debate.  Unlike gay rights alone,
   liberation stands for a broader set of cultural
   values, like political freedom for all, social
  justice and the rebuilding of community among gay,
    straight and bisexual people.  The struggle against
    racism, it stands -- it incorporates the struggle
    against sexism.  Liberation challenges us to
    articulate different codes of ethics and morality
    and individual responsibility. <p>
               In some ways, what I think we have to do
    as a movement is move from the political much more
    into the cultural.  And that's where I think the
   affiliates and your work in the nonlegal,
  nonpolitical -- extra political, if you will --
  context can be so valuable. <p>
              I want to give you four specific ideas
   about it and then we're going to open it up to your
   questions and comments and reactions.   <p>
              I really value nonlegal work, because I
   guess I'm in some ways a frustrated lawyer.  I
   always identify as an ex-lawyer.  I mean, I made it
   through that whole process and I was proud to work
   at the National Prison Project with an incredible
  legal staff, but I've always enjoyed organizing.
  And organizing is my passion.  The idea of bringing
   people together around an issue, identifying the
   problem and trying to creatively solve the problem
   is organizing.            <p>
            And I think that the affiliates nonlegal
    work on gay and lesbian issues involves four
    things:  Education, organizing, advocacy and
    building power, okay?   <p>
               Education is pretty self-explanatory.
    But I want to reiterate the point that so many
    people within the gay and lesbian community, within
    the progressive communities, liberals as well as
    uninterested or ignorant bystanders, just don't
   understand what gay rights means.  What do we mean
  by "gay and lesbian equality"?  What do we mean by
  "non-discrimination laws"?  What prejudice, what
   violence?  <p>
              That's the kind of basic education we
   still need and each of you has a role you can play
   in that.  Every chapter, every affiliate can
   sponsor talks.  It's just that repetition is the
   only way we're going to get through, you know, and
   that kind of grassroots repetition about this is
   what is going on in our community, this is the kind
  of prejudice people are living with, or the lack of
  protections, and this is what it means in real
   people's lives, will make a tremendous difference.
   The polls show that people just don't know that or
   don't believe it, so that kind of a political
  education is really important. <p>
               Another kind of education that I know
   every affiliate does, is education of the media,
   and that is vitally important.  So we need you very
    much, all the executive directors of the
    affiliates, all the staff members, to speak out
    about gay and lesbian issues whenever you do any
    interviews.  Weave it in, come on, you can do it.
    Even if it's not directly on point, weave it in as
   an issue that the affiliate cares about, that the
  ACLU cares about.  It's a really important,
  practical thing that has an impact. <p>
              On the issue of organizing, I'm
   including coalition building in that organizing,
   and I think that that is one of the most important
   roles that a presumptively straight organization
   like the ACLU -- you know, I mean I'm just joking,
   of course --     <p>
              [ LAUGHTER ].  <p>
               -- that a non-gay identified
  organization like the American Civil Liberties
  Union can take an enormous leadership role.  And
   it's a role that's needed.  When Chai describes how
   recent the LCCR's commitment on lesbian and gay
   rights issues is -- I mean, 1992, we're at 1995 --
 you can see how new it is for non-gay allies to
    step forward and say:  Yeah, this is preposterous.
    You know, we oppose homophobic discrimination,
    period.  <p>
               And we need you to do that.  We need you
    to convene the coalitions.  Because it's one thing
    for me, as a lesbian, to call up all the nonprofit
    organizations in my community and say NAACP, labor,
    you know, women's rights organizations, come on
   over, we're going to get together and talk about
  how we can work together in Massachusetts, where I
  live.    <p>
              Because he's no friend, I'm sorry.  More
   on that in the question and answer period.   <p>
              [ LAUGHTER ].<p>
              I mean, I don't consider a guy who says
   he supports gay rights, but dismantles the rights
   of -- I mean, like destroys the welfare programs in
   the state, destroys education, privatizes
   everything, I don't consider him a champion of gay
  rights.<p>
             [ APPLAUSE ].       <p>
              And that's what I'm talking about, in
   terms of a shift in the way we look at our
   movement.  If what we're about is social change,
 these rights are indivisible, so that's -- I'll
    stop preaching.  <p>
               But the coalition building piece, the
    leadership role that you can play is invaluable.
    It means a lot -- it means something else for the
    Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts to convene
    such a meeting as I was describing.  And it carries
    so much clout, more clout to state legislators, to
    the state's media, and even to your members.  It's
   really important.       <p>
              The third area that I mentioned was
   advocacy.  Now, that is a directly legislative role
   that I really urge you to play more.  Every single
   state legislature has faced AIDS legislation, you
   know it, you've been dealing with it, and it's
   going to be facing more and more gay legislation,
   both pro-active and pro gay, as well as anti gay.
   And Matt's project is the absolute best resource
   you have within the agency to know how to respond
   to that kind of legislative effort.  But we also --
   I mean, just the basic kinds of stuff that you do,
   again, carry the gay and lesbian agenda in with you
   when you walk in to talk with legislators about
   anything, make sure it's included.  Talk about the
   positions -- the realities of gay people.
   Commission surveys to find out, if there's no data
    in the state.  Be a resource for the media and for
    state legislators.  Push politicians, we've got to
    do that at the state level. <p>
               Finally, the whole thing about power.
    June Jordan is a wonderful poet, says "There is
    difference and there is power, and who holds the
    power defines the meaning of the difference."
    Okay?  I'm interested in all of us, as progressive
   people, being much more straightforward about a
  movement for power.  In many ways that is going to
  require an electoral consciousness, if you will.
   We've got to register people to vote.  We've got to
   have, and see ourselves, our membership lists as a
   source of power.  And I'm not so sure that we have
   used those in that way.   <p>
              In every federal gay rights measure that
   I've worked on or seen my colleagues work on, we
   have not been able to generate grassroots support.
   Letters, phone calls, E-mail just haven't been
  flooding in from supporters of lesbian and gay
  rights.  Now, that happens at the same instance
   that we have the official support from
   organizations like the ACLU for these bills, like
   the NAACP, NOW and all these organizations.  There
  is somehow a disjunction between the organization
     support and it getting down to the level of members
    and our communication to those members to say write
    to the federal legislators or the state legislators
    in support of this measure.      <p>
               We've got to use our mailing lists and
    our memberships in a much more concerted way for
    political ends, and not be afraid of that.  What
    are we afraid of?  The Christian right does it all
   the time, their tax status doesn't suffer.  I don't
  know.     <p>
             But I just think the building of power
   is what progressives, frankly, have not been
   doing.  And to do that, I feel, requires a shift in
   all of our ways of thinking about our work.  We are
   an opposition movement.  This organization, in my
   view, represents an opposition to the politics that
   are in power in Washington today.  And I think we
   have to take our role much more consciously as
   leaders and organizers of that opposition.        <p>
             Thank you very much.    <p>
             [ APPLAUSE ]   <p>
</blockquote>



