<TITLE>Sima Rabinovicz Story</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<blockquote>
<img src="/graphics/courthdr.gif">
<CENTER><H2>ACLU Client - Sima Rabinovicz</H2></CENTER>
<font size=4>
<img src="/graphics/sima.jpg"i align=left><blockquote>A Russian immigrant, Sima has been called the Jewish Rosa Parks -- recalling
the African American woman who sparked a 1960s boycott that eventually
desegregated public transportation in Birmingham, Alabama.  Rabinovicz
commuted daily from her suburban home to her city job on a bus that had a
curtain separating men from women.  The curtain accomodated Hasidic riders,
whose religion requires the sexes to pray separately.  Told to change her
seat one day in December 1993, Rabinovicz refused, saying later, "I didn't
feel it was right just because I'm a woman for them to tell me what to do."
She won her civil rights lawsuit, brought by the ACLU. </font>
</blockquote><P><br clear=all><br>

