<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU Press Release -  09/01/96 -- Background:  Congress Considers
Anti-Gay Marriage Bill and Employment Non-Discrimination </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/graphics/pressrel.gif">
<CENTER>
<H2>ACLU Background Briefing:<BR>Congress Considers Anti-Gay Marriage Bill and
Employment Non-Discrimination Act</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> <B>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>August 6, 1996</B></P>
<P></P>
<P>WASHINGTON -- Congress is currently considering legislation that would deny
Federal recognition of marriages between same-sex couples, and allow states to
ignore such marriages performed in any other state.  The American Civil
Liberties Union believes that the so-called Defense of Marriage Act (DOMA) is
unconstitutional and bad public policy.</P>
<P>DOMA was approved by the House on July 13, and is now pending action by the
full Senate, where an amendment barring workplace bias against lesbian and gay
Americans is likely to be attached when Congress returns from its August recess.
The amendment, known as the Employment Non-Discrimination Act (ENDA), would
prohibit discrimination based on sexual orientation in all employment decisions,
such as hiring, termination and promotion.</P>
<P>ENDA addresses the serious problem of employment discrimination against gay
Americans.  Therefore, the ACLU is working to build support for the ENDA
amendment while vigorously continuing to oppose DOMA.  This background briefer
outlines both measures, and explains the ACLU's position in fuller detail.</P>
<H3>I.  THE ANTI-GAY PROPOSAL</H3>
<P>The only reason why the Defense of Marriage Act, S. 1740,  is being debated
now is election-year politics. The proposed legislation goes beyond legislators
saying they are not ready to accept same-sex marriages.  It is an unnecessary
and offensive attempt by anti-gay extremists in Congress to single out lesbian
and gay Americans to score political points.</P>
<P>The issue of gay marriages has arisen, in part, because of a ruling by the
Hawaii Supreme Court in May 1993 that denying marriage licenses to same-sex
couples may violate the state constitution's guarantee of equal protection.  But
a final ruling by the Hawaii courts is not expected for at least two years.  In
the meantime, no state currently recognizes marriages between gay Americans. 
Nonetheless, members of Congress are seeking to preempt such marriages before
any state permits them.</P>
<H3>The &quot;State Law&quot; Part of DOMA</H3>
<P>DOMA raises several serious constitutional and public policy concerns. The
first provision of the bill purports to allow states to ignore each other's
legal marriages.  Section 2 of the bill says:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;No State, territory, or possession of the United States, or Indian
tribe, shall be required to give effect to any public act, record, or judicial
proceeding of any other State, territory, possession, or tribe respecting a
relationship between persons of the same sex that is treated as a marriage under
the laws of such other State, territory, possession, or tribe, or a right or
claim arising from such relationship.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>DOMA Mocks &quot;Full Faith and Credit&quot;</H3>
<P>This provision of DOMA directly violates the Full Faith and Credit Clause of
the Constitution (Article IV, Section 1), which provides that the court
judgments of one state shall be recognized as valid in other states. The Clause
says:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Full Faith and credit shall be given in each state to the public acts,
records, and judicial proceedings of every other state.  And the Congress may by
general laws prescribe the manner in which such acts, records and proceedings
shall be proved, and the effect thereof.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The Full Faith and Credit clause was designed to ensure that the United
States would operate as one nation, making sure states do not ignore the rights
and obligations imposed by sister states.  Congress has used its power to
enforce the Full Faith and Credit Clause on only four occasions -- and only when
it sought to promote, not diminish,  uniformity among the states.</P>
<P>The U.S. Supreme Court has consistently ruled that the Full Faith and Credit
Clause requires that each state  honor the court judgments of sister states.
Since the court has applied that rule in cases involving divorce, there can be
little question that DOMA violates Full Faith and Credit.</P>
<H3>DOMA Violates the Right To Travel</H3>
<P>The &quot;state law&quot; part of DOMA violates another cornerstone
principle of the Constitution: the right to travel, temporarily or permanently
from state to state.  By allowing states to ignore the legal marriages of
lesbian and gay couples, DOMA would create the absurd scenario of having a
couple's marital status depend on the state in which they happen to be at any
given moment.  It would force people who are transferred for work, or who want
to relocate near family, into the unfair position of having to choose between
their legal marriage and their career or family.  Similarly, DOMA would prevent
lesbian and gay couples from traveling through certain states if they want to
avoid the risk of being treated as strangers in an emergency or a crisis.</P>
<H3>The &quot;Federal Law&quot; Part of DOMA</H3>
<P>The second provision of the bill, Section 3, would define marriage for the
purposes of all federal laws and programs as a &quot;union between one man and
one woman.&quot; The provision states:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;In determining the meaning of any Act of Congress, or of any ruling,
regulation, or interpretation of the various administrative bureaus and agencies
of the United States, the word ?marriage' means only a legal union between one
man and one woman as husband and wife, and the word 'spouse' refers only to a
person of the opposite sex who is a husband or a wife.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This would be the first time in U.S. history that the Federal government
adopted a definition of marriage of any kind.  Until now, the Federal government
has always accepted state definitions of marriage for Federal law. DOMA  would
have the effect of treating all lesbian and gay couples as strangers under
Federal laws, denying them such basic considerations as:</P>
<UL>
<LI>bereavement or sick leave to take care for a partner or a partner's child;</LI>
<LI>pension or social security continuation when a partner dies;</LI>
<LI>the ability to keep a jointly owned home if a partner goes on Medicaid,
dies, or becomes sick;</LI>
<LI>joint tax returns and exemptions for primary relationships on estate taxes;</LI>
<LI>veteran's discounts on medical care, education, and home loans;</LI>
<LI>immigration and residency for partners from other countries.</LI></UL>
<P>This would create an unworkable set of legal and logistical problems in
determining estates, taxes, securities, property, debt, and insurance -- in
fact, any area that takes marriage into account.</P>
<H3>DOMA Violates Equal Protection</H3>
<P>The entire bill (both the state law and the federal law sections) violates
the Fifth Amendment guarantee of equal protection.  DOMA creates second- class
status for legally married same-sex couples, denying them all the
responsibilities and respect other married couples enjoy, for no reason other
than hostility and disapproval.  There can be little doubt that under Romer v.
Evans -- the 1996 Supreme Court decision striking down Colorado's anti-gay
Amendment 2 -- DOMA is unconstitutional.</P>
<H3>DOMA is Unfair</H3>
<P>Civil marriage is the way our society defines committed emotional
relationship.  Accordingly, we attach a wealth of legal and economic
consequences to it, ranging from visitation rights and parenting
responsibilities, to joint taxes and insurance coverage.  It is also the device
our society uses to identify partners for virtually every practical situation --
whether it be at the hospital, in emergency situations, or the home -- in which
it is important to identify the person who is closest to you.</P>
<P>For example, if you were not legally married to your partner, you could lose
your home despite having lived in it with a partner for 30 years because of
insurance or inheritance problems.  If you were not married, you could be denied
the right to take care of a sick or dying partner in most hospitals.  And in
many cases, you could even lose your children because the government does not
recognize your relationship.</P>
<P>It is fundamentally unfair to say, on the one hand, that you must marry to
be treated as next of kin, and then to deny an entire class of Americans -- who
are, for all practical purposes, each other's next of kin -- the right to marry.</P>
<H3>DOMA is Anti-Relationship</H3>
<P>Marriage is a basic human right that should be available to all Americans.  
Making a commitment to a life-long relationship is a fundamental human need that
should not be denied to anyone.  If two gay people want to get married, and take
responsibility for each other for better or worse, in sickness and in health,
why should the government legislate against their commitment?</P>
<P>While marriage has traditionally been defined as a union between people of
different sexes, it was also traditionally defined as between people of the same
race.  As recently as 1967, more than a dozen states had laws barring
interracial couples from marrying.   Marriage was also traditionally understood
to transform a woman into the property of the man.  But as our society evolved,
those &quot;traditional&quot; elements of marriage changed to reflect our belief
that people should be free to choose their life partner without government
intrusion.</P>
<P>For more than 200 years, Congress has left it to the states to decide who
they will marry, and to the courts to make sure they respect each other's
decisions.  That is a fine tradition that ought to be respected.  The proposed
legislation, however, throws that tradition on the trash heap and belittles the
relationship of lesbian and gay men.</P>
<H3>DOMA Summary</H3>
<P>DOMA is bad constitutional law and bad public policy.  It is an unnecessary
and offensive bill that would violate several core principles of our
Constitution in addition to creating an unworkable patchwork of government rules
and regulations for marriage.  Apart from being an unmistakable violation of the
Constitution, it is a deplorable act of hostility unworthy of support.  The bill
does nothing to &quot;defend&quot; marriages; it only attacks lesbian and gay
Americans.</P>
<H3>II.  A PRO-GAY AMENDMENT</H3>
<P>Most Americans agree that no one should face job discrimination for reasons
unrelated to their performance and ability.  But lesbians and gay men continue
to face severe discrimination in the workplace.   Even worse, there is no
federal law, and only a handful of states laws, that prohibit an employer from
firing someone simply because he or she is gay.</P>
<P>The Employment Non-Discrimination Act, or ENDA, would address this pressing
concern. Senators Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.), Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.), and
James Jeffords (R-Vt.) intend to offer ENDA as an amendment to the anti-gay
marriage bill if it reaches the Senate floor.</P>
<P>The amendment would outlaw employment discrimination based on sexual
orientation, in much the same way that Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964
outlawed discrimination on the basis of race, religion and gender.  The core
section of ENDA is found in Section 2:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>A covered entity, in connection with employment or employment opportunities,
shall not --</P>
<P>(1) subject an individual to different standards or treatment on the basis
of sexual orientation;</P>
<P>(2) discriminate against an individual based on the sexual orientation of
persons with whom such an individual is believed to associate or to have
associated; or</P>
<P>(3) otherwise discriminate against an individual on the basis of sexual
orientation</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>ENDA is narrowly tailored to deal only with discrimination in employment
decisions, such as hiring, termination, promotion and compensation. While
extremists have sought to paint ENDA as an affirmative action policy for
lesbians and gay men, the proposed amendment explicitly prohibits preferential
treatment for gay workers. Furthermore, the amendment makes exemptions for the
military and religious organizations.</P>
<P>The definition of &quot;employers&quot; covered under ENDA is the same
definition of &quot;employer&quot; used in Title VII. Small businesses with
fewer than 15 employees are exempt.  Finally, the measure does not require
businesses to provide equal fringe benefits to the partners of lesbian and gay
workers (although hundreds of companies -- including half of the Fortune 500 --
have already done so voluntarily as a good business measure).</P>
<H3>ENDA Addresses Widespread Problem</H3>
<P>Workplace discrimination based on sexual orientation is prevalent throughout
the nation.  Many businesses continue to fire lesbian and gay employees without
apology, and some states even maintain policies that exclude gay people from
certain positions.  Every year, untold numbers of lesbian and gay Americans are
passed over for promotion and are denied equal pay or equal work.</P>
<P>The ACLU's Lesbian and Gay Rights Project and its affiliate offices are
involved in more than a dozen workplace bias lawsuits, including:</P>
<P><B>Sension v. University of Denver (Colorado):</B> Mark Sension was hired
in June 1994 by the University of Denver to be  an associate director at a
private school run by the university. About a month later, shortly after he told
his supervisor that he is gay, Sension was fired without warning and escorted
from the university grounds by security personnel.  The supervisor claims that
Sension's firing was &quot;an issue of trust,&quot; since she was not made aware
of his sexual orientation before Sension was hired.</P>
<P><B>Blain v. Golden State Container, Inc. (Arizona):</B> Jeffrey Blain was
hired in January 1993 to work in sales for Golden State Container, a
Phoenix-area manufacturer.  He had a good work record, receiving a 37.5 percent
raise during his first six months.  But several months later, the company fired
him for no reason.  Blain took Golden State to court, claiming that he was fired
because he is a gay man.  The judge instructed the jury that &quot;an employee
is not wrongfully terminated if he is fired for being homosexual.&quot;  Blain
lost his case.</P>
<P><B>Shahar v. Bowers (Georgia):</B> Robin Shahar graduated as an honor
student from Emory Law School in 1991, and accepted a job offer as a staff
attorney with the Georgia Attorney General, Michael Bowers.  But before she
started work, Bowers found out that Shahar had participated in a commitment
ceremony with her lesbian partner, and fired her.  Although Georgia does not
offer job bias protection for gays, the ACLU brought a federal lawsuit claiming
that Shahar's constitutional rights were violated.  The appeal is pending.</P>
<P>These cases, of course, represent only the tip of the iceberg.  Every year ,
the ACLU receives hundreds of phone calls from people who have been
discriminated against because of their sexual orientation -- more than any other
gay-related claim.  The ENDA amendment would confront a serious issue of
unfairness that persists in the American workplace.</P>
<H3>ENDA Provides Much Needed Protection</H3>
<P>As the cases above illustrate, lesbian and gay workers have few legal
protections when they are discriminated against on the job.  Nine states, the
District of Columbia, and about 160 local jurisdictions currently have
non-discrimination laws on the books protecting gays workers: California,
Connecticut, Hawaii, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Jersey, Rhode Island,
Vermont.  While this represents significant progress, this also means that
forty-one states don't have any such laws. In other words, a gay person in those
states (and not in a place with a local law) may be legally fired simply because
of his/her sexual orientation.</P>
<P>In addition, there is no Federal statute protecting lesbians and gay men
from bias in the workplace.  A U.S. postal worker, for example, can be
terminated anywhere in this country without cause if his or her supervisor
decided that a gay person should not be delivering mail.</P>

<P>Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 provides basic legal protections
against employment discrimination on the basis of race, gender, religion,
national origin, or disability, but not sexual orientation.  Using Title VII as
a template, the ENDA amendment would prohibit discrimination on the basis of
sexual orientation, proving basic protection to ensure fairness in the workplace
for Americans who are currently denied equal protection under the law.</P>
<H3>ENDA Enjoys Broad Support</H3>
<P>ENDA is supported by the overwhelming majority of Americans.  According to a
recent Newsweek poll, 84 percent of Americans who voted last year also support
equal rights for lesbians and gay men in the workplace.</P>
<P>Furthermore, ENDA currently has 137 co-sponsors in the House and 30
co-sponsors in the Senate. ENDA also has the endorsement of President Clinton,
who said in October 1995 that the bill would provide much needed legal
protection, as well as ensure that &quot;all Americans, regardless of their
sexual orientation, can find and keep their jobs based on their ability to work
and the quality of their work.&quot; Other notable supporters include Coretta
Scott King, New Jersey Governor Christine Todd Whitman, and former Senator Barry
Goldwater.</P>
<P>Although only nine states have laws barring workplace discrimination based
on sexual orientation, such laws have been adopted by cities and counties --
small and large -- across the country.  Beginning with East Lansing, Michigan in
1972, more than 160 local jurisdictions today have recognized this problem and
passed legislation to include gays and lesbians in their laws against workplace
discrimination.</P>
<P>Recognizing that job discrimination also leads to bad business, more than
1,000 U.S. companies have adopted non-discrimination policies that include
sexual orientation.  A report released by the Human Rights Campaign, a national
gay rights group, found that more than half of the nation's Fortune 500
companies have already adopted similar non-discrimination policies.  ENDA also
has the endorsement of more than two dozen leading U.S. corporations, including
AT&amp;T, Eastman Kodak, Merrill Lynch, Microsoft, RJR Nabisco and Xerox.</P>
<P>Finally, numerous labor unions, religious organizations, civil rights
organizations and newspaper editorials have endorsed ENDA, and it is among the
top legislative priorities of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights.</P>
<H3>ENDA Conclusion</H3>
<P>All Americans have a right to be treated equally and fairly at the
workplace, regardless of their sexual orientation.  The ENDA amendment offers
basic civil rights protections for lesbian and gay Americans, and provides
much-needed recourse when they are discriminated against at their jobs.  It is a
reasoned and balanced approach to remedying a serious workplace problem. 
Congress should act immediately to ensure that gay Americans are judged by their
ability and performance on the job, and not by the prejudices of some employers.</P>
<H3>ENDA Conclusion</H3>
<P>All Americans have a right to be treated equally and fairly at the
workplace, regardless of their sexual orientation.  The ENDA amendment offers
basic civil rights protections for lesbian and gay Americans, and provides
much-needed recourse when they are discriminated against at their jobs.  It is a
reasoned and balanced approach to remedying a serious workplace problem. 
Congress should act immediately to ensure that gay Americans are judged by their
ability and performance on the job, and not by the prejudices of some employers.</P>
<H3>CONCLUSION</H3>
<P>DOMA is a divisive and offensive attempt to vilify the relationships of
lesbian and gay American in order to manufacture a political wedge issue. 
Moreover, DOMA is bad law and even worse public policy.  It flouts several basic
constitutional guarantees that hold our nation together and keep the promise of
equality alive for all Americans.  The ACLU considers DOMA to be one of the
worst and most hostile attacks on gay Americans by any Congress in American
history.  Therefore, the ACLU has placed defeating the bill among its top
legislative priorities for 1996, and is urging Congress in the strongest
possible terms to abandon it.</P>
<P>For those in Congress who insist on supporting DOMA, ENDA addresses a
widespread problem in the workplace, and provides basic legal protection for
employees who are currently denied equal protection under the law.  While DOMA
serves to further discriminate against a group of Americans, ENDA ensures that
all Americans are treated fairly and equally on the job regardless of sexual
orientation.  Therefore, the ACLU is urging Congress to attach ENDA to the
anti-gay marriage bill, and outlaw a pervasive problem in the nation's
workplace.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P></P>
