<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fact Sheet: Able v. USA</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/graphics/courthdr.gif"></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">Fact Sheet: Able v. USA</H2>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B>Facial Challenge to the Military's &quot;Don't Ask, Don't
Tell&quot; </B></P>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">Ban on Lesbian and Gay Servicemembers</H3>
<H4>The Case.</H4>
<P>Filed in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of New York, <I>Able
v. USA</I> challenges the constitutionality of the military's latest ban on open
lesbian and gay service members, which was signed into law by President Clinton
in 1993.</P>
<P>The Lesbian and Gay Rights Project of the American Civil Liberties Union and
Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, the national gay legal organization,
represent six lesbian and gay plaintiffs -- two active and four reservist.</P>
<P>The plaintiffs contend that the law is discriminatory and violates their
constitutional rights to equal protection and free speech and the rights of all
lesbian and gay men in the service.  They further contend that the statute and
regulations serve no legitimate military interest, impose punitive rules on
lesbian and gay service members that are unrelated to the ability to serve, and
are solely based on prejudice. In addition, plaintiffs intend to prove at trial
that the statute and regulations unconstitutionally burden and chill the speech
and expression of gay and lesbian service members.  <I>(Able et al v. USA, U.S.
Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit, 95-9111 (L))</I></P>
<P><B>The Legislation.</B></P>
<P>The &quot;National Defense Authorization Act,&quot; the current statute that
bars lesbians and gay men from openly serving their country, was passed by
Congress on November 17, 1993. The presence of openly gay and lesbian service
members, according to the law's stated rationale, assertedly poses &quot;an
unacceptable risk to the high standards of morale, good order and discipline,
and unit cohesion that are the essence of military capability....&quot; because
of the discomfort their mere presence supposedly causes heterosexual soldiers
and sailors.</P>
<P>The Act mandates that a service member &quot;shall be separated&quot; if one
or more of three findings is made: (1) that the &quot;member has engaged in, 
attempted to engage in, or solicited another to engage in a homosexual act or
acts,&quot; (2) that the &quot;member has stated that he or she is a homosexual
or bisexual, or words to that effect,&quot; (3) that the &quot;member has
married or attempted to marry a person known to be of the same biological sex.&quot;</P>
<P>Plaintiffs allege that the Act and regulations violate their constitutional
rights in the following ways: (1) they violate the Fifth Amendment, which
provides for equal protection of the law because they intentionally discriminate
against gay and lesbian service members and subject them to different and
punitive treatment, (2) they violate their First Amendment rights of free speech
and free expression because they proscribe, punish and chill all public and
private speech and expressive behavior that would tend to identify them as gay
men or lesbians, and do so on the basis of the content and viewpoint of such
speech and expression, and (3) they violate First and Fifth Amendment right of
expressive association because they punish any associational  activity that
might identify plaintiffs as lesbian or gay service members.</P>
<P>Passage of the statute marked the first time in our nation's history that
the military's anti-gay discrimination had been codified in federal law, making
the armed services, which together are the largest employer in the country, one

of the last bastions of official, governmentally sanctioned discrimination in
America.</P>
<H4>The Plaintiffs.</H4>
<P><B>&#183; Jane Able, U.S. Army Reserves Lieutenant Colonel.</B>  Lieutenant
Colonel Able commands a battalion, has served for more than 20 years in the Army
and Army Reserves, and is based on the West Coast. (Jane Able is a pseudonym.)</P>
<P><B>&#183; Robert Heigl, U.S. Coast Guard Petty Officer.</B> Petty Officer
Heigl, U.S.C.G., has served on active duty as a corpsman at the Governor's
Island Coast Guard facility.  He resides in the New York.</P>
<P><B>&#183; Kenneth Osborn, U.S. Army Reserves Captain</B>. Captain Osborn, a
citizen of California, serves with the 155th Corps Support Battalion
Headquarters, South El Monte, California.  He has been a member of the Army
Reserve since 1986. Prior to 1986, he served two and a half years with the
United States Marine Corps Reserve.</P>
<P><B>&#183; Stephen Spencer, U.S. Army Reserves Sergeant</B>. Sergeant
Spencer, who lives in the State of Washington, served from 1990 to 1992 as a
combat medic and, since 1992, has served as a licensed practical nurse with the
164th Mobile Army Surgical Hospital at Camp Murray, Washington. He served on
active duty with the United States Army from 1987 to 1990.</P>
<P><B>&#183; Richard von Wohld, U.S. Navy Reserves Lieutenant Commander</B>.
Lieutenant Commander von Wohld lives in California and has served as a naval
Flight Officer with Patrol Squadron 91, a reserve squadron at Naval Air Station
Moffett Field, California. He enlisted in the United States Navy in 1979, earned
an appointment to the United States Naval Academy in 1981, was commissioned as
an Ensign in 1985 and served on active duty in the United States Navy until
April 1993.</P>
<P><B>&#183; Werner Zehr, U.S. Navy Seaman</B>. Seaman Zehr is now stationed
in Florida.  Previously he served with Surface Group 6, Fort Wadsworth, Staten
Island, New York. Prior to his recent reassignment, he served as a quartermaster
on the U.S.S. Clifton Sprague. He enlisted in the United States Navy in November
1991.</P>
<P></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
