<CENTER><A NAME="introduction"></A> 
<H3>INTRODUCTION</H3></CENTER>
<H4>The docket.</H4>
<P>This docket summarizes the work of the American Civil Liberties Union's
National Lesbian and Gay Rights Project and the work of the ACLU's 53 state
affiliates on gay rights issues.  The ACLU works on more lesbian and gay related
litigation and legislation than any other organization.  </P>
<P>The docket focuses primarily on litigation, but it also includes summaries
of some of the legislative advocacy undertaken by the state affiliates.  The
docket is organized by subject, and within each subject by state. It was
compiled during the summer of 1996, with an effective cut-off date of September
15, 1996.</P>
<H4>The staff.</H4>
<P>The Lesbian and Gay Rights Project, based in New York, coordinates the
ACLU's gay-related work nationwide.  <B>Matt Coles</B> is the Director, <B>Michael
Adams</B> and <B>Marc Elovitz</B> are Staff Counsel.  <B>H. Alexander Robinson</B>
is the Project's legislative representative in Washington, D.C.  <B>Denny Lee</B>
handles media relations.<B>  Ben Dinglasan</B> is the Development Associate,
and <B>Jerl Surratt</B> is the Project's Development Consultant.  Three ACLU
affiliates have lawyers who specialize in lesbian and gay rights: <B>Roger
Leishman</B> at the ACLU of Illinois, <B>Kelli Evans</B> at the ACLU of
Northern California, and <B>Taylor Flynn</B> at the ACLU of Southern
California.</P>
<H4>The supporters.</H4>
<P>The Lesbian and Gay Rights Project is largely supported by individuals and a
few Foundations.  We are deeply grateful for the support of the Projects' major
donors, the Friends and Associates.  The ACLU is able to do all the work it does
because of the many lawyers who volunteer their time as cooperating attorneys. 
We have only been able to mention the names of some of the scores of cooperating
attorneys here.  We are deeply grateful to all of them for the time they give
us.</P>
<H4> We Need Your Help</H4>
<P>Like all ACLU special projects, the Lesbian and Gay Rights Project is funded
solely by contributions specifically designated for it.  The ACLU accepts no
government money of any kind; it depends entirely on gifts from individuals and
a small number of foundations.  The Project's ability to work toward equality
depends on your willingness to support it.</P>
<H4>Why Give To the Project</H4>
<P>Because it is a part of the ACLU, the Project brings a unique voice to the
fight for lesbian and gay rights.  The ACLU puts lesbian and gay rights in
context as part of a larger program to preserve and promote basic rights for all
Americans.  Because of its strong national presence and its nationwide affiliate
 network, the ACLU can respond to discrimination whenever it occurs. </P>
<H4>Ways to Help</H4>
<P>Contributions to the ACLU's Lesbian and Gay Rights Project are
tax-deductible, and support both national and local work.  The Project has a
FRIENDS group for those who contribute $1,000 or more per year, and an
ASSOCIATES group for those who give $500 or more per year, but every
contribution helps.  We can also provide help with bequests, life income and
other planned gifts which may have unique tax and financial benefits.  </P>
<P>Please print the coupon below to request additional information by postal
mail.</P>
