<CENTER>
<H2>SPOTLIGHT ON 1996</H2></CENTER>
<H3><A NAME="romer"></A>Our Finest Day In Court:<BR>Romer v.  Evans</H3>
<P>In what is doubtless the most important lesbian and gay rights case ever,
the U.S. Supreme Court struck down Colorado's Amendment 2 in <I>Romer v. Evans</I>.
 Amendment 2, passed by the voters in 1992, would have deprived every branch of
government of the power to protect lesbians and gay men from discrimination. 
When it passed, it was immediately challenged by a coalition of groups including
the National ACLU Lesbian &amp; Gay Rights Project, the ACLU of Colorado, the
ACLU of Northern California, Lambda Legal Defense and a coalition of Colorado
groups.</P>
<P>	After the Colorado Supreme Court twice upheld lower court orders preventing
Amendment 2 from taking effect, the state appealed to the U.S. Supreme Court. 
In a sweeping 6-3 decision, the court struck Amendment 2 down for good.  It gave
two reasons for doing so.  First, it said, devices which take away all of a
state's power to protect any group from discrimination are simply inconsistent 
with the very idea of &quot;equal protection of the law.&quot;  That is good
news indeed.  It means neither gay people nor anyone else will ever have to face
another initiative designed to prevent them from ever being protected by civil
rights laws.</P>
<P>	The Court's second reason for striking down Amendment 2 was that its
different treatment of lesbians, gay men and bisexuals was motivated by
hostility.  Animosity, the court said, is never a legitimate reason for treating
one group of Americans differently.  </P>
<P>	This part of the decision will be very important in all sorts of future

cases involving lesbians and gay men.  For ten years now (since the Supreme
Court decision in <I>Bowers v. Hardwick</I> upholding Georgia's sodomy law)
cities, states and the federal government have been allowed to justify
discrimination in everything from child custody to employment by saying that
society disapproves of gay people.  That day is over.  From now on, dislike,
disapproval, etc. will not be enough.  Government will need <I>legitimate</I>
reasons for treating lesbian, gay and bisexual Americans differently.  </P>
<P>	This doesn't mean we will necessarily win all of these cases; the
government will make other arguments that discrimination serves legitimate
purposes, and we will have to fight them.  But the <I>Romer</I> decision does
take away the &quot;slam dunk&quot; defense the government have had up until
now.</P>
<P>	But the tone of the <I>Romer</I> opinion, and what it says about the
movement for lesbian and gay equality, may prove to be the most important part
of the decision.  The court decided to take on the argument that protecting
lesbians and gay men from discrimination is &quot;special rights.&quot;  It gave
the most eloquent answer to that slogan that anyone has given so far.</P>
<P>	The right to be able to work, to have a home, to eat in a restaurant
without fear of being thrown out because of who you are, is, the court said,
taken for granted by most of us.  We either have that right in law, or we have
no need for it because we do not face that kind of discrimination. But to those
who do face it, civil rights laws are the only thing preventing exclusion from
the limitless activities that &quot;constitute ordinary life in a free society.&quot;
 &quot;We find nothing special,&quot; the court said, &quot;in the protections
Amendment 2 withholds.&quot;</P>
<P>	It is important to keep these words in context.  The decision does not say
that lesbians and gay men are now legally protected from discrimination. 
Amendment 2 said neither cities nor the state of Colorado itself would ever have
the power to protect gay people from discrimination.  The Supreme Court ruled
that the power of government to decide that we should be protected can not be
taken away.  Whether we will be protected is up to lower courts, legislatures,
city councils and Congress.  Which means, of course, that it is up to us to
convince them.
</P>
<P>	In effect, the court gave us the &quot;level playing field&quot; we were
asking for.  But it sent us back into the fray with a boost of inestimable
value.  For in addition to its powerful answer to the special rights argument,
the Court gave us a remarkable, deeply stirring statement about the legitimacy
of our case for equality.</P>
<P>	Justice Kennedy began his opinion for the court by invoking the most famous
dissent in American legal history: Justice Harlan's opinion in <I>Plessy v.
Ferguson</I>, the case that upheld racial segregation.  &quot;One century ago,&quot;
Justice Kennedy wrote, &quot;the first Justice Harlan admonished this Court that
the Constitution 'neither knows nor tolerates classes among citizens.'  <I>Plessy
v. Ferguson</I>, 163 U.S. 537, 559 (1896) (dissenting opinion).&quot;  Although
those words were unheeded at the time, Kennedy wrote, our acceptance of their
wisdom today requires that Amendment 2 be struck down.</P>
<P>	The message could not be much plainer.  The closest thing we have to an
institutional conscience in this country says that discrimination against
lesbians and gay men is wrong, the moral equivalent of race and sex
discrimination.  That is the single most powerful thing any institution has ever
said about our fight for equality.  Now it is up to us to make the most of the
it.</P>
<P></P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="military"></A> &quot;Don't Ask, Don't Tell&quot; --<BR>The
Overall Picture</H3>
<P>The &quot;don't ask, don't tell&quot; ban on gays in the military has two
parts.  The so-called &quot;statements&quot; part says that gay men and lesbians
may not say or do anything which reveals that they are gay.  The second, the
so-called &quot;conduct&quot; part says that lesbians and gay men may not do
anything affectionate or sexual with each other.  It also says that gay people
who engage in misconduct, like sexual harassment, will be punished more harshly
than heterosexuals who do the same thing.</P>
<P>	Until <B><I>Able v. USA</I></B>, most attacks on anti-gay military
policies focused on the statements ban (the first part), arguing that it was a
violation of due process and freedom of expression to exclude lesbians and gay
men just for being gay or talking about it.  The military responded, with an
argument accepted so far by every federal appeals court, that it was ejecting
gay people because it was reasonable to assume that someone who said he or she
was lesbian or gay was more likely than someone else to violate the conduct
rule.  </P>
<P>	<I>Able</I>, the joint challenge put together by the ACLU Lesbian and Gay
Rights Project and Lambda Legal Defense takes a new approach.  Building on the
Congressional record from the 1994 hearings on &quot;don't ask, don't tell,&quot;
the case maintains that it simply is not correct to say that the military ejects
lesbians and gay men because it believes we will violate the conduct rules.  The
only reason behind the ban (both the conduct and the statements portions), we
argue, is the military's belief that heterosexuals will be so disconcerted if
they <I>know</I> they are serving with lesbians and gay men that they, the
heterosexuals, will be unable to do their jobs.  That means, <I>Able</I>
argues, that the only purpose of the policy is to prevent communication, and it
should fail under the First Amendment for that reason.</P>

<P>	Equally important, the <I>Able</I> case argues, the &quot;conduct&quot;
rules themselves are unconstitutional.  The only reason for having a different
set of rules about affectionate and sexual conduct is that the military believes
that heterosexual troops disapprove of both sex and affection by lesbians and
gay men.  But, we argue, discrimination against one group of Americans can never
be justified on the basis that another group disapproves of them.</P>
<P>	The District Court in Brooklyn accepted the first argument, and struck down
the policy without reaching the second.  In July, the United States Court of
Appeals for the Second Circuit sent the case back to District Court.  The Second
Circuit accepted as plausible the government's argument that it was using &quot;statements&quot;
to identify people who might violate the conduct rules.  But the court said,
that begged the question of whether the different conduct rules were
constitutional.  The Court sent the case back to the District Court for a
decision on that issue.</P>
<P>	<B><I>Philips v. Perry</I></B>, a case being handled on appeal by the
ACLU Lesbian and Gay Rights Project, only challenges the conduct portion of the
law.  When asked, Petty Officer Philips said that he had been intimate with
other men, although never on board a ship, on duty, or with another service
member.  This case takes the same approach that <I>Able</I> takes.  It was
argued before the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit in March.</P>
<P>	In <B><I>Thomasson v. Perry</I></B>, the full United States Court of
Appeals for the Fourth Circuit upheld the policy in the face of an attack on the
&quot;statements&quot; rule.  The plaintiff has asked the U.S. Supreme Court to
take the case.  The ACLU and Lambda filed a &quot;friend of the court&quot;
brief making arguments similar to those made in <I>Able</I>.  	</P>
<P>	<B><I>Richenberg v. Perry</I></B> is another &quot;statements&quot; case.
 The United States Court of Appeals for the Eight Circuit upheld the policy,
over one dissenting opinion.  The ACLU and Lambda filed a &quot;friend of the
court&quot; brief making arguments similar to those made in <I>Able</I>. </P>
<P>	<B><I>Holmes v. Perry</I></B> and <B><I>Watson v. Perry</I></B> are
pending before the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit. 
Although <I>Holmes</I> is a &quot;statements&quot; case, it takes an approach
similar to that taken in <I>Able</I>.  The trial court treated <I>Watson</I>
as a conduct case much like <I>Philips</I>, although the plaintiff insists that
it is a statements only case.  The ACLU and Lambda filed a &quot;friend of the
court&quot; brief making arguments similar to those made in <I>Able</I>. </P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="marriage"></A> DOMA &amp; ENDA: <BR> Not the Rout It Appeared to
Be</H3>
<P>To many, it looked at first glance like two crushing defeats on the same
day: Congress passed the so-called &quot;Defense of Marriage Act&quot; (DOMA),
designed to minimize recognition of lesbian and gay marriages when Hawaii
permits them, and the Senate failed to pass the Employment Non-Discrimination
Act (ENDA), the law which would have made it illegal to discriminate in
employment on the basis of sexual orientation.  </P>
<P>	But viewed in perspective, the ENDA vote has to be counted a win.  Some
version of the law has been in Congress every session since 1976.  The bill has
never gotten out of committee before.  This time, it was not only considered by
the full Senate, it came within a single vote of passage in a Republican
controlled Congress.  With this vote, there is a good chance that ENDA will move
along further in the next Congress.</P>
<P>	ENDA's strong showing was due in large part to the steadfast advocacy of
Senator Kennedy, support from a broad coalition of civil rights groups, and the
lobbying of the Human Rights Campaign (HRC).  The Project's Washington lobbyist
worked with HRC on passage, and for the first time, we marshaled affiliates in
an effort to lobby Congressmen and Senators on both DOMA and ENDA.  </P>
<P>	The Project's legal staff in New York helped HRC draft the original text,
and worked on amendments into the final days before the vote. The entire text
will be reviewed before the next Congress begins.   At the same time, ACLU
affiliates around the country will continue to work for state and local non-bias
laws in a continued push for ENDA.</P>
<P>	DOMA was a defeat, to be sure -- although there were actually more votes
against it than most people expected.  But the section of the law which purports
to allow states to ignore same-sex marriages performed in other states may not
mean very much.  Indeed, the battles over recognition are likely to turn on
state law and the federal constitution -- not DOMA.  The ACLU has been working
with Lambda Legal Defense to devise a careful, thought out strategy to focus the
gay community's resources on cases and litigation which are most likely to win
wide spread recognition of same-sex marriages.</P>
<P>	The other part of DOMA, under which federal programs do not recognize
same-sex marriages, will also take some time to undo.  But they are also
vulnerable if attacked thoughtfully.  </P>
<P>	So while DOMA was a defeat, the battle is far from over.  The ACLU and
other groups are already implementing a strategy which we think will ultimately
be its undoing.</P>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H2>1996 LESBIAN AND GAY RIGHTS DOCKET</H2></CENTER>
<H3><A NAME="1"></A>1.  ANTI-GAY INITIATIVES</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Colorado</H5></CENTER>
<P>(For discussion on<B><I> Romer v.  Evans</I></B>, the historic challenge
to the state's anti-gay Amendment 2 struck down by the Supreme Court, see <I>&quot;Spotlight
on 1996</I>&quot; above.)</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Idaho</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Initiative</B><BR>	Within eight months of the defeat by Idaho
voters of the 1994 anti-gay initiative, the Idaho Citizens Alliance (the
initiative's sponsors) filed another anti-gay initiative for the 1996 ballot. 
</P>
<P>	The ACLU of Idaho submitted argument to the Attorney General explaining why
the initiative is not constitutional.  Subsequently, the Attorney General issued
a certificate of review in which he noted various constitutional problems with
provisions in the initiative and advised the ICA to delay the initiative until
after the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in <I>Romer v. Evans</I>.  </P>
<P>	However, the ICA only slightly revised the initiative before circulating it
 for petition signatures.  Working with the statewide coalition opposing the new
anti-gay initiative, the ACLU of Idaho campaigned heavily to persuade Idaho
voters not to sign the initiative.  </P>
<P>	On July 1, 1996, just prior to the signature gathering deadline, the ICA
abandoned the anti-gay initiative.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Kentucky</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Initiative Bills</B><BR>The ACLU of Kentucky opposed three
bills seeking to make Kentucky an &quot;initiative state&quot; with a Colorado
Amendment 2-type statute.  All died in Committee. 
</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maine</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Wagner v. Cosby</B><BR>	The Maine Civil Liberties Union and Boston's
Gay and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders (GLAD) brought this pre-election
challenge to an initiative proposed by Concerned Maine Families.  The initiative
would have amended Maine law to say that no locality could pass a law preventing
discrimination based on any characteristic unless the characteristic is one of
those specified in the initiative.  Sexual orientation was not on the
initiative's list.  Although the initiative, entitled, &quot;An Act to Limit
Protected Classes Under Maine Law,&quot; made no specific reference to gays and
lesbians, Concerned Maine Families left little doubt that excluding gays,
lesbians and bisexuals from anti-discrimination protection was the purpose of
the bill.  The bill would have repealed Portland's existing ordinance
prohibiting discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation.</P>
<P>	The primary argument in the challenge was that the initiative was a veiled
effort to amend the Maine Constitution (which cannot be done by initiative) on
the ground that it purported to prevent the state legislature from ever adopting
a law protecting lesbians and gay men.  The Maine Law Court held that the
initiative could be interpreted only to prevent cities from passing
anti-discrimination laws, and that so interpreted, it would be constitutional.
In the event of the initiative passing, the MCLU and GLAAD prepared a
post-election challenge.  The initiative was rejected by the voters in November
1995.  The MCLU was assisted by cooperating attorney Patricia Peard.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Ohio</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Equality Foundation v. Cincinnati</B><BR>	On November 2, 1993, the
voters of Cincinnati approved &quot;Issue 3&quot; an amendment to the city
charter which deprives all branches of local government of the power to pass
laws that ban discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation.  It also
repealed the existing nondiscrimination law.  The ACLU of Ohio, joined by
attorneys from Lambda Legal Defense Fund, challenged the initiative in Federal
District Court and obtained a landmark ruling striking down the measure as
unconstitutional.</P>
<P>	The City and the initiative's proponents appealed to the Sixth Circuit,
which reversed the District Court's decision concluding that since &quot;homosexual
conduct&quot; may be criminalized without offending the Constitution,
discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation is not constitutionally
suspicious.  The ACLU and Lambda petitioned the Supreme Court to take the case
and hold it pending the outcome of the &quot;Amendment 2&quot; case. After it
decided <I>Romer v. Evans</I>, the Supreme Court sent the case back to the
Sixth Circuit for reconsideration.  The case is now being re-briefed.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Oregon</H5></CENTER>
<P><I>(Although their specifics vary, all these state or local ballot measures
would have prohibited laws that protect lesbians and gay men from
discrimination.)  </I></P>
<P><B>Doe v. Keisling I</B> and <B>Doe v. Keisling II</B><BR>	The ACLU of
Oregon is spearheading two challenges to an anti-gay ballot initiative slated
for the November 1996 election.  Popularly referred to as &quot;Daughter of 13&quot;
because it most closely resembles Measure 13 from 1994, it is styled by its
promoters the &quot;Child Protection Act.&quot;  See Keisling I and II.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Rooney, et al. v. Keisling I and II</B><BR>	These are two ballot title
challenges to Oregon Citizens Alliance proposed anti-gay constitutional
amendments slated for the November 1996 ballot.  Oral arguments before the
Oregon Supreme Court took place on May 11, 1995.  The OCA withdrew four of its
eight petitions and the Oregon Supreme Court certified ballot titles for the
remaining four.  The certified language adopts some of the language proposed by
the ACLU and does not reflect the wishes of the OCA.  After certification, the
OCA chose the initiative for which it will gather signatures.  After the
decision in <I>Romer</I>, the OCA abandoned the effort.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Boytano v. Klamath Falls</B><BR>	The ACLU of Oregon is providing direct
representation on this appeal of a pre-election challenge to a local OCA
measure.  The challenge argues that HB 3500, which prohibits &quot;enacting&quot;
laws that single out individuals based on sexual orientation, prohibits
elections on OCA anti-gay and lesbian rights initiatives.  The Oregon Supreme
Court accepted review and oral arguments took place May 4, 1995.  The Court
concluded that an initiative measure is &quot;enacted&quot; when an elections
officer tabulates the votes and certifies that a majority of voters approved the
proposed measure, so that elections are not prohibited.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Kinney v. O'Connor, Lake County I</B><BR>	The ACLU of Oregon filed this
pre-election challenge to a local OCA measure.  The challenge incorporates the
arguments against HB 3500 that the ACLU made in <I>Boytano v. Klamath Falls</I>.
 Lake County Circuit Court rejected the challenge, upholding the measure and
certifying it for the ballot.  The ACLU appealed the decision to the Oregon
Court of Appeals; oral arguments took place June 21, 1995.  In December 1995,
the Court of Appeals decided that &quot;[a] measure's potential substantive
invalidity will not prevent it from being placed on a local ballot.&quot;  The
ACLU then filed a motion to reconsider in the Court of Appeals based on the
court's decision in <I>Boytano v. Klamath Falls</I>.  In February 1996, the
Court of Appeals ruled that HB 3500 does not prohibit counting votes.  In May
1996, the Oregon Supreme Court denied the ACLU's petition for review.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Ladehoff et al. v. Keisling I and II</B><BR>	The ACLU filed a
pre-election challenge to the anti-gay &quot;Grandson of 9&quot; measure (named
for its resemblance to 1992's Measure 9) which was slated for the 1996 November
general election.  The ACLU argued that the proposed constitutional amendment
did not qualify as a proper subject for the initiative because of the numerous
substantive defects.  The OCA notified the Secretary of State that it did not
intend to pursue action on this proposed initiative.  </P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Rose et al. v. Keisling</B><BR>	The ACLU filed a pre-election challenge
to the eight anti-gay constitutional amendment proposals targeted for the
November 1996 ballot.  The ACLU argued that the measures did not qualify as
proper subjects for the initiative because of the numerous substantive defects. 
In October 1995, the trial court judge dismissed the ACLU's complaint because of
Lowe v. Keisling, the ACLU's unsuccessful challenge of Measure 13.  The ACLU
filed an appeal with the Oregon Court of Appeals in December 1995.  The case is
pending oral arguments.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Carver et al. v. Marion Co.</B><BR>	The ACLU of Oregon filed a
post-election challenge to Measure 24-5, the anti-gay OCA measure passed by
Marion County voters in March 1994.  The ACLU's complaint included the HB 3500
argument as well as numerous other constitutional claims.  The ACLU requested a
stipulated judgment that the measure would not be enforced.  The County filed a
motion for summary judgment; the ACLU responded with its own motion on September
21, 1995.  On November 6, 1995, Marion County Circuit Court judge Pamela
Abernathy ruled that Measure 24-5 violates the provisions of ORS 659.165 (HB
3500) and is thus null and void.  The judge permanently enjoined Marion County

from enforcing or implementing the measure.  The ACLU was awarded modest
attorney's fees.</P>
<P> </P>
<P><B>Jackson v. Lebanon and Bonds v. Albany</B><BR>	On August 1, 1995, the
ACLU of Oregon filed a post-election challenge to the OCA's anti-gay and lesbian
rights initiative that was passed in these two cities.  In both, the respective
city agreed to the stipulated judgment and the ACLU was awarded attorneys fees.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="2"></A>2.  ANTI-GAY VIOLENCE</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Mackler v. City of Los Angeles</B><BR>	The ACLU of Southern California
filed this case against the City of Los Angeles for Peter Mackler, who was
violently assaulted by the Los Angeles Police Department in November 1991, at a
demonstration protesting the veto of a bill that would have prohibited
employment discrimination based on sexual orientation in California.  After
Mackler and others were pushed and jabbed with police batons, Mackler (who was
wearing a &quot;National Coming Out Day&quot; T-shirt) asked, &quot;What's his
badge number?&quot;  The officer who was pushing Mackler responded by lifting
his baton above his head and hitting Mackler with the baton, knocking him to the
ground and breaking his eyeglasses.  Mackler was then grabbed by two other
officers who lifted him from the ground and threw him.  The Police left Mackler
lying on the ground injured.  The case is slated for trial in January of 1997.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Marmillion v. City of Los Angeles</B><BR>	In this case, 28 individuals
represented by the ACLU of Southern California sued the City of Los Angeles for
police brutality, assault, and harassment.  The plaintiffs were either
participants in or passers-by at a demonstration in October 1991 protesting
Governor Wilson's veto of a bill that would have prohibited sexual orientation
employment discrimination in California.  Over 100 police officers on horseback
and on foot, wearing full riot gear, charged the demonstrators, repeatedly
beating and trampling them, finally chasing them through the Century City
shopping center mall, where further police assaults took place.  Throughout,
many officers shouted slurs.  An estimated 60-90 day jury trial has been
scheduled for late 1996.  The ACLU is being assisted by cooperating attorneys
Hugh Manes and Carol Watson.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Mexico</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Hate Crimes Bill</B><BR>	In the January - March 1995 New Mexico
legislative session, ACLU of New Mexico was the originator of a hate crime bill
which included &quot;sexual orientation.&quot;  The bill would have added
penalties for assault and other crimes targeted at religious, ethnic, racial and
other minorities.  The legislature passed the bill, but it was vetoed by the
governor.  During the 1996 session, the ACLU was part of a coalition seeking an
override of the Republican Governor's veto of the hate crimes bill.  The
override vote failed.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New York</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anderson v. Branen</B><BR>	The Project brought this gay-bashing and
police abuse case on behalf of two gay men, Jeffrey Grubb and Marc Anderson, who
were physically attacked without provocation by three Drug Enforcement 
Administration agents after a minor traffic mishap.  Throughout the assault, the
DEA agents called the men faggots and made various other homophobic comments. 
Grubb and Anderson suffered serious injuries.  Anderson was arrested and charged
with resisting arrest and harassment.  Grubb was arrested and charged with
harassment, obstruction of government administration, leaving the scene of an
accident, and operating a vehicle without a license.  All of these charges were
later dropped.  Anderson and Grubb sued the three agents in federal district
court for violation of their constitutional rights.  In April 1995, a jury
convicted the agents and awarded Anderson and Grubb $111,000 in damages.  The
government appealed.  While the appeal was pending, the government agreed to
settle the case by paying $99,000 in damages.  Cooperating attorneys were Joseph
Tringali, Nicholas Even, and Nancy Hood of Simpson, Thatcher &amp; Bartlett.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Virginia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Hate Crimes</B><BR>	The ACLU of Virginia supported this bill,
introduced by Delegate Almand, which would have added &quot;sexual orientation&quot;
and &quot;gender&quot; to categories of victims (currently race, color, national
origin, or religion) whose selection for a &quot;hate crime&quot; involving
assault or trespass amplifies the penalty to a six-month minimum.  This bill was
carried over to the 1997 session in the House Committee for Courts of Justice.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>West Virginia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Hate Crimes Law</B>	<BR>The West Virginia ACLU supported a bill,
introduced in both the House and the state Senate, which would have amended the
state's hate crimes statute to include &quot;sexual orientation&quot; and &quot;disability.&quot;
 It died in committee.  </P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="3"></A>3.  BOY SCOUTS</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Curran v. Mt. Diablo Council of Boy Scouts</B><BR>	This lawsuit filed
by the ACLU of Southern California challenges the Boy Scouts' policy excluding
gay men and lesbians.  Tim Curran, a former Eagle Scout, charges that the policy
violates the Unruh Civil Rights Act, a California law which prohibits arbitrary
discrimination by businesses.  The complaint was originally dismissed, but the
Court of Appeals reversed and sent the case back for trial.  The Superior Court
held a two-phase trial.  In November 1990, it ruled that the Boy Scouts were

subject to the Unruh Act.  But in May 1991, it found that the Scouts have a
constitutional right to exclude open lesbians and gay men in order to further
its asserted goal of teaching Scouts that homosexuality is immoral.  The Court
of Appeals upheld that decision, 2-to-1, in 1994.  The California Supreme Court
granted the ACLU's petition for review, but the Court deferred briefing pending
decision of <I>Warfield v. Peninsula Golf and Country Club</I>, a gender
discrimination case in which the ACLU of Southern California is also counsel. 
</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>District of Columbia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Pool v. Boy Scouts of America and Geller v. Boy Scouts of America</B><BR>	In
1992,  the ACLU of the National Capital Area filed complaints with the D.C.
Department of Human Rights on behalf of two gay men who wished to serve as scout
leaders, alleging that the Boy Scouts' policy of excluding gay men from serving
as adult leaders violates the D.C. Human Rights Act's prohibition of
discrimination based on sexual orientation in employment and in access to places
of public accommodation.  After lengthy administrative proceedings, the
Department ruled in April, 1995 that it had no jurisdiction over the cases
because the Boy Scouts are not a &quot;place of public accommodation&quot;
covered by the Human Rights Act, and because a volunteer is not an &quot;employee&quot;
within the meaning of the Human Rights Act, and the only paid Boy Scout
employment positions in this area are in Maryland.   We sought reconsideration
of that decision, and in May 1996, the Department agreed to reopen these cases.
ACLU cooperating attorneys are David M. Gische, Merril J. Hirsh, Susan M. Camp
Stocks, and Jennifer Young of Ross, Dixon &amp; Masback.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>

<H5>Illinois</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Richardson v. Chicago Area Council of Boy Scouts of America</B><BR>	The
ACLU of Illinois is representing Keith Richardson, an Eagle Scout who was
excluded from consideration for employment by the Chicago Area Council because
he is gay.  In February 1996, the Chicago Commission on Human Relations' Board
of Commissioners found that the Chicago Area Council's employment policy
violated the Chicago Ordinance's prohibition against discrimination on the basis
of sexual orientation.  The Council was fined $100, and enjoined from further
violations of the ordinance.  Our client was awarded $500, as well as attorneys
fees and costs.  The Boy Scouts have appealed.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Jersey</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Dale v. Boy Scouts of America</B><BR>The ACLU of New Jersey and the
Lesbian and Gay Rights Project filed an amicus brief challenging the Boy Scouts'
policy of excluding gay men and youths from membership.  The brief argues that
the Boy Scouts is a public accommodation and that New Jersey's Law Against
Discrimination requires that the Scouts treat all individuals equally, without
regard to sexual orientation.  It also disputes the Boy Scouts' claim that the
constitutional right to freedom of association exempts the Boy Scouts from
compliance with state civil rights laws.</P>
<P>	The Law Division judge granted the Defendant's motion for summary judgment,
 and dismissed all of Dale's claims.  In a disappointing, and homophobic
opinion, the Judge held that the Boy Scouts were not a public accommodation
within the meaning of New Jersey's Law Against Discrimination, and held that
even if they were, application of the LAD to them would violate their free
expression rights, since he believed that they were a private organization
established to express certain &quot;moral&quot; principles which he viewed as
incompatible with homosexuality.</P>
<P>	Dale has appealed to the Appellate Division, and the ACLU-NJ and the
National Project have filed an amicus brief in support of his claims.  The
cooperating attorney is James D. Esseks, of Vladeck, Waldman, Elias &amp;
Englehard.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="4"></A>4.  CIVIL RIGHTS LAW</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Discrimination Legislation</B><BR>Two bills, one aimed at removing
the prohibition against marital status discrimination from the Fair Housing and
Employment Act and another seeking to prohibit discrimination in housing and
employment on the basis of one's gender identity, both failed to pass.  The ACLU
lobbied against the first bill and supported the second.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Delaware</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Lesbian and Gay Rights Bill</B><BR>Along with several other groups, the
ACLU of Delaware is preparing a bill to add sexual orientation to the state's 
civil rights law.  The coalition hopes to introduce the bill for the first time
in the next session of the legislature.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maine</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Lesbian and Gay Rights Bill</B><BR>The Maine Civil Liberties Union
opposed this legislation which was ultimately withdrawn by the sponsor.  The Act
prohibited discrimination based on sexual orientation in some cases but
authorized it in others, including employment by nonprofits that primarily work
with children, in adoption and foster care placements, and with small employers.
 It also established public policy on marriage, forbidding lesbian and gay
marriages.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maryland</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Lesbian and Gay Rights Bill</B><BR>The ACLU of Maryland unsuccessfully
lobbied for this bill which would have added sexual orientation to the list of
categories protected from discrimination under state law.  This bill failed,
again, but each year it gets a little closer to passage.  The ACLU was part of
the statewide coalition in support of the bill.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Employment Discrimination Based on Gender Identity</B><BR>The ACLU was
unsuccessful in its support for this bill which would have prohibited employment
discrimination against transgendered persons.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Reissue of Birth Certificates after Sex Change</B><BR>	The ACLU was
unsuccessful in its lobbying effort in support of this bill which would have
required the Vital Records Bureau to reissue birth certificates with new gender
identity.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Nebraska</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Employment Discrimination</B><BR>This bill sought to add sexual
orientation to the protected classes of workers under Nebraska's fair employment
laws.  ACLU of Nebraska testified before the Unicamera's Business and Labor
Committee arguing that every worker deserves to be judged on merit.  The bill
died in committee on a 5 to 2 vote.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Hampshire</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Lesbian and Gay Rights Law</B><BR>	The legislature is again considering
legislation to extend civil rights protection to gays and lesbians in housing,
employment and public accommodations.  Last session, the bill passed the House
and was defeated in the Senate, in part due to assurances from the governor that
it was not needed.  This session the bill was sent to study by the House, since
the governor is not seeking reelection.   The ACLU lobbied in favor of the
measure.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Jersey</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Orthodox Presbyterian Church v. Florio</B><BR>	The Orthodox
Presbyterian Church (OPC) is suing the State of New Jersey over provisions of
the Law Against Discrimination (LAD) which bans discrimination based on sexual
orientation.  The OPC argues that prohibiting discrimination against gays and
lesbians in employment and business transactions violates its right to free
exercise of religion and free speech.  In April 1992, the OPC's motion for a
temporary restraining order against enforcement of LAD was denied.  The Third
Circuit affirmed the denial and the State moved to dismiss the complaint,
arguing plaintiffs lacked standing to pursue the challenge in federal court. 
The ACLU of New Jersey submitted a friend of the court brief arguing that,
although the ACLU supports the broadest possible right of access to the courts
for resolution of constitutional claims, under the facts of this case the OPC
did not present a real case or controversy as required by Article III of the
federal Constitution.  </P>
<P>	The District Court dismissed the case, plaintiffs once again appealed and
the Third Circuit upheld the District Court's ruling with regard to the
organizational plaintiffs, but found that the one plaintiff who filed suit in
his individual capacity had standing.  The ACLU submitted a letter brief to the
District Court supporting the constitutionality of the ban on sexual orientation
discrimination.</P>
<P>	On remand, the District Court held that Rev. Cummings, the individual
plaintiff, had abandoned his challenge to much of the statute.  With respect to
the remaining portions, the court held that the challenge to requirement that
covered entities to display notices of individual's rights under the law was not
ripe, because no regulations had been issued, and held that the facial challenge
to the aiding and abetting sections failed because they regulated conduct, not
speech.  Finally, the court abstained from reaching the as-applied challenge, on
the ground that the state law on the issue was unsettled.  The plaintiff had
appealed to the Third Circuit.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Oklahoma</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Resolution</B><BR>	Despite opposition from the ACLU of
Oklahoma in 1996, legislative leaders passed a resolution which was a policy
statement by the legislature against gay men and lesbians.</P>

<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Rhode Island</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Lesbian and Gay Civil Rights Law</B><BR>	The ACLU of Rhode Island
lobbied for a bill which would have barred discrimination on the basis of sexual
orientation in the public schools.  The bill was amended instead to create a
House study commission to look into the issue.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Washington</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Discrimination Bills</B><BR>	Senate Bill 6657 would have expanded
the jurisdiction of the Human Rights Commission to prohibit gender identity
discrimination and SB 6534 would have expanded it to include sexual orientation.
 The ACLU supported both pieces of legislation but, unfortunately, both bills
died in the Law and Justice Committee. </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>West Virginia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Lesbian and Gay Rights Law</B><BR>The ACLU of West Virginia lobbied for
a bill which would have amended both the Human Rights Act and the Fair Housing 
Act to include &quot;sexual orientation.&quot;  It did not make it out of
committee, and therefore died at session's end.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="5"></A>5.  CRIMINAL LAW</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Georgia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>State of Georgia v. Christensen</B><BR>This was a challenge to
Georgia's sodomy law under the Georgia State Constitution.  The defendant was
arrested after an undercover police officer successfully induced him to ask the
police officer to go to a motel for sex.  Since the acts were to take place in
private, the defendant was charged with soliciting sodomy.  The ACLU of Georgia
assumed representation in the Georgia Supreme Court.  We argued that the Georgia
sodomy statute violates the Georgia constitutional right to privacy, the first
constitutional right to privacy to be recognized in America.  The court upheld
the law over two strong dissents.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Kansas</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>City of Topeka v. Movsovitz</B><BR>	This is a challenge to both a state
and a city law which prohibit sodomy but only when the couple involved is
lesbian or gay.  The Defendant was the victim of a police sting.  After talking
with an undercover officer for some time, he agreed (at the officer's
suggestion) to participate in an act of oral sex.  The City agrees that had the
officer been a woman, no crime would have been committed.  The trial court
denied our motion to dismiss the case on the basis that the law violates equal
protection.  The case is now before the Kansas Court of Appeals.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Kentucky</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Sodomy Laws</B><BR>	The ACLU of Kentucky supported the Kentucky
Fairness Alliance in its successful efforts to oppose a raft of anti-gay and
lesbian and anti-privacy legislation including efforts to put a state
constitutional amendment on the ballot that would recriminalize &quot;deviate
sexual intercourse&quot; between consenting adults and effectively repeal a
landmark privacy decision from the Kentucky Supreme Court.  </P>
<P>	Three bills were introduced seeking to criminalize sodomy between
consenting adults.  The ACLU opposed all such attempts and all three died in
Committee. 
</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Missouri</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Joplin's Mashing Case</B><BR>	The ACLU of Missouri, with the assistance
of volunteer attorney Robert Payne of Springfield, MO, is representing a gay man
who was charged in an undercover operation by the Joplin police force with
violating the city's &quot;mashing&quot; ordinance; the ordinance defines &quot;mashing&quot;
as the use of words or acts &quot;to annoy or attract the attention of any
person by any suggestive act or word.&quot;  From newspaper reports, as many as
thirty gay men were charged with &quot;mashing&quot; in Joplin in April.  There
has yet to be a hearing in the city court.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Montana</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Gryczan v. Montana</B><BR>	The Project is filing an amicus brief, along
with Lambda Legal Defense &amp; Education Fund, before the Montana Supreme Court
in support of this challenge to the constitutionality of the state's &quot;Deviate
Sexual Conduct&quot; statute.  The statute criminalizes any sexual contact
between members of the same sex.  Plaintiffs -- six lesbian and gay Montanans --
brought suit in 1993, claiming that the statute violated their constitutional
privacy, dignity and equal protection rights.  In February of 1996 the trial
court judge ruled in plaintiffs' favor.  On appeal, the State argues that
plaintiffs do not have a sufficient interest in the case and that, in any event,
the statute promotes morality, deters inappropriate sexual conduct and reduces
the spread of AIDS.  The amicus brief explains to the court that lesbians and
gay men have the right to challenge the statute since they are targeted by it
and that the statute violates their right to equal protection of the law since
it is grounded in animosity toward lesbians and gay men.  The amicus brief will
be filed in Fall 1996 and the case set for argument thereafter.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Sex Offender Registration</B><BR>	The ACLU of Montana lobbied against a
sex offender registration law which, as amended in the state senate, would have
required anyone convicted of violating Montana's sodomy law (which only applies
to lesbians and gay men) to register as a sex offender for life.  The bill was
withdrawn after protests.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Oklahoma</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>City of Oklahoma City v. Sawatzky</B><BR>	During the summer of 1994, an
Oklahoma City police officer invited a young man to come back to his hotel room
with him.  When the man accepted, he was arrested for soliciting sodomy.  The
ACLU of Oklahoma defended the man in municipal court, which issued a guilty
verdict.</P>
<P>	The Oklahoma affiliate challenged the verdict and the State's anti-sodomy
statute in the Oklahoma Court of Criminal Appeals, which had previously held
that the law was an unconstitutional violation of the right to privacy as it
applied to heterosexuals.  Cooperating attorney Mark Henricksen argued the case
before the Court of Criminal Appeals in August of 1995 and attempted to convince
the Court that the right to privacy applies to all Oklahomans, regardless of
sexual orientation.  In November of 1995, the Court issued a ruling that refused
to address the sodomy statute but upheld the client's municipal court conviction
based on the government's interest in regulating sexual speech in public places.</P>
<P>	With the help of the Lesbian and Gay Rights Project, the Oklahoma affiliate
filed an appeal with the U.S. Supreme Court.  In April of 1996, the Supreme
Court declined to hear the appeal without comment.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Rhode Island</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>State v. Lopes</B><BR>	In this case in which a heterosexual man was
charged with violating Rhode Island's sodomy statute, the ACLU of Rhode Island
filed a friend of the court brief arguing that the sodomy law violated the state
constitutional right to privacy.  Citing an earlier decision, the court simply
rejected the challenge and upheld the law.  The U.S. Supreme Court declined to
review the case.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>State v. Quitevis</B><BR>	The ACLU of Rhode Island is handling an
appeal for a person found guilty of &quot;loitering for indecent purposes&quot;
at an adult video store after allegedly offering to perform oral sex for an
undercover police officer.  The trial court rejected the defendant's challenge
to the constitutionality of the &quot;loitering&quot; ordinance.   The defendant
entered a <I>nolo</I> plea and the complaint was &quot;filed&quot; for one
year.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Tennessee</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Campbell v. Tennessee</B><BR>	In January 1996, the Tennessee Court of
Appeals affirmed Circuit Court Judge Walter Kurtz's decision that the Tennessee
Homosexual Practice Act was unconstitutional.  The Court ruled that the statute
violated privacy rights guaranteed by the Tennessee Constitution.</P>
<P>	The ACLU of Tennessee filed an amicus brief urging the Court to affirm the
lower court's decision on the grounds that the statute violates the privacy and
equal protection guarantees of the Tennessee Constitution and that the Tennessee
Constitution ensures greater protection than the United States Constitution. Our
cooperating attorneys were Vanderbilt Law Professors Robert Rasmussen, Rebecca
Brown, and Susan Kay.</P>
<P>	In June 1996, the Tennessee Supreme Court, in effect, affirmed the lower
Court's ruling when it denied the State's request for a hearing and urged
publication of the Court of Appeals decision.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Texas</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Burdine v. State of Texas</B><BR>	Calvin Burdine was convicted of
capital murder and sentenced to death by a Houston jury in 1984.  The Project
filed an amicus brief in support of his federal court petition for habeas corpus
arguing that Burdine's constitutional rights were violated by the extreme
homophobia that permeated his trial.  Among the more egregious examples was the
prosecutor's argument to the jury that putting a gay man in prison is not
punishment but is, instead, akin to putting a kid in a candy store, and the
court's decision that the jury could use a 1970 consensual sodomy conviction as
proof of future dangerousness.  Also at issue are allegations that the defense 
attorney slept through important parts of the trial; and that while on death
row, Burdine was subjected to a &quot;mock execution.&quot;  Burdine's execution
was stayed, and a hearing will be set on the merits of his habeas petition.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Virginia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Sodomy Decriminalization</B><BR>	The ACLU supported HB 1468, introduced
by Delegate Darner, which would have legalized intimate sexual acts between
consenting adults which are done in private and for non-commercial purposes. 
This bill was carried over to the 1997 session by the House Committee for Courts
of Justice.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="6"></A>6.  DOMESTIC PARTNERSHIP</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Colorado</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Ross v. Department of Health and Hospitals</B><BR>	Ross was employed by
the City and County of Denver.  When her life partner was injured in an
accident, she took off three days to be with her.  She requested the days be
treated as sick leave under a policy that allows employees to use sick leave to
care for immediate family members.  The City refused to consider a lesbian or
gay life partner an &quot;immediate family member,&quot; despite a personnel
policy that prohibits discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation.  Ross
appealed the refusal to the Denver Career Services Board in October of 1991,
where she prevailed.  The Hearing Board reopened the case, however, and reversed
itself.  Ross filed a complaint for review in court.  The trial court ruled in
favor of Ross, but the Court of Appeals reversed.  The Colorado Supreme Court
denied a petition for review.  Ross is currently working with the ACLU in an
attempt to change the agency's definition of &quot;immediate family&quot;
through an administrative rule-making process.  The ACLU of Colorado is being
assisted by cooperating attorney Lino Lipinsky de Orlov.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Delaware</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>In Re Marley</B><BR>	The ACLU of Delaware recently won reversal of a
decision by the Court of Common Pleas that denied a woman the right to change
her last name to that of her female partner.  The presiding Judge in Delaware's
Superior Court stated that under common law it is well-settled &quot;an adult
may adopt any name they desire provided the change was not intended to further
fraudulent or illegal purposes.&quot;  The Judge said: &quot;[I]t is not
sufficient reason to deny a common law right because it represents a 'departure
from what the court has done in the past.'&quot;  </P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Domestic Partnership Bill</B><BR>	A bill that would recognize domestic
partnerships and allow a couple to share certain benefits and visitation rights,
H.B. 694, the &quot;Domestic Partnership Act,&quot; was introduced in the House
but died at the end of the session.  The Governor has assigned a task force to
explore lesbian and gay relationships further, and the ACLU of Delaware has
members on the Commission.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Georgia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Domestic Partnership Law</B><BR>	In a prior challenge to Atlanta's
domestic partnership bill, providing a formal registry and benefits, the
benefits portion of the bill was struck down by the Georgia Supreme Court.  In
striking it down, the court provided directions on how to properly draft a
benefits section.  This summer, the City Council of Atlanta redrafted and passed
a new benefits bill.  The ACLU expects this to be challenged again, and is
preparing to help out in this second challenge.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Jersey</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>American Association of University Professors v. Rutgers University</B><BR>	The
ACLU of New Jersey represents two of five gay Rutgers faculty members who
brought this suit against the school and the State Health Benefits Commission. 
The suit challenges the school's refusal to provide domestic partners the
benefits that are given to the spouses of heterosexual employees.  The suit
alleges that this practice violates the New Jersey law against discrimination on
the basis of sexual orientation, a state executive order prohibiting
discrimination in the provision of benefits on the basis of sexual orientation,
a similar policy adopted by Rutgers, a provision of the collective bargaining
agreement prohibiting discrimination, and the State Constitution.  In February
1994, the Superior Court ruled that the claims as to the State are in the nature
of an appeal of a state administrative agency's ruling and transferred those 
counts to the Appellate Division.</P>
<P>	This suit is still pending in the New Jersey Superior Court, Appellate
Division.  The briefs have been filed and the ACLU is awaiting the schedule for
oral argument.  The case has moved slowly because of a great deal of procedural
wrangling over whether the ACLU would be able to supplement the record.  The
ACLU is co-counsel with Denise Reinhardt of Reinhardt &amp; Schachter, and
Rosemary DiSavino of Ball, Livingston &amp; Tykulsker.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Oregon</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Tanner, et al. v. OHSU et al.</B><BR>	Three lesbian couples are suing
the state for discrimination for failing to provide health care and other
benefits to their partners.  The ACLU of Oregon filed an amicus brief in their
support.  A trial took place in February 1995 before Judge Gallagher.  On June
14, 1996, the court decided that Oregon Health and Sciences University's
insurance benefits program violates the state constitution's guarantee of equal
privileges and immunities as well as the state statute which prohibits
employment discrimination on the basis of sex, marital status, or the sex or
marital status of any other person with whom the individual associates.  OHSU is
enjoined from continuing the practice of denying life and group medical and
dental insurance coverage to its lesbian and gay domestic partner employees
which it affords to its heterosexual married employees.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Pennsylvania</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Domestic Partnership Benefits</B><BR>	On June 7, 1996, Philadelphia
Mayor Ed Rendell fulfilled a campaign promise when he issued an Executive Order
granting some gay and lesbian city employees domestic partnership benefits.  The
Catholic Church, Black Clergy and several members of City Council immediately
announced their vehement opposition.  John Street, President of City Council,
introduced an ordinance calling for a nonbinding referendum on the Mayor's
Executive Order.  Street immediately scheduled a public hearing on his proposal.
 The ACLU presented testimony in opposition to the referendum and in support of
domestic partnership benefits.  Shortly after the hearing, Street canceled a
session of City Council that he had scheduled for the purpose of voting on the
referendum.  Instead, Street went to court in an attempt to block the
implementation of Mayor Rendell's Executive Order.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Henson v. University of Pittsburgh</B><BR>	The Pittsburgh chapter of
the ACLU of Pennsylvania is representing law instructor Deborah Henson, whose
lesbian partner of nine years has been denied health benefits by the University

of Pittsburgh.  Although the University offers health benefits to heterosexual
couples who are married under either civil or common law, school officials have
repeatedly informed Henson that she cannot receive health insurance benefits for
her partner.  The ACLU argued that the school's refusal to provide health
benefits to the partners of lesbian and gay employees violates Pittsburgh's
Human Relations Ordinance.  An administrative complaint filed with the
university is pending.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Hospital Visitation</B><BR>	A gay man visiting his partner in a state
mental hospital was banned from visiting the hospital for ten days after he gave
his partner a quick kiss on the lips to say goodbye.  When he was allowed to
visit again, the man again gave his partner a goodbye peck.  The hospital then
banned his visitation completely.  The ACLU registered a complaint with the
state hospital on his behalf.  After offering a series of inconsistent
explanations, claiming the ban was for a variety of therapeutic reasons, the
hospital relented and allowed visits to resume.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>West Virginia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Domestic Partnership Law</B><BR>	The West Virginia Civil Liberties
Union opposes a bill, provoked by efforts earlier in the year to extend limited
benefits to domestic partners at West Virginia University, which would prohibit

any state agency, including institutions of higher education, from granting
benefits to unmarried partners of employees or students.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Domestic Partnership Recognition</B><BR>	Last year the West Virginia 
University System Board of Trustees voted not to extend basic university
benefits -- such as access to the library and the recreation center, eligibility
for child care and scholarships, but not health care -- to domestic partners of
the statewide System's staff, faculty and students.  The Board of Trustees
intervened in this matter, which concerns only one university, after the policy
decision, supported by the West Virginia University Social Justice Council and
the University President himself, had been made.  Domestic partners, under the
proposed policy, would have included heterosexual unmarried couples as well as
gay and lesbian couples.  The West Virginia Civil Liberties Union lobbied in
favor of the policy.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="7"></A>7.  FREE EXPRESSION</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Housley v. San Diego Lesbian &amp; Gay Pride</B><BR>	San Diego Lesbian
and Gay Pride, Inc. sponsors San Diego's annual Lesbian and Gay Pride Parade and
Festival.  In early 1994, former San Diego mayor Roger Hedgecock and a group of
supporters -- calling themselves the &quot;Normal People&quot; -- declared their
intention to march in the 1994 parade &quot;in political disagreement to the
homosexual agenda.&quot;  Pride rejected &quot;Normal's&quot; application and &quot;Normal&quot;
then filed suit in San Diego Superior Court, alleging that the exclusion was
based on its members' heterosexual orientation -- in violation of San Diego's
Human Dignity Ordinance.  </P>
<P>	The ACLU of San Diego &amp; Imperial Counties, in conjunction with Lambda
Legal Defense and Education Fund, defended Pride.  Pride argued that &quot;Normal
People&quot; was excluded because its message was antithetical to the message of
the Pride parade, not because of sexual orientation, and pointed to the hundreds
of heterosexuals (including the mayor and the police chief) who had been invited
to march.  Pride's First Amendment rights of speech and association would be
violated, we argued, if the Court required that their parade include avowed
opponents who sought to dilute Pride's message.  The Superior Court agreed, and
denied &quot;Normal's&quot; application for an emergency order, and the Parade
went forward as scheduled without &quot;Normal.&quot;  &quot;Normal&quot;
continued to press a claim for damages, but eventually gave up and dismissed the
case.  The cooperating attorney was Dale Manicom.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Voices '96 v.  GOP Convention</B><BR>	On June 20, 1996, Voices '96, a
coalition of 20 San Diego-area lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender groups,
filed suit against the Republican National Committee (RNC) after the RNC
succeeded in getting the demonstration area designated far away from the
convention site.  Originally, the San Diego Convention Center was to serve as a
&quot;free speech zone&quot; for demonstrators.  The FBI and Secret Service
endorsed the selected site.  But the RNC proposed that the &quot;free speech
zone&quot; be relocated a third of a mile away.  San Diego City Manager Jack
McGrory came up with a &quot;compromise&quot; site, moving the zone three full
city blocks from the originally designated location.  The ACLU of San Diego is
representing Voices '96 in its suit, filed in U.S. District Court.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maine</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Lyons v. City of Lewiston et al.</B><BR>	ACT UP member Dennis Lyons was
in Lewiston in September 1991 as President Bush was arriving at the high school
to give a speech.  With other demonstrators carrying signs protesting the
administration's AIDS policies, Lyons walked toward the route of the motorcade. 
A police officer told the ACT UP protesters to remain behind a roped-in area for
demonstrators that was several hundred feet from the motorcade route.  When
Lyons refused and continued on his way to the sidewalk, he was arrested for
unlawful assembly and failure to disperse.  The ACLU of Maine filed a lawsuit
charging violation of Lyons's right to free speech.  The Law Court denied
defendants' request for summary judgment on federal issues and the case will go
to trial soon.</P>
<P><I>(Erratum: This entry should have been included in the &quot;Free
Expression&quot; section of the ACLU's 1996 AIDS Docket.)</I></P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Massachusetts</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Reproductive Rights Network v. Duffey</B><BR>	The ACLU of Massachusetts
represented ACT UP/Boston, the Coalition for Gay and Lesbian Civil Rights, and
the Reproductive Rights Network in this state court action.  The groups were
organizing a demonstration against Cardinal Law because they believed he
improperly interfered with public policy on AIDS education, gay rights, and
abortion rights.  As part of their organizing efforts, the coalition of groups
scheduled a planning meeting at the University of Massachusetts in Boston. 
Trustees of the university and the staff of the president of the Massachusetts
Senate objected to the meeting.  As a result, university officials shut down the
building to prevent the meeting from taking place.  The plaintiffs sued and a
Suffolk Superior Court judge ruled that university officials violated the
plaintiff's rights to freedom of speech and association under the state
constitution.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Wisconsin</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Southworth v. Grebe</B><BR>	Three law students filed suit on April 2,
1996 in federal court in Madison against the University of Wisconsin-Madison
Regents challenging the &quot;unconstitutional practice of compelling students
to pay a mandatory fee to fund private ideological and political groups on
campus.&quot;  The suit mentions the UW Greens, Lesbian, Gay, and Bisexual
Campus Center, WISPIRG, Campus Women's Center and others as among those who
promote and advocate &quot;specific ideological and political points of view.&quot;
 The student plaintiffs allege that they are compelled to fund organizations'
positions to which the plaintiffs are opposed based on their &quot;personal
ideological and religious beliefs.&quot;  Their legal claims are based on the
First Amendment's Free Exercise Clause and the Religious Freedom Restoration Act
(RFRA), and violation of the Wisconsin Constitution &quot;public purpose
doctrine&quot; (spending public money for a private purpose).</P>
<P>	The ACLU of Wisconsin is preparing an opposition amicus brief.  This brief
advocates the proposition of an open public forum, the free exchange of ideas,
and the avoidance of restricting, and/or curtailing of one's beliefs.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="8"></A>8.  HOUSING DISCRIMINATION</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Smith v. FEHC</B><BR>	In California, the Fair Employment and Housing
Act expressly prohibits discrimination in housing on the basis of marital
status.  Uniformly, courts have held that this prohibition includes a ban on
housing discrimination against unmarried couples.  Nevertheless, a landlord
refused to rent an apartment to an unmarried couple on the basis of her
religious belief that having a sexual relationship outside of marriage was
sinful.  The Fair Employment and Housing Commission found that the landlord had
violated state anti-discrimination laws.  </P>
<P>	The Court of Appeals reversed, concluding that the free exercise clause of
the state and federal constitutions protected the landlord's refusal to rent. 
On April 9, 1996, the California Supreme Court held that the fair housing law
protected unmarried co-habitating couples from discrimination and that the free
exercise clause did not exempt the landlord from complying with
anti-discrimination laws.  The ACLU and the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith filed amicus briefs in support of the unmarried couple in the Court of
Appeals and the California Supreme Court.  </P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="9"></A>9.  JOB DISCRIMINATION</H3>
<P>(For a discussion on the federal Employment Non-Discrimination Act, a bill
that would prohibit employers from firing someone based on their sexual
orientation, see &quot;<I>Spotlight on 1996</I>&quot; .)</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Colorado</H5>
</CENTER>
<P><B>Sension v. University of Denver</B><BR>	On June 1, 1994, Mark Sension
was hired by the University of Denver to be the Associate Director for
Operations of the Ricks Center for Gifted Children, a private school run by the
University.  About a month later, he let his supervisor know he is gay.  She
asked why he had not mentioned this before he was hired and he responded by
saying that the question had not been asked.  On August 22, 1994, Sension was
fired without warning and escorted from the building by university security
personnel.  He was told that his firing was a result of an &quot;issue of trust.&quot;
 The ACLU of Colorado filed suit in Denver district court.  The case was settled
favorably for the client.  The ACLU was assisted by cooperating attorney Jim Goh
of Holland &amp; Hart.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Connecticut</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Gay and Lesbian Law Students Association v. University of Connecticut 
Law School</B><BR>	In May of 1992, the Lesbian and Gay Rights Project and the
Connecticut Civil Liberties Union filed suit on behalf of the University of
Connecticut Gay and Lesbian Law Students Association against the University
seeking to bar the use of the School's employment recruiting services by
military recruiters.  The complaint alleged that the Law School's failure to bar
military recruiters violates the Connecticut Gay Rights Law, the Law School's
non-discrimination policy (which requires that all recruiters agree not to
discriminate), and a Connecticut law stating that military recruiters shall be
permitted on campus on the same terms as other employers.</P>
<P>	In October 1992, the court granted plaintiff's motion for a preliminary
injunction and barred the school from permitting the military to recruit on
campus.  This ruling marked the first time that a state court had ever barred
the U.S. military from recruiting on the basis that its actions discriminate
against lesbians and gay men.  In 1994, a final hearing was held to determine
the effect of the U.S. military's new policy on the injunction.  At that
hearing, the injunction was made permanent and the University then appealed to
the Connecticut Supreme Court.</P>
<P>	In a three-to-two decision, the Connecticut Supreme Court affirmed the
permanent injunction barring the University of Connecticut Law School from
permitting military recruiters on campus under the state gay rights law.  The
opinion has subsequently been applied by the Attorney General to bar the
military from career services at other state campuses.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Georgia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Shahar v. Bowers</B><BR>	Robin Shahar graduated sixth in her class from
Emory Law School in 1991 and accepted the offer of a staff attorney's job with
the Attorney General of Georgia.  Before she started work, Shahar and her
partner of five years participated in a private commitment ceremony, conducted
by a rabbi and attended by family and friends.  When the Attorney General found
out about the ceremony, he fired Shahar.</P>
<P>	The National Project, with the ACLU of Georgia and cooperating counsel
Debra Schwartz of Atlanta's Stanford, Fagan &amp; Giolito, sued in federal
court.  The suit argues the firing violates Shahar's rights to freedom of
religion, freedom of association, equal protection, and due process.  In October
of 1993, the district court granted the state's motion for summary judgment,
ruling that it would not have been unconstitutional for the attorney general to
have fired Shahar either for her sexual orientation, or the fact that she went
through the commitment ceremony.  </P>
<P>	In January, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 11th Circuit reversed the
trial court and reinstated Shahar's suit.  Lesbians and gay men, the court
ruled, have a right to intimate association just as others do, and the state may
infringe on the right only in the most compelling circumstances.  The Attorney
General petitioned the entire 11th Circuit court to rehear the case, which it
agreed to do.  The case has been re-briefed, and is awaiting oral argument.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maryland</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Hopkins v. Baltimore Gas &amp; Electric</B><BR>	The Maryland Civil
Liberties Union, along with the ACLU National Women's Rights Project, filed a
friend of the court brief with the Fourth Circuit. This case involved a man who
was sexually harassed by his male supervisor and who was retaliated against when
he complained.  The District Court decided that the federal civil rights law
which prohibits sexual harassment on the job does not apply to same-sex sexual
harassment.  A three-judge panel unanimously upheld the dismissal of Hopkins'
complaint, splitting on whether Title VII, which prohibits discrimination based
on sex, covers same-sex sexual harassment.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Washington</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Nelson v. McClatchy Newspapers</B><BR>	Sandy Nelson, a journalist with
the Tacoma Morning News Tribune, worked in her off-duty hours on gay rights
issues, including a law prohibiting sexual orientation discrimination.  In 1990,
the Tribune, owned by McClatchy, Inc., reassigned Nelson to a job as copy-editor
because of her political activities.  The ACLU of Washington filed a lawsuit on
her behalf suit alleging that the Tribune's actions violated her employment
contract and the constitutional policies of freedom of speech, of association
and to petition.  The Pierce County Superior Court granted a summary judgment
dismissing three of the plaintiff's six counts.  The plaintiff appealed to the
state Court of Appeals, but then filed a statement of grounds for direct review
which the Supreme Court granted.  Oral arguments were heard in June 1996.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="10"></A>10.  MARRIAGE</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Alaska</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Brause v. Alaska</B><BR>	Two gay men denied a marriage license sought
to challenge the constitutionality of Alaska's exclusion of same-sex couples
from its marriage law.  The Alaska Civil Liberties Union was prepared to join as
a &quot;friend of the court&quot; but the plaintiffs decided to stay the suit
pending the outcome of the marriage case in Hawaii.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>District of Columbia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Dean &amp; Gill v. District of Columbia</B><BR>	In 1992, Craig Dean and
Patrick Gill sued the District of Columbia for denying them a marriage license
on the ground that they are of the same sex.  The D.C. Superior Court ruled that
D.C. law does not authorize same-sex marriages and that the Constitution does
not require it to do so.  The plaintiffs appealed, and the ACLU of the National
Capital Area filed an amicus brief on their behalf in the D.C. Court of Appeals,
arguing that the D.C. Marriage Act should be interpreted, in light of the
prohibition against sexual orientation discrimination in the D.C. Human Rights
Act, to permit same-sex marriages.  In January, 1995, the Court of Appeals
upheld the trial court.  The court was unanimous in ruling that D.C. law did not
authorize same-sex marriages; one judge dissented from the grant of summary
judgment on the equal protection claim and would have remanded for fact-finding
on that issue.  The plaintiffs filed a petition for rehearing <I>en banc</I>,
which was denied.  The ACLU was assisted by W. Stephen Smith and Micki M. Chen
of Morrison &amp; Foerster.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Hawaii</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Baehr v. Lewin</B><BR>	A lesbian couple and a gay male couple brought
this case challenging Hawaii's ban on same-sex marriages.  They claimed the ban
violated the state constitutional rights to privacy and equal protection.  The
trial judge dismissed the case, ruling that the marriage ban was a valid way to
promote the state's interest in procreation.  On appeal, the Lesbian and Gay
Rights Project and the ACLU of Hawaii with assistance from the ACLU of Northern
California, filed a friend of the court brief in support of the plaintiffs in
the Hawaii Supreme Court.</P>
<P>	In a landmark decision, the Hawaii Supreme Court reversed the trial court
and sent the case back.  Because the law makes one's ability to marry dependent
on gender, the court said, the ban constituted sex discrimination.  Under the
Hawaii constitution, the court said, sex discrimination is as suspicious as race
discrimination.  The state can engage in it only if it has a compelling goal and
there is no other way to achieve the goal.  The high court sent the case back to
the trial court with instructions to the lower court to apply the strictest
constitutional standard in assessing the constitutionality of the ban.</P>
<P>	The case went back to trial in September, 1996, and the trial lasted two
weeks.  The ACLU plans to file a friend of the court brief, and to stay with the
case if, as expected, it returns to the Hawaii Supreme Court.  The bulk of the
ACLU's efforts this year were devoted to fighting attempts to overrule the first
Hawaii Supreme Court decision, either in the legislature or by calling a
constitutional convention.</P>
<P><I>The 1995-1996 legislative session saw anti-gay marriage bills introduced
in more than thirty states.  At press time, these proposals were blocked in
twenty states and passed in fifteen (AL, AZ, DE, GA, ID, IL, KS, MI, MO, NC, OK,
PA, SC, SD, TN, UT).</I></P>
<P>(See &quot;<I>Spotlight on 1996</I>&quot; for analysis of the Defense of
Marriage Act, which has been signed into law in 1996.)</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Alabama</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU of Alabama fought a bill which
would have banned same-sex marriage.  The bill was introduced and failed in both
the regular and the special session of the Senate.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Arizona</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	The ACLU of Arizona unsuccessfully
opposed a bill which prohibits marriage between persons of the same sex and
voids same-sex marriages validly performed in other states.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage/Domestic Partnership Bill</B><BR>	This bill, which
would deny recognition to same-sex marriages, passed the Assembly and was
amended in the Senate Judiciary Committee to include a domestic partnership
provision that would grant domestic partners hospital visitation rights,
conservationship rights, and require employers to provide health insurance
benefits to domestic partners.  The bill then failed to pass.  In addition to
lobbying against this bill, the ACLU submitted a letter brief to the Attorney
General concerning the constitutionality of failing to recognize same-sex
marriages validly contracted in another jurisdiction.  Another bill which would
have codified the public policy against same-sex marriage failed to move in
Assembly.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Delaware</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	The Governor signed legislation banning
gay and lesbian marriages in Delaware.  The House of Representatives approved
H.B. 503 by a vote of 39-0, and the Senate passed the legislation 17-3.  The 
ACLU opposed.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Georgia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	Rep. Ron Crews and Senator Ed Gochenour
introduced a bill to officially ban same-sex marriages in Georgia. 
Unfortunately, this bill passed, and the Governor signed it.  The ACLU fought
the bill.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Hawaii</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Various Same-Gender Marriage and Domestic Partnership Bills</B><BR>	Just
before the 1996 legislative session started, the Hawaii Commission on Sexual
Orientation and the Law issued its report.  The Commission's majority members
found that there was no compelling state interest to deny the right to marry to
same-sex couples and that the denial of same-sex marriage was a violation of
equal protection of the law.  As a result of this finding, the Commission's
majority recommended that the State Legislature amend the law to allow same-sex
marriages or, in the alternative, to enact a statewide and comprehensive
domestic partnership law.  The ACLU publicly supported both of these findings
and recommendations.</P>
<P>	The ACLU testified in favor of the bills that would have recognized
same-sex marriage and was opposed to HB 2366 which called for a constitutional
amendment prohibiting same-sex marriage.  HB 2366 passed the House on March 5,
1996.  On the same day, the Senate responded by passing SB 3113 which legally
recognized domestic partnerships.  Unfortunately, this bill was dead on arrival
in the House, which refused to even hold a hearing, let alone vote on SB 3113. 
A slew of bills taking alternative positions on same-sex marriage and domestic
partnership benefits, both in the form of amendments to the Hawaii constitution
and as amendments to the Hawaii Revised Statutes, were also introduced.  All of
these bills died.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Idaho</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	The ACLU unsuccessfully fought this bill
which denies state recognition of same-sex marriages validly performed in other
states.  The ACLU testified, lobbied, spoke to the media, and worked with a
coalition of organizations and religious leaders who also testified against the
bill.  We networked with sympathetic legislators and met with the Governor's
staff.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Illinois</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	The ACLU of Illinois unsuccessfully
lobbied against Senate Bill 1773 which requires Illinois to refuse to recognize
same-sex marriages validly performed in other states.  The bill was amended to
read &quot;A marriage between two persons of the same sex is contrary to the
public policy of this State.&quot;  As part of its lobbying effort, the ACLU of
Illinois testified before the Illinois Senate Judiciary Committee, worked with a
coalition to compile petitions, and spoke to legislators directly.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Iowa</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>The ACLU of Iowa successfully opposed a
bill that would have prohibited marriages validly performed in other
jurisdictions from being recognized in Iowa if the marriage would be invalid if
performed under Iowa law.  The bill passed the House but died because it never
made it to a Senate vote.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Kansas</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>The ACLU of Kansas unsuccessfully lobbied
against a bill prohibiting the recognition of same-sex marriages validly
performed in other jurisdictions.  Kansas law prior to passage of SB 515 defined
marriage as &quot;two parties of the opposite sex.&quot;  The bill added, &quot;All
other marriages are declared to be contrary to the public policy of this state
and are void,&quot; and &quot;it is the strong policy of this state only to
recognize as valid marriages from other states that are between a man and a
woman.&quot;</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Kentucky</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	Four bills were introduced attempting to
limit legal recognition of marriage to those between one man and one woman.  All
four failed.  The ACLU helped fight all four with the Kentucky Fairness
Alliance.  The coalition also successfully defeated legislation that would have

explicitly denied recognition of same-sex marriages validly performed in other
states.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maine</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	Concerned Maine Families, the
organization that initiated the anti-gay initiative defeated by Maine voters in
1995, has begun gathering signatures to put before Maine voters an initiative
that would &quot;protect traditional marriage and prohibit same-sex marriages.&quot;
 The MCLU has joined the Decline-to-Sign Campaign that is developing in
response.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maryland</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU of Maryland successfully
lobbied against this bill which would have made marriage between a man and a
woman the only recognized form of marriage.  The ACLU was part of the Same-Sex
Marriage Coalition.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Michigan</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	The ACLU was unsuccessful in its
opposition to two bills relating to same-sex marriage.  The House and Senate
passed a bill which prohibits same-sex marriage.  The House and Senate also
passed a bill which prohibits the recognition of same-sex marriage from other
states.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Minnesota</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	There was an attempt to attach an
amendment banning same-sex marriages (which the ACLU opposed) to a bill on the
floor.  The Committee Chair refused to attach the amendment to any bill, and the
amendment's sponsors were unable to get the bill introduced.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Missouri</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	The ACLU was unsuccessful in its
opposition to SB 768 which amends the state marriage statute to read, &quot;it
is the public policy of this state to recognize marriage only between a man and
a woman.  Any purported marriage not between a man and a woman is invalid.  No
recorder shall issue a marriage license except to a man and a woman.&quot;</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Nebraska</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Pro-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU of Nebraska testified in support
of a bill which would have recognized same-sex marriages as valid under state
laws.  The bill was left in the Unicameral's Judiciary Committee without a vote
ever being taken, so it died at the end of the session.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Jersey</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU of New Jersey is leading the
coalition of groups fighting the proposed anti-same-sex marriage bill.  The

group is an outgrowth of a conference that the ACLU sponsored with People for
the American Way on fighting the radical right in New Jersey.  A number of the
original co-sponsors of the bill have withdrawn their sponsorship, and the
Governor has indicated that she does not think the bill is necessary.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Mexico</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU of New Mexico successfully
stayed off attempts to introduce a ban on same-sex marriage.  The proposed
legislation was stalled in committee.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>North Carolina</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	ACLU of North Carolina worked in
coalition with lesbian and gay rights organizations to oppose S.B. 1487/H.B.
1452, which would deny recognition of same-sex marriages validly performed in
other states.  The bill passed in June, 1996, despite testimony and extensive
lobbying by the coalition, and was signed by the Governor.</P>
<P></P>

<CENTER>
<H5>Pennsylvania</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU, working with a coalition of
organizations, successfully stayed the passage of anti-same-sex marriage
legislation.  In May, legislation was introduced in both the Pennsylvania Senate
and House of Representatives which would ban same-sex marriages in Pennsylvania
and bar recognition of such marriages validly performed in other states.  On
June 28, 1996, the Pennsylvania House of Representatives adopted an amendment,
based on the anti-marriage legislation.  The amendment was added to SB 434, a
bill concerning the issue of grandparents' custody.  SB 434 is now headed back
to the Pennsylvania Senate where it may be considered in the fall.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Rhode Island</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU of Rhode Island fought a bill
which would have barred Rhode Island from recognizing gay marriages that were
legally performed in other states.  The House Judiciary Committee voted to take
no action on the bill and to await the outcome in Hawaii.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>South Carolina</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	The ACLU was unsuccessful in its
opposition to a bill that would prohibit same-sex marriage.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>South Dakota</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	The ACLU of South Dakota was unsuccessful
in its efforts to defeat HB 1143 which would define marriage as &quot;a personal
relationship, between one man and one woman.&quot;  In the 1995 legislative
session a similar piece of legislation was defeated. </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Tennessee</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Law</B><BR>	During the 1996 Tennessee General
Assembly, the ACLU of Tennessee was part of a coalition of organizations
lobbying against the anti-marriage (same-sex marriage) bill.  Unfortunately, the
bill passed overwhelmingly.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Virginia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU opposed this bill, introduced
by Delegate McClure, which would have provided that any marriage which is
unlawful in Virginia though lawfully entered into in another jurisdiction, is
void in Virginia.  This bill was stricken from the docket of the House Committee
for Courts of Justice.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Washington</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU of Washington was successful in
its opposition to HB 2262 which would have prohibited same-sex marriage.  The
bill purported to &quot;reaffirm&quot; that marriage is a union between men and
women, and that reproduction is its fundamental purpose.  The bill provided that
same-sex marriages validly performed in other states would not be considered
valid in Washington.  The bill died in committee.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>West Virginia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU of West Virginia opposed a bill
which contained a number of marriage-related items, including a provision
specifying that same-sex marriages performed in other states would not be
recognized in West Virginia.  The bill did not pass.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Wyoming</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Marriage Bill</B><BR>	During the 1996 Legislative session, the
ACLU of Wyoming lobbied against a same-sex marriage bill, which failed
introduction.  The ACLU expects to see a similar bill brought next year.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="11"></A>11.  MILITARY</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California, Nebraska, New York, Virginia, Washington</H5></CENTER>
<P>(See &quot;<I>Spotlight on 1996</I>&quot; for overall picture of challenges
to military's &quot;don't ask, don't tell&quot; ban on lesbian and gay service
members, including <I>Able v. United States</I>, <I>Philips v. Perry</I>, <I>Thomasson
v. Perry</I>, <I>Richenberg v. Perry</I>, <I>Holmes v. Perry</I> and <I>Watson
v. Perry</I>.)<B></B></P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Oregon</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Oregon National Guard v. Work</B><BR>	In April, 1993, Lieutenant Elli
Work, a member of the Oregon National Guard, testified before the Oregon Senate
Judiciary Committee urging support of SD 34, a proposal to expand the state's
civil rights law to provide protection based on sexual orientation.  In her
testimony, Lt. Work identified herself as a lesbian.  The National Guard began
an investigation of whether she had violated the &quot;don't ask, don't tell&quot;
law, and the ACLU of Oregon took her case.  Lt. Work has since been promoted to
1st Lt., and the discharge process appears to be on hold.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Washington</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Cammermeyer v. Cheney</B><BR>	The plaintiff is a colonel in the
Washington National Guard.  Following a hearing in June 1991, the plaintiff was
discharged in 1992 on the ground that she acknowledged that she was a lesbian
during a top secret security clearance check required for admission to Army War
College.  Plaintiff brought suit in U.S. District Court against the Secretary of
Defense alleging that her discharge (1) constituted an equal protection
violation under the Fifth Amendment, and (2) violated her right to privacy under
the First, Fourth, and Ninth Amendments.  The U.S. District Court held plaintiff
was entitled to judgment on her equal protection and due process claims,
required the Defendants to reinstate her in the military, and held that the
regulation mandating separation from the service based on homosexual status or
statements was unconstitutional.  The Defendants have appealed.  The ACLU of 
Washington has filed an <I>amicus</I> in the case.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="12"></A>12.  PARENTING</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Colorado</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>G.K. &amp; L.J.</B><BR>	Two lesbians in an 18-year relationship each
have a child conceived through artificial insemination.  Both wanted to adopt
the child of their partner.  The court dismissed their joint adoption petitions
since the couple was not married.  The women filed a notice of appeal.  The
Colorado Attorney General's Office entered the case and is aggressively arguing
the constitutionality of the statute and the inability of same sex partners to
adopt.</P>
<P>	In September 1995, the ACLU filed an amicus brief on the
unconstitutionality of the adoption law.  In October 1995, counsel for the women
withdrew, and the ACLU, through cooperating attorney Kathy Pek of Holme, Roberts
&amp; Owen, took over their representation.  In June 1996, the Colorado Court of
Appeals ruled that a lesbian couple cannot adopt each other's children, that
under state law the couple must be married to make such adoptions, and that
Colorado does not recognize same-sex marriages.  The women have filed a Petition
for Rehearing.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Connecticut</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>In Re Baby Z (Superior Court, 1996)</B><BR>	In this second parent
adoption case, brought by the National Project and the Connecticut Civil
Liberties Union, Connecticut Superior Court Judge Hadley Austin reversed the
probate court and held that Connecticut law does not bar the nonbiological
mother in a lesbian couple from adopting their three-year-old son.  The case was
referred to the Connecticut Adoption Review Board for a waiver of the statutory
requirement that parental rights of the biological mother be terminated before
an adoption can proceed.  The case is now before the Adoption Review Board.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Florida</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Velen v. Velen</B><BR>	After the plaintiff told her husband and
daughter that she is a lesbian, her ex-husband insisted their daughter could
stay with the plaintiff only on condition that the plaintiff sleep in the same
room as her daughter, in a separate bed, and that the plaintiff's partner sleep
in a separate room with the door closed.  The plaintiff believed the arrangement
violated her right to privacy.  The ACLU of Florida represented the mother.  A
settlement satisfactory to the plaintiff was worked out.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Cox v. HRS</B><BR>	The ACLU of Florida and the Project represented a
gay man who sought to adopt a special-needs child.  Cox was denied the
opportunity to apply because of a Florida statute which says that &quot;no
person eligible to adopt under this statute may adopt if that person is a
homosexual.&quot;  In 1991, Cox filed suit challenging the constitutionality of

this section.  The trial court entered summary judgment, concluding that the
statute violated the Florida constitution.  The second district Court of Appeals
reversed and upheld the statute.  The decision was appealed to the Florida
Supreme Court.  The Supreme Court ruled that a more complete record was
necessary in order to determine the constitutionality of the statute under the
equal protection clause of the Florida Constitution.  The court affirmed the
district court's decision upholding the statute under Florida's right to privacy
and due process.  The court remanded the case for further proceeding in the
trial court.  Mr. Cox, however, decided not to pursue the case, and he filed a
motion for voluntary dismissal.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Amer v. Children's Home Society</B><BR>	After June Amer attempted to
become the adoptive parent of a special needs child, and learned of Florida
statute prohibiting lesbians and gay men from becoming adoptive parents, the
ACLU of Florida filed a challenge to the law.  The case was put on hold pending
the decision in Cox v. HRS.  Since that case was dismissed, the Amer case is now
going forward.  A trial should be held next spring.  The Project is assisting.</P>

<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Georgia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Duda v. Duda</B><BR>	A man who had concluded that he might be gay filed
for divorce.  The trial judge struck jurors who said they might be prejudiced
against gay men and lesbians and who indicated an inability to decide the case
on its law and facts.  The Georgia Supreme Court granted review.  The ACLU of
Georgia filed an amicus brief arguing that it was not an abuse of discretion to
strike such jurors for cause.  The case was decided favorably.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Missouri</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Denial of Adoption</B><BR>The ACLU of Missouri is representing a gay
man who applied through the Jackson County Division of Family Services in May of
1995 to adopt.  The home studies were very positive.  In February of this year,
complainant was notified by DFS that his application was denied because &quot;Missouri
case law does not support an award of legal custody to a homosexual.&quot;  The
case is now in an administrative appeal.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Jersey</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>In The Matter of the Adoption of 2 Children by H.R.</B><BR>	In 
September 1994, a New Jersey Superior Court judge denied H.R.'s application to
legally adopt her partner's two children as a co-parent.  Both children were
conceived through artificial insemination.  The trial judge denied the adoption,
on the ground that the statute required terminating the parental rights of the
biological parent unless the new parent was a spouse of the biological parent. 
The ACLU of New Jersey filed an amicus brief on appeal, arguing that the lower
court's ruling violated both the New Jersey constitution and statutory law, and
was contrary to the best interests of the children.  The New Jersey Superior
Court, Appellate Division, held that New Jersey's adoption statute permitted
same sex partner adoptions.  In a precedent setting opinion that is binding
state-wide, the Appellate Division held that the statute had to be read broadly
so as to promote the best interests of the child, which precluded limiting
co-parent adoptions to legal spouses.  Professor Annamay Sheppard of Rutgers Law
School was the cooperating attorney.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New York</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>In Re Dana</B><BR>	In a very important precedent setting decision, New
York's highest court ruled that the unmarried partner of a lesbian mother may
adopt the mother's child.  In a stirring opinion, the court said no interest was
to be served by denying the child a legal relationship with both of her parents.
 The Project filed an <I>amicus</I> brief on behalf of the partner.  It argued
that New York's adoption law should be interpreted to allow the unmarried
partner of a biological mother to adopt without affecting the legal relationship
between the biological mother and the child.  It also discusses constitutional
problems that would arise if the court came to the contrary conclusion, allowing
children of married couples to have two legal parents whereas other children
cannot.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Ohio</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Adoption Bill</B><BR>	In February, 1996, State Senator Gary
Suhadolnik, R-Strongsville, attempted to add a last minute amendment to an
adoption reform bill which would have barred gays and lesbians from adopting
children or becoming foster parents.  The ACLU of Ohio was successful in getting
the measure tabled.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Virginia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Bottoms v. Bottoms</B><BR>	The Lesbian and Gay Rights Project and the
ACLU of Virginia represent Sharon Bottoms in her fight to regain custody of her
son.  Ms. Bottoms' son was taken away from her by her mother because Ms. Bottoms
is a lesbian.  The Virginia Court of Appeals reversed the trial court's decision
awarding custody to Ms. Bottoms' mother in a strong opinion which said that
sexual orientation had no place in custody determination.  That decision was
unfortunately reversed by the Virginia Supreme Court, which ruled that being gay
means that a person is generally unfit to parent.  A new trial court proceeding
has been filed based on &quot;changed circumstances&quot; to try and reunite
Sharon and her son.  In February 1996, Henrico County Juvenile and Domestic
Relations Court, refused to restore custody.  A hearing was scheduled for August
1996, but the plaintiff has decided to discontinue the litigation.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Washington</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Wicklund v. Wicklund</B><BR>	Following the divorce of Ward and Corinne
Wicklund in 1994, the court produced a parenting plan for the couple's four
children which forbade Ward from any affectionate behavior which reflects the
fact that he is gay in front of his children.  The court restricted both parents
from hand-holding, kissing or hugging another partner in front of the children
unless they are married to that person.  The court based its decision on the
children's strong religious upbringing.  The ACLU of Washington is representing
Ward in his appeal of the court's parenting plan to the Washington Court of
Appeals.  Oral arguments were heard in May of 1996.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Anti-Gay Adoption Bill</B><BR>	The ACLU was successful in its
opposition to HB 1171 which would have &quot;prohibit[ed] the adoption, foster
care, and placement of children by homosexuals, based on the belief that it is
not in the best interest of a minor child to be placed in a household with a
homosexual.&quot;  This bill also declared itself &quot;necessary for the
immediate preservation of the public peace, morals, or safety.&quot;  HB 1171
died in the Committee on Children and Family Services.  </P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="13"></A>13.  PRIVACY</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Acevedo v. City of Los Angeles</B><BR>	As part of Acevedo's worker's
compensation case, the City Attorney's office demanded that she name all sexual
partners. When she refused, the city filed a motion to stop payment of her
worker's compensation benefits.  Federal and state law specifically preclude
this type of questioning.  The ACLU of Southern California filed an amicus brief
before the Worker's Compensation Board alleging the questions violated her First
Amendment and privacy rights.  The Los Angeles City Attorney's office agreed
that the questioning was &quot;over broad&quot; and agreed to retract the
request to terminate Acevedo's benefits.  In addition, the City Attorney agreed
to train all city attorneys in the worker's compensation division on the 
impropriety of similar questions.</P>
<P></P>

<P><B>Juvenile Offenders</B><BR>	The ACLU of Northern California persuaded
Sacramento County Juvenile Hall to stop its practice of displaying juveniles'
sexual orientation on charts visible to the other detainees.  Prior to our
intervention, Juvenile Hall placed distinctive symbols next to the names of gay
and lesbian youth which set the stage for constant harassment and threats from
other detainees.</P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="14"></A>14.  STUDENTS &amp; SCHOOLS</H3>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Alabama</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Gay/Lesbian/Bisexual Alliance at the University of South Alabama v.
Evans</B><BR>	The National Project and the ACLU of Alabama represent the
Gay/Lesbian/Bisexual Alliance at the University of South Alabama.  The alliance
is challenging an Alabama statute which forbids any college or university from
recognizing or providing facilities or funding to any lesbian or gay student
organization. 
</P>
<P>	In January, the U.S. District Court struck the statute down as a violation
of the First Amendment.  After the decision, the Attorney General requested a
stay of the decision so that he could use the law to prevent a southeastern
conference of lesbian and gay students from meeting at the University of
Alabama.  Both the District Court and the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals refused
stays.  The case is now on appeal before the 11th Circuit. Fern Singer is the
cooperating attorney on the case.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>In re: EB &amp; MO</B><BR>	ACLU of Northern California directly
represents two public middle school teachers facing credential revocation for
presiding over a class at which outside speakers answered students' questions
about the lives and problems faced by lesbians and gay men.  The complainants
assert that the gay and lesbian speakers graphically described their personal
sex lives.  The teachers strongly deny that this occurred, and assert that they
would have interrupted had the speakers done so.</P>
<P>	Based on the hotly disputed allegations, a state credentialing committee
recommended its most extreme sanction -- license revocation.  The case is
currently pending before the state Commission on Teacher Credentialing.
Ballinger Kemp is co-counsel in the case.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Schools Project</B><BR>	The ACLU of Northern California implemented a
Gay &amp; Lesbian Youth project designed to secure and defend gay and lesbian
youths' rights to receive education in a discrimination free environment.  The
project consists of in-service educational programs regarding homophobia and
advocacy and litigation to protect the rights of lesbian and gay youth.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Georgia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Sex Education</B><BR>	Senator Perry McQuire introduced a bill to
severely restrict sex education in the Georgia public schools.  Four hearings
were necessary in order to accommodate all of the speakers.  The ACLU testified
that the restrictions in the bill on what could be taught were so severe that
only religious based curricula, such as Sex Respect, could be taught.  Though a
slightly watered down version did pass the Committee, it died in the Rule
Committee. </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Kansas</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Stevana Case, et al. v. Unified District No. 233, Johnson County, Kansas</B><BR>	On
November 29, 1995, the Federal District Court in Kansas City, Kansas, ruled in
favor of ACLU plaintiffs from the Olathe, Kansas school district who had filed
suit to protect against censorship by the school district.  The superintendent
and school board members of the district removed copies of <I>Annie On My Mind</I>,
a lesbian-themed national book award novel, from the shelves of the school
libraries in the district.</P>
<P>	When the school district refused to return the book, the ACLU filed suit. 
During the 1995 trial, the school board president testified that homosexuality
is a mental disorder that leads to a destructive life and is a sin.  Although
the district claimed it removed the book because it was &quot;educationally
unsuitable,&quot; the judge ruled the district had removed the book because it
disagreed with ideas expressed in it. </P>
<P>	The court ordered the return of the book to the Olathe public school
libraries by January 2, 1996.  The school district did not appeal.  The
volunteer attorneys handling the case for the affiliate were David J. Waxse, J.
Eugene Balloun, and John Bullock from the Kansas City area law firm of Shook,
Hardy &amp; Bacon.  They were assisted by Marjorie Heins of ACLU's Art
Censorship Project.
</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Hampshire</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Walker v. Merrimack School District</B></P>
<P>	The Project and the ACLU of New Hampshire, along with People for the
American Way and Gay and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders in Boston filed this
case, which challenged a school board policy which prohibited anything in the
curriculum which might have the effect of &quot;encouraging or supporting
homosexuality as a positive lifestyle alternative.&quot;  The case, filed in
federal court in New Hampshire, had the support of the local school teachers
association.  The filing of the case made the policy the central focus of the
school board election in May.  The voters elected a board majority composed of
candidates who pledged to repeal the policy.  Shortly after the election, on
June 3, they did so, bringing the case to a successful conclusion.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>North Dakota</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Community Values in Public Schools</B></P>
<P>	The ACLU of North Dakota served on a committee assigned to identify and
define &quot;community values&quot; for the Bismarck (ND) public school system. 
The ACLU was critical of the committee's refusal to be inclusive of and
sensitive to the community's gay and lesbian students, and engaged the School 
Superintendent in an ongoing dialogue about anti-gay harassment and violence. 
The school system is slowly beginning to be more sensitive to the special needs
of its gay and lesbian students.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Utah</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>High School Student Clubs</B><BR>	Sponsored by Craig L. Taylor, Senate
Bill 246 limits teachers' ability to speak about lesbian and gay issues as well
as their ability to sponsor gay clubs at high schools.  The bill was introduced
in response to the formation of a Gay/Straight Alliance at a Salt Lake City high
school.  The ACLU of Utah actively lobbied against the bill which was vetoed on
March 20, 1996 by the Governor.</P>
<P>	Senate Bill 1003 was another bill sponsored by Craig L. Taylor.  This bill
prohibits schools from allowing clubs that &quot;involve human sexuality.&quot; 
Despite active lobbying efforts by the ACLU of Utah, the bill was passed on
April 18, 1996, and signed into law on June 18, 1996.  Currently the ACLU of
Utah -- in conjunction with the ACLU Lesbian and Gay Rights Project, Lambda
Legal Defense Fund, and the National Center for Lesbian Rights -- is preparing a
lawsuit to challenge the newly enacted law.<BR></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P>    
</P>
