</DOCHDR>
<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Substantive Plenary V</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><h1>Transcript of Substantive Plenary V<br>
 Racial Equality</center></h1>
<blockquote>
MR. WARE:  Thank you, Rosetta, and I
    would like to thank you all for hanging in there.
    It's been a pretty long day and I know you must be
    feeling a little bit exhausted.  But I think this
    is a very important plenary, certainly very
    important to me because I think it's not an
    overstatement to say that the state of race
    relations in America in 1995 is headed in a
    direction that was reached in 1895, one year before
   Plessy v. Ferguson was decided which, in turn,
   erected an elaborate system of racial segregation
   in America.<p>

              Just a couple of days ago, in a meeting
   with a group of black journalists, the speaker of
   the House, Newt Gingrich, suggested that
   African-Americans should look inward for the
   resolution of our problems.  If we are denied
   mortgages because of redlining and other
   discriminatory practices, we should not seek
   redress in the courts.  Instead, we should organize
   our own credit union so we won't have to rely on
   the lending institutions that violate federal law.<p>


              Now, if that is not a call for
   resegregation, I don't know how we should interpret
   the untenured professor from Georgia now.<p>


           The U.S. Supreme Court is no less
    cynical and condescending.  In Adaran Construction
    v Penia, the affirmative action case decided just a
    few days ago, the court held that the standard
    applies to affirmative action programs established
    by the federal government.<p>


               I think I need to remind everybody that
    these programs were intended to break down
    discriminatory barriers.  However, the court was
   concerned that the 10 percent of the contracts
   reserved for disadvantaged businesses might unduly
   limit the competitive opportunities of white
   males.  The remaining 90 percent was not an
   equitable share.  The majority was concerned that
   innocent white males would suffer diminished
   opportunities.<p>

              Now, it does not matter that Adaran
   never hired a minority worker or a contractor with
   a minority company.  It does not matter that Adaran
   benefits from an old boy network of white males
   from which blacks and women are excluded.  The
   government can't act to break down these barriers
   because it might result in a white-owned company
   losing a contract.  The majority ignored years of
   precedent, overruled the one precedent that it did
     not ignore, and to quote from the dissent, it
  cannot tell the difference between a no-trespassing
   sign and a welcome mat.<p>

             And finally, speaking for the forces of
  what I don't know, Justice Clarence Thomas declared
   that affirmative action was stigmatizing to
    African-Americans.  I wish he would speak for
    himself.<p>

               Now, the affirmative action defeat,
   Adaran, was coupled with a blow against equal
   education in the Missouri school segregation case
   decided the same day.  Speaking next will be Julius
   Chambers, who in the late 1960s persuaded a very
   different Supreme Court that states should be
  obligated to eliminate all vestiges of segregation,
  root and branch.  This formally changes the
   standard and alters that to the extent
   practicable.<p>

              It does not matter that schools are
   still segregated and black children are still
   receiving separate and demonstrably unequal
  educational opportunities.  That would, said the
   majority view, would be attributable to societal
 discrimination, rather than by the actions taken by
  any local school boards, and is therefore
    irrelevant.<p>

               The decisions in these cases and the
    attitudes of political leaders like Newt Gingrich
    makes the agendas of those in power clear.  Race
    and gender equality has never been an aspect of
    American society and those in power are intent on
    keeping that great American tradition intact.<p>

               Now, the ACLU is committed to race and
    gender equality, and it is one of the few
 organizations that is attempting to promote equal
   protection under the law, and it is in a unique
   position to commit its vast resources to protecting
   these principles in the courts and in the
   legislature.<p>

              The ACLU could, as some would prefer,
   limit its efforts to freedom of speech and freedom
  of religion, or it can redouble its efforts to
   advancing equality.  But I submit to you that
   speech, free speech and religion cannot be
   exercised if liberty and equality do not exist.<p>

             So I hope that the national organization
   and all of the affiliates and chapters will
   recognize this as you set your agendas for the
   upcoming year.  Thank you very much.<p>

              We will now hear from Julius Chambers
   and we will hear from all of the speakers and then
    at the end we hope that we will have time to take
    questions from the audience.  Thank you very much.<p>

               MR. CHAMBERS:  Thank you, Professor Ware
    and thank you, members of the ACLU.<p>

               Some years ago I served as a member of
    the national board of ACLU and began a relationship
    that has continued through today.  I worked with a
    number of your state members in North Carolina in a
  number of cases and I continue to work with the
   North Carolina Civil Liberties Union and I continue
   to pay my annual dues.<p>

              But you know, from those early
   experiences, I was asking myself, what am I going
   to talk to the ACLU about today?  You guys have
  read all the cases, you know all of the legislation
   and you know everything that's going on even in the
   area of civil rights.  I did remember, however,
   some years ago, Justice Marshall, shortly before
  leaving the bench, talking about how civil
   liberties and civil rights were intertwined and
   where there was retrenchment in one area, there was
   also retrenchment in the other and one can't expect
  to pursue one without the other.<p>

              I also remember an experience that I had
    during the riots in central Los Angeles that
    brought home to me how divided we are in America.
    For some years, as director-counsel of the Legal
    Defense Fund, I had been trying to build a closer
    relationship with the Puerto Rican Legal Defense
    Fund, the Mexican-American Legal Defense Fund and
    the Asian-American, and I thought we had
    established a rapport and that we understood each
    other.<p>

              Well, to some extent lawyers did
   understand each other, but I have not gotten over
   yet the division that I saw in several meetings we
   had trying to build a better relationship.
  Somewhere along the line we developed more lack of
   trust in each other.<p>

              I also remember experiences here in New
   York where we were talking about the congressional
  districts and the Hispanics were demanding more
   congressional seats and African-Americans were not
   willing to relinquish a seat.  There were four
  African-American congressman and one Hispanic, and
   in order to increase Hispanic representation, we
   would lose an African-American seat.  We didn't
  give it up then and I am not sure we will give it
   up in 1995 or 1996, and I remember experiences in
    Texas, the same kind of problem.<p>

              Then I went back home to North Carolina
    and began to note that the increasing division
    between blacks and whites.  I had lived in North
    Carolina eight and a half years before and thought
    we had begun to build a relationship that would
    make for a true America.  I was also smarting from
    comments of a very close friend of mine, Derrick
   Bell, who asked, look at what you have accomplished
   with all these years of civil rights litigation.
   Your schools are resegregated, you can't get a job
   like a white person, we are not enforcing
   Title VIII, we are now arguing about the
   constitutionality of Title II.  Everything you
   worked on where you thought you had accomplished
   something is now being wiped out.  And the races
   are just as divided today as they were when you
  started.  What have you accomplished?  And what can
   you tell young people about using the law to effect
   change and lasting opportunities among people?<p>

        It's a good question, isn't it?  I grew   up in North
    Carolina.  My father couldn't get a
   lawyer because no lawyer in North Carolina would
   represent a black person in suing a white person,
  and I decided at an early age to go to law school.
    I went to segregated schools and I know what it was
    like to try to get a job despite one's ability to
    perform.  I went to Chapel Hill, graduated, I am
    told, at the top of my class, and no law firm in
    North Carolina was prepared to hire a black
    lawyer.<p>

               North Carolina wasn't unique, because I
    will never forget going to Washington and having an
    interview with Covington & Burling, and being told
   when I walked in, we never have hired any colored
   boys.  That was my introduction, and I remember
   talking about Justice Marshall and Jack Greenberg
   in 1961 about how one might use the law to effect
   change.<p>

              And, you know, I became a disciple, a
   believer, and I set about using the law to effect
   change.  And we did.  Just look at it.  I came
   along after Brown v. Board of Education, when our
   U.S. Supreme Court was still reluctant to accept
   any other decision or case talking about
   implementing Brown.<p>

              I went through the same struggle as all
   of us in getting a court eventually to decide Green
   v. New King County Board of Education and I will
   never forget going through the struggle of
   Charlotte v. Mecklenburg Board of Education and
    being asked even by Justice Stewart, do you really
    think your clients want integration of the schools,
    because a black group during the argument tried to
    submit an amicus brief opposing busing and
    desegregation.<p>

               We prevailed in that case, and I know,
    going out of Swann, we saw integration going on in
    a number of schools throughout the South.<p>

              I also remember going through with
   lawyers all around the country with litigating
   Title VII, employment discrimination based on race
   or gender.  I remember the strategies that we went
   through, how we really worried whether the court
   would impose procedural rules that would permit one
   to litigate a case or whether the substantive rules
   the courts would adopt would permit one to
   establish a violation and what the court would
   finally do with remedies.  We made some progress.
   We got some remedies.  We opened up some
   opportunities.<p>

              I also remember going through the same
   trying moments with housing discrimination, with
   voting rights, and how we began with new ventures
   in health and in what we call environmental
   equity.<p>

               I was teaching a class at the University
    of Michigan about five years ago, and one of my
    students asked, if you had a chance to do it over
    again, would you do it?  Another tough question.  I
    began to see, in 1975, retrenchment by a Supreme
    Court that was setting the tone for how the court
    was cutting back on procedural rules and
    substantive rules and remedies that would affect
   everything we had been about, you and I.  And I
   began to worry.<p>

              Well, we don't have but a few minutes
   and then I understand we have questions.  I want to
   tell you, going through the decisions of the
   Supreme Court in the last four or five years have
   been trying.  It's as though the Supreme Court
   never heard of slavery and never heard of race
   discrimination.<p>

              Just read with me the court's decisions
   this term.  There is an assumption that since 1954
   we eliminated race and gender discrimination and it
   is incumbent on anybody who contends that there was
  race discrimination to go through again and prove
   there was race discrimination; and race
   discrimination agenda is not a group practice, it's
    an individual practice, so even if you prove all
    blacks and women were excluded, you are not
    entitled to a group remedy, you get only an
    individual remedy.<p>

               I read the Supreme Court's decision in
    Kansas City, and I couldn't help but ask, have we
    really reversed Brown v. Board of Education?  What
    do I tell the students now in Charlotte-
    Mecklenburg, where we are resegregating the
   schools?  Or students in Durham, North Carolina,
   where a group of white parents just filed a lawsuit
   to enjoin desegregation of city schools because any
   desegregation order would have to consider race,
   and you can't consider race unless you have a
   legitimate reason for doing so; and even if you
   consider race and have a legitimate reason,
   whatever remedy you impose has to measure the
   violation you established, and certainly
   reassigning students on the basis of race is in
   excess of whatever constitutional violation one
   might find.<p>

              I remember Norfolk, Virginia, where we
   resegregated the schools because we wanted
   neighborhood schools, and I watched 60 and 70 and
   80 percent of young black children dropping out of
    school, and that would finish them.  Do we worry
    about it?<p>

               I also remember testifying in Congress
    and listening to congresspeople indicate this
    belief that race discrimination doesn't continue to
    exist in 1995, and wondering why one would be there
    talking about school desegregation, employment
    discrimination, housing discrimination.  And if one
    extended it to discrimination against the poor,
   they would be equally as appalled.<p>

              I gave that brief history because I want
   to conclude suggesting something to my brothers and
   sisters at ACLU.  Back in the 1930s lawyers got
   together and began to map strategy on how they
   would encourage the U.S. Supreme Court to change
   this interpretation of equal protection.  It was a
   long struggle and they mapped strategy on how to
   achieve that objective.<p>

              In 1995, I think it is imperative for
   ACLU and other civil rights and other civil
   liberties groups to step back and map strategies
   anew.  We are not going to win this battle with the
   same approach we have taken over the years.  We
   just aren't going to convince this Court, and
   perhaps the one that follows.<p>

               I have argued for years that my reading
    of equal protection is not one where one is
    required to establish purpose and intent.  My
    reading of equal protection is not one where a
    court simply enjoins a discriminator from
    discriminating in the future.<p>

               I read the Civil War amendments or post
    Civil War amendments as imposing an affirmative
    obligation on the part of the federal government to
   ensure that all citizens are accorded equal
   protection of the law and I read the amendments as
   saying to the U.S. Government, you are obligated to
   go out and ensure that no citizen is deprived of
   equal protection because of race or gender or color
   or any other objectional feature.<p>

              That is my reading of the equal
   protection clause, and I know people differ, they
   ask me, where do you draw a line.  I don't care
   right now where you draw a line.  They ask me,
   where do you get affirmative obligation.  That's
   what I think the court will eventually hold.<p>

              How do you protect the poor?  The same
   way you protect black folks and women and other
   nationalities.  It is that kind of bold approach
   and strategizing that I think ACLU and other civil
  rights organizations must begin to address.<p>

               Our America is disintegrating along
    racial and ethnic lines.  We are disintegrating
    according to our economic status in life.  And we
    can talk about all of the civil liberties we want.
    Until we adopt a position and pursue it vigorously,
    ensuring a reading of the Constitution that will
    accord protection to all people, then we are
    barking up a hollow tree.  And I would urge you,
   like I have been urging the other civil rights
   organizations, to step back a moment and map a new
   strategy and map a new reading of the Constitution
   along the lines that I have suggested.  Thank you.<p>

              (Applause.)<p>

            MR. WARE:  We will now hear from
   Jonathan Kozol.<p>

              MR. KOZOL:  I am not going to be very
   much more cheerful, I am afraid.  I will try to
   be.<p>

              I don't need to tell anybody here that
  in terms of school segregation and inequality our
   nation is now in a situation very much like that of
   a hundred years ago, before Plessy.  It's obvious
   to everybody that our schools are separate and
   unequal.  I started in this profession years ago in
    Boston, just walked into a school, said I wanted to
    be a teacher, and I ended up teaching in a
    segregated Boston school, and like many young
    people in that hopeful era, I was convinced, you
   know, that within another generation, we would have
    that licked.  I thought, in another generation,
    this won't be an issue in America.<p>

               Well, in a horrible sense, that proved
    to be true.  It's not an issue now, it's accepted.<p>

              I guess what upsets me the most is that
   when I talk about the fact that our schools are
   still separate and unequal to white affluent
   audiences, even liberal audiences in New York, for
   example, people who live here in New York, I get a
  kind of aching weariness in them, a sense that, oh,
   we have heard all that, and somehow the sense that,
   we cared about that enough long ago, so we made the
   contribution.<p>

              There is also the illusion that caring
   about something for 20 or 30 years is the
   equivalent of doing something about that.  I am
  sorry to say I feel that, more amongst liberals in
   New York than in the ordinary mainstream of people
   in America, there is a kind of cynicism amongst the
   privileged in this city.<p>

             I sense it often when -- and I talked to
    journalists, I have a lot of friends in the press
    here, some of my college classmates, and I will
    say, why do people here, good, thoughtful people,
    why do they accept all of this, and he explains to
    me, well, it is compassion fatigue.<p>

               I guess you have heard that phrase,
    compassion fatigue, and that's why they, you know,
    they will walk over the bodies of beggars on the
   street.  That's why they will agree to let business
   groups round up the homeless and put them on the
   trains and ship them back to the ghetto, where they
   belong.<p>

              I repeat everything, everything that
   white privileged people tell me, I repeat to poor
   black people.  I consider that my job as a
   subversive intellectual, and my newest book, which
   is going to be published in the fall, I spent most
  of a year in the poorest congressional district in
   America, which is the South Bronx, right here in
   New York, in the poorest neighborhood in the South
   Bronx, and talked with a lot of children and
   parents.  The book is different than most books
   about the poor in that they don't spend most of
   their time telling me what is wrong with themselves
    but they spend a lot of time commenting on our
    society, on the privileged.<p>

               One of the ministers I met in the Bronx,
    one of the priests, said, in our society, the poor
    consider it a problem for the rich, and so the rich
    set up these think tanks and institutes to study
    the defects of the poor.  Now I am beginning to
    think, well, maybe it would be great to set up a
    think tank of the poor to study the defects of the
   rich to find out what their value problems are
   and -- I mean, I think, yes, the poor sometimes are
   a problem for the rich, but in this city, at least
   the rich are an infinitely greater problem than the
   poor, no question about it.<p>

              But anyway, I guess what upsets me most,
   is that even among my allies, the good folks,
   people I have worked with for years, some of them
   actually in power, some of them in the House of
   Representatives, in the Senate, many in fairly
   authoritative positions around the country, the
   entire dialogue about these issues is so low-key
   and muted.  It doesn't have enough energy, it
   doesn't have enough frenzy.<p>

              I would even go so far as to say it
  isn't apocalyptic enough to equal the amount of
suffering that is going on now.  What frustrates me
    is that the enemies, the spokespeople of the
    privileged, the Rush Limbaughs, the Newt
    Gingriches, they have plenty of energy, plenty of
    passion; the Pat Buchanans, they soar with elegant
    intensity, raw, vicious and mean, and they are not
    tired.<p>

               I read and reread Yates' lines, where
    they say the best lack all conviction.  It comes to
   mind every time President Clinton gives a press
   conference, every time.  I work for him, I like him
   very much, I like him personally, but why -- and
   our press, the centrist or liberal press in the
   country, to the extent there still are centrist or
   liberal papers, they often seem manacled by an
   enforced civility they will not call things by
   their right names.<p>

              In New York City, I cull the papers year
   after year.  I see the descriptions of the poorest
   neighborhoods I know.  They never call them
   ghettos.  The poorest segregated neighborhoods,
   they don't call them segregated.  Yes, they do in
   other parts of the country, but not in New York.
   They call them gritty neighborhood, hard-bitten
   neighborhood, low-income neighborhood populated by
  people called minorities, as if they were Albanians
    or something like that, and impacted communities.<p>

               One black man I know said I hate that
    word when I see that in the newspaper, impacted
    neighborhoods, it is like our black children are
    like so many teeth who came through the gums at a
    bad angle.  They should call things by their right
    names.<p>

               Most of you who are not from New York
   City, and I gather most of you are not, do
   something while you are here, something I do when I
   go to the South Bronx in New York, but go down to
   the subway train, right here at 42nd Street, or
   59th Street, get on the number 6 train, the number
   4, or the number 2 train heading north, and watch
   what happens.<p>

              For about six or eight stops, you will
   see people of all races together on the train.
   Then at 86th Street, most of the white people
   leave.  At 96th Street, all of the white people
   leave, except you, if you are still on the train.
   Then you will ride on into one of the largest
   ghettos in the western world, the combined ghetto
   of Harlem, Washington Heights, the South Bronx,
   which by the end of the century will constitute an
   almost uninterrupted ghetto the size of Houston,
    Texas.<p>

               I can't tell you anything about law,
    litigation, how to fight these cases; I don't know
    that.  But I can give you a sense briefly, for a
    couple of minutes, of what it is like, what it
    feels like now.  I have spent a lot of time, either
    in the schools or in the churches, where the
    children's mothers come to pray for their kids,
   where the kids come sometimes after school for
   food.<p>

              Let me describe some of the schools I
   see.  I see schools -- I think of a school in the
   South Bronx where there is so little money that
   when little girls go out to recess and jump rope --
   they do double-dutch.  Do you know what that is?  I
   love to watch it, I love to hear the rhymes the
   children make up, it is so beautiful.  But the
   school can't afford jump rope, so they give them
   cut-up pieces of TV cable to use in place of jump
   ropes.<p>

              This school is a classic New York
   segregated school.  Two thirds of the teachers of
   the school aren't certified.  They dump permanent
   subs into these schools.<p>

               Another school in the neighborhood, it
    is so crowded the children are having classes in
    urinals, they just take over a former bathroom.  Or
    coat closets without windows.  One teacher said,
    well, at least there is nothing to distract them,
    they can't look outside the window.  Closets and
    stair landings.<p>

               One famous high school in New York,
    Morris High School, which I wrote about in Savage
   Inequalities, just a monument to pedagogical
   apartheid in America, a huge school of 1,600 kids,
   and last year I think 80 children graduated,
   wherein it should have been 400 or 500.  A famous
   school where Colin Powell went, when it was an
   integrated school long ago.  He went back there a
   couple of years ago to give a talk.<p>

              This is part of this fatuous boosterism
   that is going on, where you had a segregated,
   unequal school but you send some black hero in to
   give the kids a talk, and sometimes it is
   wonderful, like with Jesse Jackson, it is really
  terrific, he says, kids, you are somebody, and they
   chant back, I am somebody, and he is really good.
   He has a wonderful, electric effect on the kids.<p>

              But the thing is, it is all for nothing,
   it doesn't work.  They can say it a hundred times,
    I am somebody, but everything about that school,
    that neighborhood, the physical stink of the
    school, the demographic composition of the school
    tells him, in the eyes of this society, you aren't
    anyone at all, and they get the message.<p>

               Colin Powell isn't that good a speaker,
    he is really boring, but he went there, gave the
    kids the typical sound bite speech, you know, told
   the kids don't use drugs, have good values, all
   those things.<p>

              A boy, part of the ritual for the TV
   cameras, the boy got up after his speech and gave
   him a trophy to show -- for Colin Powell -- how
   much his speech meant to him.  Ten months later,
   the boy who handed him the trophy was arrested for
   homicide.<p>

              One doctor I know in the South Bronx
   says that even when a charismatic person comes to
   speak to these kids, it is like walking into an
   intensive care ward in a leper colony and saying,
   rise.  He is right.<p>

              There is one school in The Bronx called
   Taft, 4,000 kids go there.  The school has broken
   down their self-respect so much -- I mean, I won't
    even describe it to you, I have written so many
   books about it it makes me sad to recapitulate the
    details, but you can imagine what it is like.  It
    is a horror house.<p>

               The kids, their self-respect has been
    broken down so much, they made a joke about the
    name of the school.  The kids tell me all these
    things.  The kids tell me what Taft stands for, it
    means Training Animals for Tomorrow.  That's what
   we have done to them, that they believe that now.<p>

              Last Christmas, I was visiting in the
   home of one of the families I am friends with in
   the South Bronx.  This is a wonderful family and I
   know the mother, who is a little younger than I am,
   a beautiful woman, wonderful woman, a black woman
   who has AIDS, she has had it for 12 years, she is a
   survivor, and her daughter, a lovely person, she is
  about 25, and her two children, and they live on a
   street where there were 21 murders in that block,
   21 murders in the past three years, just in that
   block.<p>

              The elementary school in the
   neighborhood ranks 625 out of 626 elementary
   schools in New York City in reading.  The school
   has 800 children, one white student out of 800.  A
   teacher at the school told me that when she had
    that white boy last year, she said, that's the
    first white student I have had in 18 years.  It's
    just like Mississippi 40 years ago, 50 years ago.
    No difference at all.  Except at least in
    Mississippi you could look out the windows and see
    the healing greenery of pretty countryside.  Here
    you look out the window at a homeless shelter in
    one direction and a sewage plant in the other.<p>

              These children have been so broken
   down.  They have a wonderful grandma and a
   wonderful mother.  But they are so demolished in
   their spirits.  I watched them pray on Christmas
   Eve, when they went into their bedroom, knelt down
   by the bed, and the beds are very low, almost near
  the floor; the people are afraid of having regular
   beds there, for fear of bullets coming through the
   window, and a lot of people have beds on the floor,
   so these people had low beds.  I heard them go in
   and pray, God bless Mommy, God bless Nanny.  God,
   don't punish me for being black.<p>

              I said to their mother, did you teach
   them that.  She said, of course not, I hate that
   when I hear them say that.  Where they learned it,
   they learned it from their friends.<p>

           The schools are only a small part of the
    picture for these children.  I encourage people to
    bring suits, equality suits, desegregation suits in
    the courts.  But it is a small part of the
    problem.  They have to rely on segregated
    hospitals, where they almost never see a white
    American doctor, or black American doctors either.
    One woman going to the hospital said to me, last
    time I was there, I had six different doctors, one
   was Pakistani, one was Korean, one was Philippine,
   one was from Haiti, Africa, and they are nice
   people, but I can't understand them, and she looked
   at them in amusement and she said, where are all of
   the doctors from America?<p>

              The same kids live in housing which is
   as bad as anything I saw in the rural South, in
   Tunica, Mississippi, 30 years ago.  I know of three
   children who died this year, two in household
   fires, because they were living in firetrap
   apartments, and one in the building where the
   elevator didn't work.  It had been broken for
   years.  Complaints were made, nobody ever did
  anything about it, and finally the door just opened
   one day and the boy fell three flights to his
   death.  These are little kids, innocent children.<p>

              A lot of these kids have asthma.  I
    mean, that is the least of their worries, in a way,
    I mean, this is a neighborhood where one in four
    women who come to obstetric wards are
    HIV-positive.  25 percent.  You can imagine the
    rate of pediatric AIDS in this neighborhood.  It is
    a neighborhood of AIDS orphans, dozens and dozens
    of children whose mothers and daughters have AIDS.
    The less apocalyptic things, ordinary things like
   asthma, I don't know if they are more interesting
   to me, or maybe I write about asthma because more
   people can identify with that.<p>

              You have a whole neighborhood where the
   kids carry a pump like this in their pockets.  I
   carry one.  I grew up in the home of a neurotic
   Jewish psychiatrist, a very typical upbringing for
   a Jewish kid, so naturally, I had asthma.  It went
   away completely when I went to Harvard, and it went
   away completely until I went back to the South
   Bronx.<p>

             It is a neighborhood where the kids feel
   everything is conspiring against them.  The city,
   yes, puts everything smelly and toxic in their
   neighborhood.  There is a waste incinerator right
   near their homes which was supposed to go in this
    part of Manhattan but it was stopped here because
    white families here recognized it posed a cancer
    risk, respiratory risk to their children, so they
    put that in The Bronx instead.<p>

               That might have something to do with it,
    that might be a good civil liberties case, I
    guess.  But I don't think you really need to look
    for a scientific explanation.  I mean, all you need
    to look at is the racism of some and the inequity
   of others to see where the kids can't get fit air
   into their lungs.  Some of them have it so bad they
   have breathing machines next to their beds, oxygen
   tents next to their beds.<p>

              I will not go on any longer other than
   to say my new book, which will be out in the fall,
   has a hopeful title, and I don't know how I came up
   with a hopeful title because I was so depressed,
   but I spent a lot of time in church, and I agree
   with the Civil Liberties Union that religion should
   be kept separate from the state.  But I have been
   forced by what I have seen this year to take
   religion very seriously.  In a way, I feel
   heartsick to see the way the right wing has sort of
   been able to seize God as their ally in America.<p>

              The poor children I know are very
   devout, they believe in God, their mothers believe
    in God.  They have to, they have nothing else.  I
    asked the group of kids in school, what is the most
    beautiful thing you can think of.  Every time, the
    answer is heaven.  They never say anything on
    Earth, they speak of heaven.<p>

               I asked one lovely little girl I am
    going to see tomorrow, I asked her, where is
    heaven.  She said, upstairs.  I asked her where is
   hell.  She said, downstairs.  Then I asked, how
   far.  All the way down.  Like somebody in Saks
   Fifth Avenue takes the elevator, they drive it all
   the way down.<p>

              She was so vivid about it, I asked her
   what is it like in heaven, what is it like in hell,
   and she said, in heaven, you wear nightgowns,
   white, because you are angels, and in hell, you
   wear red pajamas.  You don't pay for things in
   money in heaven, you pay for things with smiles,
   and she also said, if you have a dog you loved, the
   dog would go to heaven, too, which made me very
   happy, because at the time she told me, I was
   mourning for my beagle who had just died.  After
   she told me that, I spent a long time trying to
   picture Newt Gingrich in red pajamas.<p>

              The thing I wanted to say to you is, I
    know this isn't of any use to you as lawyers, but I
    never took, I never thought much about heaven and
    hell, for years.  Probably not since I was an
    infant, a child.  You know, I went to Harvard, we
    are sophisticated, you don't believe in things like
    that, or if you do, you are not supposed to talk
    about them.  But this year I have thought about it
    a lot.<p>

              I will tell you, I think about it a
   lot.  I hope there is a heaven.  I hope there is a
   heaven, because it is unbearable to think that what
   these kids are getting in America is all there is.
   This is unacceptable, life at that level isn't
   enough.<p>

              Well, I wish you good luck in court and
   I will do my best in church.  Thank you.<p>

              (Applause.)<p>

              MR. WARE:  Thank you, Mr. Kozol.  We
   will now hear from Karen --<p>

              AUDIENCE MEMBER:  Point of information,
   what is the hopeful title?<p>

              MR. KOZOL:  Oh, I never said it.  It's
   Amazing Grace.<p>

              MR. WARE:  We will now hear from Karen
        Narasaki.<p>

               MS. NARASAKI:  Good afternoon.  I suffer
    from a small minority, vertically challenged, so I
    try to stay away from the big podiums.  I hope you
    will excuse me.<p>

               It is a very great honor for me to
    participate in the ACLU's national convention,
    particularly with such a distinguished panel.
    There is a special link with the ACLU and the
   Asian-American community.  As many of you know, it
   was an ACLU attorney who brought the suit and
   defended Fred Koramatsu in the infamous Kormatsu v
   the United States, on the internment of the
   Japanese Americans, and it was the ACLU who stood
   with a number of civil rights organizations filing
   for redress of the Civil Liberties Act which
   finally passed in 1988.  They have understood that
   race, unfortunately, in America is very
   complicated.  It is not just black-white, in all
   senses of that word.<p>

              Now, I have enormous admiration for the
   attorneys who work for ACLU because I have learned
   over the last several years what it is like to try
   to defend unpopular causes or unpopular groups.  In
   the three short years that I have worked in
    Washington, Asian-Americans have dropped from being
    held up as the model minority to now the reason for
    every ill, as immigrants, that this country now
    faces.  I just went to a press conference yesterday
   that Lamar Smith held on the introduction of his
    immigration bill and one of the congressmen said,
   we could solve our problems with having to build so
    many prisons, we could solve our overcrowding in
   schools, we could solve all of our economic
   problems if we just stopped immigration.<p>

              Now, I was never fond of the model
   minority myth, but I have to say that it's
   beginning to look pretty good to me these days.
   The kinds of rhetoric that I hear today are really
  scarily, eerily reminiscent of what was being said
   when the Chinese Exclusion Act was passed back in
   the 1800s and what was being said right before my
   parents were sent to internment camps in the
   1940s.<p>

              I think the challenge for those of us
   who believe in America's ideals and who struggle to
  ensure that the communities we belong to actually
   realize the fruits of these ideals is to not allow
   ourselves to become divided.<p>

              Two years ago, when the anti-gay
   Colorado initiative was being pushed, I was very
   proud when the Asian-American community stood with
   the gay community because we were smart enough to
   realize that that was only the first step in a hate
   movement, the first attempt to pick off what was
    perceived as the most vulnerable of communities.<p>

               Then last year, as you know, it was
    Prop 187 in California, targeted Latino and Asian
    undocumented immigrants, another vulnerable
   community.<p>

              This year the march of hate has
  accelerated to a record pace because now they have
   declared war on legal immigrants a la the cuts in
   immigration and welfare reform and on all
   minorities and on women now, with the attack on
   affirmative action.<p>

             I wonder -- and unfortunately my talk
   will not be more cheerful than my predecessors -- I
   wonder who is going to be left standing, what group
   is going to be left surviving, what group will be
   deserving enough to be deserving of equality and
   justice in this country.<p>

              AUDIENCE MEMBER:  The Senate.<p>

              MS. NARASAKI:  I don't know.  I think I
   can picture them in red pajamas, too.<p>

              And if you don't believe all of us are
    in this together, let me read you some of the
    recent quotes out of the violence report for 1994.
    These are things that actually happened in 1994,
    and I apologize in advance for the language.<p>

               In 1994, when there was a Proposition
    187 flier that was being stuffed into mailboxes in
    LA, it read:  "We need a real border.  First we get
    the spics, then the gooks and at last we get the
   niggers.  Deportation.  They are all going home."<p>

              And in a campus bathroom in a
   Connecticut university, swastikas and a message
   purportedly signed by the KKK was scrawled on the
   wall.  It read, "minority women will be raped and
   murdered if blacks, Latinos and Asians refuse to
   leave the campus."<p>

             Now, in this atmosphere, here are just a
   few of the challenges that we are facing today.
  Immigration.  To put this in context as to why this
   is so important to the Asian-American community,
   you have to understand our history.  For well over
   75 years, Asians' immigration to the United States
   was either totally blocked or restricted.  Even
   after the repeal of the Chinese Exclusion Act in
   the 1940s, immigration from China was at a level of
   105 persons per year at the same time when
    immigration from Germany was 20,000 per year.  It
    was not until 1965 that the racial premises of our
    immigration laws were dropped, thus starting the
    great wave both from Latin America and from Asia,
    both as refugees and as legal immigrants, and it
    has only been 30 years since immigration became
    race neutral, and again we face a racial battle
    ground.<p>

              Now, however, they don't have to
   expressly say, they don't have to exclude Chinese
   or Asians.  They just say, we don't want any
   immigrants, because the immigration stream for the
  last 20 years has been 80 percent Asian and
   Latino.<p>

             The 20 to 30 percent cuts being proposed
   in Congress would prevent 1.5 million Asians from
   joining their families in the United States.  To
   put that into context, our population here in 1995
   is about 9 million, so you can see the devastating
   effect that has on our community, and these are
   just individuals who have been on waiting lists for
  10 to 17 years.  We are talking about children, we
   are talking about parents, brothers and sisters.
   Somehow this Congress seems to have adopted the
   notion that when your child turns 21 they mean less
    to you, that they suddenly become a stranger that
    you have no responsibility to, no ties to, and they
    have no responsibility back to you.<p>

               I was talking to a New York Times
    reporter and I said, "you know, I just can't
    understand how someone who is a father or a mother
    or who has brothers and sisters can say that these
    family members just shouldn't be important to you.
   Don't they love their families?  I don't think it
   is just an Asian feature to love your children, to
   care about your brothers and sisters, to feel
   obligated and loved towards your parents."  He said
   to me, "Karen, it's not that they don't love their
   own children, they just don't love yours."<p>

              Some of the things in the bills, I
   think, even just from a straight civil liberties
   perspective is quite frightening.  Senator
   Simpson's bill which just got out of committee, was
   voted out of committee, says that if you represent
   someone who is not a citizen or a legal permanent
   resident -- it could be a foreign student, it could
   be anybody even lawfully here -- you will not be
   able to get attorney's fees and costs.  The court
   would not be able to award those simply because you
   are not a citizen or a legal permanent resident.<p>

               I think the intent of that is pretty
    clear.  It's a pretty glaring attempt to stop those
    of us who care about these communities from being
    able to make sure that their rights are protected
    in this country.<p>

               Now, you may be thinking to yourselves,
    why is she talking about immigration?  Well, I know
    this audience is not naive enough to know that the
   immigration debate is not about resources or the
   environment or our economy.  It's about race.<p>

              And as cynical as I have gotten working
   in Washington, even I was shocked to hear someone
   in an immigration reform commission hearing say
   that the decision that faced America was just how
   many tacos and chop suey did we really need, or to
   hear Senator Simpson's top aide tell me the reason
  he no longer supported family reunification was
   because he was promised it would not be Asians,
   that he was told it was for Europeans, and when we
   tried to explain to him, what is exactly the
   concern, because even with the 40 percent rate over
   the past few decades, the Asian Americans only make
  up 3 percent of the community, and that worldwide
   Asians make up 50 percent of the world population,
  just to try to explain, you know, that certainly
    3 percent seemed fairly modest, the aide turned to
    us and said, "You don't mean that you think this
    country should be 50 percent Asian?"  I thought he
    was going to fall off his chair.<p>

               Now, this anti-immigrant tide is flowing
    into every sector, unfortunately, for the
    community.  Education in general is under attack.
    They are going so far as to say they should wipe
   out the entire Department of Education.  One of the
   particularly targeted programs is bilingual
   education, even though studies show there is a
   direct correlation between poverty and the ability
   to adequately speak English.<p>

              One of the complaints about immigrants
   is they are not able to fluently speak English.
   Apparently they want to complain but they don't
   want to do anything about it.  These are the same
   people who support English-only laws, who support
   laws that would say to us, you can't have
   translators in courts because we don't want to hear
   anything but English in the courts, so if you
   happen to represent a defendant who doesn't speak
   English, too bad.  If you happen to need a crucial
   witness who does not speak English, too bad.<p>

         What kind of justice will we get in this
   country if that is the kind of attitude that this
   country is going to take?  These laws would also
   make it illegal to even serve, to provide
   government services in English, and would wipe out
   the voting rights assistance, the language
   assistance ballots in New York and in other
   cities.  It is so important for these non-English
    speaking people to exercise the right to vote.<p>

              Imagine a world where you could be fired
   or sued because you were speaking Chinese on the
   job.  That is already happening.  There are
   corporations who have laws that say you can only
   speak English as long as you are on the premises.
   It doesn't matter if your customer doesn't speak
   English that well, or if you could communicate
   faster in a different language.  They just don't
   want to hear anything but English, and in a world
   that is so global, that's becoming so globally
   dependent, it's just incredible to me that that's
   the direction that our nation seems to be heading
   in.<p>

              And I wanted to talk about access to
   government benefits because there my wildest
   nightmares have been exceeded.  Not only are we
  cutting off benefits to the undocumented, including
    undocumented children, including things like health
    care, we are cutting off aid to legal immigrants,
    many of whom have been here for 20, 30, 40 years,
    people who pay taxes, have served in the military
    -- and you may not be aware of this, but legal
    residents serve in the military at higher rates
    than citizens.  They could have done all of that
    but still be deprived of the safety net that this
   country enjoys, or what will be left of it after
   Newt and company are done with it.<p>

              The Senate would also now limit you,
   even after you become a citizen -- I could not
   believe this, when I saw the bill, and the change
   happened at the very last minute, and we called
   Senator Packwood and said, do you realize what you
   have just done?  It said that even if you become a
   citizen, you will still be limited.  You have now
   created two classes of citizenship in this country,
   something that we thought was over with the
   internment of the Japanese and the ending of at
   least legally recognized segregation.<p>

              The starkest irony of this attack is
   that Asian immigrants were prevented by law from
   becoming naturalized citizens until 1952 because --
  and this was actually upheld by the Supreme
    Court -- Justice Sutherland said that the reason
    you should uphold it is that the racial difference
    was of such character and extent that the great
    body of our people instinctively recognize it and
    reject the thought of assimilation.<p>

               Now, my grandmother was not allowed to
    become a citizen until after 1952.  That is within
    my parents' lifetime.  After all, that's less than
   45 years ago.  And yet now, the community is under
   attack as not being citizens.<p>

              This whole outflow is not only affecting
   Asians, Latinos and other immigrants, but it will
   soon be brought home to each and every one of us,
   with the introduction of the national ID card,
   which is gaining a lot of favor.<p>

              Senator Feinstein is one of the most
   enthusiastic proponents, going so far as to
   recommend that we encode retina scan information
   into our Social Security cards, and what is even
   scarier is that in a bill that passed that is part
   of Senator Simpson's bill that got out of
  committee, there is a provision that says that when
   your child is born, you must get a Social Security
   number for that child and that number must be made
   part of his or her birth certificate, and then,
   when the child turns 16, that child must go and get
    their fingerprints or a retina scan or some other
    identifier encoded into the birth certificate.<p>

               Obviously, the FBI and others are
    salivating at the idea of having everybody in this
    country fingerprinted and retina-scanned.  I don't
    know about you, but it is not a country that I want
    to be part of.<p>

              Voting rights, as you have heard, is
   also under attack in court and in the Congress, for
   Asians, Latinos, and Asian-Americans.  Section 203,
   which is the language provisions which have been so
   important in assuring that hundreds of thousands of
   minorities can exercise intelligently their right
   to vote, has been targeted specifically for repeal,
   which is particularly depressing to my community,
   because it was only three years ago that we
   successfully won an amendment to actually broaden
   it to cover effectively our communities.<p>

              Now we face a massive disenfranchisement
   of the many new citizens that are becoming
   naturalized.<p>

              Lastly, I want to talk about affirmative
  action.  Contrary to popular stereotypes, most
     Asians -- at least from the press, the ethnic press
    that I have been reading -- support affirmative
    action, yet we are being used by the media and
    others as an example of a group, of a minority
    group that does not support affirmative action.  I
    was particularly incensed when I read a New York
    Times article about Berkeley, the admissions
    program there, and they quoted Chancellor Ti-Yen, a
    prominent Chinese-American leader, and said his
   idea was outside of the norm, and then they quoted
   a 21-year-old college student and said that they
   represented the community.<p>

              Now, I don't know, but most communities,
   that is not the way, the recognition, the
   leadership usually works, and I thought it was a
   pretty blatant example of someone's preconceived
   ideas of where the community is coming from.  We
   are just as concerned about the loss of affirmative
   action, not only because of the discrimination that
   still persists against our own community, but we do
   not see a level playing field for other women and
   minorities.<p>

              Even more troubling to us is the general
  tack, the attempt to divide and conquer, to
   separate the Asian community out.  There are
   attempts in Washington to tell other minority
    communities, we should drop Asians because they are
    mostly immigrants and they don't need it, and yet
    then they hold up the Asians to the other
    minorities and say, well, Asians don't like it, so
    that's why we should drop it.  A very dangerous
    path to tread on.<p>

               We understand what this debate is all
    about.  It is an attempt by those still with the
   power in this country to hold on to it.  People ask
   me all the time, why is affirmative action being
   attacked, and I believe because it is doing
   precisely what it was meant to do, it's forcing
   white men to share the wealth.<p>

              Unfortunately, the pandering by
   politicans, especially those with presidential
   aspirations, to the fears and bigotries that
   unfortunately have never been far below the
   surface, have life-and-death consequences.<p>

              And I will give you a few examples
   before I close.  These are just incidents that
   happened in 1994.  An Asian-American man was
   stabbed by a white man in Sacramento, California.
   The attacker explained that he was just trying to
   defend our country.<p>

             A white man attacked an Asian-American
    man with a bat while yelling "You are in my
    country.  Get out, go back to your country.  This
    is America."<p>

               An Indian-American student in
    Pennsylvania was assaulted by a group of white
    youths who were yelling "Go home, fucking Iranian,
    you Asian shit, go home, foreigner."<p>

               We have a saying in the
   Japanese-American community called kodomo no tame.
   Literally translated, it means for the sake of the
   children.<p>

              Dr. Chambers is absolutely right.  We
   must all work together to overcome our differences,
   to build trust, because only in that way will we be
   able to defeat the tide of bigotry and fear that
   threatens to destroy the best of what our country
   has to offer:  Freedom, equality and justice.
   Thank you.<p>

              (Applause.)<p>

              MR. WARE:  I am afraid that we went over
   and we will not be able to take any questions
   because of the time lag and conflict with other
   panels, but I would like to thank you all for
   coming.
  </blockquote>



