<HEAD>
<TITLE>IS SEPARATE BUT UNEQUAL THE STANDARD FOR EQUAL PROTECTION OF THE LAW FOR
WOMEN IN STATE-FUNDED HIGHER EDUCATION?</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>  <IMG SRC="/graphics/women.gif">     </CENTER>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">IS SEPARATE BUT UNEQUAL THE STANDARD FOR EQUAL PROTECTION OF
THE LAW FOR WOMEN IN STATE-FUNDED HIGHER EDUCATION?</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This term, more than 40 years after its decisions in Brown v. Board of
Education and Sweatt v. Painter, the Supreme Court will hear argument in the
case of Commonwealth of Virginia v. United States, often referred to as the VMI
case, which presents the question whether a state can deny unique state-funded
higher educational opportunities to women solely on the basis of their sex.  The
case also poses the question whether the creation of a separate state-funded
women's institution which is admittedly not equal to the challenged men's
institution provides a sufficient remedy for a violation of the equal protection
clause.  Finally, this case presents the Court, primarily through the amicus
brief co-authored by the Women's Rights Project, with the historic opportunity
to decide whether discrimination on the basis of sex should be subject to the
highest level of constitutional scrutiny, strict scrutiny, rather than the
existing intermediate scrutiny standard.</P>
<P>Below is a brief background of the VMI case, and a summary of the briefs
filed with the Supreme Court. </P>
<P><B>Background of the Case</B></P>
<P>In 1990, the United States sued the Commonwealth of Virginia and others
challenging the state-funded Virginia Military Institute's [&quot;VMI&quot;]
males-only admissions policy as violative of the equal protection clause.  In
1992, the Fourth Circuit found that VMI's exclusion of women was not
substantially related to an important governmental interest and therefore
violated the Fourteenth Amendment's equal protection guarantee.  While
recognizing that &quot;some women would qualify for and benefit from&quot; VMI,
the Fourth Circuit refused to order the admission of women as a remedy for the
constitutional violation.  The Commonwealth of Virginia then paid approximately
$6 million to nearby Mary Baldwin College, a private women's college, to create
a publicly funded women-only leadership program, the Virginia Women's Institute
for Leadership [&quot;VWIL&quot;].  In the Spring of 1995, the Fourth Circuit in
a 2-1 decision upheld Virginia's proposed remedy, the VWIL program, which was

designed for women's alleged &quot;special&quot; educational, psychological, and

developmental needs.  VWIL rejects the military model of VMI as inappropriate
for educating women, providing instead a cooperative confidence building model
deemed appropriate by VMI, VWIL, and their supporters for the &quot;different
educational needs of most women.&quot;  The Fourth Circuit upheld the exclusion
of women from VMI on the basis that the admission of a single woman would
destroy VMI's &quot;methodology&quot; and, while conceding that some women
qualify for and would benefit from VMI, that VMI was not appropriate for &quot;most
women.&quot;</P>
<P>The Supreme Court granted certiorari on the cross petitions for review filed
by the United States and the Commonwealth of Virginia.  Virginia challenges the
Fourth Circuit's liability determination while the United States challenges the
adequacy of VWIL, which the Court of Appeals' dissent characterized as a &quot;pale
shadow&quot; of VMI, as a remedy for the constitutional violation.   Oral
argument is set for January 17, 1996.</P>
<P><B>Brief of Petitioner United States of America</B></P>
<P>The U.S. argues that, as the Fourth Circuit correctly found, under
Mississippi University v. Hogan(1), VMI's male-only admission policy violates
the 14th Amendment.  The remedy adopted by the Fourth Circuit also excludes
women on the basis of sex, not individual qualifications.  The U.S. argues that,
contrary to the Fourth Circuit's remedial decision, the only remedy that can
provide women the equal opportunity they have been denied is to open admission
to women.  The small changes needed to accommodate women at VMI, such as
parallel physical training standards, separate bathrooms, etc., would not
fundamentally alter the functioning of the institution.  </P>
<P>It is undisputed that no college in Virginia offers women the same or
similar type of program as men are offered at VMI.  Not only does barring women
deny them the benefits of a VMI education, it also denies them the very real and
substantial lifelong career and social benefits which accrue to those who attend
VMI.  A separate new women's institution cannot remedy the denial of admission
to an institution which has been in existence for 150 years and which has an
important history, reputation, prestige and strong and influential alumni
network.  The denial of similar intangibles to blacks resulting from the
exclusion from white-only institutions mandated desegregation.    </P>
<P>The U.S. argues that contrary to Hogan, Virginia's remedy &quot;reflects
archaic and stereotypic notions.&quot;  Hogan invalidated a single sex
admissions policy because it &quot;tend[ed] to perpetuate the stereotyped view
of nursing as an exclusively woman's job.&quot;  Exclusion of women from VMI
(and creation of a separate and inferior women's-only program) perpetuates
exactly the same type of impermissible stereotypes that women are not suited for
rigorous military training, military service or leadership, particularly in
male-dominated environments.  The design of the remedy itself embodies
impermissible sex-based stereotypes about the different emotional and
educational needs of women and men.     Rather than looking at individual
abilities, as commanded by the Fourteenth Amendment, the court improperly used
sex as proxy for ability and looked at women at as group rather than as
individuals.  Even if sex stereotypes are somewhat based in reality, the U.S.
argues relying on J.E.B. v. Alabama ex rel. T.B., use of them as the basis for
the allocation of rights and benefits is impermissible because it continues
forward historical sex bias and law cannot be used to restrict men and women to
socially assigned spheres.</P>
<P>The U.S. also argues that while the remedy fails under intermediate
scrutiny, the exclusion of women from VMI should be subject to strict scrutiny,
the same level of scrutiny applicable to classifications on the basis of race.</P>
<P><B>Brief of the Commonwealth of Virginia, et al.</B></P>
<P>Virginia's initial brief argues that the Fourth Circuit wrongly applied
Hogan when it found that VMI's male-only admissions policy violated equal
protection.  Virginia argues that the Fourth Circuit's decision will wrongly
prevent states from developing educational programs to meet the &quot;special
needs&quot; of its citizens on the basis of sex and disallow the development of
single-sex education for one sex absent a parallel program for the other.    
</P>
<P>Virginia argues that providing diverse educational opportunities in general
and single-sex education in particular are important government objectives,(2)
that single-sex education provides important benefits and provides some students
with a better learning environment than co-educational settings.  Virginia uses
the examples of private single-sex schools and public secondary schools for
African-American boys to bolster its argument that women can be constitutionally
excluded from VMI.  </P>
<P>Virginia relies on the testimony of educators to bolster its argument that
women and men have different educational needs which validates the offering of
different types of state-funded programs on the basis of sex.</P>
<P>According to Virginia, since single-sex education is in itself an important
governmental objective, [as evidenced primarily by the VMI board's decision to
remain all male], then ipso facto VMI's exclusion of women is substantially
related to that objective and the exclusion satisfies Hogan.  To admit women
would by definition, Virginia argues, frustrate the state's goal to provide
single-sex education.        </P>
<P>Virginia argues that the admission of women would drastically alter VMI,
arguing that changes such as parallel physical standards and increased privacy
would be incompatible with VMI's methodology.  Virginia argues that requiring
VMI to admit women would deny men the benefits of single-sex education and VMI's
method of education without extending that benefit to women.  </P>
<P>Virginia adopts the Fourth Circuit's formulation that women need not be
granted equal educational opportunities, that &quot;substantively comparable&quot;
opportunities are sufficient to satisfy equal protection.  It is a
misinterpretation of Hogan, argues Virginia, to require that, absent significant
demand by women as a class, an individual woman be provided access to all the
educational opportunities available to an individual man.  Arguing that only
relatively few women are interested in a VMI education, Virginia argues that the
state should not be required to provide this type of education to any woman. 
Virginia argues that an application requiring equal opportunities for women in
public education could lead to the barring of government funding to private
single-sex schools.  It also argues that funding for battered women's shelters
could be found unconstitutional if parallel programs were not provided.</P>
<P><B>Amici Curiae Brief of ACLU, National Women's Law Center et al.</B></P>
<P>This brief primarily argues that while the VMI remedy clearly fails under
the intermediate level of equal protection scrutiny, that the Supreme Court
should use this case as a vehicle to decide that sex-based discrimination must
be subject to strict scrutiny.  The brief argues that, as the result in this
case demonstrates, the intermediate scrutiny standard has proven unworkable as
applied to gender-based classifications and has resulted in incorrect decisions
because of reliance on gender-based stereotypes.  We also argue that the Court's
recent decision in Adarand v. Pena applying strict scrutiny to race-based
affirmation-action programs indicates that in practice and policy such programs
for women will also be subject to heightened scrutiny.  As a result
discrimination against women must receive the same level of scrutiny as programs
intended to remedy such discrimination.  We argue that given that sex is an
immutable characteristic unrelated to ability, the long history and continuing
practice of sex discrimination, and the underrepresentation of women in the
political process that it is appropriate that sex-based classifications be
subject to strict scrutiny.</P>
<P><B>Amici Briefs by Private Women's Colleges</B></P>
<P>Two briefs, on opposing sides of the litigation, were submitted by private
women's colleges.  An issue of concern in this litigation and one exploited by
Virginia has been the impact of a decision requiring VMI to admit women on the
continued viability of private single-sex and traditionally African-American
colleges.  </P>
<P>Twenty-six women's colleges filed a brief in support of the United States,
arguing that the male-only admissions policy of VMI as a publicly funded school
violates equal protection and the Fourth Circuit's remedy also violates equal
protection because it justifies differential treatment of women and men on the
basis of impermissible gender-based stereotypes.  The amici further argue that
invalidation of VMI's policy will not threaten the continued existence of
private women's colleges because the Fourteenth Amendment does not apply to them
and the colleges' tax-exempt status is not threatened by the public policy
requirement enunciated in Bob Jones University v. United States.</P>
<P>Three private women's colleges weighed in on the side of VMI, arguing that
publicly funded sex-segregated schools of higher education are justified due to
the educational benefits conferred to women by single-sex education.    </P>
<P><B>Amici Brief of Scientists, Scholars, Educators, and Professional
Organizations</B></P>
<P>This brief addressed scientific issues of gendered patterns of
psychological, emotional, and educational development raised in this case,
including research of some of the amici, particularly Carol Gilligan author of
In A Different Voice, relied on by the courts below to support the separate but
unequal remedy.</P>
<P><B>Amici Brief of Past and Present Military Personnel in Support of the
United States</B></P>
<P>This brief, organized and substantially written by the Women's Rights
Project, was filed on behalf of approximately 20 past and present members of the
armed forces and support organizations.  The amici were an illustrious group,
including six women who were in the first class of women to graduate from West
Point, several women who graduated at the top of their class at West Point and
the Naval Academy, several retired generals, and such well-known figures as Dr.
Margarethe Cammemeyer and Major Rhonda Cornum, one of two American women POWs in
the Gulf War.  The main points raised in this brief were that women have
demonstrated their ability to serve with distinction in the military and
military academies rebutting the Fourth Circuit's conclusion that VMI was too
tough for women and that the integration of women had not destroyed the military
or the academies.  The brief also discussed how VMI had at one time resisted
race integration on much the same grounds that it now resists sex integration. 
Finally, the brief discussed how the remedy for women, VWIL, would not
adequately prepare women for a military career.</P>
<P><B>Amicus Brief of Nancy Mellette in Support of the United States</B></P>
<P>This brief was submitted on behalf of the young South Carolina woman who
intervened in the pending action against The Citadel after Shannon Faulkner
withdrew.  Since the Fourth Circuit's decisions in VMI have provided the
controlling authority in The Citadel case and since Mellette seeks to dismantle
The Citadel's male-only admissions policy, she has a substantial interest in the
Supreme Court's review of the VWIL remedy.  Mellette argues that the VWIL remedy
itself violates equal protection. </P>
<P><B>Amici Brief of Employment Law Center, Equal Rights Advocates, Inc.,
several women law professors, etc. in Support of the United States</B></P>
<P>This brief argues that while the VWIL remedy cannot survive intermediate
scrutiny, the Court should use this opportunity to adopt strict scrutiny for
gender-based discrimination.  The brief further argues that the Court should
reject its jurisprudence of &quot;consistent&quot; application of the strict
scrutiny standard to both invidious and remedial classifications most recently
discussed in Adarand.  Amici argue that strict scrutiny should be limited to
invidious classifications, while the Court should recognize the continuing need
for remedial classifications and subject them to a lesser standard of scrutiny.</P>
<P>(1)  Hogan, applying intermediate scrutiny which permits the use of
sex-based classifications only if the classification &quot;serves important
governmental objectives&quot; and is &quot;substantially related to the
achievement of those objectives,&quot; held that a state cannot prohibit
enrollment in a state institution of higher education on the basis of sex
without an &quot;exceedingly persuasive justification.&quot; </P>
<P>(2)  In its constitutional argument, Virginia blurs the distinction between
public and private colleges, arguing that it has a long history of support for
single-sex education, through the state-funded VMI and through tuition
assistance to students who attend private single-sex schools.  As the state
admits, however, at the time the U.S. sued over VMI's exclusion of women, VMI
was the only single-sex public college in Virginia.  Virginia argues that since
the state disproportionately provides tuition assistance for women attending
private women's colleges that VMI's male-only policy serves to equalize the
single-sex opportunities for men and women. </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
