<html>
<head><title>National Security</title>
<!JM 1/5/96>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<center>
<img src="/graphics/security.gif">
</center>

<P>
<br>
<blockquote>
<P><center><img src="/graphics/redline.gif">
<h4><p>The following op-ed by ACLU Associate Director Barry
Steinhardt<br>appeared in the NY Daily News on December 1995
</h4><img src="/graphics/redline.gif"></center>
<center>
<h3>     What is the FBI up to?
</h3></center>
<p>     In a November letter to the House Judiciary Committee, FBI Director Louis Freeh
assured a nervous Congress that his agency  had no intention of expanding the number of
wiretaps it uses. Yet only two weeks before, the FBI had published a  notice in the Federal
Register , which told a much different tale. Followng up on the &quot;Digital Telephony&quot;  law it had
won in the last Congress, the FBI served notice that it intended to require  the nation's phone
companies to alter their modern digital networks -- the backbone of the coming information
superhighway --  to enable police agencies  to eavesdrop on as many as one out of every one
hundred telephone conversations in big  cities like New York..
</p>
<h3>     Which FBI statement should we believe? The facts speak for themselves.
</h3>
<p>     According to data from the Administrative Office of the United States Courts, federal
law enforcement agencies like the FBI increasingly use wiretaps or other forms of electronic
surveillance. In fact, from 1984 to 1994, the number of federal law enforcement electronic
surveillance intercepts doubled. (Electronic surveillance, these days, includes wiretaps,
electronic listening devices commonly known as &quot;bugs,&quot; and interception of pager
transmissions, E-mail and cellular telephone conversations.)
</p>
<p>     And the future, if the FBI has its way, is even more grim. The Clinton Administration's
so-called counter-terrorism legislation -- which is being pushed hardest by Director Freeh --
would expand the list of  investigations in which an electronic surveillance order could be sought
and expand the authority to wiretap without a court order.
</p>
<p>     Although the FBI would have us believe that more wiretapping is needed to save the
country from terrorists and prevent another Oklahoma City, the facts tell us otherwise.
Wiretapping is almost never used to investigate bombings, arson or firearms violations. Indeed,
the last time a wiretap was requested by a law enforcement agency to investigate one of these
crimes was seven years ago in 1988.
</p>
<p>     Ironically, while the number of wiretaps has been increasing, they have become even less 
useful as a law enforcement tool. Again, according to the government's own figures, the
proportion of incriminating conversations snarred by a wiretap has been steadily dropping  over
the last two decades from 50% in the early 1970's, all the way down to 17% in 1994.
</p>
<p>     In other words, the government concedes that 83% - five out of every six -- of  the
conversations it has intercepted in recent yerars were totally innocent.
</p>
<p>     But this is not a meaningless debate about numbers. What is at stake, is our personal 
privacy in the age of electronic communications. As electronic communications beome
dominant, do we really want to give  Federal Law Enforcement agencies  -- the same agencies
which conducted the disasterous raids in Waco and Ruby Ridge -- more authority and
increasingly poweful tools to eavesdrop ? 
</p>
<p>     The Digital Telephony, with its requirement that new digital network have built in
wiretapping capacity,  was the first time in our history that an entire industry was required to
alter its technology to the government would be guaranteed success in its snooping. It  was akin
to requiring builders to put listening devices in the walls of the new homes they build , in case
the government ever wanted to listen in.
</p>
<p>     The new wiretapping proposals  are only part of a concerted effort to increase by the
Federal Government to increase its power to eavesdrop.  Federal Intelligence agencies  have also
poposed a number of schemes to prevent American industry and private citizens from protecting
the confidentiality of sensitive communications with strong encryption  -- coding--- unless the
government  is given access to the keys to crack the code and listen in. So far, those schemes,
which began with the infamous &quot;Clipper Chip&quot; for every telephone, have been rejected.
</p>
<p>     In this age when every detail of our private lives, is stored in massive computers and
transferred around the country -- even the world -- digitally,  it would be nice to think that
technological advances are actually improving our privacy rights. Congress would be wise to put
the brakes on the FBI and take a second look at the digital telephony legislation it adopted last
year.  It could start by denying the FBI the funding,,it has sought to implement the bill.
</p>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
