<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Substantive Plenary VII</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><h1>Transcript of Substantive Plenary VII<br>
 Youth & Civil Liberties</center></h1>
<blockquote>
<STRONG>MS. MURRAY:</STRONG>   Thank you very much.
To set a framework for this discussion,
I wanted to begin on a personal note.  In 1963, I
    was a high school editor in a school not far from                           
    here, and I wrote what must have been an incredibly
    ponderous article about the test ban treaty, saying
    what a good idea it was to have it and perhaps we
    really should be putting our enmity with the Soviet
    Union to rest.  That had a rich reward in terms of
   a letter from the American Legion, and I will never
   forget one of its lines.  It said, "how can you sit
   at your school window and see the American flag
   waving and not feel like a traitor."  It also got
   my newspaper shredded or whatever they did in 1963
   to offending newspapers.
<p>
              Now, at that time I hadn't heard about
   the ACLU, I didn't know that much about the Bill of
   Rights.  I certainly didn't think it applied to me,
   and at that time, halfway across the United States,
   Mary Beth Tinker was, I believe, 11 years old by my
   calculations.  It was two years before she was to
   wear her black armband to school with other
   students and before she was to take a stand for her
  rights which would culminate in a Supreme Court
   decision at the end of the '60s, which really
   brought the explosion of rights into the
   schoolhouse all around the United States.  25 years
    later, in Massachusetts, and in other states, where
    the ACLU was working with schools, states like
    California, Indiana, Illinois, Connecticut, and
    many others, 25 years later, the Tinker case is
    really a household or a classroom term.
<p>

               Now, on our first, in one of our student
    conferences in May of 1982, Mary Beth Tinker was a
   speaker and I would like to bring to your attention
   what she told students at our conference.  She
   said, "You students are strong, you have more power
   than you may think.  All of you, all you have to do
   is realize it, use it."
<p>

              And the students here who you will be
   hearing about are certainly students who have
   realized and they are using it as you will hear
   shortly.  But before I ask them to speak, I do want
   to address the political climate in which we face
   ourselves and to say something about how we can
   realize that power and help students realize that
   power, when the explosion of rights has clearly
   long run its course in this country, and when so
   many young people are being forced to spend more
   time honing their survival skills than their
   academic skills in schools.
<p>
               How can we really reach young people
    with our message when youth are so mistrusted,
    indeed, feared, and even criminalized?  To the
    extent that in the liberal state of Massachusetts,
    in fact, recently passed a law which subjects kids
    to what is in effect an educational death penalty,
    which says if they bring an illegal substance, or a
    weapon, which they did not define, to school, they
   will be expelled, permanently expelled, no
   alternative education has to be provided.  In other
   words, a form of one strike, you're out.
<p>

              Now, this climate has forced us in
   Massachusetts to develop new ways of trying to do
   our work and inspire young people to realize that
   the phrase "with liberty and justice for all" can
   be more than a pious hope, and that is what Project
   Hip Hop is all about, our civil rights tour to help
   young people come face to face with a history of
   struggle made by young people like themselves.
<p>
You know that the civil rights movement
 was not just about a leader here or there, but it
 was a movement made by young people, and I think --  
 I bring that in because that is a dimension I
 believe we must be increasingly thinking of if we
are to really have hope for the future.  But I'm
sure, as you listen to the people here, you will
leave this room with a sense of that hope.  So let
me now introduce Mary Beth Tinker.

<p>

<STRONG>MS. TINKER</STRONG>:  
Thank you very much,
Nancy.  That is a person who has been a great
    inspiration to me as I work with youth, teenagers,
    children, in St. Louis, and also in the country.
<p>

               I would like to thank ACLU for inviting
   me here.  It is such an honor and it is such a
   heartening experience to be among people that are
   supportive and warm and basically like-minded.  We
   all go out in the world in such a battle we are up
   against every day, it's really great just to be
   here, and also to hear some of my great heroes
   speak on the issues of our time this last week.
   It's just really been a joy.
<p>

  I am going to talk a little about the
   armband case, the Tinker armband case and the
   Hazlewood case, and then I would like to link it up
   a little bit to students rights and children's
   rights in general, and lastly, I would just briefly
   like to add to what Nancy has talked about, the
   situation in the 1990s that we are facing right
   now, which is an absolutely dire crisis for
   children.
<p>

 I go out and talk to groups of mostly
   kids and this is really one of the first times I
   have talked to an all-adult group, but I really
    like to talk to kids because they get so excited
    and interested in the subject of student rights and
    they can relate immediately to what I am talking
    about and they always get a lot of hope from that,
    And there is a shortage of hope among our kids
   today, and I am sure you are all aware of that,
   too.
<p>

  But my son especially thinks it is a
   pretty cool case, he is 14, and he got suspended,
   and I am going to talk about suspension a little
   bit, too, and expulsion, because it is a really big
   problem in our country right now because we have
   schools that don't want kids there, they are
   telling them in messages every day, that we don't
   want you in our school.  And this particular day,
   he was one of the ones getting the message, and he
   had been throwing an eraser across the class, so he
   went into the in-school suspension, and the vice
   principal was in there minding the kids, dealing
   with them, and he said to her, kind of menacingly,
   have you ever heard of Tinker v. Des Moines?
<p>

              Well, that was a good try, we laughed
   about it later, the principal and I, she had heard
   about it but apparently he didn't realize one of
   the finer points was that you couldn't use that to
   throw erasers at the teacher's head.  The sad part
   about that is lately you can't use Tinker to do
   much of anything, and especially since some of the
   recent decisions that have come down since then,
   especially Hazlewood, and I am going to talk about
   that some, but I really think, if it wasn't for
   Hazlewood, I am not sure what difference it would
   make to the reality in a lot of schools in our
   country today because we have got kids that are
   just undergoing such hard times.
<p>
   I just was very interested to hear what
   was going on in Texas at the small committee that
   we had on schools this morning, where kids are
   being paddled, and that's happening in Missouri,
   too, they said they had 140,000 paddlings reported
   this year in Texas.  We have kids punished right
   and left that are not allowed to wear their hair
   the way they like, are not allowed to say the
   things they want in their school reports, they
   can't talk in the school newspaper, that are not
   getting through high school, that are not getting
    through seventh grade, that are being excluded from
   our public schools.  Anyway, I want to talk a
   little bit about the armband case specifically.
<p>
   My parents were religious people and my
   father was a minister, as you have heard.  They
   subscribe to a way of thinking about Christianity
   where you are supposed to put your beliefs into
   action; kind of a curious phenomenon, but they
   still tried to do it.  So they believed in things
   like brotherhood, peace, you know, the meek shall
   inherit the Earth, and that got them in about as
   much trouble as it did Jesus, maybe a little less,
   but basically, in the early '60s, when I was about
   10 or 11, my father was under so much pressure for
   his activities in the civil rights movement, and we
   would go out picketing and we would go to all of
   the black and white churches, and spread the
   message from our little integrated group from Core,
   the NAACP, and he was trying to integrate the
   neighborhood church and also the neighborhood
   swimming pool he had been involved in in Atlantic,
   Iowa.
<p>

  So anyway, he had to leave the church in
   the early '60s because he was under so much
   pressure which, of course, made me cynical about
    organized religion for some years because I was
   really disappointed by that.  So luckily, my father
   went to work for the American Friends Service
   Committee, which was taking wayward ministers on at
   that time, and he used to joke about how it really
   was just a group of kicked-out preachers, you know,
  that couldn't find work, so he was one of them.
<p>
  And so, since I had been taught to put
   my views into action, and this was a religious
   philosophy that my parents trained me with, which
   is that we are, that God is working through us, our
   actions, we are here to put into action his word,
   that we are here to put these things into action.
   So it was really not hard for me to volunteer when
   there was a call put out to students to wear black
   armbands in mourning for the dead in Vietnam, and
   that's what we planned to do.  I heard about this
   project through the Liberal Religious Youth, the
   Unitarian youth group, which I had gotten involved
   in, a real radical, subversive group, the church.
<p>
    So anyway, the principals, you know,
   decided we couldn't wear the armbands.  The rest is
   history.  It went to the Supreme Court, thanks to
   the ACLU, because we could never have afforded or
   been able to do it without them.  And we also
   probably couldn't have done it without the support
   of people like yourselves who were there when our
   lives were threatened, when someone called me on
    the telephone, and said, you are going to be dead
    by morning, on Christmas Eve, your house is going
    to be firebombed, the red paint which was thrown at
    our house, which was so ridiculous because my
    parents were far from Communist, they were
    religious zealots, so I guess, under those terms,
   Jesus would be a Communist as well.
<p>
   So anyway, that brings us up to the
   Hazlewood case, where we lost, we had a major loss
   in students' rights, and as you will probably hear
   more, in St. Louis, Missouri, the students wanted
   to write about the controversial issue of pregnancy
   and divorce in the newspaper, and God forbid kids
   should have anything to say about that.  Anyway,
   the students lost in the Supreme Court, and the
   court declared the school has an interest in
   publications and school activities and can have
   some say about what goes in those.
<p>
   To talk a little bit about children's
   rights, I think students' rights are really in that
   context.  There is a very good book out right now
   that is called Lives On The Edge, that talks about
   single mothers.  The lives of children and mothers
   have always been connected and it wasn't until
    1874, for example, that children received legal
    recognition for abuse, and that was only because
    the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty
    to Animals decided that children should be
    included, that there were laws on the books against
    abusing animals, so you really should include
    children.
<p>
 So this goes on throughout history.  The
   whole thing right now that's going on against --
   the juvenile justice right now, scapegoating
   teenagers, and especially black teenagers, is
   really nothing new.  In 1826, in Britain, a
   magistrate said there was so much juvenile crime
   that we really should ship the kids off and
   emigration would be a good solution, and, in fact,
   they did, they sent kids off and they would go
   to -- Australia was a favorite place to send kids,
   there were 502,000 kids sent off a year for quite a
   while.  It is really nothing new.  In colonial
   America, the same situation, the evangelicals said
   you should beat the will out of children, that was
   a way of keeping them from being strong-minded, and
   the slaves, I think we all know what happened
    there.
<p>
 I don't know if you realize that white
   children were sold in those years as well.  Here is
   an ad from 1760, "To be sold by Thomas Overend at
    the drawbridge, two white boys and a Negro lad, all
    about 14 years old.  Also very good lime juice."
<p>
  So, you know, this is what we are
    dealing with now today.  We come up to 1990 -- and
    I just want to take a few minutes to tell you about
   a situation you are all fairly familiar with, but
   as a nurse, I work with children, I work with a
   children's hospital, and also work in schools as a
   nurse and in my neighborhood as a nurse as well.
<p>
 What we are dealing with is a wave of
   violence that is unprecedented in this country.
   Teenagers are being killed, little children are
   being killed.  One of the leading causes of death
   right now of children under five is death at the
   hands of their parents.  The abuse and sexual abuse
   is just incredible.  The AIDS problem.  As you
   heard Joycelyn Elders, one of my heroes, say, AIDS
   is growing fastest among the teen population.
<p>
  Suicide.  It has increased something
   like 300 percent among teens in the last 30 years,
   a lot of that has to do with gay teenagers, and I
    am waiting for the Baptist, the Southern Baptist
   church to give us an apology for the way they have
    treated homosexuals.  Since they apologized for
    slavery, I think it is time they apologized for
    that.
<p>

 The sexual issues we deal with with
    teenagers are out of control, the birth rate, the
    pregnancy rate.  And also when we deal with
    teenagers, as I was saying about the suicide rate
   in gay teenagers, it is a very bad problem.
   Teenagers are not all heterosexual.  I myself was a
   gay teenager, and I know the pain that you go
   through and this is often ignored by our schools
   and they don't want to talk about it.  There is a
   very interesting case right now that the ACLU is
   pursuing in Kansas City on this issue.
<p>

              I just wanted to wind it up by
   encouraging everyone in the ACLU to join with
   others that are advocating for children, and to
   think of student rights in connection with
   children's rights and teenagers' rights, and join
   especially with child advocacy groups as we go out
   and try to improve the lot of America's youth.
   Thank you.
<p>

             <STRONG> (Applause.)</STRONG>
<p>
<STRONG>MS. MURRAY:</STRONG> Next we have Jeffrey Pyle.
<p>

<H2>MR. PYLE</H2><P>
  Hi.  I would like to tell you
    a little bit about my case, and then also speak a
    little bit on the problems with my generation and
    their apparent lack of interest in civil
    liberties.
<p>

               My story begins in 1992 when my mom
    bought me a Christmas present.  It was a T-shirt
    which said "Coed Naked Band, Do it to the rhythm."
<p>

              I was the drum major of the band at the
  time, so my mom thought it was pretty funny, I
   don't know.  So that following March I wore the
   T-shirt to gym class and my teacher pulled me aside
   halfway through the class and told me that the
   shirt was demeaning to women and would create an
   emotionally unhealthy environment in her class if I
   continued to wear it.
<p>

              I politely informed her it was my First
   Amendment right to wear the shirt, no matter who it
   offended, and you cannot censor something simply
   because you don't like it, especially in a school.
   She disagreed.  She said, "I don't get paid enough
   to listen to this crap."  So I realized that I
   couldn't get anywhere with her.  So I took it to
   the school committee because I wore the T-shirt
    back to her class again after she walked away from
    me, and was charged with insubordination, as if I
    was her subordinate.
<p>

               So I took it to the school committee and
    asked them, and told them that at South Hadley, we
    need a Constitutional speech code that allows for
    unpopular expression, and doesn't allow teachers to
    make up their own regulations on the spot as to
    what is allowed.  They disagreed with me also.  And
   they passed what is now the most restrictive dress
   code in the State of Massachusetts.
<p>

              We did a survey of a lot of them.  The
   dress code prohibits anything which they deem to be
   obscene, lewd, profane or vulgar, and which has the
   effect of demeaning someone on the basis of race,
   sex, color, national origin, and sexual
   orientation, religion, et cetera.  And it
   prohibited anything which advertised alcohol, or
   illegal drugs.
<p>

              After three months of arguing before the
   school committee, after talking with them about the
   unconstitutionality of the dress code, and bringing
   in a lawyer from the ACLU who also spoke to them,
   we realized we couldn't get anywhere with them
  either, and we filed suit in the Federal District
      Court, the case is called the Pyle v. South Hadley
    School Committee.  Something interesting about the
    dress code, something that was spoken about a
    couple of nights ago, is the alliance of the
    organized left, as Lee Strasberg calls them, and
    the religious conservative right to ban all forms
    of sexual speech, kind of the new Victorianism, as
    it is called in the book, and -- but there is very
    little difference between the new Victorianism and
   the old Victorianism in that this kind of sexual
   repression will eventually end up hurting women
   more than than it does men, so this case is not
   just about First Amendment rights but it is also
   about gender equality and the right to openly
   express sexual ideas.
<p>

              So we went to court and at the district
   level, we persuaded the judge to overturn the
   second clause of the dress code about hate speech,
   that is the second time that's been done, I think a
   very important precedent.  However, the judge also
   upheld the vulgarity clause, and in a really
   radical decision, I think, said the school
   committee, as elected officials, reflect the moral
   fiber of the community and can decide what is and
   is not vulgar for other people's children.
<p>

   This is a really radical decision, and I
   think -- and my brother and I demonstrated, in our
    protest, that it is not something that can be done
    consistently.  We wore a whole series of test
    shirts to test out the ban.  My brother wore one
    which said "Coed Naked Gerbils."  Some people will
    censor anything.  He had to carry around a pass
    every time he wore that shirt.
<p>

               I wore a shirt with a picture of two men
   on it kissing in military uniform that said, "Read
   my lips."  And that was allowed.  That was
   allowed.  However, my brother wore one with "See
   Dick Drink, See Dick Drive, See Dick Die, Don't be
   a Dick."  And that was banned.  But my favorite was
   one that I wore.  It read "Coed Naked Civil
   Liberties, Do it to the Amendments."  And not
   surprisingly, I was thrown out school for wearing
   that one, and when the principal threw me out of
   school for wearing that one, he reminded me that
   the Roman Empire fell from within, not from
   without.  Presumably, they were all wearing
   T-shirts.  The ACLU probably had something to do
   with it.
<p>

  Anyway, despite the egregious violations
   of student First Amendment rights that went on in
     this case, very few students, in fact, no students,
    came out in support of what my brother and I were
    doing.  There were no letters to the editor, very
    few showed up at school committee meetings, and
    that was pretty disappointing.  And it was
    especially distressing that none of my friends
    would come to my aid when I was personally attacked
    in the newspaper.  I was called a white male
    elitist who wanted to see 12- and 13-year-old girls
   go naked.  That was kind of strange.
<p>

              But I think it was even more distressing
   that so few students cared enough about their
   fundamental freedoms to join the fight, and I asked
   myself, as I was writing this speech, why is this,
   why don't students get involved in the numbers they
   should?
<p>

             Ira Glasser pointed out in the film we
   saw the other night that kids are born with the
  innate instincts to know what is fair, what their
   rights are, but by the time they get to high
   school, they have been denied those rights so often
   and been patronized so often when they try to
   assert those rights, that they end up forgetting
   what those rights are, and thinking, if they know
   what the rights are, thinking that the Bill of
   Rights doesn't apply to them.  We are just kids,
    right?
<p>

               So that's why I think the education
    programs that the ACLU had and that Nancy and
    Warren do and Loren do are incredibly important.
    Their efforts are too often lost in the rhetoric of
    civil liberties.  They have touched a lot of kids
    and I think they really deserve our thanks.
<p>

               But clearly, the ACLU cannot teach every
   high school kid, everybody in the nation, what
   their rights are.  I mean, we are just not big
   enough.  That is why the Constitution also has to
   be taught in the schools.  There has to be less
   preaching about responsibilities and duties, and
   more teaching about the rights that make those
   responsibilities worthwhile.
<p>

   And I also think that it's more often
   the teachers who need to be taught.  Teachers -- we
   can't blame them too much.  They are understandably
   jealous and even paranoid about the powers and
   prerogatives, because obviously, the school systems
   in this country are in a terrible mess, but
   teachers should also understand that civil
   liberties and civil rights are not inconsistent
   with an orderly school.  That's simply not the
     case.  But I think for teachers and students,
    simply knowing one's rights is not enough.  I think
    groups like the ACLU need to show kids that you can
    fight City Hall and win, as Mary Beth did.  I think
    many people in my generation suffer from a social
    disease which I call IDS, idealism deficiency
    syndrome.  This disease is brought about my
    America's proclivity for hypocrisy and is summed up
    by a popular rock song which goes, when I fight
   authority, authority always wins.
<p>

  Kids at an early age, to continue with
   the metaphor, need booster shots, and examples of
   courage.  I think Project Hip Hop, which Miriama is
   going to speak about in a minute, is a good example
   of that.  It shows kids what kids in the past
   generation did to further the rights of everybody
   else.
<p>
 And the story of Mary Beth Tinker, I
   think, also needs to be taught.  This image of the
   13-year-old girl fighting the agents of
   totalitarianism at the Supreme Court, is something
   which should shame most Americans and certainly had
   me going, to shame Americans to really reconsider
   their apathy.  I think once we cure IDS and get
   more kids involved and teach, and try to have
    children educated not to abridge rights, we will
    have a lot better future for America.
<p>

   Thanks a lot.
 
<p>

             <STRONG> MS. MURRAY</STRONG>:  Knowing people like Jeffrey
    is what makes my job so incredibly worthwhile.
<p>

               I would like to invite Preet Sabharwal
    to talk about what he is doing in California.
<p>

<STRONG>MR. SABHARWAL:</STRONG>
To all of you out there
    that have ever consumed alcohol, cut your hair or
   gone one day without praying, I cannot look you in
   the eye with respect anymore.  You cut your hair, a
   gift from God, and what is your justification for
   consuming alcohol, a controlled substance, and for
   any of you to not pray and thank God every day, I
   have absolutely no respect for you.  If any of you
   have excuses or justifications for any of your
   actions, you should.  You should.  But I have made
   arrangements with the hotel to have you removed
   because you do not conform to my religious tenets.
<p>

              If any of you feel disrespected, if any
   of you feel offended or appalled, you should.  You
   should, because I have just told 500 ACLU members
   to leave because many of you do not embrace the
   tenets of my religion, but as guardians of the Bill
   of Rights who understand their civil liberties and
   know that they can make choices for themselves, I
    know that not one of you will leave this ballroom
    nor one of you will leave this hotel.
<p>

               I speak with experience when I say you
    wouldn't accept such an injustice, such a
    superfluous order, because you are defenders of
    civil liberties, for 75 years, and during that time
    a number of battles have been fought for student
    civil liberties, for the civil liberties of young
   people.  From Brown v. Board of Education, to
   Tinker v. Des Moines, and now Cheemu v. Thompson,
   in California.
<p>

              In the latter case, the ACLU is
   valiantly fighting to allow a Sikh student to carry
   a kirpan to school.  The ceremonial knife is a
   small, blunt, tightly sheathed ceremonial knife
   which ranges in size.  However, when one student
   playing basketball with a Sikh student carrying
   such a ceremonial knife, meaning that the Sikhs
   have been oppressed, and the reason they carry this
   is because of the fact they want to keep at hand
   what went on in the past, much like the cross
   depicting crucifixion.
<p>

              However, when another student saw one of
   the Cheemu children wearing a kirpan at a
     basketball game in elementary school, the dull
    ceremonial dagger was labeled as a weapon and
    students were suspended until they abandoned the
    symbol.
<p>

               However, as orthodox Sikhs are required
    to carry the symbol at all times, the parents of
    the three Cheemu children decided to put their
    children out of school.  They also contacted the
    ACLU of Northern California, which filed suit in
   the U.S. District Court in April.
<p>

              The students were suspended in January.
   But the judge ruled in favor of the school district
   and the children were suspended for the duration of
   the spring semester, deprived of a semester of
   education.
<p>

              However, the relentless ACLU lawyers
   went back to court in August where the Ninth
   Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the children
   should be let back into school immediately because
   of the 1993 Religious Freedom Restoration Act
   because the kirpan is a religious symbol
   permittable in schools which does not constitute an
   immediate danger.  The ACLU lawyers successfully
   contended that the tightly sheathed kirpan is no
   more dangerous than baseball bats, compasses or
     scissors, all commonly found in the schools every
    day.
<p>

               In addition, the ACLU found that the
    kirpan is a dull ceremonial religious symbol and
    not a knife and therefore is permitable in
    schools.
<p>

               However, following the injunction and
    numerous other arguments by the ACLU, the school
    district still appealed the injunction, and after
   this attempt to bar the children from attending
   school again, the district appealed -- the district
   was denied.  They appealed the denial again.  The
   case is now pending a constitutional trial.
   Nonetheless, the three Cheemu children, ages 7, 8
   and 10, are back in school from last September,
   finished school this June, thanks to the ACLU.
<p>

             <STRONG> (Applause.)</STRONG>
<p>

              MR. SABHARWAL:  And although this case
   was the first of its kind because of the kirpan,
   with half a million Sikhs, currently in American
   has never been documented as a violent weapon, the
   ACLU won a battle for all of them.  The case
   reinforces the fact that if a district succeeds in
   denying students their religious liberties, then
   other school districts in other states and around
     that area will do the same.
<p>

               The ACLU once again has upheld civil
    liberties for youth, and as a card-carrying member
    for two years, I am proud to be affiliated with an
    organization that fights for the civil liberties of
    all citizens.  The American Civil Liberties Union.
    No barriers, not Sikhs, not Muslims, not Blacks,
    not Whites, not Mexicans.  The American Civil
    Liberties Union.
<p>

              Moreover, this helps more than just
   Sikhs.  I work with the Howard Friedman First
   Amendment Education Project from the Northern
   California ACLU affiliate.  When we hold
   conferences for high school students, they are
   taught of these cases, Tinker v. Des Moines, about
   censorship rights, about rights they have with
   their student newspapers, about their freedom of
   the press, freedom of expression, and these
   students not only learn from these cases that we
   students study, they know when their civil
   liberties are in jeopardy.  They know when their
   rights have been violated and they know where to go
   and what to do because of the ACLU.
<p>
   These students who come to our
   conferences are potential future members of this
     illustrious organization.  They are the future of a
    successful ACLU of tomorrow.
<p>

               At conferences sponsored by the Friedman
    project, I can attest to students are fighting for
    their civil liberties.  Not only do they want to
    learn about them, they want to exercise them.
    These students, if educated nationwide about their
    civil liberties, will realize that when someone
    denies them attendance due to their religious
   belief or any other civil liberties guaranteed in
   the Bill of Rights, they will be educated to
   recognize to not leave the ballroom.
<p>

              Thank you.
<p>

 <STRONG>MS. MURRAY: </STRONG>  Thank you, Preet.  Now we
   have Miriama White-Hammond.
<p>

<STRONG>MS. WHITE-HAMMOND</STRONG>:
 First, I just want
   everyone to stretch for a couple of seconds,
   because it seems like everyone is getting tired in
   their seats, so I will give everyone just a moment
   to stretch.
<p>

              I will just say, my name is Miriama
   White-Hammond, and I work with the Hip Hop
   Project.  And I am here today to talk to you about
   youth issues, not only because I feel they are
   being threatened, but because I think they are
    central to any working democracy, for any country
    that wants to move ahead.
<p>

               It seems today there seems to be so much
    cynicism about young people.  They are not
    motivated, they don't do anything, all they do is
    watch television.  We can't get them to work, they
    have no work ethic, and I think what has started to
    happen is we see divides being set up, where the
    adults look at the young people and say, goodness,
   what's going on with them, and the young people
   look back saying, they just can't understand us.
   It's a scary situation.
<p>

              I find so many young people who know
   that there is a problem, who see what's going on
   around them and it scares them but they don't seem
   to know what to do.  It's very easy to get
   discouraged in a country where nobody seems to
   listen to you, or a time when it seems like people
   are unconcerned about what's going on with you.
<p>

              I have been to many high schools where
   people say to me, we have problems here, the gay
   and lesbian students are being discriminated
   against, the disabled students are being
   discriminated against.  There are many racial
   problems here, but what can we do?
<p>

             Through the Hip Hop Project, we have
   taken the civil rights movement and not only
   studied it as an important time in history but
   looked at it as a model for how young people can
    make change.  Anytime through history, when you
    look back at the great movements that have brought
    about more democracy and more rights, it has been
    young people who are at the forefront, moving
    things.  When you look at Tienamen Square, when you
   look at the March on Washington, other historical
   events, you will see young people who are shining
   and are standing up for what they believe in.
<p>

              Last summer we traveled into the South,
   many of us naive, just thinking that all we would
   encounter was a little hot weather and a couple of
   old people that we were going to speak to.  We
   didn't think our lives would be changed.  Some of
   us thought it was just a summer vacation.  But it
   became so much more than that.
<p>

              We went into Mississippi, which was in
   1960 labeled as the most backward state.  We saw
   places where people had died, shed blood.  We
   walked along the road where the Freedom Selma
   workers were abducted.  For many of us, it was a
   wake-up call, a realization that people shed blood
   so that we could exercise the rights which many of
    us were being denied.
<p>

               We learned about hundreds of young
    people, we learned about Claudette Colvin.  It's
    interesting to find out how many people didn't know
    about her.  Rosa Parks was a special woman and I
    don't want to deny her the recognition she
    deserves, but she was not the first to sit on the
    bus.  It was Claudette Colvin, a sophomore in high
   school, who refused to give up her seat.  The
   police were called.  It was only when Rosa came and
   bailed her out that the idea of no longer sitting
   in the back of the bus was conceived.
<p>

              Because these hundreds and thousands of
   young people have been denied the right to be in
   history books, so many of our people do not know
   where to look when they need a model.  Not enough
   people know about a Mary Beth Tinker and what she
   did.  Not enough young people now about a Claudette
   Colvin and how she acted.  Not many people know
   about the Goodman and Chaney and Schwerner boys who
   gave their lives.  They have been denied the access
   to this information.
<p>

              But instead of just complaining about
   this problem, Project Hip Hop has sought to change
  it.  We have educated ourselves and now we are
    taking that education back into the schools.  We
    realize that the curriculum has denied them this
    information, and we are committed to making sure
    that it gets to the people who need to know about
    it the most.  We have debunked many of the myths
    saying all the civil rights movement was a bunch of
    people getting together with a couple of great
    leaders.  You can organize, create a forum for the
   issues that are important to you.
<p>

              Recently, in May, I went to speak at
   Lexington, Kentucky, high school.  At the beginning
   of December, there was a party held at which many
   people got drunk and then one person proceeded to
   shout racial slurs.
<p>

              What erupted was a racial battle that
   shocked not only the people involved, but the
   entire school and the community.  But through the
   example of the students at Lexington, and the
   administration, we saw people who did not sweep it
  under the carpet but, rather, acted.
<p>

              I went there and I saw thousands of
   students who were actually concerned about what had
   happened at that school.  Many students who had
   decided not to skip on a half a day, but rather to
come in and talk about the issues that were
    important to them.  People stood up and said, as
    one student said, we have many skinheads in our
    school and we don't know what to do about it.  We
    don't know how to fight against many of the
    messages that are being put on to us every single
    day.
<p>

               And I challenged them that as long as
    there is something wrong in your community, and all
   you do is look at it, then you are partly
   responsible for what is going on.  If you have a
   problem with what's being said and the messages
   that are being given out, then you can stand up and
   say, I don't accept that, that I don't believe in
   that.  So many students don't even know what they
   can do to change the problems they see around
   them.
<p>

              It seems as though now, unlike what we
   saw in the civil rights movement, we are fighting
   against an invisible enemy.  Many people don't know
   who are making the decisions that affect their
   lives, but we hope that through the Hip Hop Project
   and other projects like them, that people will
   begin to look at where the problems are coming from
   and what they can do to effectively change them.
<p>

              We hope that we can inspire thousands of
    students, maybe not everyone will be able to go on
    Hip Hop, but that students will act like Jeffrey
    did, to try to challenge the kinds of things that
    their school board may be trying to make them do,
    that they will challenge many of the codes that are
    put against them, that they will challenge curfews
    and criminalization that is being put against
    them.
<p>

              I think one of the most interesting
   examples I can think of is that in the community I
   live in, which is a predominantly black community,
   often stereotyped as a ghetto, and I remember
   riding the bus one day and looking at the
   construction that was going on, and in Dudley
   Square, which is the center of the community, where
   the bus station is, there is the library here, the
   police department here.  You would think they were
   almost conflicting interests.  But as I looked over
   and I looked at the construction, I said, wow, they
   are rebuilding the library.  Then I looked over
   again and realized they were rebuilding the court.
<p>

              It is going to take thousands of us to
   protest these kinds of things, where all of the
   money is being spent on controlling the bad youth
  or making sure that they don't run rampant in the
    city, rather than investing in the education in the
    lives of young people who are working to do
    something different, to be something stronger than
    what is seen on television.
<p>

               I hope that you will stand with us as we
    try to encourage and support young people who are
    trying to do something different and who are trying
    to challenge a system which is supposed to be for
   them but is so often against them.  Thank you.
<p>

             <STRONG> MS. MURRAY</STRONG>:   Thank you very much.
   Miriama.  Miriama will be going on Project Hip Hop
   again this summer as a leader, and I am very much
   looking forward to her support as I drive the van.
<p>

            Now let me turn to Loren Siegel, and I
   hope maybe we will then have time at least for one
   or two questions.
<p>

<STRONG>MS. SIEGEL:</STRONG> I will try to be brief.
   Jeff, Miriama and Preet are very hard acts to
   follow, but I am honored, but I am very much
   honored to be the person who summarize what has
   been said today.
<p>

              When I was preparing for this talk and
   looking through, you know, clippings, notes,
   reports of various kinds, a question kept popping
   up in my mind and that question was, why is it that
    in American society, many people like to deal with
    young people prophylactically except where sex is
    concerned.  Let's not give them truthful AIDS
    education or distribute condoms in our schools to
    prevent AIDS and unwanted pregnancies, because it
    might encourage them to do naughty things, which,
    of course, is a false premise to begin with, but
    let's do adopt stricter and stricter rules and pass
   more and more repressive laws designed to deter
   kids from maybe doing something in the future we
   are not going to like.
<p>

              To me, the Acton case that is pending
   before the Supreme Court and will be pending only
   for another day or two, is a great point.  That is
   the student drug testing case many you have heard
   about already at the biennial, that was handled by
   the Oregon affiliate.
<p>

              To me, the really interesting thing
   about this case, when I was reading through all of
   the court papers was that this is a situation in
   which a highly invasive mandatory urine test --
   invasive in the sense that it was actually
   witnessed specimen collection -- was imposed on
   12-, 13-, and 14-year-old students who wanted to
   participate in sports, even though there was
   absolutely no evidence of a drug problem in the
    school.  The principal, it turns out, was concerned
    about a decline in student deportment.  He
    testified the students were less well-mannered than
    in the past, refused to pay attention in class,
    said rude, obscene and disrespective things, and
    laughed out loud at serious moments.  Terrible,
    just terrible.  And there was a corresponding
   increase in kids given disciplinary referrals.
   From all of this the principal drew the obvious
   conclusion that the students had a drug problem
   that warranted mandatory testing.
<p>

              Another thing that had been going on is
   Drug Alert, a product being very aggressively
   marketed to parents who think their kids might be
   doing drugs.  As you have probably heard, the kit
   consists of a chemically treated cloth and parents
   are instructed to enter their children's rooms when
   they are not there, rub the cloth on the clothing
   and furniture and send the swipe in for a chemical
   analysis to discover what drugs their kids may have
   been exposed to.
<p>

              The trouble, of course, is that this
   test cannot and does not distinguish between active
   and passive exposure.  A child passing a group of
    adults smoking marijuana on a street corner, which
    is a fairly common experience in Times Square,
    where I work every day, shows up just as positive
    as a child who, God forbid, smoked a joint with his
    friends after school.
<p>

               This is what I say when reporters call
    to ask me about Drug Alert.  There is always the
    follow-up question, invariably the follow-up
   question, and I think they are probably
   paraphrasing the entrepreneurs and proponents of
   Drug Alert, and that question is: But isn't it
   worth doing if we can prevent one kid from using a
   bad drug?
<p>

              Then there was the law that was passed
   not too long ago in the town of Harvard, Illinois,
  described in The New York Times as a small farm
   town 60 miles from Chicago, that made it illegal,
   "for any person in the city to knowingly use,
   display or wear colors, emblems or insignia that
   suggest membership in or sympathy with gangs."  In
   this town, that included the Star of David, which
   apparently had some identification with a gang.
<p>

             I thought the most interesting thing
   about the article was that the mayor of Harvard's
 justification for taking such strong anti-gang
    action, in the total absence of a gang problem was,
   "we wanted to take a proactive approach."  At the
  time the article was written, 14 kids had already
    been charged with violating the ordinance, and one
    14-year-old girl who was interviewed in the article
    said, very wisely, "It's a control thing."
<p>

               Then there is the AP story that I read
    about cities who are trying new aggressive crime
  fighting techniques, calling them magic bullets to
   deter the terror of the '90s.  In St. Louis, Mary
   Beth's hometown, police knock on doors of certain
   residents, not the ones in the middle class
   neighborhoods, by the way, and tell parents, we
   think your child might have a gun.  Would you mind
  terribly filling out this form so we can come in
   and take a look?
<p>

              In Union Point, Georgia, in order to
   deter shoplifting youth, the authorities put
   together a list of 21 young people they assumed
   were responsible.  This list was published and
   those kids were banished from the stores in town.
   Banks, video arcades and laundromats.  Guess what,
   all of the kids were African-American.
<p>

              Lots of towns and cities, of course, opt
   for the good old-fashioned curfew.  More than a
    thousand cities and counties have a curfew now.  In
    San Diego, a vintage curfew law, from 1947, was
    brought up that bans kids from being out after 10
    o'clock at night.
<p>

               The assumption that all these kinds of
    strategies will deter bad behavior is just that, an
    assumption that is totally unproven.  Deterrence is
    a very tricky thing.  There is no evidence that
   curfews, bans on certain clothes or insignia or
   drug testing will have the desired effect of
   preventing kids from getting into trouble.
<p>

              But that's not really what it's about.
   It's about control, it's about getting votes,
   making people feel they are doing something about
   difficult and complex social and economic problems,
   and above all, it's something that doesn't cost a
   lot of money, which makes it very popular with the
   politicans.
<p>

              Another whole range of issues I think
   that come up in this area, and I will conclude in a
   moment, are the attacks that we are seeing now on
   youth culture, and of course there is nothing new
   about that.  I mean, when I was growing up, it was
   Elvis Presley who was being accused of creating
   juvenile delinquency.
<p>

               But the thing that's changed a little
    bit about this whole debate is that now the
    proponents of control are citing all kinds of
    conclusive scientific studies that purport to show
    that there is some connection between the spoken
    word or image and later bad behavior.  Of course,
    if you look at the studies, that turns out not to
    be the case.  They have proved nothing of the
   sort.
<p>

              So what's to be done about all of this?
   I think one thing that we need to do, and I am
   speaking "we" generically, the ACLU, is to have
   more faith in young people, even more than we
   already have.  I think that hearing the three young
   people who spoke today really is an inspiration to
   me in my capacity as public education director.  I
   pledge to consult with them and their peers more
   about the kinds of things we are doing, to have
   focus groups, even on an informal basis, when we
   want to put out a publication, to make sure that it
   really is addressing the concerns and speaking in
   the language that kids want to hear.
<p>

              You have really given me some ideas of
   how I want to proceed with my work, and I thank you
 very much for being such an inspiration.
<p>

           <STRONG>MS. MURRAY</STRONG>:   Unfortunately, since we
    are now a half hour late, we won't have time for
    questions, but please feel free to approach our
    panelists and please join with me one last time in
    giving them a real round of applause.
<p>

               <STRONG>(Applause.)</STRONG>
<p>
<STRONG>
(A standing ovation.)</STRONG> 
</blockquote>




