<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
Internet Resources -- Church and State</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/religion.gif">
</CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The following sites provide comprehensive or unique resources relating to
the work of the ACLU in this issue area.  While some of these sites are operated
by organizations that work frequently in coalition with the ACLU, the sites may
also include materials on positions we do not share. 
</P>
<P>To report a broken or relocated link, or to suggest a site for inclusion on
this page, use the feedback button at the bottom of this page. </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE><IMG SRC="/../graphics/rbline.gif" WIDTH="100%">
<P><B><A HREF="http://www.uark.edu/depts/comminfo/www/religion.html">Freedom
of Religion Resources</A></B>  <BR>This section of the American Communication
Association site contains a list of resources on the topic of religous freedom.
There are about 100 links, many of them leading to academic papers on gopher
servers.    
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
<B><A HREF="http://northshore.shore.net/rf/">Religious Freedom Home Page</A></B>
 <BR>The full text of the Religious Freedom Restoration Act (1993) is
available, as is information on its significance, its history, FAQs, and related
law review cases.   </P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P><B><A HREF="http://www.louisville.edu/~tnpete01/church/index.htm">SEPARATION
OF CHURCH AND STATE HOME PAGE</A></B>  <BR>An excellent site maintained by a
Professor at the University of Louisville, an independent researcher, and a
member of the US Supreme Court bar who practices law in Virginia. The goal of
the site is to &quot;explain and defend the constitutional principle of
separation of church and state&quot; in light of attacks by the religious right.
The page argues that the religious right is wrong and details why their
arguments are unfounded.</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://www.berkshire.net/~ifas/fw/">The Freedom Writer:  A Hard
Look at the Right</A></B>  <BR>This monthly publication of the Institute of
First Amendment Studies  emphasizes church/state separation and First Amendment
freedoms.  Full issues are achived at this site, and while there is currently no
cumulative index, each issue's Table of Contents is provided.  </P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://www.intr.net/tialliance/">The Interfaith Alliance</A></B> 
<BR>The Interfaith Alliance is a nonpartisan organization of religous leaders
committed to countering the hard-right.  Its site includes a quarterly
newsletter (the Religious Right), information on Alliance actions, and links to
related news articles.       </P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
<B><A HREF="http://www.fac.org/default.htm">The Freedom Forum First Amendment
Center</A></B>
<BR>This site is centered around general information on the Center's activities
and publications.  The publications section can be searched by keyword.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P><B><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/classics/schoolprayer.html">School
Prayer Decisions</A>
</B><BR>This site, a Legal Information Institute reference page for six Supreme
Court decisions pertaining to school prayer, contains the Court syllabus for
each case and links to related cases and opinions.  
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://w3.trib.com/FACT/1st.pres.rel.html">President Clinton's
Memorandum on Religious Expression in the Public Schools</A></B>
<BR>This section of the First Amendment Cyber-Tribune site contains the text of
the July 13, 1995 Presidential memo.
</P>  
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A><P>
