<CENTER><A NAME="introduction"></A>
<H3>INTRODUCTION</H3></CENTER>
<H4>The docket.</H4>
<P>This docket summarizes the work of the American Civil Liberties Union's
National AIDS Project and the work of the ACLU's 53 state affiliates on HIV and
AIDS issues.  The ACLU works on more HIV-related litigation and legislation than
any other legal organization.</P>
<P>The docket focuses primarily on litigation, but it also includes summaries
of some of the legislative advocacy undertaken by the state affiliates.  The
docket is organized by subject, and within each subject by state.  It was
compiled during the summer of 1996, with an effective cut-off date of
approximately September 15, 1996.</P>
<H4>The staff.</H4>
<P>The National AIDS Project, based in New York, coordinates the ACLU's
HIV-related work nationwide.  <B>Matt Coles</B> is the Director, <B>Michael
Adams</B> and
<B>Marc Elovitz</B> are Staff Counsel.  <B>H. Alexander Robinson</B> is the
Project's legislative representative in Washington, D.C.  <B>Denny Lee</B>
handles media relations.<B>  Ben Dinglasan</B> is the Development Associate,
and <B>Jerl Surratt</B> is the Project's Development Consultant.  Three ACLU
affiliates have lawyers who specialize in AIDS: <B>Roger Leishman</B> at the
ACLU of Illinois, <B>Kelli Evans</B> at the ACLU of Northern California, and
<B>Taylor Flynn</B> at the ACLU of Southern California.</P>
<H4>The supporters.</H4>
<P>The National AIDS Project is largely supported by individuals and a few
Foundations.  We are deeply grateful for the support of the Projects' major
donors, the Friends and Associates.  All the Project's significant supporters
are acknowledged at the back of this docket.  The ACLU is able to do all the
work it does because of the many lawyers who volunteer their time as cooperating
attorneys.  We have only been able to mention the names of some of the scores of
cooperating attorneys here.  We are deeply grateful to all of them for the time
they give us.</P>
<H4>	 We Need Your Help
</H4>
<P>Like all ACLU special projects, the AIDS Project is funded solely by
contributions specifically designated for it.  The ACLU accepts no government
money of any kind; it depends entirely on gifts from individuals and a small
number of foundations.  The Project's ability to work for people with HIV
depends on your willingness to support it.</P>
<H4>Why Give To the Project</H4>
<P>Because it is a part of the ACLU, the Project brings a unique voice to
advocacy for people with HIV.  The ACLU puts fighting for people with HIV in
context as part of a larger program to preserve basic rights for all Americans. 
Because of its strong national presence and its nationwide affiliate network,
the ACLU can respond to attacks on people with HIV and AIDS whenever they occur.
</P>
<H4>Ways to Help</H4>
<P>Contributions to the ACLU AIDS Project are tax-deductible, and support both
national and local work.  The Project has a FRIENDS group for those who
contribute $1,000 or more per year, and an ASSOCIATES group for those who give
$500 or more per year, but every contribution helps.  We can also provide help
with bequests, life income and other planned gifts which may have unique tax and
financial benefits.  </P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER" CELLPADDING="25">
