<HR>
<CENTER><A NAME="docket"></A>
<H3>1996 AIDS DOCKET</H3></CENTER>
<H4><A NAME="1"></A>1.   ACCESS TO HEALTH CARE</H4>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Illinois</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>G.S. v. Dr. Karim Baksh</B><BR> 	G.S. was a dental patient of Dr. Baksh
for more than ten years.  When G.S. told Baksh that he had tested positive for
HIV, the dentist refused to provide even routine dental services.  The ACLU of
Illinois filed a complaint with the state Human Rights Commission (HRC) alleging
that Baksh was guilty of discrimination on the basis of handicap.  The
commission ruled that Baksh was guilty of discrimination, and awarded damages
and attorneys' fees.</P>
<P>	This was the first HIV discrimination claim to be brought under the
Illinois law banning disability discrimination.  It established both that the
law applied to HIV and that dental offices are public accommodations covered by
the law.</P>
<P>	Following the AIDS-related death of G.S., the ACLU successfully moved to 
substitute the Estate of G.S. as Claimant.  Dr. Baksh then moved to dismiss the
case on the ground that all claims were extinguished upon G.S.'s death.  The HRC
denied Dr. Baksh's motion, ruling for the first time that a discrimination claim
under the Human Rights Act survives the death of the claimant.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Cut'n Dried Salon v. National Group Life Insurance</B><BR> 	The ACLU of
Illinois challenged an insurance company's refusal to provide employee health
insurance to hairdressers, graphic designers, florists, and others in
professions believed to be heavily filled by gay men.  The complaint is 
currently pending before the Illinois Human Rights Commission.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Jersey</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>D.B. v. Madison Dental Center</B><BR> 	The ACLU of New Jersey
represents a plaintiff who was denied treatment by a dentist after the patient
told him he was HIV-positive.  The suit alleges that the denial of treatment
violated New Jersey's Law Against Discrimination, which prohibits discrimination
in public accommodations, and the federal Americans with Disabilities Act, which
prohibits dentists from refusing to treat patients because of HIV status.  On
August 29, 1994, the U.S. District Court issued a default judgment against the
dentist and his employer for failure to provide information in pretrial
procedures.</P>
<P>	After a hearing on damages, the  Court entered judgment for $25,000 in
compensatory and $25,000 in punitive damages against the dentist, who has
absconded.  The ACLU is attempting to track down his assets for seizure.  John
Jacobi of Crummy, Del Deo, Griffinger &amp; Vecchione was the cooperating
attorney.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Confidentiality in Insurance</B><BR> 	The ACLU of New Jersey submitted
detailed comments in opposition to a proposed change in the state's insurance
regulations which would have permitted insurers to ask questions about HIV
status if the questions were &quot;phrased in the same manner as questions
related to other diseases and conditions,&quot; and would have allowed insurers
to test for HIV &quot;if they require screening tests for other diseases or
conditions.&quot;</P>
<P>	The ACLU argued that the proposed legislation would permit discriminatory
treatment of HIV positive persons because it did not require that HIV be treated
similarly to all actuarially similar diseases.  The ACLU also argued that the
regulations violated the ADA.  Finally, the ACLU argued that regulations
defeated the cost-spreading purpose of insurance.  The insurance Commissioner
withdrew the proposed regulations.  John Jacobi of Seton Hall Law School was the
ACLU cooperating attorney, along with former ACLU Legal Director Marsha Wenk.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New York</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Cahill v. Rosa</B> <BR> 	The Project filed an <I>amicus</I> brief
before the New York Court of Appeals on behalf of a coalition of national and
state organizations committed to securing the rights of people with disabilities
including HIV/AIDS.  Roy Grabowski was denied dental treatment by Dennis Cahill,
D.D.S. in August 1991 because Dr. Cahill believed that Mr. Grabowski could be
infected with HIV.  Mr. Grabowski was told that &quot;if [he] was positive, [he]
would have to find someplace else to go.&quot;  </P>
<P>	The State Human Rights Commission found that Dr. Cahill had violated the
New York State Human Rights Law.  On appeal, Dr. Cahill argues that his office
is not covered as a &quot;public accommodation&quot; under the law and that he
is therefore not subject to its non-discrimination mandate.  The Project's <I>amicus</I>
brief explained how a dentist's office is covered under the terms of the Human
Rights statute and how the history and purpose of the statute require a broad
and inclusive interpretation of its provisions.  Briefs were submitted in the
Summer of 1996, the case was argued in early September and a decision is
expected shortly.  Cooperating attorneys for the Project were Robert W.
Lehrburger and David M. Levin of Patterson, Belknap, Webb &amp; Tyler.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>South Carolina</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Givens, et al. v. South Carolina Health Insurance Pool, et al.</B>	
<BR>	This is a challenge under the Americans with Disabilities Act to the
express exclusion of people with HIV from the South Carolina Health Insurance
Pool.  The insurance pool is designed to provide health coverage to people who
are otherwise uninsurable because of pre-existing medical problems.  It is
prohibited from setting rates based on medical condition.  By definition the
pool covers expensive high-risk conditions such as heart, lung, or liver
disease, diabetes, and cancer.  But all people with HIV are absolutely excluded
from the pool.  The lower court held that the ADA allows an insurer &quot;to
exclude any risk it wishes from coverage.&quot;  Oral arguments on appeal were
heard April 1, 1996.  The appeal is being handled by the Project with the
affiliate.</P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="2"></A> 2.   CONFIDENTIALITY</H4>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Connecticut</H5> </CENTER>
<P><B>Doe v. Marselle</B><BR> 	In a unanimous decision, the Connecticut
Supreme Court reversed a lower court's narrow reading of the state HIV
confidentiality law.  The Supreme Court held that a doctor could be liable for
knowingly (as opposed to accidentally) disclosing a patient's HIV status, even
if he had no intent to cause harm to the patient.  The decision restores the
ability to seek damages for persons whose HIV status has been unlawfully
revealed.  The Connecticut Civil Liberties Union submitted an
<I>amicus</I> brief on behalf of the American Public Health Association, the
Connecticut AIDS Action Council and thirteen other individuals and groups.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Hawaii</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Jane Doe v. City and County of Honolulu</B><BR> 	The Hawaii ACLU
represents a woman who was arrested and charged with reckless endangerment in
1988, when she allegedly offered to have unprotected sex with an undercover
police officer who believed she had HIV.  The police attempted to test her for
the presence of the virus without consent and publicly claimed that they
believed she was infected.  The suit alleges violation of state law guaranteeing
confidentiality of HIV status and prohibiting HIV testing without informed
consent.  The suit also alleges violation of the right to privacy.  The case is
awaiting trial.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Idaho</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Teacher and Student HIV Disclosure</B><BR> 	The Minidoka School
District has a policy that requires all public school students and school 
employees who are HIV-positive to disclose their status to school officials. 
ACLU cooperating attorneys are advising the school district that the policy is
illegal and unconstitutional.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maine</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Joseph T. v. Brighton Medical Center and Dr. Robert Warner</B><BR> 	The
ACLU of Maine represents Joseph T., a Massachusetts resident injured in a car
accident in Maine in December 1992.  He was taken to Brighton Medical Center for
treatment and told hospital personnel, doctors, and staff that he had HIV.  The
hospital and Dr. Warner later disclosed his HIV status to third parties
(including his health insurance company) in violation of the Maine Medical
Conditions statutes.  The district court ruled that Joseph first had to go
through a pre-litigation medical malpractice screening procedure.  On appeal,
the Superior Court ruled that the Medical Conditions Act does not require the
screening.  The case has been sent back to the district court.  The ACLU is
being assisted by cooperating attorney Hugh Calkins.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Massachusetts</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Medical Records</B><BR> 	The ACLU of Massachusetts, in coalition with
other groups, has been developing privacy legislation for medical records which
the ACLU hopes to see introduced before the end of this legislative session.</P>
<P>	Massachusetts current law requires written informed consent to test or
disclose information on AIDS/HIV.  The coalition has been able to prevent
changes.  The ACLU has opposed a bill for mandatory HIV counseling for pregnant
women.  The bill has not made progress.  The ACLU was prepared to oppose a
limited involuntary testing program that was proposed, but it made no progress.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Jersey</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Jane Doe v. Passaic General Hospital</B><BR> 	The ACLU of New Jersey is
representing a client who is challenging a hospital policy of including a
patient's HIV status on hospital bills that are routinely sent to employers. 
After the plaintiff was hospitalized for tonsillitis (unrelated to her HIV
status), the hospital sent a bill to the personnel department of the plaintiff's
employer, indicating that she was HIV-positive.  The hospital claims that
confidentiality laws do not prohibit the release of this medical information. 
This case was settled for an undisclosed sum and the hospital agreed to change
its forms and procedures to ensure that HIV status will not be revealed without
the patient's consent.  Betty Goldman was the ACLU's cooperating attorney.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>North Carolina</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>ACT UP v. NC Health Service Commission</B><BR> 	This case challenges an
 administrative regulation that would have eliminated anonymous testing for HIV.
 The Superior Court issued an order requiring the state health commission to
reconsider the regulation in light of evidence that it would deter people from
being tested.  The ACLU of North Carolina helped provide evidence to the
Commission showing that the elimination of anonymous testing in the past has
resulted in a decrease in overall testing for HIV, especially among gay men and
adolescents.</P>
<P>	Nevertheless, the Health Services Commission voted to enact the regulation
effective June 15, 1995, and the Superior Court upheld the decision.  The North
Carolina Court of Appeals in turn upheld that decision.  The case is now before
the North Carolina Supreme Court, where the ACLU-NC has filed an <I>amicus</I>
brief.</P>

<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>North Dakota</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Anonymous Testing</B><BR> 	The ACLU of North Dakota participated in a
statewide public policy task force charged with developing recommendations to
the state's Health Department about appropriate ways to provide education,
information and referral services to at-risk groups within the state.  At the
urging of the ACLU, the Task Force included recommendations for anonymous
testing sites and public education outreach efforts in the Native American
community.  The ACLU also worked to defeat a recommendation calling for
mandatory testing of at-risk populations and pregnant women.</P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="3"></A>3.   CONDOM DISTRIBUTION</H4>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Massachusetts</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Marchisio v. Kouloheras</B><BR> 	The ACLU of Massachusetts represented
a group of AIDS outreach workers who were threatened and physically assaulted by
a Lowell school committee member who opposed their distribution of condoms in
downtown Lowell. The plaintiffs sued the committee member under a state civil
rights law which prevents interference with rights through threats,

intimidation, and coercion.  As trial was to begin, the member agreed to settle
the case by issuing a public apology and making a donation to an AIDS service
organization.  The ACLU was assisted by cooperating attorney Jay Kelley-Crawford
of Mintz, Levin, Cohn, Ferris &amp; Glovsky.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New York</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Kalke et al. v. City of New York</B><BR> 	The All Saints Lutheran
Parish in the Bronx wanted to distribute condoms and demonstrate their use as
part of its Second Annual Basketball Tournament.  The parish, through the South

Bronx Ecumenical ministry, trains young people to teach their peers about risk
reduction, including condom use.  The New York City Department of Parks approved
the permit for the tournament, but refused to allow the parish to make condoms
available at the event, citing an &quot;unwritten rule&quot; prohibiting condom
distribution.  The New York Civil Liberties Union sued and got an order
permitting condom distribution at the tournament.  The NYCLU is now seeking an
order setting aside the &quot;unwritten rule&quot; completely.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Alfonso v. Fernandez</B><BR> 	This suit was brought by certain parents
of New York City public school students.  They wanted to prohibit the Chancellor
of the City Board of Education from making condoms available on request to New
York City high school students.  The New York Civil Liberties Union filed a
friend of the court brief in which approximately 38 other groups and individuals
joined, supporting the Board of Education's condom distribution plan.  While the
trial court upheld the plan, the Appellate Division reversed, and ordered the
program to end.</P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="4"></A>4.   CRIMINAL LAW</H4>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Criminalizing Transmission</B><BR> 	The ACLU affiliates in California
fought AB 380, which would have imposed 15 years to life imprisonment for
individuals who committed certain offenses, knowing that they were HIV-positive.
 This bill also would have added these offenses to the list of &quot;violent
felonies&quot; which incur sentencing enhancements; and added these offenses to
the list of &quot;serious felonies&quot; that could not be subject to plea
bargain.  This bill did not pass.</P>
<P>	The California affiliates are fighting AB 2147, which would criminalize
knowing exposure of another to HIV by engaging in unprotected sexual activity or
 needle sharing.  The term of imprisonment would depend on whether or not the 
individual intended to infect the other person.  The bill passed the assembly
and is now in the Senate Health &amp; Human Services and Criminal Procedure 
Committee.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Maryland</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>McPeak v. Cecil County</B><BR> 	More than 20 years ago, Steven McPeak
was convicted of raping the daughter of a prominent local citizen, and was given
a long sentence.  While in prison, McPeak contracted HIV and became acutely ill
with AIDS.  Toward the end of his sentence, McPeak was granted a rare medical
parole and he returned to his mother's home.  But when the victim's father, now
the mayor, learned of McPeak's release, he sent police to rearrest him on false
charges of engaging in sexual activity and infecting others with HIV.  McPeak
spent nearly a month in jail without being charged.  Finally his public defender
won his release, but only on the condition that McPeak never set foot in Cecil
County.  The ACLU of Maryland and the Legal Aid Prisoner Assistance Project
began efforts to invalidate the ban so that McPeak could go home to die.  Sadly,
however, McPeak died before these efforts could succeed.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Texas</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>In Re Weeks</B><BR> 	The Project assumed post-trial representation of a
Texas prison inmate who was sentenced to 99 years for attempted murder because
he spit on a guard.  At his trial, the court accepted as &quot;expert&quot;
testimony on HIV transmission from Lorraine Day, a bone surgeon, and Paul
Cameron, a psychologist, both of whom contradicted the generally accepted view
that HIV could not be transmitted via saliva.  The jury convicted and on appeal,
the state courts held it was not error to allow &quot;experts&quot; to testify. 
Following recent directives from the U.S. Supreme Court to give the widest
latitude to state courts in criminal cases, the U.S. District Court at the 5th
Circuit Court of Appeals refused to disturb that decision.</P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="5"></A> 5.  EDUCATION</H4>
<P></P>

<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Permission for AIDS Education</B><BR>	AB 2472 would bar any student in
grades K-9 from receiving education on AIDS prevention, sex or family life, and
venereal disease if the school district has not received written permission from
the parent or guardian.  This bill passed assembly, and is now in the Senate
Education Committee.  The ACLU affiliates in California are fighting the bill.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Kentucky</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>AIDS Education Content</B><BR>	The ACLU of Kentucky joined the Kentucky
Fairness Alliance in its successful efforts to oppose a raft of anti-gay and
lesbian and anti-privacy legislation, including legislation which would have
required that students in public schools be taught that &quot;homosexual sodomy
is the primary mode of transmission of HIV and is against the public policy of
Kentucky.&quot;  Another bill which was defeated would have prohibited people
with HIV from obtaining a cosmetologist's license.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Massachusetts</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Brown v. Hot, Sexy and Safer Productions, Inc.</B><BR>	A small group of
parents brought a federal lawsuit seeking millions of dollars in damages against
Chelmsford school officials, an AIDS educator and her business, a representative
of the parent-teacher organization, and a local pediatrician for their
involvement in an AIDS education assembly at the high school.  The parents
claimed that their children were required to attend the assembly which they said
contained lewd and indecent expression.  They charged that the assembly violated
their freedom of religion and their freedom as parents to raise their children
according to their own values.  The lawsuit also claimed the assembly
constituted sexual harassment.</P>
<P>	The U.S. District Court dismissed the lawsuit for failure to state any
recognized legal claims.  After the plaintiffs appealed, the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the First Circuit affirmed the dismissal, emphasizing that exposure
to ideas that some find offensive did not violate any legal rights and that
parents could not restrict the flow of information in public school based on
individual moral or religious beliefs.  The plaintiffs petitioned the U.S.
Supreme Court to review the case.  That petition was denied in March.  In the
meantime, the plaintiffs also filed a state court action raising the same
claims.  That case is still pending and the ACLU continues to represent some of
the defendants.  Other defendants in the first case were represented by John
Foskett of Deutsch Williams, Mary Bonauto and Ben Klein of Gay and Lesbian
Advocates and Defenders, and Neila Straub.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>AIDS Education Content</B><BR> 	The ACLU of Massachusetts supports a
bill to make AIDS/HIV education mandatory.  Although the bill made some process
early in the session, it is not expected to get further this year.</P>
<P>	The ACLU of Massachusetts opposes a so-called &quot;parents' rights&quot; 

bill.  With a large coalition, the ACLU has been able to amend the bill into a
single provision requiring school districts to notify parents of any school
program that is primarily involved with human sexuality and provide them the
opportunity to opt out.  Unfortunately, the language of the bill is patently
offensive in its definition of human sexuality.  The ACLU remains opposed to the
language and is working to defeat the bill or amend it.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Hampshire</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>In Re WMUR-TV</B><BR> 	The ACLU of New Hampshire represents the Steve
Michaels for President Campaign Committee in a complaint against WMUR-TV.  The
station refused to air two of three commercials for AIDS activist Michaels'
campaign for the Democratic Presidential nomination in the New Hampshire
primary.  One of the disputed commercials showed how to clean a syringe, and the
other showed two men kissing and carried a message about condom use.  WMUR
argues that the commercials are indecent.  The ACLU argues that the station does
not have the right under the statute governing campaign commercials to censor
content.  The case is before the FCC.</P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="6"></A>6.   EMPLOYMENT</H4>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Doe v. U.S. Attorney General (FBI)</B><BR>	The ACLU of Northern
California and the Employment Law Center represented a doctor with AIDS who sued
the FBI for discrimination under the Federal Rehabilitation Act.  Upon learning
that the doctor had AIDS, the FBI canceled its contract with him for physical
exams on agents.</P>
<P>	Following a trial in 1989, the United States District Court ruled that no
one could sue a federal agency under the Rehabilitation Act.  The doctor
appealed, and the Ninth Circuit reversed, holding both that the United States
could be sued and that it had waived immunity from damage claims.</P>
<P>	In December 1994, the District Court again decided in favor of the FBI. 
The District Court held that Dr. Doe could not win because having AIDS was not
the &quot;sole&quot; reason why the FBI discharged him.  The Ninth Circuit
originally upheld the trial court decision.  However, after two rehearing
petitions, the Court reversed, holding that while the FBI was entitled to know
what risks a physician with HIV would present and what precautions Dr. Doe was
taking, it was not entitled to know if Dr. Doe had AIDS, because the evidence
showed a doctor with AIDS performing routine physicals poses no significant
risk. </P>
<P>	The FBI asked the U.S. Supreme Court to take the case for review and hold
it pending the resolution of Lane v. Pena, another ACLU case which poses the
same question posed in the first appeal in our case: had the U.S. waived
immunity from damages.  In 1996, the U.S. Supreme Court held in Lane that the
United States is not liable for damages in disability cases.  The Court then
sent our case back to the Ninth Circuit for further proceedings.  While the case
was pending before the Supreme Court, the ACLU began settlement negotiations. 
The government agreed in principle to embody the main points of the favorable
Ninth Circuit decision about health care workers with AIDS in &quot;guidance&quot;
memos it publishes interpreting the ADA.  Settlement negotiations are
continuing.  Kirke Hasson of Pillsbury, Madison &amp; Sutro is the cooperating
attorney.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Testing Boxers</B><BR>AB 2472 requires anyone applying for a license as
a professional boxer to provide evidence that he or she has tested negative for
HIV within the past six months.  The bill passed assembly and the Senate and is
now in the Appropriations Committee.  The ACLU opposes the bill.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>	
<H5>Michigan</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Sanchez v. Kostas Lagoudakis</B><BR>	The ACLU of Michigan represents a
waitress who brought suit against her former employer under the Handicappers'
Civil Rights Act (HCRA) after the employer told her that she had to get medical
evidence that she was disease-free before she could continue to work.  The trial
court dismissed the plaintiff's claim on the ground that she did not have a
handicap as defined by the HCRA.  The Supreme Court reversed on the ground that
the perception that a person has a handicap, even if wrong, was actionable under
HCRA.  The Supreme Court then remanded the case to the trial court.  The trial
awarded Sanchez lost wages and tips, costs and attorney's fees.  The defendant
appealed.  The Court of Appeals concluded that a severely compromised immune
system associated with AIDS was unrelated to an individual's ability to
satisfactorily perform the duties of waitress.  This case has been appealed to
the Michigan Supreme Court.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Utah</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Allred v. Solaray</B><BR>	The ACLU of Utah filed suit on behalf of
Wallace Kim Allred, who was fired because he had AIDS.  Seven months later, Mr.
Allred died.  The ACLU is currently preparing a response to Solaray's Motion for
Summary Judgment which is based upon the premise that the action does not
survive Mr. Allred's death.  All other proceedings have been stayed.  </P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="7"></A>7.   NEEDLE EXCHANGE</H4>
<CENTER>
<H5>Massachusetts</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Clean Needles</B><BR>	The ACLU of Massachusetts continues to support
expansion of the clean needles pilot program beyond the existing four cities
which are currently involved.  No progress is expected this year since there is
strong opposition on the local level.  The program is limited to ten pilot
projects.</P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="8"></A>8.   PARENTING</H4>
<CENTER>
<H5>Nebraska</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Brummett v. Nebraska and In Re JNT</B><BR>	The ACLU of Nebraska is
providing direct representation to foster parents who were denied the right to
adopt their child because Ms. Brummett is HIV-positive.  The child, J.T., lived
with the Brummetts for over 3 years under the state's &quot;fos-adopt&quot;
program.  The Department of Social Services removed J.T. from the Brummetts
when, during the course of the foster parent application, the department
discovered that Ms. Brummett was HIV-positive.  J.T. was eventually returned to
the Brummetts by the Nebraska Supreme Court, and the Brummetts are close to
becoming J.T.'s adoptive parents.  The Brummetts are now suing the state in a
federal court, under the Americans with Disabilities Act and the Rehabilitation
Act.  Lincoln attorney Chuck Bentjen is the cooperating attorney for this
action.</P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="9"></A> 9.   PRISONS AND INMATES</H4>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Bullock v. Gomez</B><BR>The ACLU of Southern California brought this
case against the California Department of Corrections (CDC) and California Men's
Colony under the Americans with Disabilities Act and the Rehabilitation Act.  It
challenges the state's blanket exclusion of all HIV-positive prisoners from the
conjugal visitor program.  The plaintiffs, a husband and wife, have been denied
visits even though both are HIV-positive, the couple is unable to bear children,
and they have agreed to use condoms.</P>
<P>	The case was successfully settled in June with the plaintiffs being granted
conjugal visits.  The visits are particularly important in this case because the
plaintiffs have not been able to visit each other for the past year, and it is
not expected that the husband will survive the length of his prison term. The
ACLU was co-counsel with the Prison Law Office and Kaye, Scholer, Fierman, Hays
&amp; Handler.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Gates v. Deukmejian</B><BR> 	Under a consent decree, the California
Department of Corrections instituted a &quot;pilot program&quot; designed to
show that HIV-infected inmates need not be segregated from the general prison
population.   In February 1991, the Department pronounced the pilot a success
and announced its plans for housing HIV-infected inmates in the future.</P>
<P>	Although the plans were acceptable in many ways, the ACLU of North Carolina
has been mediating disagreements with the Department about the criteria used to
decide how HIV-infected inmates are housed, some programming restrictions which
are still imposed on inmates (limitations on overnight visits with spouses, no

jobs in food services), and programming in the remaining closed units
(maintained for inmates who have demonstrated a significant risk of engaging in
conduct likely to spread the virus).</P>
<P>	After an evidentiary hearing on the housing criteria, the parties settled
the issue with defendants adopting criteria somewhat more stringent than those
originally suggested by plaintiffs.  The issue of jobs in food services went to
an evidentiary hearing and the mediator ruled in favor of plaintiffs. 
Defendants appealed to the Ninth Circuit, which reversed and permitted job
exclusion.  The Court held that although Congress did not exempt prisons from
the disability discrimination laws, discrimination laws do not apply with full
force in a prison.  The parties were able to resolve differences about
restrictions on work furlough and programming including closed units.  The
overnight spousal visits claim was dropped.  The Prison Law office, Warren
George of McCutchen, Doyle, Brown &amp; Enersen, and Sally Rosen and Sam Miller
of Rosen, Bien &amp; Asaro are co-counsel.<B></B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Shumate v. Wilson</B><BR> 	The Central California Women's Facility in
Chowchilla and the California Institution for Women in Frontera currently house
over 5,500 women.  Many of them suffer from  chronic conditions such as HIV
infection, tuberculosis, diabetes, hypertension, and sickle cell anemia.  The
medical care available to these women, as well as to other women at the
facility, is seriously deficient.  They are often denied timely and effective
treatment, have difficulty in refilling necessary prescriptions, and are unable
to obtain needed pain medication.  Moreover, policies in place at these
institutions often result in the disclosure of confidential medical information,
such as a prisoner's HIV status.  On April 4, 1995, the ACLU of Northern

California, working with the ACLU's National Prison Project and a coalition of
other civil rights and civil liberties organizations, filed a class action
lawsuit in federal court in Sacramento to remedy this situation.  The class has
now been certified and discovery is proceeding.  The case is scheduled to go to
trial in early 1997.</P>
<P></P>
<P><B>Testing of Prisoners</B><BR>	AB 3288 would require mandatory HIV,
tuberculosis, and hepatitis testing of all incarcerated persons.  This bill
passed the Assembly but died in the Senate Criminal Procedure Committee.  The
ACLU opposes the bill.</P>
<P>	The ACLU opposes AB 3378, which authorizes the Department of Corrections to
use every means necessary to ascertain the existence of all AIDS cases in
prisons, and eliminates the appeal process for a prisoner who is mandated to
take an HIV test.<B></B></P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Kansas</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Prison Medical Care</B><BR> 	The Criminal Justice AIDS Network
contacted the ACLU about complaints from the Johnson County jail that inmates
with HIV were not receiving proper care.  The ACLU contacted the jail and
registered the complaint.  The Criminal Justice AIDS Network reports that the
inmates are now receiving proper care as a result of the letter.<B></B></P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Massachusetts</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Medical Parole Bill</B><BR> 	The ACLU of Massachusetts supports a bill
to permit medical parole of prisoners with less than six months to live.  This
bill has made great progress through the legislature but has had exemptions for
certain criminal histories attached.  The bill is currently being held up in the
House Ways &amp; Means Committee. </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Missouri</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Prison Medical Care</B><BR> 	The ACLU of Missouri was contacted about
the lack of medical care and treatment of prisoners in the Kansas City jail by
the Criminal Justice AIDS Network.  The ACLU is gathering additional information
about treatment and conditions at the facility.  </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Rhode Island</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Testing of Prisoners</B><BR> 	The ACLU of Rhode Island opposed
legislation mandating HIV testing for all prisoners, including pre-trial
detainees, and allowing correctional officers to learn the HIV status of all
inmates.  The bill passed both houses of the legislature, but was vetoed by the
Governor in July, 1995.  A similar bill is pending now.  <B></B></P>
<HR>
<H4> <A NAME="10"></A>10.   REPORTING</H4>
<CENTER>
<H5>California</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Test Reporting</B><BR>	AB 2812 would have required physicians to report
HIV test results to local and state health officials.  The California affiliates
fought the bill, which died in the Assembly.</P>
<CENTER>	
<H5>Florida</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Test Reporting</B><BR>	On May 17, 1996, Florida enacted legislation
which requires physicians and laboratories to report HIV infection to the public
health authorities.  S.B. 474 became law without Governor's signature.  The ACLU
fought the law.</P>
<CENTER>
<H5>		Georgia</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Vaccination Registry</B><BR>A bill was introduced by Rep. Billy Randall
that would have created a childhood immunization registry in order for the
Department of Health to remind parents when booster shots were due.  During the
floor debate in the House, an amendment was adopted to include an &quot;HIV
registry&quot; for children.  Ultimately, that amendment was stripped in the
Senate and the sponsor accepted some of the changes proposed by the ACLU to
protect the rights of religious minorities prior to the bill's passage.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>		Montana</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Contact Tracing</B><BR>	The Montana Civil Liberties Union successfully
worked to defeat an AIDS testing bill which would have required all those who
test positive for HIV to disclose the names of anyone with whom they have had
sexual contact.  The bill would also have permitted HIV testing without consent
if a person exposed health care providers or corrections officials to blood or
other bodily fluids.  Finally, the bill would have allowed health care providers
to end anonymous HIV testing.  The bill did not pass.  </P>
<HR>
<H4><A NAME="11"></A>11.   TESTING</H4>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Hawaii</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Roe v. Oku</B><BR>	The Hawaii ACLU represented an individual who was
tested for HIV and had his HIV status revealed without his permission while he
was a prisoner.  The ACLU argued the tests and disclosure violate state law, the
right to privacy, and the U.S. Constitution.  The case originally included the
doctor who performed the test, as well as officials of the Department of Public
Safety.  The doctor settled.  The case was set to go to trial, but the state
settled on satisfactory terms.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>	
<H5>Illinois</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Doe v. Alexian Brothers Medical Center</B><BR>	John Doe was admitted to
Alexian Brothers Medical Center for minor surgery in April 1995.  While
hospitalized, he was tested for HIV without his knowledge.  He discovered that
he had been tested for HIV when he received a copy of his insurance bill.  On
April 8, 1996, the ACLU of Illinois filed suit in federal court asserting claims
against the doctor and hospital under the federal Rehabilitation Act, the
Illinois AIDS Confidentiality Act, and Illinois common law.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>		Kansas</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Testing Criminal Defendants</B><BR>	The ACLU of Kansas was unsuccessful
in its bid to oppose new HIV testing legislation.  HB 2586 gives victims of
crime in adult as well as juvenile proceedings the ability to request HIV
testing of a person who is charged with a crime when it appears body fluids may
have been transferred.  The court is required to order HIV testing if requested
by the victim, the prosecutor, or if the person charged tells the arresting
officer he or she is HIV-positive.  The bill also allows the employer of a
corrections officer, emergency services employee, or law enforcement employee to
request HIV testing.  If the test is negative, the court may order a retest six
months later.  Test results are inadmissible in any criminal or civil
proceeding.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>	
<H5>Missouri</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Testing Criminal Defendants</B><BR>	The ACLU of Missouri opposed
numerous bills requiring HIV testing, including a bill which would have required
the testing of prostitutes, persons arrested for drug offenses, anyone an
emergency room medical technician believes might have exposed him or her to the
disease, and any defendant a judge has reason to believe might have put another
at risk.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Jersey</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>State in the Interest of J.G., N.S., and J.T.</B><BR>	This is a
challenge to two New Jersey laws which require HIV testing of juvenile and adult
sexual offenders upon request of the victim.  The ACLU of New Jersey argued that
the testing constitutes an unreasonable search under the Fourth Amendment
because it cannot provide useful knowledge to the victim.  A negative result is
not conclusive, due to the latency period for HIV, and  positive test does not
mean the virus has been transmitted.</P>
<P>	The ACLU-NJ has participated as a friend of the court at all stages of the
litigation, beginning at the trial level, where the ACLU presented extensive
expert testimony on the irrationality of the testing, and testimony from
victim's rights advocates that testing would be harmful to the victim.  The
trial judge found the law unconstitutional but was reversed by the Appellate
Division.  The New Jersey Supreme Court has granted certification, the case has
been briefed, and is awaiting oral argument.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>New Mexico</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Testing Criminal Defendants</B><BR>	The ACLU of New Mexico worked with
women's rights activists on a bill which requires HIV testing for those charged
with rape.  In coalition with HIV lobbyists, the ACLU was successful in its
attempt to alter the suggested bill so that it would have a less prejudicial
impact on the gay community.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>	South Carolina</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Confidential Testing</B><BR>	The ACLU of South Carolina successfully
lobbied for the passage of an anonymous home HIV testing bill.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>	
<H5>South Dakota</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Testing Criminal Defendants</B><BR>	This bill required those arrested
for any offense in which there may have been an exchange of body fluids to be
tested for hepatitis B and HIV.  Additionally, the bill would have given broad
discretionary powers to the police for determining who would be tested.  As a
result of the ACLU's lobbying efforts, this bill was amended to require only
that the state provide information and referral services on testing and
counseling to the victims of sexual assaults.  The bill passed both houses and
was signed into law. </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Utah</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Testing Criminal Defendants</B><BR>	The Utah ACLU successfully opposed
H.B. 267 which would have required mandatory HIV testing for any person accused
of a sexual offense.  An amendment attached in committee also would have
required testing of the victim of the sexual crime.  An active lobbying effort
was mounted by the ACLU and the bill died before reaching the floor of the
Legislature.</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<H5>Vermont</H5></CENTER>
<P><B>Testing Criminal Defendants</B><BR>	S.B. 135 would have required a
person who is charged with a sexual offense to be tested for HIV.  The bill,
which the ACLU opposed, died in committee. </P>
<P></P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P>    
</P>
