Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Substantive Plenary II</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<center><h1>Transcript of Substantive Plenary II<br>
 Free Speech</h1></center>
<blockquote>
<h3>Nadine Strossen, ACLU President:</h3>
<P>
              Thank you very much.  I'm
   thrilled to be here, and especially thrilled to
   introduce Erica Jong, our keynote speaker this
  morning.
<P>
              Erica Jong has been a great friend of
   free speech, as well as other civil liberties, and
   she has also exercised her own rights of free
   expression and her great gifts of expression to
   convey unforgettably to millions of people,
   worldwide, her messages, her insight, her wit and
   her wisdom.  She is one of the widest read and most
   influential women writing today.
<p>
              I have here, from her office, Erica Jong
   Productions, a very impressive document.  It was
   faxed to me under cover of a fax page form headed
   "A Zipless Fax from Erica Jong Productions."  Of
   course, that's an allusion to Ms. Jong's first
   runaway best seller, Fear of Flying, a galvanizing
   book for women and for the women's movement.
<p>  
            This impressive document outlines
   Erica's Jong's outstanding accomplishments and
   unfortunately -- fortunately, I want to have as
   much time as possible for you to hear from her, so
   I can't talk about her nearly as much as I'd like.
   So I'll give you a few highlights of her
   extraordinary career.
<p>
              In addition to having written six best
   selling novels, Ms. Jong is also an awardwinning
   poet, and has also written numerous articles and
   essays and a children's book.  It's going to be
   released, rereleased soon, one of the few books to
   help children deal positively with divorce.  And
   besides being hugely popular worldwide, her
   writings have also earned critical acclaim, as her
   18th Century style picaresque novel, Fanny, being
   the true history of the adventures of Fanny
   Hackabout Jones, which is a feminist answer to Tom
   Jones, if you will.  It was heralded by The New
   York Times in a front page review as "A quantum
   leap in literary prodigy."
<p>
              In all of her writing, Erica Jong has
   celebrated women's strengths and possibilities with
   energy and passion, and she has also given
   generously of her time to the causes of free
   expression, artists and authors' rights and women's
   rights.  Among many other things, she served as
   president of the Authors Guild of the U.S. from
   1991 to 1993.
<p>
              I have to inject a personal note,
   because I know it's so typical of Erica's
   generosity.  That while she was on a very
   strenuous, around-the-world book tour promoting her
   latest wonderful book, Fear of Fifty, A Mid-Life
   Memoir, she took the time to actually carry the
   galleys of my forthcoming book on Pornography, Free
   Speech and Feminism with her.  I understand from
   her assistant, she read them between Venice and
   Hong Kong, and wrote a very generous blurb enroute
   from Hong Kong to Australia.  She just told me that
   as a result of that blurb, Andrea Dworkin no longer
   speaks to her, so...<p>
              <b>(APPLAUSE).</b><p>
   Before closing, I can't
   resist strongly recommending to those of you who
   have not yet had the pleasure, to read Fear of
   Fifty.  It is already a best seller here and in
   half a dozen other countries.  It is a wonderfully
   inspiring book, which I have taken to giving as a
   birthday present to my many friends, including many
   of you out there, who are approaching or, indeed,
   have even crossed over the threshold of 50.  And I
   have to say, not only is the book wonderful in and
   of itself, but it's a great improvement of what
   over used to be my stock fiftieth birthday gift,
   namely the ACLU Handbook on the Rights of Older
   Persons.<p>
             <STRONG> (LAUGHTER).</STRONG><P>
              Erica, thank you very, very much for all
   you've done for the cause of human rights for
   individual human beings, women as well as men, and
   thank you for being with us here today.<p>
            <STRONG>  (APPLAUSE).</STRONG>
<P>
<H3>Erica Jong</H3>
<P>
            What a great introduction.  I
   feel the same way about Nadine.
<p>
              You know, I want to speak to you today
   about the creative imagination and censorship and
   why censorship is such a dire threat to creative
   people.  But first I want want to define some
   terms.  I think that one of the reasons that we are
   embroiled in this tremendous argument about
   censorship and where we are vis-a-vis censorship,
   the so-called Communications Decency Act that is
   being floated in the Congress of the United States,
   is because we live in a time when we have a very
   diverse population.
<P>
              And interesting enough, calls for
   censorship always increase when the population is
   extremely diverse and different standards prevail.
   This is almost a given:  When you have an elitist
   or traditional society in which everybody agrees
   about who gets access to stuff, you don't have
   calls for censorship.  They only occur in a society
   in which there are many different groups struggling
   for a place and trying to figure out whose word
   goes.
 <p>
             So it's very interesting.  It's almost a
   product of the diversity of our society that we
   have these new calls for censorship.  And I think,
   although it seems very depressing some days to open
   the paper and see so many of the things that we've
   fought for going down the drain, it's in a way a
   symbol of how much we have reached people, that
   there should be a worry about pornography on the
   internet, too free an expression of ideas and so
   on.  So maybe there is a little bit of hope here.
<p>
              Forty years ago Margaret Mead, who wrote
   beautifully about so many things that were not in
   her anthropological purview, supposedly said that
   censorship would always increase in a pluralistic
   democracy as each group warred with the other,
   trying to figure out who had the right to be on top
   and who had the right to say what other people
   could speak about.
<p>
              I think we live in a time where the
   freedom to publish sexually oriented material is
   increasingly coming under attack.  Large publishing
   conglomerates increasingly control all means of
   communication and the forces of cultural reaction
   are becoming extremely well organized.  The brief
   cultural glasnost that we enjoyed in the sixties is
   already beginning to seem quaint.  And when you
   think about this century and you think that it's
   the century that started with The Wasteland, with
   Prufrock, with Ulysses, and with great fights to
   liberate literature, which came to fruition just
   about 1962 when the Supreme Court liberated Tropic
   of Cancer.
<p>              And then, in the sixties, a time that we
   all remember, probably well, there was a moment
   when literature all over the world was changed by
   the release of Tropic of Cancer.  Suddenly authors
   didn't have to shut the bedroom door when they
   wrote about sexuality.  Suddenly, the tremendous
   force and passion of sexuality inspired the whole
   culture and created a kind of exuberance that went
   to other areas as well.
<p>              But that period of time was extremely
   narrow.  I would say 20 years, 25 years.  And then
   there was a tremendous desire for censorship
   again.  And we come to the end of the century, and
   we seem to be back in 1895.  It seems that we have
   made a complete circle.
<p>              And now the calls for censorship are
   coming not just from the right, but also from the
   left.  They are coming distressingly from
   feminists, members of my own movement, who believe,
   some of them, like Andrea Dworkin and Catharine
   MacKinnon, that there is no danger in their joining
   forces with the forces of reaction.  For example,
   Andrea Dworkin and Kitty McKinnon joined the Meese
   Commission in 1986, which was very strange.
<p>              So there are feminists who are saying:
   We don't care about the First Amendment; the First
   Amendment is sentimental; the First Amendment is
   foolish; the First Amendment is romantic and
   Rousseauish.  We don't need that, a higher good is
   protecting women and protecting women against rape
   and protecting women against being denigrated in
   print, in pictures, on the internet and so on.
<p>              Well, let's look at that and what that
   has really accomplished in the last few years.
   Basically what it has accomplished, is it has given
   guys like Dole, like Gramm, a new vocabulary.  And
   it's given people like Pat Robertson a new
   vocabulary.  Instead of having to say now they are
   for censorship, because they want to keep all women
   barefoot and pregnant in Christ, they can now say:
   We are protecting women against denigration and
   abuse.  And the reason that we want the
   Communications Decency Act is in order to protect
   women.
 <p>             In other words, they have taken the
   vocabulary that Dworkin and McKinnon have given
   them and they've used it to drape their old
   barefoot and pregnant ideas.  So they've become
   very much harder to counter.  All those same old
   farts, the alter kockers in the Congress who sat
   there when Anita Hill was being pilloried and
   toremented, and who didn't understand anything, who
   didn't get it, they are getting up and saying:  We
   are protecting women against denigration and abuse.
<p>              So basically, what Dworkin and McKinnon
   have done for the evangelical right, is that
   they've given them a new dialect that they can use
   to cloak their very, very ancient ideas.  And
   that's even more terrifying, I think, than anything
   else that they've done and they seem not to
   understand that they've done this.
<P>              I'm not so interested in talking to you
   about why it's important to have free sexual
   expression in society, because I think probably
   many of us here agree with that.  But I want to
   talk about why people are so interested in
   censoring expression when there are so many other
   problems in our society that need addressing.
<P>              I think that people become hysterical
   about expression when they feel out of control:
   They cannot stop rape.  Children are raised in a
   way that they are not parented, they are not
   educated, they are not given values, there are too
   many of them, they are too poor, they are too ill,
   they are too hungry.  Instead of addressing these
   problems in society, problems that come from
   overpopulation, problems that come from the
   breakdown of the family, problems that come from
   the severe inequity of financial access between
   races, between rich and poor, instead of addressing
   these questions, which are the real questions, it's
   easier to address expression and censorship.  It's
   easier to get up and rave about how our society is
   being corrupted by pornographic images on the
   internet.  Much easier to talk about that than it
   is to talk about the fact that there is inequality
   economically and that because there is inequality
   economically, we have people who are not socsocialized
   to be part of our society, and we don't know what
   to do about that problem, so let's talk about
   censorship and expression.
<P>              It is absolutely a red herring.  It is
   total bullshit.  It is like arresting prostitutes
   instead of Johns.<P>
             <STRONG> (APPLAUSE).</STRONG>
<P>              Do you remember last year there was a
   mayor, I believe it was in Miami, who decided that
   she was going to have the names of the Johns who
   frequented prostitutes read on television and
   printed in the newspaper?  And I thought, what a
   sensible idea.  Rather than arresting these women
   whose financial lack of access has put them in this
   profession, which is the only way they can make
   money, instead, expose the guys who are using the
   prostitutes.  Don't criminalize these poor women.
<P>              It never lasted very long.  It spread to
   a couple of other cities, but basically it didn't
   last very long.  And we have a perfectly analogous
   situation, for example, in the whole debate about
   pornography.  If criminal acts are perpetrated when
   pornography is made, if a child is injured, if a
   woman is drugged and raped during the making of a
   pornographic film, why not arrest these guys for
   rape or for child molestation.  We have plenty of
   laws on the books that protect against rape and
   child molestation.
<P>              But, no, that would mean that we were
   going to come down on organized crime, which
   basically profits from pornography, and that's too
   hard.  Perhaps it's too hard because organized
   crime basically contributes to the PAC funds of the
   people in the Congress.  Who knows why?  Maybe it's
   too hard to do that.  Better to jump on expression
   and say that free expression is causing these
   problems.
<P>              So look at the underside of the
   problem.  Look at this great debate that we've been
   having about censorship, free expression, the
   internet.  It's not really about that.  It's not
   really about whether it's good or bad to have
   Tropic of Cancer out there so people can read it.
   It is not really about any of the things that it
   claims to be about.
<P>              What it is really about is that people
   do not know how to stop the Mafia from selling
   pornography in which children are abused, or they
   don't want to do it because they profit in some way
   from it.
<P>              And so instead of going to the root of
   the problem, instead of exposing the Johns,
   basically it's much much easier to beat up on a
   bunch of fuzzy minded liberals who want to make
   little distinctions about what is right and what is
   wrong, i.e. us.
<P>              And we play right into their tendency to
   smokescreen the real problems, because as members
   of the left we're more interested in fighting each
   other than in fighting our real enemies.  We love
   to fight each other.  We love to make subtle
   distinctions and argue with each other.
<P>              And I think that we better really look
   at what's going on in our culture and we better
   look at who profits from pornography.  And we
   better look at the laws that we already have and
   which ones are enforced and which ones aren't.  And
   we better stop letting them make it an issue of
   censorship versus free speech, because really it's
   not about that.  It's about economics at the
   bottom.  It's about the fact that women and
   children are the lowest priority in this society.
   It's about the fact that women and children's
   rights are cut first.  It's about the fact that our
   teenage daughters can't walk on the streets without
   danger of being raped.  It's about a total social
   breakdown and it has absolutely nothing to do with
   expression, that is a smokescreen.
<P>              And suddenly, after having these endless
   conversations on TV with all kinds of people from
   Phyllis Schafley to Claire Short -- the shadow
   minister of labor, in England, who is calling for
   censorship of pornography because it's a wonderful
   way for her to get elected -- it suddenly occurred
   to me that this is not the issue at all.  And I
   would ask you, as my colleagues, to please address
   the basic issue.
<P>              Rather than arguing with the people who
   would censor, about whether or not this is
   censorship.  I would look at the root causes.  I
   would look at the root causes of why people
   participate in pornography.  I would look at the
   inequalities, the economic inequalities that
   underlie the system and I would address those and
   not be jollied into this whole argument about
   censorship.  Because the truth is that anybody's
   political agenda, if it is not your own, is
   obscene.
<P>              <STRONG>(LAUGHTER).</STRONG>
<P>              And basically censorship, once it gets
   on the books, is always used in that way, to
   politically harass the dissenter.  The reason I
   remain a First Amendment fundamentalist, is because
   I understand as a feminist, as a Jew, as a woman,
   as a woman who has been battered for expressing
   herself freely in all her books, I understand the
   First Amendment protects the minority, protects the
   dissenter, protects the woman, protects the witch.
<P>              Basically, I understand that unless you
   have a government of laws, rather than a government
   of people, you cannot protect dissent.  And I
   understand, as a woman who probably would have been
   burned in the marketplace for witchcraft only about
   200 years ago, that I need the First Amendment more
   than anybody does.  And that even if I am repelled
   by child pornography or Bob Guccione's productions,
   that I have to protect those things, because
   essentially it's in my self-interest to do so.
<P>              So those are the terms of the debate,
   the way I would define it now, and I would really
   invite your questions.
<P>
<H3>Burt Neuborne, Professor of Constitutional Law, New York University</H3>
<P>
              <STRONG>MR. NEUBORNE:</STRONG>  Thank you.  And thank
   you, Erica, for what was really a wonderful,
   wonderful talk.
<P>              In fact, it's stimulated me to tell a
   story that some of you may have heard, because I
   used to tell it 10, 15 years ago, when it actually
   happened to me.  But it seems to me so consistent
   with the theme of Erica's remarks, that it's worth
   reminding some of you of and maybe telling some of
   you for the first time.
<P>              For many years my wife and I were, I
   think, the last middle class residents of
   Brooklyn.  We lived across the bridge and we would
   come into Manhattan to see shows.  And so, we drove
   in one night and I couldn't find a parking space.
   And I didn't want to take out a second mortgage, so
   I was driving around looking for a parking place.
   I dropped Helen at the theater and drove around and
   found a parking space on about, oh, I'd say 10th
   Avenue and about 50th Street, where a nice bunch of
   kids said they'd watch the car for me.
<P>              So I dropped the car off and walked over
   to 8th Avenue and started walking south, down 8th
   Avenue to get to the theater.  And I walked past a
   doorway, and from the doorway comes, psst, psst.  I
   look at the doorway and it is a beautiful woman all
   dressed up who wants to suggest a commercial
   transaction with me.  With my usual aplomb I said,
   no, and I tripped over the curb.  I walked away and
   kept walking south.  I get to the next block and I
   pass a doorway and from the doorway I hear psst
   psst, look at the doorway and it's a guy six eight,
   dressed head to toe in black leather and he wants
   to discuss certain relationships that we could have
   as well.  I said, no.  I walked past him, got down
   to the next block, out of the doorway comes, psst
   psst.  I look into the doorway and there is some
   guy who says, I've got stuff to smoke, stuff to
   snort, anything you want.  Do you want to do a
   deal?  I say, get lost.
<P>              I walked past him and grabbed a pretzel
   from the pretzel lady.  As I turned the corner -- I
   had skipped dinner -- I am walking into the theater
   and the last thing I see as I walk into the
   theater, are the police arresting the pretzel lady
   for vending without a permit.
<P>              Now, that's directly related to the
   message of Erica Jong's talk.  It doesn't matter
   whether are a society, whether you are a law
   school, whether you are an ACLU, whether you are a
   police force:  Confronted with hard problems and
   with easy problems, we will all choose to deal with
   the easy problems.  We will attempt to arrest
   pretzel ladies whenever we can, because what it does,
   it keeps us busy when we know we have a hard time
dealing with the more difficult problems in life.
<P>              She's absolutely right when she
   characterizes censorship as a grand form of
   arresting pretzel ladies.  Censorship gives the
   illusion that politicians are dealing with serious
   social problems.  It is a part of a great disease
   we have in this country, which is a politics of
   symbolism.  Politics in the United States has been
   turned into a huge shadow play, where a group of,
   usually men, go behind a screen and act out
   symbolic events and then think they've done
   something very important in terms of dealing with
   society.  And censorship is, of course, the
   quintessential symbolic event.  It is a statement
   of value, a statement of aspiration and it avoids
   having to ask hard questions of what you do about
   serious problems.
<P>              One of the things, one of the great joys
   of having been associated with the ACLU for all
   these years, it is one of the organizations in
   American life, I think it is probably our principal
   role to keep telling the society to stop arresting
   pretzel ladies.  That's our job, and the job really
   of free speech, I mean, the function that free
   expression plays in society, is to make it
   impossible to sweep problems under the rug, to make
   it impossible to pretend to ourselves that there
   aren't 25 percent of Americans that went to bed
   last night without the same chances that all of us
   take for granted.
<P>              And that that other America, the America
   that's been left behind, and that is in such
   jeopardy at this point, free expression is
   ultimately their only hope.  Because the only hope
   of continuing to set the national agenda and to
   insist that politicians stop playing games and
   start dealing with issues, is an uncensored flow of
   information that will force us, if anything will
   ever force us, to be better than we are and to come
   to grips with these problems.
<P>              I can stand here now and I can say to
   you:  If we've had one success story in my years in
   the ACLU, it's been the First Amendment.  One
   continual effort to keep open the channels of
   communication, it's been the First Amendment.
<P>              And there is a reason.  One reason is
   that there is a natural coalescence between the
   left and the right on the First Amendment.  It
   wasn't a coincidence, you know, the flag burning
   case, that the key vote in the flag burning case
   was Anthony Scalia.  Just as it isn't a
   coincidence, when he wakes up and decides to be
   honest, instead of posturing, Newt Gingrich doesn't
   think censorship on the internet is a good idea.
   That is because right libertarians and left
   libertarians understand in a deep sense that there
   is a commonality of interest in keeping expression
   open.
<P>              And so the suggestion from the floor
   that we not write the right off in the First
   Amendment war is exactly right.  There is a very
   strong --<P>
             <STRONG> (APPLAUSE).</STRONG>
<P>               -- a very strong coalescence and a
   very strong commonality in interest that we can use
   effectively and strategically in order to advance
   freedom for everybody in the country, and I can say
   to you with a good deal of pride, that that's been
   our strategy.  In the 1970s, in the national
   office, we sat around and we talked about free
   speech being essentially a left phenomenon in this
   country, that free speech was something that
   benefited the left, that the left liked what the
   right didn't like, that authoritarians were always
   standing up trying to bash it, libertarians tended
   to be -- left wing libertarians who were defending
   it, we said, look, unless we find ways to broaden
   the idea of free speech, to create a constituency
   that transcends our own narrow political aims, free
   speech will be in danger.  All the precedents in
   the world won't help free speech once it loses its
   deep political constituency in the nation.  And
   that led to what was, for some of us, a troubling
   political judgment, but I think an absolutely
   correct, both strategic and moral judgment, and
   that is, the ACLU threw its support behind things
   like corporate speech, commercial speech, speech of
   the right, speech that gave the right a strong
   vested interest in the continuation of a powerful
   First Amendment.
<P>              That coalescence is what bore fruit in
   the flag burning case.  It's why Scalia looks at
   free speech and says:  There's something in it for
   me.  And it is important for us to remind everybody
   in this country that there is something in it for
   them.  So that we have had, I think, a very
   powerful success story in putting together public
   education, the creation of political self-interest
   and the creation of powerful intellectual ideas
   that have translated themselves into strong
   precedent.
<P>              Now, the question is what do we do for
   an encore?  What do we do now in this area of free
   speech?  It's obvious that we keep fighting the
   traditional battles.  The Exon amendment, the
   counter-terrorism nonsense, the flag burning stuff,
   all of that is traditional efforts by
   authoritarians to reimpose restrictions on free
   expression.  It has to be fought and fought as hard
   as we can.
<P>              I will just mention to you, in just a
   few seconds, something that bothers me.  It bothers
   me when I work on ACLU briefs, it bothered me when
   I worked on the St. Pat's brief, it bothers me when
   I work on the hate speech briefs, it bothers me
   when I work on some of the briefs involving
   political contributions, and that is this:
<P>              Having succeeded, I think succeeded
   beyond our wildest expectations, in creating a
   legal and political structure in which free
   expression is extraordinarily protected, we may
   have created problems for the culture that flow out
   of the existence of free expression.  After all, we
   are -- no culture has ever really had free
   expression for a very long time.  We may be the
   first to be experimenting with free expression at
   the level we are.
<P>              So we're beginning to learn that when
   you do have free expression, there is pain
   involved.  There is pain involved because it
   disproportionately empowers the rich.  There is
   pain involved, because it hurts weak people who are
   harmed by the expression and who find it difficult
   to deal with the expression.  It hurts because it
   tends to coarsen the culture by creating the lowest
   common denominator of ambient noise that we are
   surrounded by.
<P>              Now, not for a minute do I suggest that
   those harms would justify going back to
   censorship.  But as an organization that has always
   been ahead of the wave, as an organization that
   built the existing First Amendment because we saw,
   10 and 20 years ago that we could build a great
   national coalition of left and right behind it, it
   seems to me that we should be very, very aware that
   the next wave is how the culture is going to deal
   with the fruits of the expression, with the pain,
   with the coarseness, with the inequality.
<P>              And that as an organization, we now have
   to be thinking of ways to lessen that pain.  It's
   our job -- I used to say to people:  The ACLU's job
   is not just to say no.  Our job is also to say
   yes.  Our job is also to develop solutions for
   social problems, not just to stand around and tell
   people that their solutions are unconstitutional.
   So it seems to me that we have an obligation as an
   institution now, to take seriously the cries of
   pain that come from gays when they're excluded from
   the parade, and the cries of pain that come from
   women when they feel that they've been harmed or
   cheapened in some way by speech, and the cries of
   pain that come from the poor when they are excluded
   from the political debate.
  <P> 
           And take those, take those cries
   seriously, respond that censorship can't be the way
   that we deal with your pain.  That the ACLU can't
   walk away from that pain.  It is our job to help
   this culture develop mechanisms that deal with the
   pain, that don't include censorship.
<P>
<H3>David Bunnell, editor and publisher, New Media</H3>
<P>
<P>              I was just curious, to start here:  How
   many people in this room have access to the
   internet?
<P>              Hey, all right.
<P>              This morning, before I came, I decided
   to send an obscene, lewd, lascivious, filthy and
   indecent E-mail message to Senator Exon, but I
   couldn't.  He doesn't have an E-mail address.  He's
   not on the internet, so unfortunately I couldn't do
   that.
<P>              But I did, in scouring through some
   on-line forums today, I found some words.  The
   Senate has a chaplain and on the morning that they
   passed the indecency act or whatever they call it,
   he gave his prayer.  And I wanted to -- I thought
   the words were kind of moving, so I wanted to share
   that with you.
<P>              "Almighty God, we praise you for the
   advancements in computerized communications that we
   enjoy in our time.  Sadly, however, there are those
   who are letting this information -- who are
   littering this information highway with obscene,
   indecent and destructive pornography.  Virtual but
   virtueless reality is projected in the most
   twisted, sick, misuse of sexuality.  Violent people
   with sexual pathology are able to stalk and harass
   the innocent.  Cyber solicitation of teenagers
   reveals a dark side of on-line victimization."
   Et cetera, et cetera.
<P>              I mean, no wonder they passed that act,
   my God.
<P>              I would -- before you all rush out to
   embrace the right wing and, you know, get carried
   away with that -- I would like to point out that
   the vote in the Senate was 84 to 16 and there were
   plenty of liberal people who voted for that act,
   including a couple of Senators from my home state
   of California, Senator Boxer, who I think she's a
   liberal, anyway, the last time I checked.
   Feinstein is more middle of the road.  But they
   both voted for that act, so, you know, it seems
   like we have a lot of work to do among our own kind
   before we embrace people on the right like Newt
   Gingrich.
<P>              Anyway, what I really want to discuss
   with you is why it is really important to protect
   free speech on the internet and what it is about
   the internet that is truly important.  Really,
   on-line computing is about speech, that's what
   people do on-line.  The difference is it's
   electronic waves instead of sound waves.  People
   participate in forums, in bulletin boards.  And the
   fight over censorship on the net is really a
   smokescreen for control of the only place that I
   know of, where almost anyone can talk to the
   masses.
<P>              You may not realize this, but the
   internet is not owned by Rupert Murdoch or Ted
   Turner, or anybody.  The internet is free and open
   and available to everyone.  For the cost of $500,
   you can go to a book store and buy the software to
   set up your own internet node and become a
   publisher and have access to millions of people.
   Currently about seven million people are on the
   worldwide web.  By the year 2000 it's projected
   that this number will reach 40 million people.
<P>              And you, as an individual, a student in
   high school or college could start a magazine or a
   newspaper on the internet at a very low cost, using
   a Macintosh or a PC, and the appropriate software
   and reach just as many people as Rupert Murdoch
   reaches with his Fox cable TV networks, and that is
   what is revolutionary and very important about this   
precious new medium.  The fact is it's not owned by
   anyone, it's accessible to everyone.
<P>              It's one to make communications.  It is
   the medium that will give us the power to turn the
   tables on the publishing industry, to turn the
   tables on a government that is too much in the
   hands and the control of lobbyists and special
   interests.
<P>              It is the medium that will give
   individuals power and give individuals
   opportunity.  It is a medium that we can use, this
   organization and others, to organize people, to
   galvanize people, to get people on the move again,
   to educate them.
<P>              The net is the breeding ground for
   revolution and treason, and that --<P>
              (<STRONG>APPLAUSE).</STRONG>
<P>              -- that is the reason that we have this
   move to censor it, that's what people are really
   afraid of.
<P>              They're not afraid of pornography on the
   internet.  There is so little of it compared to the
   vast amount of information on the internet.  You
   would get this impression from reading the
   newspapers, that's all that the internet is about,
   it is dirty pictures.  Well, that's just baloney.
   It's such a small, teeny fraction.  You know, a
   hundredth of a percent of the content of the
   internet has to do with pornography, the rest has
   to do with all kinds of information and material
   from all kinds of people.
<P>              There are at least 25,000 internet sites
   today.  There will be 100,000 soon.  Each of these
   internet sites is really a publishing station.  And
   what the economics of this, I think you understand,
   is that you don't have to pay for the cost of paper
   and printing and distribution.  You just put it on
   your computer and people come to you and they can
   download and access it.
<P>              The internet is going to change
   everything and it's very important that we stand
   behind it and don't allow it to be censored.
<P>              There are ways, in fact, that
   individuals, parents, if you are concerned about
   your children, you can censor it yourself with
   things called filters and blockers.  This is
   software that is being developed that allows -- you
   put it on your machine and it will just block out
   all the sex forums and things like that.  So there
   are ways that the individual parent can be
   empowered to control what their children are
   looking at on the internet.  And this is a much
   better solution than censoring the whole thing for
   everybody.
<P>              Of course, there are some problems with
   that, too.  There is some software called Surf
   Watch.  The other day there was quite an uproar
   about Surf Watch, because the people who are
   developing Surf Watch decided any forum with the
   word "lesbian" or "gay" or "homosexual" in them
   had, by their very nature, had to do with sexually
   explicit material, so they just censored all of
   that.
<P>              One of the things that they blocked out
   was the International Association of Gay Square
   Dance Clubs.  And when this was pointed out to
   them, they did back off and change it.  So there's
   even dangers there, that software like Surf Watch,
   which goes to individuals, pretty soon parents
   could demand that you have Surf Watch on all the
   computers at schools and libraries and such.  So we
   have censorship coming at us from all kinds of
   directions.
   <P>           I want to tell you, though, that this
   will never fly, the Communication Decency Act will
   never fly because of the technology.  It's very
   impractical.  It's written by people that have no
   comprehension of what on-line communications are
   all about.  The reason it will never fly is that
   thousands and thousands and thousands of people
   will immediately start putting up millions and
   millions of obscene messages and pictures on the
   internet as soon as that law goes into effect, and
   there just aren't enough jail cells for all of us.
<STRONG>(APPLAUSE).</STRONG>
<P>              That's why it will never fly.
<P>              I guarantee you, that will happen.
   There are people publishing newsletters today
   on-line, that are just ordinary business
   newsletters, that have announced that they are
   going to fill these newsletters full of filthy
   words, if this Communication Decency Act passes.
   <P>           I just want to close on a quote from a
   fellow named Thomas Jefferson.  He one time said,
   "I hold it that a little rebellion now and then is
   a good thing.  And it's necessary in the political
   world, as storms are in the physical world.  It is
   a medicine necessary for the sound health of
   government."
              Thank you.
<P>
<H3>Laura W. Murphy, Director, ACLU National Washington Office</H3>
<P>
       Thank you, Barry, and thanks  to all of the panelists.
<P>              I feel like there is a certain
   atmosphere of optimism and happiness, that we ought
   to take these things in stride, we shouldn't get
   too excited.  But again, my role is to get excited
   about these things that are happening to the Bill
   of Rights and to the Constitution.  And
   notwithstanding Ira's tremendous talk and uplifting
   talk about how far we've come in 75 years, and
   notwithstanding Burt Neuborne's talk about how far
   we've come with regard to the First Amendment, and
   notwithstanding the fact that Newt Gingrich has
   seen the light on censorship on the internet.
<P>              I think we are under assault in the
   Congress on the First Amendment from every
   conceivable direction.  It's what you hear, with
   whom you associate, when and where and how you
   pray, what you say, what you see, the right to
   petition the government.  The First Amendment is
   one of the focal points of all of the leadership in
   the Congress.
<P>              It's as if censorship of indecent, lewd
   and lascivious words on the internet is not enough,
   as if a flag desecration constitutional amendment
   is not enough.  As if a constitutional amendment,
   which is the cornerstone of the Contract with the
   American Family, that would allow religious
   expression in public places is not enough, or
   restrictions on the rights of nonprofit groups to
   lobby is not enough, school vouchers, all of that.
<P>              We have, what I think is a watershed
   crisis embodied in the bill, the counter terrorism
   bill that is now coursing it's way quickly through
   the United States Congress.
<P>              Several days ago it passed in the Senate
   on a vote of 91 to 8.  And this bill is the real
   wolf in sheep's clothing with regard to the First
   Amendment.  It's lurking out there, ready to pounce
   on a number of freedoms that we've come to enjoy.
   And the funny thing about this bill is that Joe Six
   Pack and the average activist has no idea how this
   bill will curtail their rights, much less the very
   sophisticated editorial writer of your major
   dailies.
<P>              This Trojan Horse, sold to the American
   people as protection against future World Trade
   Center bombings and Oklahoma City bombings, is
   nothing more than a massive dismantling of the
  freedom to associate and the freedom of expression.
<P>              The House Judiciary Committee, for its
   part, voted 23 to 12, to pass this out of the House
   Judiciary Committee.  And the only opportunity that
   we can have to stop this terrible piece of
   legislation is on the House floor.
<P>              And I hold some limited optimism about
   this because, in part, in the closing days of the
   Judiciary Committee's consideration of this bill,
   we had four ultra-conservative Republicans who also
   voted against the bill.  And these were four that
   we targeted, the ACLU targeted to vote against this
   legislation.  And they were concerned about the
   impact that this legislation would have on their
   constituency.
<P>              Let me talk about some of the things
   that the bill will do, in case you aren't aware.
   It would allow the Secretary of State to designate
   any group a terrorist organization.  It's a form of
   blacklisting that would not be subject to
   meaningful judicial review.  And terrorism would
   then become defined not as a series of criminal
   acts, which it is, but as a series of
   associations.  So that even people who give to
   organizations unknowingly, thinking that they're
   giving for charitable and humane purposes, like the
   IRA orphans fund, or the hospital for the ANC, they
   would be, then, guilty of contributing to terrorist
   activity and they would be subject to criminal
   penalties and they would be subject to fines up to
   $50,000 and their assets could be seized by the
   federal government.
<P>              This is, indeed, a dark day for civil
   liberties if this kind of thing is allowed to
   pass.  Just think of the chilling impact that this
   legislation would have on people who believe that
   the U.S. government is engaged in activity abroad
   that runs counter to their opinions.
<P>              One person's freedom fighter is another
   person's terrorist.  I remember the days when the
   African National Congress was deemed to be a
   terrorist organization.  Who would have guessed in
   our lifetime its leader is now the head of the
   Republic of South Africa.  That is the kind of
   arbitrary and capricious power given to the
   executive branch.
<P>              Democrats would be delighted if I said
   that this bill was only a creature of Senator Dole
   and Newt Gingrich and Henry Hyde, but it is not.
   The impetus for this legislation came from the
   President of the United States, Bill Clinton.  And
   had he not appeared on the Larry King Live program
   two or three days before the Senate vote, and said
   that he believes that this terrorism bill had to
   pass quickly, and he believed that this terrorism
   bill had to pass with a repeal of the habeas corpus
   laws, what's left of them, we would not have had
   such a horrible bill. We met with a senator the day
   of the vote, and he admitted that the President had
   pulled the rug from out under the Democrats in the
   Senate.
<P>              We had them primed to offer amendments
   so that there could be a counter terrorism bill
   that didn't violate civil liberties.  I agree very
   much with what Burt Neuborne said:  Our role in
   Washington isn't just to say no.  Our role is to
   offer meaningful alternatives.  We had a series of
   meaningful alternatives that would not allow roving
   wiretaps; that would not allow the executive branch
   to have this far-reaching power without meaningful
   judicial review; that would not allow people to be
   deported in star-chamber proceedings.
<P>              But the President, in his desire to
   appear tough on crime and his desire to believe
   that he ought to have common cause with Senator
   Dole, who is running for president, pulled the rug
   out from under the Democrats.
<P>              We have Republicans, too, who were
   willing to limit the ability of the FBI to engage
   in wiretaps.  We had a bipartisan effort primed to
   go, but politics ruled the day.  And I hold Bill
   Clinton, and I hold Bob Dole responsible for the
   fast-tracking of this legislation.
<P>              We have some window of opportunity in
   the next couple of weeks. This bill is going to come
   to the House floor as early as July 10th. We have
   some window of opportunity to make our concerns
   known.  But I urge you to attend the workshop that
   will be headed by our legislative counsel, Greg
   Nojeim, who will go into detail about the horrors
   of this legislation.
<P>              I just think that in our effort to stick
   to our agenda, whether it is church-state issues,
   whether it is free speech issues, censorship, this
   wolf in sheep's clothing, we will rue the day that
   we didn't speak up, that we didn't get active.
<P>              I'm very proud to be in the Washington
   office at this time.  It's a lonely job.  One of
   the criticisms of our office under my leadership is
   that we are too principled.  I'm proud to be
   principled in a time when people are selling us
   down the river, left and right.  And I'm proud to
   say that we are not a left organization or a right
   organization.  We are nonpartisan in our concerns,
   in our criticisms and the people that we work
   with.  If the NRA wants to join us opposing the
   counter terrorism bill, that's fine; if the
   Christian Coalition wants to have us on their
   program to talk about broad new powers of the
   federal government, that's fine.
<P>              What we've got to do, is convince the
   Republicans that it will be their ox that's going
   to be gored by this legislation as much as ours.
   We have to convince them that Joe Six Pack, who
   wants to march around in fatigues, but who is not
   interested in planting a bomb in a federal
   building, will be wiretapped, will be infiltrated
   by the FBI.  And this comes on top of Louis Freeh
   testifying before the House and Senate Judiciary
   Committee about his new interpretation of the FBI
   guidelines.  How he and the Justice Department
   worked together to expand their authority in
   certain areas, but has refused to share this new
   interpretation with the members of the Congress and
   with the American people.  And how do we respond?
   We heap new powers on the FBI to engage in roving
   wiretaps, to give the FBI good-faith exceptions to
   use information that's illegally seized.
<P>              We've got to put a stop to this kind of
   legislation.  And we've got to pull the cover off
   things that are related to crime and violence in
   our society.  Everyone is concerned about crime and
   violence in our society, but we also have to
   understand that beneath these issues is a
   reorganization of the power that the federal
   government now holds.
   <P>           They want vast new powers.  This is
   nothing different than what the Reagan
   administration wanted, what the Bush administration
   wanted, and it's being given to us by Bill Clinton,
   and we must resist it.
 <P>             And so while I'm very happy to be here
   and very happy to put these issues in historical
   context, our work on every aspect of the First
   Amendment, whether it's the Contract with the
   American Family, and school vouchers, and religious
   expression, constitutional amendments, or our
   efforts on flag desecration, on every aspect of the
   First Amendment the rights that we have enjoyed in
   the last few decades are at risk.
              Thank you.

</blockquote>



