<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>
Internet Resources -- Reproductive Rights
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/repro.gif"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The following sites provide comprehensive or unique resources relating to
the work of the ACLU in this issue area.  While some of these sites are operated
by organizations that work frequently in coalition with the ACLU, the sites may
also include materials on positions we do not share. 
</P>
<P>To report a broken or relocated link, or to suggest a site for inclusion on
this page, use the feedback button at the bottom of this page. </P></BLOCKQUOTE><IMG
SRC="/../graphics/rbline.gif" WIDTH="100%">
<P>
<B><A HREF="http://www.feminist.org/gateway/ab_exec2.html">Abortion Rights --
The Feminist Majority Online</A></B>  <BR> The Abortion Rights section of the
Feminist Majority Online includes a special section on the
<A HREF="http://www.feminist.org/other/roewade.html">Roe v. Wade</A> decision,
<A HREF="http://www.feminist.org/gateway/ru486one.html">RU-486</A> information,
a <A HREF="http://www.feminist.org/gateway/ru486two.html">chronology</A> of the
fight to make RU-486 available to American women, and a well-described section
of links to other Internet sites.  There is also a link to the Feminist
Majority's <A HREF="http://www.feminist.org/rock4c/1_rock4c.html">Rock for
Choice</A> project, with program and concert information, quotes from rock
stars, and RealAudio clips from the Spirit of '73 CD.   
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://www.feminist.org/gateway/cv_exec2.html">Clinic Violence --
The Feminist Majority Online</A></B>  <BR> The Clinic Violence section of the
Feminist Majority Online contains the <I>full</I> text of their 1994 Clinic
Violence Survey Report, a nationwide survey of anti-abortion violence in the
United States that includes a section detailing incidents by state.  There is
also information about the Feminist Majority's National Clinic Defense Project,
the &quot;largest clinic access project in the nation,&quot; as well as a
listing of Internet sites relating to clinic violence.
</P>
<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
  
<B><A HREF="http://www.cais.com/agm">The Abortion Rights Activist Home Page</A></B>
 <BR>This site provides a variety of abortion-related news, statistics,
documents, and resources, including clinic escort information. It also provides
links to other abortion resources on the Internet, feminist activist resources
on the Internet, and on-line news services. 
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://www.ppca.org/">Planned Parenthood </A></B>  <BR>Planned
Parenthood's site, appropriately subtitled &quot;A Guide to Healthy Sexuality,&quot;
is one of the best sources of on-line information regarding safe sex and
abortions.  The site was apparently created by a Planned Parenthood chapter in
Chicago; its attractive and user-friendly layout complements the extensive
amount of practical and valuable information available.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://www.gynpages.com/">Abortion Clinics OnLine </A></B>  <BR>Abortion
Clinics OnLine is a directory service comprised of providers of abortion
services and other reproductive health care. They may be private physician's
offices, state licensed clinics, private clinics, or hospital abortion services
-- no anti-abortion &quot;pregnancy consultation&quot; centers are included. The
site allows you to choose, by state and city, from a list of abortion clinics. 
Clicking on a clinic links you to the clinic's homepage, providing more detailed
information on abortion procedures, patient instructions, prices, maps, and
other educational information.</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
 
<B><A HREF="http://www.contrib.andrew.cmu.edu/org/carr/">Carnegie Mellon
University Pro-Choice Page</A></B>  <BR>The Campus Association for Reproductive
Rights at Carnegie Mellon University is another unique and informative web page.
The site provides information on Pennsylvania laws, an essay on back-alley laws
(those laws which seek to restrict abortion access to the point of making the
process of obtaining a legal abortion almost impossible), and an essay analyzing
how parental consent laws adversely affect young women.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>

<B><A HREF="http://now.org/now/issues/abortion/abortion.html">NOW and Abortion
Rights/Reproductive Issues </A></B>
<BR>This abortion page, part of the NOW site, contains information dealing
almost exclusively with NOW's activities in the pro-choice movement.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
  
<B><A HREF="http://www.caral.org/">CARAL -- North</A></B>
<BR>Headquartered in San Francisco, CARAL (California Abortion and Reproductive
Rights Action League) is a non-profit organization dedicated to electing
pro-choice candidates to office. Their web page provides information about the 
organization, a 1994 voter's guide that is specific to California, a list of
abortion-related sites, a clinic violence page, and a listing of California
politics resources. Most notably, the site contains an &quot;activists oasis,&quot;
consisting of a wealth of information and resources for those who want to become
more involved. 
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
  
<B><A HREF="http://www.lm.com/~lmann/feminist/abortion.html">Abortion Rights &amp;
Other Feminist Issues Web - Abortion Rights Link</A></B>
<BR> The compiled documents on this site, organized into an easy-to-follow
format, provide four different categories of information: abortion related sites
(not a very extensive list), Supreme Court decisions about abortion, responding
to... (editorials put up by the authors in response to anti-choice criticisms),
and anti-abortion terrorism. While this site does not provide a comprehensive
listing of information or resources, it is a good place to start for general
information on abortion, clinic violence, and rebuttals to anti-choice
arguments.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P>
  
<B><A HREF="http://northshore.shore.net/~betsys/choice.html">Reproductive
Rights Homepage</A></B>
<BR>This site mainly provides links to other sites; the information available
on-site ranges from women's health to civil liberties. The links provide access
to political organizations' sites, women's health pages, women in science sites,
and to some pro-life sites.
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P><B><A HREF="http://www.prochoice.org/naf">The Voice on Abortion Providers</A></B>
<BR>The organization's mission is to preserve and enhance the quality and
accessibility of abortion services in the U.S. and Canada. NAF and its members
help to make the promise of reproductive choice and freedom a reality for
hundreds of thousands of women every year.  
</P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/../graphics/redline.gif" WIDTH="50%"></CENTER>
<P><B><A HREF="http://worcester.lm.com/women/resources/abortion.html"> Action
related prochoice site</A></B><BR>This site is individually run and links to
many prochoice sites.</P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A><P>
</P><H6><I>Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union</I></H6></CENTER>
