<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Yvonne Nicoletti Story</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<blockquote>
<CENTER><H2>ACLU Clients - Yvonne Nicoletti</H2></CENTER>
<img src="/graphics/nicoleti.jpg" align=left><blockquote><font size=4> Yvonne Nicoletti is from Andover, Massachusetts. In 1994, she was
represented by the ACLU of Massachusetts in an important First Amendment
case.
<P>
Yvonne's saga started one day her senior year when she wore her favorite
T-shirt to school. The shirt advertised the alternative rock group White
Zombie and bore the image of two fully clothed, large-breasted women.  The
vice-principal told Yvonne that the size of the women's breasts made the
T-shirt "obscene" and that she would have to go home and change.  Yvonne, a
self-described radical feminist and opponent of censorship, instead held a
peaceful, one-woman demonstration on a large rock outside her school to
protest the censorship.  At one point, she </blockquote><br clear=all>
slipped her bra through her
sleever and put it on over the offending images.  The police then arrived in
three cruisers and a motorcycle, arrested Yvonne, and charged her with
"disturbing a school."  The charge carries a jail sentence of up to 30 days.
<P>
Yvonne was held in a jail cell for three hours before bail was posted.
During that time she wrote a statement about her thoughts and feelings on
being locked for expressing herself.  [quote!]
<P>
The case was supposed to go to trial on July 10, but the district
attorney of Essex County chose not to pursue the charges, and the court filed
the case without a finding.  In the words of ACLU attorney John Reinstein,
the case simply "went away."
<P>
Yvonne graduated from Andover High in June and is now pursuing a singing
career in California.</font>
<P>

</blockquote>    
