<DOCHDR>
http://www.aclu.org:80/about/75th_ann/iraspch.html 204.243.96.55 19970213130646 text/html 42220
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 13:05:28 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:51:50 GMT
Content-length: 42032
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>75th Anniversary</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><h1>Transcript of Substantive Plenary I<br>
The ACLU In The Next 75 Years</center></h1>
<blockquote>
 MR. GLASSER:  I want to start off with a civil liberties problem, and I suppose an apology of sorts to the audience watching this on television.

                            I have been berated already by our
                 public relations people for not wearing a suit
                 and tie, since CSPAN and CNN are here.  But as
                 most of you know, what's more important than the
                 way we look is what we say and who we are.  And
                 anyway, this is pretty dressy for me at an ACLU
                 biennial conference.  Gone are the days of the
                 tie-dyed T-shirt.  But this is, after all, not a
                 congressional hearing.
<p>
                            Besides, I have worn television blue,
                 which I thought was an interesting concession of
                 principle, and besides, I've retained several
                 lawyers here to represent me if somebody tries to
                 throw me off.  And some of them have suits and
                 some of them don't, so we are we'll equipped to
                 proceed.
                            What I want to talk to you about
                 today, you may be surprised to hear, is morality.
                 The Bill of Rights, adopted over 200 years ago,
                 is mostly seen as a legal instrument.  It's a constitutional instrument and we, the ACLU, and
                 in the fora of public opinion in which we speak,
                 always speak in terms of law and the
                 constitution.  We don't often address the
                 question of morality, the moral nature of the
                 rights that we pursue, the moral nature of
                 equality before the law, and the moral
                 underpinnings of what the Bill of Rights was
                 about before it was a legal document.
<p>

                            That is important today, because we
                 are being assaulted with the belief that somehow
                 we are a nation in moral decline.  We are being
                 told by the new merchants of virtue that the
                 fifties were a wonderful time and we should go
                 back to those times.  That now we are a nation in
                 steep moral decline.  We hear it from William
                 Bennett, who actually writes a book called The
                 Book of Virtues.  We hear it from Gertrude
                 Himmelfarb and Newt Gingrich, who talk to us
                 about the need to revive Victorian morality, as
                 if somehow the problem of the poor in the days of
                 Charles Dickens was not the industrial revolution
                 and the power loom, but the morals, the personal
                 morals of their behavior.
<p>

We hear it from Jesse Helms, who has
                 become an art critic.  And we hear it from Robert
                 Dole, who has become a film critic, even without
                 watching the films, which is a best way to become
                 a film critic.
<p>

                            Over and over again, we see headlines
                 and polls which indicate that people somehow
                 really have come to believe that we are a nation
                 in moral decline, that something terrible
                 happened in the sixties that loosened the
                 wonderful moral bonds of the fifties.
<p>

                            By not responding to that and by
                 responding only in terms of the law and of the
                 Constitution, we miss a great opportunity, and we
                 concede much, too much.
<p>

                            We are a more moral nation today than
                 we were in the fifties, not a less moral nation.
<p>
                            [APPLAUSE]
<p>

                            The reasons are important to discuss.
                 And they are important to discuss publicly, and
                 it is an issue.  The issue of values and morality
                 are not issues we should shrink from or concede.
<p>

                            The fact of the matter is, that if you
                 look closely at what the merchants of virtue are saying,
	   they are measuring the nation's orality
                 by essentially personal choices and personal
                 behavior.  They don't like our sexual choices.
                 They don't like the decisions people are making
                 about whom to love and whom to commit their lives
                 to.  They don't like the fact that some people
                 prefer marijuana over martinis.  They don't like
                 the fact that people are having babies out of
                 wedlock, as if somehow that was an invention of
                 welfare mothers, never before seen in the world.
                 They don't like, above all, that we are not
                 pious, especially in public.
<p>

                            They trace a great deal of the moral
                 problems to the fact that the schools no longer
                 conduct prayer ceremonies every day.  And they
                 worry about the fact, and they say, well, somehow
                 if we could reinstitute prayer in the public
                 schools and expose kids to the formal prayer
                 every day, we would take a step back, they say,
                 on the road to morality.
<p>

                            They talk about the flag, even as a
                 sacred instrument.  They talk about the flag
                 desecration.  Well, in order to desecrate
                 something, of course, it has to be sacred in the 
	   first place.  And since when was the flag a
                 religious document.
<p>

                            They are so strong about this moral
                 decline, that they are willing to amend the
                 constitution which has stood us in good stead for
                 200 years.  In order to achieve it, they are
                 willing to punish people and force them, by law,
                 to observe moral behavior, personal behavior,
                 that they approve.  They are willing to use the
                 power of the state to do that.
<p>

                            If a woman decides to choose to
                 terminate a pregnancy, to have a baby or not have
                 a baby, it is their business to quarrel with that
                 choice and enforce their view on her by law.
<p>

                            If you look at what they mean when
                 they talk about morality and moral decline, it is
                 all about personal behavior, which there are a
                lot of different opinions about, even in this
                room, they might be surprised to learn.
<p>
                            But I think that the morality of a
                 nation is really measured by different things
                 than personal behavior.  The morality of a nation
                 is measured by how the society orders itself to
                 treat its people; by whether or not justice and 
	   fairness prevails; by whether or not people are
                 free to pursue happiness as they see fit; by
                 whether or not people are equal before the law;
                 by whether or not it is safe to be different in a

                 world in which the majority rules.
<p>

                            Those are the moral principles that

                 this country began with.  Those are what we used

                 to call civic virtue, public virtue, as opposed

                 to personal virtue, which is not the government's

                 business and not society's business.  But what is

                 the government's business and what is the

                 society's business is civic virtue, it is the way

                 the society is ordered to treat its citizens.
<p>

                            Now, measured by that kind of

                 morality, the fifties were a time of moral

                 depravity and the sixties a time of great moral

                 advance.  Think about it.  In the 1950s racial

                 segregation and subjugation prevailed, cemented

                 into the law and enforced by state-sanctioned

                 terrorism in some of the states of this country,

                 and prevailed by custom and practice in most

                 other states.  People of darker skin color, for

                 that reason alone, were denied the right to serve

                 on juries, denied the right to vote, denied the right to frequent places of public

                 accommodations, like restaurants, hotels,

                 swimming pools and even public toilets, were

                 denied employment, were denied everything that it

                 is a citizens' right to have.
<p>

                            Was that moral?
<p>

                            At the same time that this was going

                 on, the states where it was going on most

                 harshly, and which were killing people, killing

                 people with state sanction who dared to protest

                 against it, those were the states that had the

                 most schools that conducted daily prayer

                 sessions.
<p>

                            Now, I am not suggesting -- as my good

                 friend William Buckley might, in one of his

                 perorations on correlation -- I am not suggesting

                 that the presence of school prayer led to the

                 absence of racial morality.
<p>

                            What I am suggesting is that there was

                 no relationship.  What I am suggesting is that

                 whether Mississippi was a moral state in 1950 was

                 not to be measured by the number of schools that

                 conducted prayer ceremonies for their kids.  It

                 was to be measured by the way Mississippi was
	   ordered to treat its black citizens.
<p>
                            [APPLAUSE]
<p>

                            During the 1950s, women basically were

                 limited to the kitchen and the bedroom, there to

                 nuture their children and service their husbands.

                 They were not allowed, for the most part, equal

                 opportunity in education.  They were not allowed,

                 for the most part, equal opportunity in jobs.

                 And they were subject, constantly, to the risk of

                 death and certain degradation if they needed to

                 terminate a pregnancy.
<p>

                            Was that a moral time?
<p>

                            Even contraceptives were not freely

                 available.  It was not, I remind you, until 1965,

                 when the Supreme Court struck down a law that

                 prohibited married couples from obtaining

                 contraceptives.  1965.  All women were excluded

                 from the benefits of citizenship because of that.

                 Was that a moral time?
<p>

                            All women benefited by those changes,

                 including conservative women, who may today think

                 that they oppose them.  Was it more moral in the

                 1950s when those limitations existed?
<p>

                            Gay men and lesbians in the 1950s lived secret lives of terror, desperate to avoid

                 revelation.  Their most intimate personal

                 relationships criminalized.
<p>

                            Disabled people were almost as well

                 hidden, closeted away, removed from

                 opportunities.  Disabled more by the social and

                 economic restrictions upon them than by their

                 physical afflictions.  Was that a more moral time

                 than today?  I don't think so.
<p>

                            And free speech, it is useful to

                 remember, was not all that free in the fifties

                 either.  It was a time of loyalty oaths.  It was

                 a time when people lost jobs for attending the

                 wrong meetings or dating the wrong people.
<p>

                            It was a time when the Attorney

                 General kept a long list of subversive

                 organizations.  It was a time when infiltration

                 and surveillance by the FBI, of anybody and any

                 organization and any political point of view that

                 J. Edgar Hoover didn't like, was rampant, and

                 endemic and unchecked and unchallenged.  It was a

                 time when congressional committees regularly

                 called people of this country to account for

                 their own political beliefs and associations, and to rat on their friends.
<p>

                            Was that a time of morality?  Was that

                 the kind of public virtue, civic virtue that is

                 to be celebrated?
<p>

                            And yet, the merchants of virtue today

                 are here to tell us that they loved the fifties.

                 The fifties were a time of white bread and soft

                 lyrics.  The fifties were a time of nice movies

                 about family life, Ozzie and Harriet.  Blue

                 Velvet, maybe, is more likely.
<p>

                            Because beneath, beneath all that

                 sweetness and beneath all those bucolic suburbs,

                 there was the cancer and the sore of deep civic

                 immorality and injustice.
<p>

                            Well, the sixties changed a lot of

                 that.  Not all of it, but a lot of it.  We

                 dismantled Jim Crow laws, a monumental

                 achievement.
<p>

                            Two weeks ago, I spent a weekend in

                 Jackson, Mississippi for a reunion, which you'll

                 hear more about later, of the Lawyers

                 Constitutional Defense Committee, the group that

                 began in 1964 that the ACLU adopted and nurtured

                 in 1965, 30 years ago.  That was a group that sent lawyers down south to Mississippi and

                 elsewhere to help the emerging civil rights

                 movement protest, to help them secure their legal

                 rights, to provide what little protection in

                 those places, that the law could provide.
<p>

                            It was an inspiring weekend.  You know

                 why?  Because what they faced 30 years ago was

                 more oppressive, more suffocating, more hopeless

                 than anything that we face today.
<p>

                            None of them thought that we would

                 prevail.  All of them risked death.  They went

                 there a year after Chaney and Schwerner and

                 Goodman were murdered for registering people to

                 vote and found in a ditch.
<p>

                            Two years after James Meredith was

                 shot for trying to enroll as a student in the

                 University of Mississippi.  And when we were

                 there two weekends ago, the face of Mississippi

                 had changed against all those odds.  And now, in

                 a place where James Meredith was shot for

                 enrolling in the University of Mississippi, the

                 new dean of the University of Mississippi Law

                 School was black.
<p>

                            [APPLAUSE]
<p>
		That was only the second most amazing

                 thing about him.  The first amazing thing was

                 that he attended the ACLU of Mississippi dinner

                 that night as a welcomed guest.
<p>

                            [LAUGHTER]
<p>

                            The fact is, is that these moral

                 issues in the sixties -- and they were not only

                 the dismantling of Jim Crow laws, as you know.

                 That period of time witnessed a virtual explosion

                 of rights.
<p>

                            What happened in the sixties was that

                 every group of people who had  been shut out of

                 equal citizenship in this country began to ask a

                 very radical, moral question, and that is:  Am I

                 a person too?  Does the Bill of Rights apply to

                 me?
<p>

                            And those questions began to feed into

                 the courts and into the Congress, and into the

                 forums of public opinion.  And more and more the

                 answer came back:  Yes.
<p>

                            And by the end of that decade and into

                 the early seventies, there had been an

                 exponential rise in the realization of rights and

                 equal justice, of a kind that was unimaginible only decades before.
<p>

                            Were we a more moral nation before

                 that revolution?  I don't think so.
<p>

                            Now, it's important to remember, as we

                 always tell ourselves, but must tell ourselves

                 again, repeatedly.  Andre Gide once said, you

                 know, that everything that needs to be said has

                 already been said.  But since nobody was

                 listening or remembering, everything needs to be

                 said again.
<p>

                            For those of you who think that I

                 sometimes go on too long, that is the leitmotif

                 of my life.
<p>

                            [APPLAUSE]
<p>

                            When you're preaching, you know, you

                 can never repeat yourself too often.
<p>

                            But the fact is, is that if we see the

                 Bill of Rights as a moral document, and we assess

                 the Bill of Rights and the American Civil

                 Liberties Union today, we are a little more than

                 200 years into the history of the Bill of Rights.

                 And we are 75 years into the history of the ACLU

                 today, and it is the right time to do an

                 assessment, especially since we are facing such a
	   reactionary attempt to roll back a lot of our

                 victories, and this is the right moment for a

                 mutual assessment.
<p>

                            It is important to remember, again,

                 that the Bill of Rights was a great document when

                 it was enacted in 1791, but it was also a flawed

                 document, and it didn't work.  It was a flawed

                 document because it left out African Americans

                 entirely, as well as American Indians, neither of

                 whom were considered to be human.  It was a

                 flawed document because it left out women, who

                 were considered human, but human property of a

                 sort.  They didn't even have the right to vote.

                 What equal citizenship?  What morality?
<p>

                            And the Bill of Rights didn't work

                 real well for anybody else, either.  In 1920,

                 when the ACLU was created, 130 years after the

                 Bill of Rights was adopted, two thirds of our

                 bicentennial period, the Bill of Rights hardly

                 worked at all.  Not only was racial segregation

                 still firmly cemented into the laws of this

                 country in a way nobody thought could be changed,

                 but women still didn't have the right to vote.

                 They didn't get that until later that year, after 70 years of struggle.
<p>

                            The separation of church and state was

                 there on paper, but there weren't too many

                 schools in this country that didn't impose

                 majoritarian prayer, against traditional family

                 values, against the notion that the family has

                 the prerogative for deciding the religious

                 upbringing of their children, not the government.

                 That principle was violated every day in

                 thousands of places in this country in 1920.
<p>

                            And in free speech, people were busted

                 all the time for meetings, for distributing

                 leaflets, for organizing labor unions.  Thousands

                 of people, during the protest against America's

                 entrance into World War I, were arrested for

                 protesting.  Books were prosecuted.  People were

                 put into jail for publishing pamphlets.  The

                 foreign born were deported in the dead of night.
<p>

                            In 1920, when the ACLU was created,

                 the Supreme Court had never, never struck down a

                 single statute or governmental act on First

                 Amendment grounds.  Two thirds of our

                 bicentennial history.
<p>

                            In 1925 John Scopes was tried as a criminal for teaching evolution in the schools of

                 Dayton, Tennessee.  And in 1924 Congress passed a

                 racist act of immigration called the National

                 Origins Exclusion Act.  I don't think that was

                 its exact name, but that certainly was its exact

                 intention and its effect, which barred people

                 from immigrating into this country, pretty much

                 except for Northwestern Europe.  That was a

                 reaction to the racist reaction to the floods of

                 immigration in the late 19th and early 20th

                 Century.  And it was not undone until 1965 when a

                 new immigration act passed at the height of the

                 civil rights movement, passed in the same year

                 that the Voting Rights Act was passed, undid

                 those racial and national origin exclusions and,

                 we are today fighting reaction to that 1965 civil

                 rights act.
<p>

                            So 1920, when the ACLU was created,

                 was a time when the Bill of Rights still wasn't

                 working.  Much of it was nice on paper, but it

                 didn't actually work the way Madison and

                 Jefferson intended.
<p>

                            Well, the ACLU did something about

                 that.  And so did the NAACP, and so did the labor unions.  They provided organized support for the

                 victims of the violation of rights, when the

                 victims themselves did not have the resources or

                 capacity to even get into court.  They provided

                 organizational resources and power at a time when

                 they didn't have much themselves.  The ACLU

                 started with 30 or 40 people in a room in

                 New York.  The NAACP with fewer.
<p>

                            We were not ever in the halls of

                 power.  You know, at a conference like this,

                 recently of the Christian Coalition, to announce

                 their new Contract With The Family or against the

                 family or something like that, or on the family.

                 Ralph Reed, the sweet-voiced, baby-faced Trojan

                 Horse in which Pat Robertson rides --
<p>

                            [APPLAUSE]
<p>

                            -- was up at the lectern, and he was

                 flanked, not with the members of the  ACLU

                 biennial conference committee -- an exercise in

                 raw power that should frighten the pants off the

                 government -- he was flanked by every major

                 leader in Congress.
<p>

                            Some of you may ask, where are they?

                 How come we're not flanked by every major leader in Congress?
<p>

                            Well, you know, worry not, we never

                 have been.  They were not there in 1920 when we

                 announced our formation.  They were not there

                 throughout the thirties.  They were not there in

                 1942 when we fought against the internment of

                 Japanese American citizens.  They were not there

                 in 1950 when we fought against loyalty oaths and

                 McCarthyism.  They have never been there.
<p>

                            They are called congressional leaders,

                 but the truth is they are followers.  They follow

                 the force of movements.
<p>

                            And the movements that have prevailed

                 have never had power on their side.  They have

                 spoke truth to power; they have spoke justice to

                 power; they have spoken fairness to power.  Their

                 strength has always been moral; their strength

                 has never been political.
<p>

                            So today, when we face the sort of

                 overwhelming problems that we face, it is

                 important to remember that we are more strong,

                 more numerous, richer, more powerful, more

                 influential, more well thought of, even by the

                 average American than we have ever been in our history.  And yet, we are outnumbered by the

                 others, and outpowered by our opponents in

                 government.
<p>

                            So what?
<p>

                            It's ever been thus.  It didn't seem

                 to faze the folks that went down to Mississippi

                 in 1965.  God knows they had more power arrayed

                 against them and less chance to beat it than we

                 do today, but they prevailed.  And 30 years later

                 Jackson, Mississippi is a different place and it

                 will never be the same again.
<p>

                            Most of us, most of our goals, most of

                 our moral goals have prevailed.  We are a freer

                 nation, a more libertarian nation, a more equal

                 nation than we have ever been in our history.

                 Certainly, more than we were when we started in

                 1920, but also more than we were in 1950 and,

                 yes, more than we were in 1960.
<p>

                            Now, we are professional

                 gloom-and-doomsayers.  We are always looking, as

                 we must, not on the progress we've made, but on

                 the progress we have yet to make; not on the road

                 we have traveled and the ground we have gained,

                 but on the road we have yet to travel and the ground that still has to be gained before these

                 moral principles are firm and entrenched and

                 irreversible.
<p>

                            So we are always looking at what is

                 undone and always bemoaning the defeats, but that

                 is our strength.  But it is important once in a

                 while not to get too depressed over what we have

                 not done and over our momentary defeats.  It is

                 important once in a while to realize how far we

                 have come and how far ahead in this game we are,

                 and that we are winning, by far.
<p>

                            [APPLAUSE]
<p>

                            I'm not whistling in the dark.

                 Measure all of those indices of civic virtue, of

                 public morality that I was talking about, and

                 tell me if we are not far, far better today than

                 we were at any prior point in our history.  And

                 that is why our opponents are so damn angry, that

                 is what they are upset about, that is what the

                 merchants of virtue are trying to undue.
<p>

                            Now, the real interesting question is:

                 If so many people benefit by all these rights,

                 why is there so much public receptivity to what I

                 believe is not a conservative movement, but a  reactionary one.  A movement that quite literally

                 is reacting to the victories of the sixties and

                 the exponential growth in rights and in equal

                 justice.
<p>

                            You know, it wasn't just blacks and

                 women and advocates of free speech and gay men

                 and lesbians.  It was every kind of movement that

                 drew inspiration from what happened in the late

                 fifties and the sixties.  It was, as I've said,

                 the disabled.  It was also mental patients, and

                 prisoners and people on welfare and children in

                 foster care.  It was the soldiers in the military

                 who also asked questions, like does the Bill of

                 Rights apply to me?  And can I be courtmartialed

                 for disagreeing on a matter of public policy?
<p>

                            People got tremendous inspiration from

                 Brown against Board of Education, because this

                 was not only about racial subjugation, it raised

                 the fundamental question and caused people to

                 start thinking about their own situation and it

                 produced copycat movements of rights.  Most of

                 the organizations you are familiar with today

                 didn't exist in 1950 or even in 1960.  Run down

                 the list in your mind of most of the civic organizations, the public interest organizations

                 that you know about today.  And you will find

                 that they did not exist before 1960.  And they

                 all came into being in order to champion the

                 rights of someone who had been excluded from

                 equal citizenship.
<p>

                            I remember, even the the early

                 beginnings, we're familiar with some of them,

                 we're familiar with the early beginnings of the

                 gay rights movement at Stonewall, but there are

                 others in hidden corners.  People began to get

                 hope from the movements and the progress of

                 others, particularly of black Americans.
<p>

                            In the late sixties or early seventies

                 in Syracuse a poster went up by a small group of

                 disabled people.  The poster was made to look

                 like an old March of Dimes poster, which had been

                 prevalent throughout the fifties, when polio was

                 still a major problem in this country.
<p>

                            And the poster said:  You gave us your

                 dimes, now we want our rights.
<p>

                            It was the beginning of the disability

                 rights movement, or at least the first beginning

                 that I saw.  And it wasn't:  You gave us our
                 dimes, now give us our rights.  It was:  You gave

                 us your dimes, now we want our rights.
<p>

                            Rights have always been subject to

                 demand, because nobody gives them away.  There is

                 no fire sale on rights.  Rights have to be taken,

                 always, and they have to be taken from power.
<p>

                            You can think of a right as a limit on

                 power, that's of course what the Bill of Rights

                 literally does.  But just think of it

                 intuitively:  If you have a right to vote by

                 secret ballot, it means that the government

                 doesn't have the power to look.  If you have the

                 right not to be denied a job because you are a

                 women or black or gay or Jewish, it means that

                 somebody doesn't have the power to prevent you.

                 If you have the right to speak on the street or

                 be secure in your home without fear of government

                 intrusion, it means that that right is the

                 equivalent of:  The government doesn't have the

                 power to stop you or punish you for it.
<p>

                            Every right is a limitation on power.

                 When the labor unions organized to form labor

                 unions and extract contractual rights from

                 factory owners, they did so by limiting the
                 discretionary owner of factory owners.  Every

                 right limits somebody's power and that is why

                 it's always a struggle.
<p>

                            Now, the explosion of rights from the

                 sixties, therefore was also an explosion of the

                 limitations of discretionary power that people

                 enjoyed, and they don't like it.  They don't like

                 it.  And they began right away to organize

                 opposition.  And that opposition has been what we

                 have been fighting.  And now, it is fair to say,

                 they have gained a little ground on us.  They

                 have set us back a bit.  Progress is never

                 linear.  It doesn't go by percentage growth.

                 Even percentage growth doesn't go by percentage

                 growth.
<p>

                            There are averages, to be sure, but it

                 doesn't mean every year you gain 5 percent.  Some

                 years you lose.  What counts is what happens over

                 the long term.
<p>

                            But anyone who is depressed because we

                 happen to be having a little downturn in the

                 stock market cycle of civil liberties, doesn't

                 understand the cycle.  Linear progress never goes

                 on.
<p>

                            We are now in a dangerous period.

                 There is very good reason to be alarmed, because

                 progress is not automatic.  We just can't pass a

                 resolution about how much we've achieved and

                 assume we are going to continue to achieve it or

                 even protect what we've achieved, just by being

                 there.  It is not automatic.  It is always a

                 struggle.  If liberty can be seen metaphorically

                 as a road that's hacked through a jungle of

                 power, remember that the jungle always, if it's

                 unattended, retakes the road.
<p>

                            You've got to keep hacking away.  And

                 the fact is that that jungle is beginning to edge

                 us out a little bit and narrow and constrict

                 those arteries of liberty.  There is very good

                 reason to be very alarmed now at what is

                 happening in this country.  But there is no

                 reason to be depressed or discouraged.  There

                 really isn't.
<p>

                            If Frederick Douglass wasn't depressed

                 in 1857 when the Dred Scott decision came down,

                 why should you be?
<p>

                            If Homer Plessy, a hundred years ago,

                 boarded that segregated train in Louisiana for a
        ride he knew would not do him well, and he was

                 not too discouraged to do it, why should you be?
<p>

                            If Rosa Parks sat down that tired day

                 in December of 1955, on the bus, and a young,

                 then unknown Baptist minister named Martin Luther

                 King Jr. stood up the next day to support her and

                 organized the Montgomery bus boycott, if they

                 weren't too tired and depressed, why should we

                 be?
<p>

                            They faced much worse than we face and

                 they faced it with much less than we have.  If

                 they were not discouraged, there is no reason for

                 us to be discouraged.  If they had hope and saw

                 that hope through and lived to see the day when

                 they prevailed, so shall we.  We always have,

                 that is the significance of our 75-year history.
<p>

                            Now, I want to end on a sports

                 metaphor, because I do hope to move this

                 organization somewhere into the mass, real world,

                 before I'm done.  And I want to go further.  I

                 want to even use a football metaphor.
<p>

                            [BOOS AND APPLAUSE]
<p>

                            Just think, there is reason to be

                 alarmed.  The forces of PC are ever among us.  I

                 want to talk about something -- get ready for

                 this, hold onto your seats -- that Vince Lombardi

                 once said.
<p>

                            [GROANS]
<p>

                            Look, America is watching this, don't

                 groan.  This is football we're talking about.

                 Vince Lombardi was not only a legendary football

                 coach, he also came from Brooklyn.
<p>

                            [APPLAUSE]
<p>

                            And he once said, at a testimonial

                 dinner given to him near the end of his career,

                 he said:  You know, I never lost a football game.

                 Once in a while time ran out.
<p>

                            Well, in our game, time never runs

                 out.  It's a permanent game.  We are not at their

                 goal line, but we will get there.  And the

                 significant thing to remember is that we are a

                 hell of a lot closer to their goal line today

                 than we were 20 years ago, 40 years ago, 60 years

                 ago.  And a hell of a lot closer to their goal

                 line than they are to ours.
<p>

                            [APPLAUSE]
<p>

                            So, what counts in these struggles, we

                 have learned over and over and over again, is
                 never how much power they have or what they do.

                 What counts is how much resistance we offer and

                 what we do in response.  The tide of liberty and

                 individual rights and equal justice is clearly

                 with us, but only if we keep swimming.
<p>

                            Thank you.
<p>

                            [STANDING OVATION]
</blockquote>



