<HEAD>
<TITLE>Substantive Plenary III</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><h1>Transcript of Substantive Plenary III<br>
 Gender Equality</center></h1>
<blockquote>
      MS. MAHONEY:  We have a very impressive
    panel today, as you can see and have heard.  I
    don't want to take up too much of their time.
<p>
               I wanted to start by, like some other
    people today, talking about where we came from.  I
    don't want to go back in time quite as far as Katie
    did.  But instead, I thought I'd go back to 1964,
    an important year for me, because that was the year
    I graduated from college.  And, as some of you may
   remember, luckily some of you in this room don't,
   in 1964 there were still separate ads in the
   newspaper for women's jobs and men's jobs.  The
   men's jobs often, if not usually, were advertised
   with yearly, annual salaries.  The women's jobs had
   weekly salaries.
<p>

              I had graduated from the University of
   Chicago with a degree in history.  And I had a
   friend who worked for an employment agency, and she
   asked the person who ran the agency if they would
   be able to find me a job.  And her boss's response
   was:  Does she type?
<p>

              I didn't, so I didn't get a job.
<p>

              A year later, having gotten tired of the
   only kinds of jobs I could get with my BA, I
   decided to go to graduate school.  When I applied
  to graduate school at the University of Chicago, I
    was told that although I could get in, I wouldn't
    get a fellowship because -- and this is pretty much
    a direct quote -- the University of Chicago history
    department doesn't give fellowships to women.
<p>

               One lucky thing about those years was
    that I did not encounter, I was not subject to an
    unplanned pregnancy, but I had a lot of friends who
    did.  And there were two real solutions open to
   women of my generation, when they had an unplanned
   pregnancy.  One was to marry, and we all remember
   the phrase -- but those of us, again, that know
   that era remember the phrase -- they had to get
   married.  So we used to talk about couples our age,
   when they then, five months later had premature
   eight pound babies.  Or, they had an illegal
   abortion.
<p>

              Again, we were lucky.  We were middle
   class.  We could usually raise enough money to go
   to somebody who was at least medically qualified.
   Granted, the abortions were done without
   anesthetics, under terrifying circumstances, in
   constant fear that the police would come in and
   arrest everybody.
<p>

              None of my friends died.  None of my
   friends, to the best of my knowledge, were rendered
    sterile by the procedures.  But all of my friends
    who underwent those procedures were traumatized by
    them.
<p>

               We thought, in 1964 and 1965, that if we
    could get formal equality, this would all change.
    And we thought, after a few years, we had achieved
    formal equality.
<p>

               Title VII, somewhat inadvertently
   included women as a protected class for employment
   discrimination purposes.  Title IX, on its face,
   prohibited the University of Chicago from at least
   overtly discriminating against women in graduate
   school fellowships.
<p>

              Roe Wade extended the opportunity to
   have legal abortions for women.  A series of
   Supreme Court cases mostly, thanks to the ACLU,
   included women as a semi-protected class for equal
   protection purposes.  And by 1975 we said, wow,
   this is it, this is great, you know.
<p>

              Well, that was what, 20 years ago.  And
   as Katie pointed out just before, women lawyers,
   even controlling for time off for children, et
   cetera, women lawyers don't make what men lawyers
   make.
<p>

               Roe Wade is still the law, but legal,
    safe abortion is functionally unavailable for many
    women in our society, because they cannot get to a
    provider or they can't afford the providers
    available to them or they have 24-hour waiting
    periods.
<p>

               Women who cannot find jobs and who have
    child-raising responsibilities make due on welfare,
    which has become a lower and lower amount, as
   compared to the cost of living over the last 20
   years.  And we now see more a tax on welfare, on
   unemployed women who are trying to raise families,
   on safe and legal abortion.  And I don't know if it
   is worse -- they're all bad -- and the entire
   system of affirmative action is under attack,
   nationally and in particular in California.
<p>

              And so I suppose I would like to start
   this panel with a question, which is, to ask the
   panelists to tell us more about where we've been,
   where we are, and with any luck at all, where we're
   going, with a little hope for the future.
<p>

              So I'm going to turn it over to Sylvia
   Law now.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

             MS. LAW:  Thanks.  It's a pleasure to be
   here.
<p>

               In the early 1970s the Supreme Court
    transformed the constitutional understanding of
    gender equality in a movement that is, I think, as
    dramatic as we ever have observed in our history of
    the Constitution.  The ACLU Women's Rights Project,
    under the leadership of Ruth Bader Ginsburg, was
    instrumental in achieving this change in
    constitutional understanding and reversing this
   transformation.  The ACLU deserved a lot of credit
   for this.
<p>

              In 1973 when Justice Ginsburg urged the
   Court to treat gender-based classifications like
   those based on race, as constitutionally suspect,
   the prevailing law in 1973 still included those
   famous sexist decisions like Bradwell v. Illinois,
   Muller v. Oregon, and Hoyt v. Florida.
<p>

              Hoyt was decided in 1961.  It upheld a
   Florida statute that effectively excluded women
  from the jury pool, Gwendolyn Hoyt, the defendant
   in that case was charged with murdering her abusive
   husband.  She pled self defense.  There were no
   women on her jury and her lawyer said, this is
   unfair, to exclude women from a jury, the jury in a
   case like this.
<p>

             The court rejected her claim, stating
    that, "a woman is still regarded as the center of
    the home and family life and hence cannot be
    expected to serve on a jury."  That was 1961.
<p>

               Justice Ginsburg's 1973 brief discussed
    these cases under the wonderful lawyerly,
    consummately understated banner:  Precedent and
    need of reevaluation.  And her arguments
    prevailed.  And with a few notable exceptions, like
   the military, explicit gender based classifications
   are today presumptively unconstitutional.
<p>

              Despite this spectacular change in
   constitutional understanding, gender equality has
   not been achieved, why is that?  The ACLU and other
   women's rights advocates have suffered three major
   defeats in our efforts to establish gender equality
   as a constitutional norm.
<p>

              First, the Court has rejected the notion
   that discriminatory effects, however stark, however
   unjustified, can form the basis for finding a state
   policy unconstitutional.  Rather, the Court demands
   that people seeking equal treatment under the law
   show that the state intended to hurt them.  As open
   racism and open sexism have become culturally and
   constitutionally unacceptable, intent is virtually
   impossible to prove.
<p>

               In the area of employment, neutral
    policies for the discriminatory impact can be
    challenged under Title VII and those disparate
    impact rules have proven to be workable and have
    been effective in drawing diverse skills and
    talents into the workplace.  Not so under the
    Constitution.
<p>

               The second significant defeat for the
   proponents of meaningful constitutional guarantees
   of gender equality is the Court's holding that
   discrimination against pregnant people has nothing
   to do with gender.  Now, this is a conclusion that
   only a lawyer can reach --
<p>

              [ LAUGHTER ].
<p>

              -- and even most lawyers and judges
   find incomprehensible.  It has profound impact in
   immunizing discrimination against pregnant women
   from regular constitutional scrutiny.
<p>

              Third, despite the best efforts of the
   ACLU and others, the Court has sometimes endorsed
   the notion that government can buy up
   constitutional liberty and equality.  Medicaid pays
   for all medically necessary services except for
   those women who determine to have an abortion; the
   clinics and doctors can receive funds for
    contraceptive services only if they comply with the
    government gag rule prohibiting them from using the
    A word.  And now the Republican Congress seeks to
    punish the children of poor women, by denying aid
    to women who reject abortion and have the child.
   They lose either way.
<p>

               The net result is that while our
    constitutional commitment to gender equality is
   affirmed in the abstract, it's denied in concrete
   reality.  To put it another way, a slightly
   different spin on it, gender equality often seems
   to deliver greater benefits to men than to women,
   to the women who were and are kept down by a
   patriarchal culture law.
<p>

              Let me offer two examples of this
   phenomena.  First in Mississippi University v.
   Hogan, the Court upheld a gender equality claim of
   a man who wanted to go to an all-female nursing
   school.  Mississippi offered men a lot of
   opportunities to go to nursing school, but this guy
   wanted to go to a school right next to his home and
   happened to get the ACLU defending his claim.  The
   Court held that Hogan should not be further put to
   the inconvenience of travel, simply because he was
    a man.  That result seems right to me.
<p>

               But how do we understand then, the fact
    that Shannon Faulkner is having such a difficult
    time getting into The Citadel, the only school in
    her state that offers people the opportunity to go
    to a military academy.  How do we understand then,
    the fact that the Court upholds laws telling
    pregnant women that they have to travel great
    distances, endure bias counseling, wait for a risk
   enhancing interval, before they can obtain an
   abortion.  Why are we willing to put women to this
   inconvenience, but unwilling to put men to
   comparable inconvenience?
<p>

             The law of child support offers another
   example of how gender equality has come to benefit
   men at the expense of women.  Until recently, child
   support laws typically required parents to support
   boys until the age of 21 and girls until the age of
   18.  The theory was that boys needed to be
   supported so that they could go to school and get
   educated.  In Stanton v. Stanton, the Court held,
   Justice Brennan said, "No longer is the female
   destined for the home and only the male for the
   marketplace of the world of ideas.  The specified
   age of majority is required for the boy in order to
   assure him parental support while he obtains his
    education, so too, is it for the girl."
<p>

               Justice Brennan obviously contemplated
    that both boys and girls would be enabled to go to
    school, that is not how it's turned out.  To comply
    with the demand of equality, what states have done,
    is lowered the age of support for everyone.  So
    that the custodial parent, typically the father,
    more separated from the family, declines to
   support, and the mothers, typically who have
   custody after divorce, struggle to enable their
   children, male and female, to go to college.  Dads
   are legally off the hook in the name of equality.
<p>

              Gender equality should be a benefit to
   both men and women, however, it seems that our
   struggle for equality has succeeded best when it
   benefits men as well as women or only men, and has
   failed in many significant ways for women.
<p>

              In discussing the Court's recent
   affirmative action decision, Linda Greenhouse, from
   The New York Times, observes that while the Court
   sometimes is out in front of public opinion, as in
   Brown v. Board of Ed, and sometimes is an
   impediment to progressive change, as in the Lochner
   era, that often the Court is in sync with the
    culture.  And she argues that that is the case with
    respect to the affirmative action decisions.
    Similarly, I think that the Court's gender equality
    cases reflected a general cultural acceptance of
    formal gender equality.
<p>

               And that the Court's failures with
    respect to women who are poor, women who are
    pregnant, or the failure to take seriously the
    notion that equality is about effects, not simply
   formal rules, both reflects and reinforces more
   general cultural attitudes.
<p>

              Thus the challenge for us as civil
   libertarians and feminists is to transform the
   culture, much more difficult than writing a brief.
   Gender equality requires that we obtain respect for
   the poor as well as the rich, the pregnant woman
   and mother as well as the female CEO.
<p>

              Thank you.
<p>

              MS. MAHONEY:  Our next speaker is Faye
   Wattleton.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              MS. WATTLETON:  On January 23rd, 1917,
   The New York Times, on page 20, had a byline that
   read "Mrs. Byrne must go to workhouse."  A few days
   later, "Mrs. Byrne fasts in the workhouse cell, but
   Commissioner Lewis promises she'll eat when
    necessary.  She spurns a bath, too."
<p>

               A few days later, "Mrs. Byrne now fed by
    force.  Birth control prisoner near collapse,
    revives after food is administered.  Offered no
    resistance.  But Mrs. Sanger hears her sister was
    in a state of coma as a result of of the hunger
    strike."
<p>

               On January 29th, The New York Times
   reported, "Can't coax Mrs. Byrne to eat."  And of
   Sanger's trial, it was said that "Mrs. Sanger
   defies court before 3,000 women who cheer her
   speech."
<p>

              When I read that account of the various
   chronicles, in The New York Times, of the struggle
   between Margaret Sanger and her sister, who were
   engaged in perhaps the most important movement
   toward women's equality of the century -- and I
   speak with high regard for the right of women to
   vote, but I do believe that the right of women to
   control our most personal bodies and our
   reproductive decisions, most fundamental -- it
   reminds me of the continuing struggle for equality
   with respect to gender and reproductive rights.
<p>

              I think this is a time that we must
    examine whether this will be a place in our
    history, in which we have challenged successfully
    the forces of those who would imprison women once
    again, even to defy those forces, and to advance to
    our potential.  Our willingness to be a resonance
    of demagoguery, exclusion and repression, you
    certainly heard in the previous speaker.
<p>

               The threats that still do loom, it is
    really a time in which shocking examples of
   extremism that turn on religious beliefs and that
   require those beliefs to be translated into
   political commands have gained a currency in the
   political process and in the public policymaking
   mechanism that ought to alarm every American,
   regardless of our political persuasions.
<p>

              The fear and the anger that is reflected
   in the believers of the restoration of the status
   quo, whatever that may be, and the characterization
   of their battle as restoring the basic tenants upon
   which this country was founded, are a real
   challenge to us.  The meaning of the Bill of
   Rights, and that 200 years later women do not enjoy
   all of the protections of those rights.
<p>

              Ironically, the rights of women are wont
   to be at the center of our most contentious public
    policy debates.  Whether they are cloaked in the
    rhetoric of welfare reform or health care reform,
    it doesn't matter.  If we don't take responsibility
    for an investment in these debates, women will lose
    even more ground in our continuing quest for
    equality.  Because true equality for women resides
    on very basic principles that are important and
    inherently characteristic to our democracy, the
    principles, the tenants of religious liberty,
   freedom of expression, due process and all the
   other guarantees that Americans, that is American
   men, take for granted.  And should not be as at the
   subject of the whims of partisan politics.
<p>

              What do I mean about the need for us to
   remember the immediate past battles, as in forming
   the debates and the challenges ahead?  Well, with
  respect to reproductive rights, and I do believe
   that women's rights and women's reproductive
   equality will continue to be at the center of these
   debates, there is every evidence that they will be
   so.
<p>

              I think we have some very sobering
   lessons out of the Bush-Reagan, or the Reagan-Bush
  years.
<p>

              Let us not forget that the imposition of
    censorship on family planning clinics was not
    implemented, not because the courts struck down the
    President's right to impose such restrictions, but
    because they were not implemented due to a
    technical finding in the Court's decision.
<p>

               Let us not forget that the requirement
    to withhold information from women in Title X
    clinics has not been implemented simply because
    President Clinton has chosen not to do so.  But
   that we now have a Congress that enjoys the
   majority, that has made it as one of its central
   platform issues to restore censorship against women
   in family planning clinics.
<p>

              We must not forget the battles of the
   past in Ray versus Alexandria Reproductive Health
   Services, in which our federal government consorted
   with terrorists to deny women equal access to
   reproductive health clinics -- these were
   individuals engaged in attempting to blockade
   access to clinics -- and in trampling on the
  constitutional right to free association and
   freedom of speech and freedom of choice.  In this
   case we now see the implementation of a law that
   would deny a woman the right to freely make a
   decision about her reproduction and to exercise
   that right at her discretion, and without the state
    intervening in the process of that decision.
    Teenage women continue to be especially vulnerable
    and they are especially vulnerable in the case of
    the welfare reform debate.
<p>

               Now, there are a few within our society,
    even among teenagers, I would suspect, who would
    consider bringing a child into the world as an
    unimportant act.  I know that the popular theory is
   that children want to have children, because they
   think it's a great idea.  But the evidence simply
   does not substantiate that conventional wisdom.
<p>

              And nevertheless, we are seeing now,
   that teenagers are being held up as the blame for
   all that is wrong with our society, and the cause
   of welfare being out of control, and the need to
   somehow corral their hormones and their bodies, to
  prevent this egregious offense against society from
   going unchecked, it would seem.
<p>

              It is unlikely, with great cogitation,
   that we cannot imagine a government policy in which
   two people engaged in sexual intercourse would, in
   fact, attempt to impose upon them, to think about
   the legal consequences of welfare policy upon their
   act.
<p>

              Equally, the act of avoiding pregnancy,
    as an overwhelming number of women in this country,
    even poor women in this country attempt to do, are
    not subject to simple pronouncements.  To those
    that are subject to welfare reform, to simply say:
    If you get pregnant you will, if by happenstance
    you become pregnant, you simply will not enjoy
    equal access to health care services and to a
    decent life for you and your child.
<p>

              A lot of factors are involved in all of
   our sexuality.  Many complex issues, both among the
   poor and the affluent in this country -- and none
   of us are exempt -- integrate into the process of
   reproductive decisions, pregnancy, termination and
   childbirth.
<p>

              It makes no sense to discuss cutting off
   benefits to the poor, at the same time that we have
   not only not kept pace with providing reproductive
  health services to the poor, but we have seen our
   federal government and our Congress engage in an
   unrelenting attack on the poor's access to
   reproductive health services broadly.
<p>

              It makes no sense to attack single
 mothers.  I'm reminded, by the way, that Bob Dole
   and Newt Gingrich made their former wives single
  mothers.
<p>

               [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

               It seems to me the issue, therefore, is
    not whether you are single, but who is single.  And
    what is the moral standard, is it different by race
    and by class?
<p>

               This is the essence of this great
    debate.  Broadly labeling single-parent families as
    dysfunctional and two-parent families as healthy,
   seems to me to also be a very high disregard for
   reality.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

             I believe that major reform will take
   place when this country and the conscience of this
   country is called to give evidence that at the
   center of this debate continues to be women's
   equality and our aspirations to truly be equal,
   whether it is for reproductive equality, health
   equality or welfare equality.  The loss of the
   so-called health care reform debate was a missed
  opportunity to make women's access to health care
   truly equal.
<p>

             And the issue of welfare reform is,
  indeed, about gender equality.  The impending
 debate on welfare reform will certainly focus on
 unwed mothers and teenagers, but it will not
    refocus on what it will take to make their lives
    and their opportunities truly equal.
<p>

               In addition, we know already that the
    reformers will assume that the denial of health
    care benefits will somehow alter our libido and
    that somehow sexuality and child bearing will be
    checked by the punitive nature of their policies.
    There is no evidence in human history that this
   policy will work.  We can only see it for what it
   is:  An outrageous and angry assault on women.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              The Chinese, it is said, wish their
   friends to live in interesting times.  Well, I
  think these are interesting times, friends or foe.
   I prefer to see them, however, as great
   opportunities in which we test the strength of this
   great nation and our resolve to our democracy.
   That means that while women's equality in all of
   these debates, and these are major and pivotal,
   indeed, seminal debates for the future of our
   nation, continue to be forged and defended in the
   courts, and engagement in public policy and in the
  full participation of women in the political
   process must be at the top of all of our agendas,
regardless of our place and our station in life.
<p>

               It is estimated that based on the
    current rate of women's entry into politics, it
    will take 410 years for us to reach parity in the
    Congress alone.  That is simply unacceptable.
<p>

               Whether we praise Pat Robertson or
    Mr. Reed, we must not be blinded by the dangerous
    ruthlessness and the disregard for the civil
    liberties of women and the religious fervor
   shrouding the tactics of those who want to destroy
   our right to freedom of association, freedom of
   speech and freedom of religion, nor the tactics of
   government leaders in their unprecedented and
   continuing efforts to oppress women.  Time must not
   dull our sensitivities on the real and present
  danger that our great nation faces, regardless of
   our gender or of our station in life.
<p>

              We are facing these dilemmas, but we
   must take great courage, and I know that you do, as
   members and associates of the ACLU.  But the work
   that you have done has made it possible for women
   to enjoy the equality that we now enjoy.
<p>

              In my former association, I am very
  mindful that the ACLU was very instrumental in
   making it possible for Margaret Sanger's birth
   control movement to be launched and for helping to
    keep her out of jail.  ACLU lawyers defended her.
<p>

               I am also reminded that at the end of
    her life Margaret Sanger expressed the desire that
    she be remembered for doing something to help
    women, because women are the future of this great
    nation.  And I believe that we must ask ourselves
    every day, and not rest on the progress, nor the
    contributions that we have made in the past, but
   ask ourselves with every new day that may we hope
   that our lives will indeed have done something to
   help women, because we are the future of this
   nation.
<p>

              Thank you.
<p>

             [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              DR. ELDERS:  I want to tell you -- well,
   I need to tell you that I am really very pleased to
   be here, and on this distinguished panel with
   wonderful women, that I very much appreciate.
<p>

              The other thing is that I really want to
   thank the ACLU for inviting me to be a part of
   their national board.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              While I was sitting here this morning,
   one of our members reached over and they said,
  Dr. Elders, you finally found your home.
<p>

               And I want to tell you, you've made me
    really feel at home and I'm very grateful and very
    thankful.  And as I've said over and over, that
    I've always believed about the things and been
    about the things that the ACLU has been about, and
    I want to thank you for all the long years that
    you've worked hard to break down those barriers and
    start trying to build bridges over all of those
   rivers of racism, sexism, purposism, skepticism,
   homophobia, all those isms that we've got out
   there.  And we must work to try to build bridges
   over all of those rivers.
<p>

              But today I want to talk about some of
   those problems that are related to gender issues.
   We all know that if we want to save our society as
   we know it, we've got to control the three Ps, the
   three Ps are poverty, population and pollution.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              And we ask, who are the poorest members
   of our society?  Women and children.  The reason
   children are poor is because their mothers are
   poor.  So --
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              -- so I think we have to begin to look
 at what's happening and how this is affecting all
    of our society.
<p>

               We know that in regard to population, we
    know that 80 percent of the children born to
    mothers who are unmarried and have not finished
    high school and are single, are poor.  Whereas only
    8 percent of those born to mothers who are married,
    who have already finished high school, only 8
    percent of those children are poor.
<p>

              So that says to us that we need to try
   and look at the problems that deal with these kinds
   of issues, if we are going to really make a
   difference in our whole society.  And we've got to
   look at what we need to do to fix those problems.
<p>

              As we also know, that when we talk about
   women, you know, even for those women like me --
   I'll use me as an example -- we know that there's a
   magic glass ceiling in regard to jobs, and not many
   of us get through that glass ceiling.
<p>

              [ LAUGHTER ].
<p>

              3 percent.  3 percent.
<p>

              And so that if you know that of only
   those women who are educated and have the know-how
   and the savvy, only 3 percent gets through, well,
   you know that that says that there is a real
  problem for those that don't.
<p>

               One of the things with myself, I want to
    tell you, you know, I loved being your Surgeon
    General.  And I'll tell you one other thing --
<p>

               [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

               Thank you.  Thank you.
<p>

               I did the very best job that I knew how
    to do.  And I want to tell you, if I had to do it
    all over again, on every thing I know, starting
   today, I would do it exactly the same way.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              DR. ELDERS:  I went to Washington to be
   the Surgeon General.  I didn't go to get a job.  I
   had a job.
<p>

              So with that, the other thing that I
   want to say, my leaving Washington, for me, was a
   bend in the road, not the end of the road.  I plan
   to continue to work for the things that I believed
   in when I went there, I believed in when I left,
   and I believe in today.
<p>

              And if my leaving were to fix those
   problems, heaven knows we'd all be thrilled to
   death.  But the problems of poverty, teenage
   pregnancy, drug and alcohol abuse, violence, crime,
   all the things that I was really trying to fight
   against, are still problems that are going on in
    our society.  And I feel that we've got to make a
    difference, because we know they're most likely,
    most likely to impact women.
<p>

               We know in our society, 60 percent of
    the children born in America are unplanned.
    60 percent.  We have the resources, we have the
    know-how to make a difference, but we've not made
    the commitment to get it done.
<p>

              We have allowed those men in Washington
   to use women's uteruses to get elected, and it's
   high time --
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              -- it's high time we stop letting them
   hide behind our uteruses to get elected.
<p>

              You know and I know that they aren't
   concerned about poor children.  All these rules and
   all of these laws they're making in regard to
   welfare, in regard to Medicaid, all of those rules,
   who do you think they're affecting?  They don't
   affect the women in this room.  If any of you
   wanted an abortion or wanted, you know,
   contraceptives, whatever, you know, you may have to
   do without a new coat this winter to get it, but
   you could get it.
<p>

            They affect the young, the poor, and the
    uneducated.  And we are going to try and make a
    difference.  We have got to be the power brokers
    for the powerless, if we are going to make a
    difference.
<p>

               [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

               I just want to mention, Faye mentioned,
    when we were talking about welfare reform, it's
    amazing, we are only one of two countries -- health
   care reform, excuse me -- who do not have health
   care, universal access to health care:  The United
   States and South Africa.
<p>

              We spend 14 percent of our gross
   domestic product on health care.  The problem is we
   don't spend it on health care, we spend it on very
   expensive sick care.  We spend less than 1 percent,
   less than 1 percent of our health care budget on
   keeping people healthy.
<p>

              You know those nice little things like
   immunizations, like prenatal care, you know, these
   are all women's issues.  How many men do you see
   going for prenatal care or family planning?  All of
   those are preventive health kinds of measures.
<p>

              Health education?  Of course not.  When
   I was up there saying:  We need to educate our
   people.  We've got a health illiterate society,
    what do you think they're saying?
<p>

               They're saying, oh, you know, let the
    parents do it.  Well, the parents don't do it, they
    don't know how, nobody ever taught the parents.
<p>

               We have a health illiterate society.  We
    have a society where 45 percent of our sixth
    graders say there is more fat in watermelon than
    there is in cheese.  So we put all these labels on
   food, but they don't know what they mean.  What
   good are they?
<p>

              We feel we don't want to educate our
   society, because if we educate our children we
   might teach them something about sex.
<p>

              Well, somebody needs to teach them
   something about sex.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

             When you have the highest birth rate for
   teenage -- the highest birth rate, pregnancy rate
   and abortion rate to teens in the industrialized
   world.  When we find 60 percent of our children are
   unplanned, we have 12 million people with STD every
   year, 3 million of those are teenagers, when we
   find that we have 21 percent of our population with
   herpes virus, AIDS is increasing most rapidly in
  our adolescents.  You would think somebody needed
    to teach them something.
<p>

               You know what they tell me?  Well,
    Dr. Elders, if you tell them about it, they'll do
    it.
<p>

               But they're already doing it.
<p>

               I'm just saying:  They are really
    related to gender kinds of issues, because they
    disproportionately affect women.  And because of
   that, many young women are not able to go and get
   family planning services.  You know, can you
   believe we feel, well, we make Medicaid available
   if you're pregnant, but it's not available for
   family planning?
<p>

              As I told the group earlier, I told
   Representative Waxman, I said that the Medicaid
   system, the way it's designed, had to be designed
   by a white male slave owner who wanted to have
   healthy slaves, rather than have healthy, educated,
   motivated children with hope.
<p>

              And that's what we've got to be about.
   We need to prevent unplanned pregnancies, not look
   at it how welfare systems talk about how we aren't
   going to take care of them.
<p>

              If we put out good health care education
  systems in place, if we began to put good services
    for young people in place so they had access, well,
    I think then we can talk about reforming the
    welfare system.
<p>

               You see, you can't pay anybody enough to
    be poor.  And that's what our Congress seems to be
    thinking about.  I wonder -- you know, they need to
    rethink what they're really talking about and what
    they're doing.
<p>

              So what are some of the strategies that
   I've really been about and feel that we've got to
   do?  Many of you have heard me say many times, and
   everyone else:  That we need to try to make every
   child born in America a planned and wanted child.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              I'm not about abortions.  I've never
   been about abortions.  I support a women's right to
   choice.
<p>

              You see, I feel I don't know anybody who
   knows enough to decide for another women.  I don't
   know anybody who is good enough, even if they knew
   enough.  And lastly, we don't love enough to make
   that kind of decision.  It's a decision between a
   woman, her doctor, her significant other, and her
   God.  And it's not for the politicians in
 Washington to decide.
<p>

               [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

               So when we get those services and get
    them out there, why, then I feel that we've got to
    also, we feel so strongly about, you know, how we
    feel about children, and this is why, you know,
    I've made the statement.  And I mean it, and I'll
    make it again:  That I feel that the -- our very
    religious, non-Christian right have a love affair
   with the fetus.  If they didn't have a love affair
   with the fetus, they'd be out there fighting for
   programs for children.  Have you heard them
   fighting for welfare?  Have you seen them out there
   fighting for health care?
<p>

              Have you seen them out there fighting
   for early childhood education for all children?
   Maybe they do it in your state, they don't do it in
   mine.
<p>

              So I feel these are things that we have
   to be about if you're really for children.  You
   know, an affair is something that lasts a short
   time and you can walk out of it.  Anybody who has
   ever had children, I don't know when you get rid of
   them.  Mine are in their thirties and they're still
   around.  It goes on forever.
<p>

           And so you keep -- this is why I feel
    that we have to keep working on things of that
    sort.  You've got to make sure that we have early
    childhood education for all children, so they can
    get a good start.  And that means, if they get a
    good start, they're very likely to do well.  Only
    18 percent of Medicaid children have early
    childhood education.
<p>

               We've got to make sure that we have
   comprehensive health education programs in our
   schools from kindergarten through 12th grade.
<p>

              We've got to teach our young men to be
   responsible.  I know, I was really trying to put
   the Social Security card number of young males on
   the birth certificate, you know, and what they told
   me, why Dr. Elders, there is just no way we can get
   the money.
<p>

              I said, you can take money out of my
   check for Social Security, you take money out of my
   check every month for Medicare, why can't you take
   money for, you know, from a man's check to help pay
   for his child?
<p>

              One of the things when I talk to young
   men about the importance of being responsible, and
   when I mention that we're going to put their Social
 Security card number on the birth certificate and
    take 17 percent of their salary off the top, they
    may be asleep till I say that.  Once I make that
    statement:  What did you say, Dr. Elders?
<p>

               I'm saying, you make two parents
     responsible, not just one.
<p>

               [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

               And that means that we're really
    discriminating against women, because they're
   saying, well, it's unfair to the men.
<p>

              Well, what about being unfair to the
   women?  So I think that that's something that we
   really could do and we need to do and then we
   wouldn't have the problems of men running around
   bragging about how many children they have, none of
   whom they are taking care of.
<p>

              So what do I feel that the role of the
   ACLU is and what do I feel that we need to be
   doing?
<p>

              Well, first of all, I think you've been
   doing what you need to be doing.  We've got to be
   aware of the problem and it's obvious all of you
   are aware.  We've got to be strong advocates for
   these problems, for women's issues, and you have
   been strong advocates for a long time.  And we've
  got to develop action plans that work.  We've got
    to get together.
<p>

               We've been the world's greatest
    coalition builder, but I want to tell you, we've
    got to learn how to network and begin to go out and
    reach out to people that are not like us.
<p>

               The other thing I think we've got to do
    is, we've got to have courage.  I'll never forget
    the one thing that a woman from Alaska told me one
   time.  She said, Dr. Elders, always remember, one
   person with courage makes a majority.  And every
   time I get down and feel I can't go another step, I
   remember that.
<p>

              And you've got to be our leaders, we've
   got to be our leaders.  Leaders that are willing to
   lead, rather than leaders who go out and test which
   way the wind is blowing and jump out front.  We've
   got too many of those out there already.
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              We've got to make sure that we lead.
              And last, but not least, for you and the
   ACLU, we've got to stick together and deal with
   unity.
<p>

              You know, there is that old saying that
   when spider webs unite, they can bring down the
    lion.  I think it is time for us to unite around
    the issues, and they don't have to be perfect, and
    let's come together.
<p>

               And I'll tell you something that my
    Bishop told me, that I carry with me all the time
    wherever I go.  In the church -- and I'll tell you
    what we're doing now, and that I'm willing to use
    my platform to run away, as I run around and talk,
    to do that -- he says, Dr. Elders, in the things
   that you are fighting about, it's like dancing with
   a bear.  He said, always remember when you're
   dancing with a bear, you can't get tired and sit
   down.  You have to wait until the bear gets
   tired --
<p>

              [ LAUGHTER ].
<p>

              -- and then you sit down.
<p>

              So...
<p>

              [ APPLAUSE ].
<p>

              So I'm here today to tell you that I'm
   trying to recruit new members to help dance with
   that bear so that we can all sit down.
<p>

              Thank you very much.
<p>

              [ STANDING OVATION ]
</blockquote>




