<HEAD>

<TITLE>Substantive Plenary IV</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><CENTER>Transcript of Substantive Plenary IV<br>
Separation of Church and State</CENTER></H1>
<blockquote>
<P>
MR. DORSEN: I think I should be prepared to say something witty
about the unexpected pleasure of seeing my old friends here after
so many years not on the podium. I will just say how pleased I
am to be back amongst you and to have an opportunity to participate
in this 75th anniversary biennial.
  <P>
 I am specifically pleased to have been asked to moderate this
particular panel, because it is the subject on which I have had
a long-standing interest, and as I understand it, each of the
moderators is asked to put the subject in some context.


<P>
And I would like to start with what I hope is not a quibble, and
that is, I don't think the title of Separation of Church and State
was the title that I would have chosen if I had looked over the
program in advance, the way I used to years ago.


<P>
The title should have been Religious Liberty, and that's for two
reasons. The first reason is that the First Amendment also protects
free expression of religion, and the ACLU has often supported
the rights of those whom the state has abridged.


<P>
Even more important, perhaps, it is essential that it be understood
that separation of church and state, also in the First Amendment,
is a means of protecting religious liberty by assuring that the
government does not improperly support one religion over another
or all religions over no religions. Separation of church and state
is not a technical concept, then, but one that goes deeply to
the safeguarding of liberty in this country.


<P>
Now, in trying to suggest a terse framework for this panel, my
mind rolled back to the 50th anniversary of the ACLU and specifically
The Book of Rights of Americans, in which there was an essay by
one of the great leaders in the church-state area, Dr. Leo Pfeffer,
and his first sentence in his essay in that book, written specifically
for the ACLU's 50th anniversary, was this: &quot;A fortuitous
combination of circumstances explains the launching of the experiment
expressed in 1787 in the promulgation for the new nation of a
secular constitution, limiting the powers and concerns of the
government to secular affairs, and reiterated four years later
in the Bill of Rights, whose opening words forbade the government
to establish religion or prohibit its free exercise.&quot;


<P>
Pfeffer, in his article, then proceeds to trace the generally
favorable trend of decisions, from 1940 to 1970, including the
cases in 1962 and 1963 that banned organized school prayer, and
the Everson case, in 1968, that struck down the law that prohibited
the teaching of Darwinian evolution. A few months after Pfeffer
wrote the essay, there was the Lemon case, which invalidated several
forms of government financial aid to religious schools.


<P>
Pfeffer also referred in his essay to the case in which the Supreme
Court held unconstitutional a Maryland law that barred from public
office persons who would not take an oath that they believed in
the existence of God.


<P>
Pfeffer then said the following: That decision, the one about
the oath to support the belief in God, coupled with the Seeger
decision, that decision held that conscientious objectors to the
Vietnam War could take the same privileges, even if they were
not religious, as religious conscientious objectors could, as
long as their philosophy bore the same relationship to their being
that religious people had with their philosophies.


<P>
Pfeffer then said that this would seem to point to a trend toward
equalization of religious and nonreligious conscience. Pfeffer
attributed this trend and indeed our secular society to several
causes, including the fact that many American colonists fled religious
persecution, to the ideas of The Enlightenment, notely John Locke
of England and Voltaire and others before the French Revolution,
and to the existence of a frontier in American life.


<P>
His article was upbeat, his article was optimistic. Well, that
was then and this is now, and since 1971, things have gone in
a very mixed way for us in the Supreme Court. Organized school
prayers are still unconstitutional, but a constitutional amendment
is pending which would reverse that. Moments of silence, sometimes
mere facades for religious prayer, are gaining acceptance. Religious
displays on public property, at Christmas and other times, have
been upheld. More forms of government dollars sent to religious
schools have been upheld.


<P>
More serious to us, I think, than the record in the courts is
the movement underground. It is fascinating to me, and unfortunate,
that in speaking of threats to the First Amendment in this area,
Leo Pfeffer referred to the Roman Catholic Church, he referred
to Orthodox Jews. He did not say one word about Fundamentalist
Protestants and Evangelical Protestants.


<P>
How things change. These groups, in combination with other extremists
and zealots are now well financed, well organized. Not only do
they threaten religious liberty directly by harnessing religion
and a particular form of religion to state power, but they rely
on religious premises, that is nonnational premises, to seek to
destroy reproductive rights, the rights of homosexuals, free expression
that does not meet their criteria, and most basically, the rights
of women, indeed, the very place of women in modern society.


<P>
What we are being threatened with, it is not an exaggeration to
say, is a religious party in the United States, as John Swomley
has frequently and eloquently cautioned us, a party that already
threatens the independence of the Republican Party in many states
and nationwide.


<P>
For these reasons, I can think of few issues, if any, that more
imperatively demand the resources and energy of the ACLU and the
people in this room. This unfortunately is the context for our
75th anniversary and the panel that follows.


<P>
What I would like to do now is just perform my moderating duties
very briefly. You heard the introduction of all these people,
all well qualified to speak to us today, and the first will be
John Siegenthaler.


<P>
(Applause.)


<P>
MR. SIEGENTHALER: Thank you very much. As I listened and the previous
panel finished, I was standing talking to a friend of mine from
Tennessee there at the edge of the platform, and he asked me where
I came in the order, and I told him I thought first, and as I
walked away, I heard him say to someone I did not know, having
John Siegenthaler follow Jocelyn Elders is like having Mother
Teresa followed by Tammy Faye Baker.


<P>
It's nice to be here today. As you may tell, I am a southern boy.
I hope I don't need a translator. Norman is not qualified to translate
southern. The last time I spoke before a group of the ACLU it
was in Alabama a few years ago. It was a smaller group.


<P>
Not long after we established the First Amendment Center at Vanderbilt
University, I received a telephone call from an irate woman who
had read in the newspapers about the creation of the center, and
she demanded to know, when are you people at that First Amendment
Center going to do something to get Rush Limbaugh off the air.
And I explained to her that -- I explained to her that getting
people off the air was not really our mission, and indeed, we
encouraged more voices, not fewer, and I suggested to her that
the best way to hush Rush was simply to turn off the knob on the
dial and she said, I did that already and I got G. Gordon Liddy.


<P>
When Ira Glasser asked me to come here today, I wondered about
the rationality of the invitation. After all, I come from the
state that is headquarters for several Protestant religious institutions,
some of them Fundamentalist. For three quarters of a century,
thanks to Menken, my state is known as The Buckle on the Bible
Belt.


<P>
It struck me there is sort of a symbolic logic involved here.
For one thing, this summer is a 75th anniversary of more than
the ACLU. I cannot say from the Tennessee perspective that it's
a celebration, as it is here. 75 years ago we in Tennessee had
the Scopes trial in which a public school teacher was prosecuted
because the lame-brained legislature in my state had insisted
that the children be taught they had fallen from angels, rather
than elevated from apes.


<P>
For another reason, as I look at politics today at both the federal
and the state levels, the words that flow from the lips of our
most dominant politicans send, I think, a clear signal that much
of our entire country now is girded by the mentality of the Bible
Belt.


<P>
The Buckle reflects much of the current commercial and cultural
life of the nation's geography as well as its politics. Even as
we sit here, that Bible Belt mentality threatens to deny -- by
this time today, it may already have denied -- a qualified professional,
a decent man of Christian conviction, a product of the Bible Belt
region, his chance to serve as Surgeon General of the United States
to succeed an eloquent and effective Surgeon General denied her
opportunity to serve for many of the same reasons. Truth flowed
from the lips of Senator Phil Gramm yesterday when he said, yes,
this is about abortion.


<P>
It's interesting to me that the Senate can listen to the truth
from the lips of Phil Gramm but not from Jocelyn Elders. This,
he said, is about abortion, not abortion alone. He is right again.
Not about abortion alone. It's about other things. For one important
thing, it's about racism. To deny him this opportunity to serve
seriously plays, I suggest, to the most racist instincts of our
society.


<P>
The Bible Belt Buckle mentality of which I speak is expressed
most often, I think, in the religion of those who believe it is
a sin, the law of the land notwithstanding, a violation of moral
law, murder, for a woman to choose to have an abortion. That mentality
permeates the media, and if you pay attention -- and I know many
of you don't bother to pay attention to this -- you will find
that there is more than Rush and Liddy on the dial. There is Robertson
and Robertson and Falwell and Ainsley and Swaggart and others.
I say of those, like the organ at Winchester Cathedral, it is
audible at five miles, punishing at three, lethal at one.


<P>
But that mentality, it seems to me, saturates much of our society,
threatens basic values. It labels those who believe, as I said,
in a woman's choice as sinners, and it labels those who support
the arts of corrupting the minds of the young. It labels those
who support public broadcasting as promoters of the obscene. It
labels those who are homosexuals as sick sinners, and I tell you
what I think is sick and sinful, it is to accept the courage and
commitment and skill of those homosexuals in the military but
deny them their constitutional right to say succinctly and candidly,
I am what I am.


<P>
The know-nothing mentality of the 1850s is alive and well in the
1990s, in the military, and that same mentality, that same Buckle
and Bible Belt mentality labels those who support separation of
church and state as a vital, precious part to our national heritage
as traitors to that national religious heritage, enemies of our
religious liberty. The Buckle on the Bible Belt mentality is exemplified
by those who say that if you agree with Tom Paine, who said my
church is my own mind, you are a heretic. It says that you betray
your nation's values.


<P>
I think it says something about the failure of our educational
institutions over these several decades, and particularly the
last two decades, to understand about our religious heritage.
I think in a very distinct way that failure to reflect what our
religious heritage is about in the public schools has contributed
to this mentality.


<P>
You, with the American Civil Liberties Union do not need for some
Bible Belt yokel to come here and tell you on this 75th anniversary
what you already know, that the legacy of Roger Williams is in
jeopardy, the legacy of George Mason is in danger, the legacy
of Jefferson is threatened, the legacy of the First Amendment,
meaning the very definition of separation of church and state,
are all at serious risk.


<P>
The school prayer amendment, among others, embraced by a mentality
of the Bible Belt, has put our nation in a political stranglehold,
and the hinge on that has swung too far in one direction so it
has the potential of uprooting values planted in our culture two
centuries ago and more. It shows no sign of moving back toward
the center.


<P>
You of the ACLU know better than I what's transpired. It is not
just one senator, mine, from Tennessee, who voted yesterday against
a good man and for the Bible Belt mentality. There are others
in states far removed from Tennessee, as most of you know, who
cast that vote documenting that the Bible Belt mentality has shown
itself to be elastic enough to stretch and embrace us all.


<P>
You know better than I that for 12 years, those who wear that
belt and brandish the buckle sought to stack the Supreme Court
of the United States, and failing that, they intensified their
efforts last election to impose their will and their way in order
to have a school prayer amendment, and other amendments that threaten
to shred the First Amendment.


<P>
Are these the ruminations, mournings of the southern cynic who
smells the flowers and looks for the coffin? I don't think so.
Don't wait for judgment day, it comes every day, and I think I
saw the hearse go by the last time I went to vote. I think I heard
the funeral dirge in that election every time there was a debate
or failed to be a debate, because it seemed to me that those men
and women I had long respected in politics ran from the field,
and many who supported them took their reelection for granted.


<P>
It seems to me that success came that day, that judgment day,
that judgment day that affects us still, because those of the
Bible Belt mentality believed in themselves, better knew their
values, better understood what was important to them, were willing
to work, vote, speak, and give their money to back those values
in which they believed.


<P>
What I find shocking is that they virtually had the field of battle
in the culture war and have it still, I think, to themselves.
As one interested in promoting principles and values embodied
in the 45 words of the First Amendment, I see little indication
that the debate has been joined yet, and as a result, I think
the First Amendment values, particularly those embodying the separation
of church and state, are indeed in jeopardy, endangered, threatened,
and at risk.


<P>
I saw those candidates pay for commercials that were vapid, weak
echoes of their opponents, that endorsed school prayer, that attacked
laws and Supreme Court decisions that assured religious liberty,
freedom of conscience, freedom of choice, freedom of speech. Those
commercials paid for by candidates many of us had supported for
many years, but politics prevail over principle.


<P>
Eleanor Roosevelt once said those who stand for nothing stand
to lose everything, even their self-esteem, and it occurs to me,
sadly, that that last judgment day, many of them lost their self-esteem.
I suspect that political scientists who will review the events
of what happened in politics on that day, or what's going on in
this country right now, will look back on that campaign and find
that indeed the winning side was more highly motivated, more involved
in the struggle, more committed to their ideals, more intent on
victory than those who failed to join them in debate.


<P>
It's been said that a cult is a religious group not large enough
to be called a minority. A decade ago we ignored those from the
Bible Belt who were railing against the Supreme Court's decision
separating church and state. We called them a cult. Five years
ago they became a minority and now their voices quite often represent
the majority in our Congress.


<P>
How did they gain those converts? It's a strain of puritanism,
and you know the definition of a puritan: One who lives with the
haunting fear that someone somewhere may be having a happy and
enjoyable life.


<P>
Was that streak so broad, its appeal so magnetic? I think not.
I think there are many of us who were lulled into a sense of false
security by those very Supreme Court opinions that repeatedly
held that God was in his heaven and all was right with the world,
or perhaps there was no God in heaven anywhere but there was nothing
to worry about. But there was something to worry about because
there were millions and millions of people in this country who
did not agree with the impact and the effect and result of those
opinions, and gradually, the appeal of the Bible Belt mentality
found them, caught them up, led them on.


<P>
I think they are still ambivalent, still questioning, still in
doubt, particularly as they see mentality now expressed in ways
that they don't agree with, that do concern them, that do seem
extremist, and still the question is, have we at the other side
joined the debate.


<P>
I don't want to say more than a good old boy needs to to people
who know most of what he thinks and perhaps what he feels, but
I do worry that our failure to have a system of public education
that includes as part of its history the religious heritage of
the country is one that betrays the founders as much as if we
were pushing for the teaching of religion rather than about religion
in the schools.


<P>
I know there are those here who feel the American Civil Liberties
Union need not bother much about my concerns about public education
and whether it needs a dramatic change so that we can teach our
children about the sacrifice of Roger Williams, who was banished,
about the sacrifice of the first Jews who came to this country
and were exiled by Peter Stuyvesant from New Amsterdam and the
second wave welcomed to Rhode Island by Roger Williams, or about
the fact that John Adams wrote early in the days of this country
that it was impossible for a free society to exist in a state
where Roman Catholics were citizens.


<P>
We have had religious persecution in this country from the beginning,
with the native Americans, then the Mormons, and then the Jews
and the Catholics, many Protestant sects, and now many from Islam
suffer from it. Our children need to know about it and to make
judgments about it and to have it ingrained once more in their
lives. But again, as I say, the ACLU knows that. When I think
of the ACLU on this 75 anniversary, I think of the words of Frost.
In the heart of man is an adolescent free to go with the drift
of things.


<P>
It has never been that the ACLU went with the drift of things.
It has always been true to the heart of man and woman in this
country, true to the soul of this society. For that reason, I
am proud to be here today to talk about the threat of the Bible
Belt mentality which threatens the separation of church and state.
Thank you very much.


<P>
MR. DORSEN: Thanks very much, John. You will have a hard time
convincing people that you are just a little old country boy.


<P>
Now I would like to introduce Reverend Giddings-Ivory.


<P>
REVEREND GIDDINGS-IVORY: Good afternoon. I was asked to say, to
have a few comments after the presentation you just heard, and
excuse me, I am just getting over bronchitis, so I will really
be brief.


<P>
What I would really like to do is to share with you from the point
of view of where the churches are on these issues. We have been
working very hard on the church-state religious liberty issues
over the years, and particularly these last few years in Washington.


<P>
As we go through the halls of Congress and speak to members of
Congress, I was taken aback not too long ago when a member of
Congress asked me, what is the difference between the Presbyterian
Church and the Christian Coalition.


<P>
It caught me off guard for a moment until I realized that many
of them may not really understand the difference, and many of
the people who write our newspaper stories may not understand
the difference.


<P>
But one of the things I have begun to say is that the historic
churches in the country, like the Baptists, Lutherans, Methodists,
the Church of the Brethren and the United Church of Christ, have
a history of trying to protect religious liberty because of the
persecutions they suffered when they came to this country, and
that is very keenly a memory for many of us.


<P>
The Christian Coalition, I tell people, may have the fringe elements
of those of us who are of those denominations I just mentioned,
but the Christian Coalition is not a denomination, they do not
fit the criteria of a denomination. They do not ordain clergy,
they do not teach Bible class, nor do they have congregations,
so that is something you want to remember, if you ever encounter
this in going out to various groups.


<P>
I have with me here a statement that we have in the Presbyterian
Church that was written in 1988. It is our major religious liberty
document, and it is entitled &quot;God Alone is Lord of the Conscience&quot;
and it has various issues related to the overall topic. I would
just like to read to you briefly what that title means so you
get some indication of where we are as religious groups.


<P>
That God alone is lord of the conscience and has left it free
from the doctrines and commandments of men which are in anything
contrary to God's word in matters of faith or worship. Therefore,
we consider the right of private judgment in all matters that
respect religion as universal and inalienable. We do not even
wish to see any religious institution aided by the civil power
further than may be necessary for protection and security, and
at the same time be equal and common to all others.


<P>
I think that sets the stage or the platform or the foundation
for where we are as religious groups, wanting to protect the right
of those of us who do practice faith, who do deal with spiritual
petitions as opposed to legal petitions, how we would like to
be sure that these things are protected.


<P>
The headings that we have in this document have to do with the
conduct motivated by conscience, and under that category, we would
include military service and other civic duties, conscientious
objection and civil disobedience, the freedom to choose medical
treatment or faith healing, conditions of employment, Sabbath
observance nondiscrimination, whether a person has the right to
declare having a day off from work that is that person's Sabbath;
use of illegal drugs for religious purposes, and we all know of
that as the Peyote case, as happened over the last few years,
leading to the Religious Restoration Act.


<P>
Sanctuary for political activities. The Presbyterian Church in
particular is concerned about this in that one of our congregations
in Arizona, during the Central American refugee movement was caught
up in that, in having been infiltrated by federal entities actually
coming into Bible classes and recording prayers people were conducting
as that congregation participated in the sanctuary movement, and
we dusted that policy off recently for the counter-terrorism legislation
that was going through Washington.


<P>
We are deeply involved in government and education as it relates
to the voucher systems and tuition tax credits and not wanting
public money going to private, sectarian institutions and, of
course, we are always involved in the taxation and possible taxation
of churches and religious property.


<P>
When I worked in New York State for the New York State Council
of Churches, one of the major issues was religious conversion
or the guardianship of the individuals who are pulled into so-called
cults, and one thing that kind of dropped off of my bio for some
reason is that I did serve on the New York Civil Liberties Board
for about a year before I moved from New York to Washington, D.C.,
so I did work in some of your circles. So we are concerned about
religious expression in public places, so that it is not imposed
on other persons.


<P>
One of the things I like to share with people, especially when
we are talking about prayer in school, and that's one of the issues
we are called on a lot to deal with, and I try to explain to Congress,
or members of Congress, that even having a moment of silence is
imposing a particular religious tradition on an individual, and
we don't all have agreement about that within our religious community
as to whether a moment of silence is or is not appropriate.


<P>
But it seems to me that if your religious tradition says that
you have to chant or speak as you are in a spiritual petition
with God, as you understand God, to impose a moment of silence
on that individual is imposing a form of prayer.


<P>
I also try to remind them that even those of us who are so-called
or within the Protestant groups don't all pray alike either. Some
of us who are in the Catholic tradition or Pentecostal tradition,
when we pray, we stand. Those of us who are Episcopalians, when
they say prayers, they kneel. I would like to say most of us who
are Presbyterian, and others, we bow our heads or hold our noses.
So we cannot all be forced into one mode of prayer.


<P>
And it sounds strange, as we all, as people hear me get up as
a member of the clergy, a member of a faith group, speaking against
prayer, but we are not speaking against prayer. We all know the
Equal Access Law in 1980 allowed everyone to form their groups
and they can form a Bible study group. What we are concerned about
is state-sponsored prayer, and that's why we are continuing to
work very hard on that.


<P>
I have not watched the clock, I am probably very close to seven
minutes, so I will stop at this point and then will be available
to answer questions. Thank you.


<P>
MR. DORSEN: The next speaker will be Ruti Teitel.


<P>
MS. TEITEL: I am pleased to be here and I want to add just to
the introduction that I feel very much at home. I have served
on the ACLU Church-State Committee for a number of years now,
as well as, together with Nadine, my colleague, at the NYU Law
School.


<P>
Norman began by talking about the movement concerning religious
liberty being on the ground and I couldn't agree more. My task
is to sort of set out a little of the legal framework, so let
me just start with a recent anecdote.


<P>
Nadine Strossen and I recently were part of a debate at William
and Mary Law School with Pat Robertson on the subject of religion
in the public schools, and he began his address, which was ostensibly
about religion in the public schools, by talking about a rape
of a woman in New Bedford by a gang of men, teenagers, and he
talked in agonizing detail about this rape, and as I was feeling
more and more sick, I thought, when is the segueway going to come
to religion in the public schools, what is the rape analogy, and
he seemed, after about 10 minutes of discussing this rape, he
then said, as bad as this rape was -- this is Reverend Robertson
-- as bad as this rape was, this is nothing compared to the rape
of America, of its constitutional traditional by the liberals,
public interest lawyers and law professors. And that's us, right?


<P>
And he went on from there to say that the constitutional tradition,
the vitality of religion, he described, at the founding has essentially
been stolen, had been raped by this group, this cabal of public
interest lawyers and others, and at William and Mary Law School
-- this is the troubling part, even more troubling than his talk
-- Reverend Robertson was thanked for an inspiring address.


<P>
This is not an infrequent event. Robertson and the Christian Coalition
have been engaging in this sort of fighting words, and this is
fighting words, despite the fact that it is coming from a religious
tradition, and the analogies, and the terms are that we are in
the midst of a culture war, we are in the midst of a Civil War,
and it is we versus they, and this is the language of the Contract
with America, and that is that the religious freedom issue is
something that has been taken away from Americans, from the individual,
from the private citizen by government and it's time to give it
back to you. Essentially that citizens in this country have been
raped by us.


<P>
I want to talk about the elective developments, the movement on
the ground and then say something about the case law. Although
I think the case law is very much related to the elective initiative,
it is by no means where all the action is right now.


<P>
The proposed constitutional amendment that is part of the Contract
with America continues in this theme, and the theme is that religion
is beleaguered, in fact there is hostility against religion, and
this is due to the federal and state government. This is just
a counterpart to the Contract with America, because the Contract
with America was that economic issues have been taken away from
you by big government, just as the Republicans have been favoring
and sponsoring the balanced budget amendment, the line item veto
and have had no hesitation to alter a constitutional arrangement
that has existed for 200 years plus. The same restructuring of
federal-state relations over the economy is reflected in the church-state
area.


<P>
Now, here is why we do need to think about church-state relations,
not just individual liberty, because the way the Contract with
America reads and Contract with the Family reads, we are in the
midst of a massive constitutional transformation which would set
us back from the present balance of power, federal-state, to a
different arrangement, and the proposed constitutional amendment
reads like the Contract with America in the sense that it says
that neither the United States nor the state shall abridge --
and they talk about freedom of a person or a group -- in a way
that would discriminate on the basis of religion, all of which
sounds very nice and uses equality of access language.


<P>
It then goes on to say nothing in the constitution should deprive
individuals of public or ceremonial accommodation, meaning that
there should be much more religion in the public sphere.


<P>
What I would like to do is talk about these three parts of the
program of this political manifesto and then show how these three
parts connect up with the developments in the case law.


<P>
The idea that in some way constitutional tradition in this country
has turned its back on the individual is very insidious and there
are three claims that are made or three agendas. One concerns
religion in the public schools, religion for children, and this
has been an area of enormous struggle, and it's probably the central
area of debate concerning religion in this country, and it is
about the values of the future, future values in America.


<P>
Why do we care so much about what goes on in the public schools?
It's the future. That's why they call it a Civil War. It is a
war about the future values of America, so it is very important
what goes on in the public schools.


<P>
The second part of the program concerns funding and here there
is a debate, of course, about to what extent religious schools
and other religious organizations can be beneficiaries, like other
nonreligious organizations, of funding, government funding, state
funding. Call it benefits, call it parochia, that is the second
part of the change.


<P>
The third part is even broader, that is all forms of religion
in public life. This goes way beyond the question of church-state
relations, and it is about having more religion in public life.


<P>
The second part of the constitutional drive talked about ceremonial
religion, about public officials being engaged in religious practices.
It's about having prayer before government meetings, it is about
religious displays in City Hall, in front of courthouses and so
forth.


<P>
Now, in these three parts, the claim is that religion has been
discriminated against in these three areas and that religion is
sort of a stepchild in this country, that it is beleaguered, that
there is a hostility, in sharp contrast to the presentation we
just heard about the vitality of the Presbyterian Church and about
the vitality of churches in this country, which is ironically
reflected by the political activities we have seen the Christian
Coalition able to engage in. But the claim is just the reverse,
that somehow religion is suffering in this country and we need
a constitutional amendment and other changes in the courts to
bring that to an equal status with other nonreligious secular
philosophies and secular values.


<P>
Now, one part of this claim is clearly false, you know, and this
debate is part of a very big PR drive and I am happy to say the
ACLU has taken a very affirmative stance, I have seen ads in The
New York Times the ACLU has taken out, trying to correct the errors
and statements of the Christian Coalition, so that part, there
is a part that is clearly falling, and I will talk about the state
of the law and the way individual liberty and expression is covered
in schools and elsewhere.


<P>
There is another part, however, that raises a broader issue for
us and I want to touch upon that in discussing the cases, and
that is the question of to what extent religion should be treated
in the exact same way as secular philosophies and secular organizations
that are not churches, and that is a broader debate, something
being discussed at every level and it is an issue that all of
this political activity raises.


<P>
Let me talk about both aspects, both the question of what is the
existing status of religion and the legal protection, and what
about this country, to what extent should religion be treated
differently both in constitutional law and in our political life.


<P>
On the three points, religion in the public schools, parochia
and religion in public life, let me just say something about each
of them just briefly, concerning religion in the public schools,
and you will see a lot of discussion about this in political debate
today, there is separation of church and state still.


<P>
The Supreme Court had ruled in the 1960s that there couldn't be
teacher-led school organized prayer. Now, having said that, okay,
and you have to pay attention to every part of that sentence,
there is a lot of other alternative prayer and individual prayer
in the schools. For one thing, the Supreme Court has not unambiguously
ruled out moments of silence. In a case that followed the school
prayer case, the court said that moments of silence might be constitutional
so long as they weren't intended to be allowing school prayer,
that they were not intended to be prayer. There has been a lot
of development concerning moments of silence, about 20 states
in the country have moments of silence laws, allowing the students
moments of silence.


<P>
Now, in addition to that, there is a whole other area of school
prayer development, and that is although the Supreme Court said
there couldn't be school-sponsored school prayer, the developments
-- and this is certainly something that the Christian Coalition
has been spearheading, the development has been in the area of
student-initiated school prayer, quote, unquote, student initiated,
because what we are seeing is whether the schools and state individuals
can delegate the decision over school prayer to private individuals,
and to what extent does this then become private prayer.


<P>
This is a very big question all over both the elective initiatives
and in the case law, and what we have seen is there is a big debate
about this question, and just to give you an example, there are
two Circuit Court decisions, each of which has held in the opposite
way concerning student initiated graduation prayer, and that's
where this debate has been most vigorous, is whether student initiated
graduation prayer is constitutional. That has yet to be decided
by the Supreme Court because the case that the Supreme Court did
decide was not one initiated by the students, but rather led by
an outside rabbi.


<P>
Now, this debate about student initiation was one that the ACLU
was part of and it grows out of the last time that a serious constitutional
amendment initiative was initiated in Congress, and that was in
1984, and even though we won that struggle in the sense that there
isn't a constitutional amendment that would override the Supreme
Court's decisions in the 1960s, we did end up with the first federal
law protecting school prayer and which ended up encouraging all
of this development at the high school and junior high school
level all over the country, and that was the Equal Access Act
which followed that initiative that began in 1984.


<P>
Now let me turn to the second area of development and area of
case law, which is the question of funding and benefits, and here,
as Norman reminded us, in the 1970s, Lemon v. Kurtzman, one word
that people remember about church-state relations, it's the Lemon
test, and that seems that it should be, that separation of church
and state went all the way back to the founders, that there shouldn't
be funding for religious education, and that is certainly an area
where the United States has been unique, almost unique, in modern
democracies.


<P>
Recent developments suggest a movement away from this, and recent
cases in the Supreme Court have said that if it isn't just religious
schools that are being benefited, but other nonreligious beneficiaries,
that it would uphold such as constitutional.


<P>
That means to me if there ever were a serious voucher drive, the
Supreme Court would uphold vouchers without a doubt and we would
see a very big change in the area of funding for religious education.


<P>
There is a case we are all watching. The Supreme Court is going
to decide Rosenberger in the next couple of weeks and that is
a case concerning funding at the university level for a student
club that produces a religious publication, and that will be a
mini case that will give us some sense of the direction of which
way the wind is blowing in the Supreme Court concerning religious
funding.


<P>
There is one other development I think is very interesting in
the area of funding and then I will move quickly to religion in
public life, and that is that the legal arm of the Christian Coalition
has dared to change the 501(C)3 limits on politicking by church
groups and other religious organizations. They are defending Ralph
Reed's church which has been sued by the IRS for putting up an
ad against Clinton which was clearly political activity.


<P>
Now, if the 501(C)3 protections go by the wayside, I think we
are seeing a completely different, a completely different legal
framework for churches in this country and really, I would say
a major shift in church-state relations.


<P>
Let me end lastly with the area of ceremonial religion and religion
in public life, religion in politics, and that is that we have
seen the Supreme Court all over the map on this issue. On the
one hand, the Supreme Court had said that prayers in the legislature,
prayers in state legislatures is constitutional. On the other
hand, the court says that prayer at graduations raises establishment
clause issues and protecting children from the broader role of
religion in public life.


<P>
But there is a much broader question still, which is that the
movement now in this country, it suggests, the rhetoric suggests
that religion is somehow hidden, it is private, and that's what
the liberals have favored and it is time to get religion out in
the public square. They talk about the naked public square and
we are seeing a lot of case law and discussion about religious
symbols and crosses, and there is a case pending in the Supreme
Court which will soon get a decision on, on a KKK cross right
in front of the Ohio statehouse.


<P>
Now, these cases are difficult and I don't want to minimize the
complexity, because in many instances, for instance, the cross
in front of the statehouse, in involves what many consider traditionally
a public forum. However, the lines between private and public
in this age of technology have become blurry. A park right next
to a statehouse gains the legitimacy, a cross right in front of
the statehouse gains the legitimacy of the statehouse. That's
why the KKK are right there in front of the statehouse.


<P>
I think it is time to address those areas of ambiguity and it
is time for us to think about better explaining why there needs
to be special treatment for religion and that it's not an answer
to simply assert that religious equality will benefit from the
exact same constitutional traditions and structure as apply to
secular and political organizations.


<P>
I think that it is time for the ACLU and for others, for all of
us to go back and to explain better in what way the founders struggled
with this issue and ultimately came down on the side of individual
religious liberty being better protected by not having state religion
or anything like it.


<P>
And we also have to explain that religious diversity and religious
practice are healthy and very vital in this country. That was
true at the time that de Tocqueville wrote, and it is obviously
very true today, and that this is because of the separation of
church and state and not despite it.


<P>
I would be happy to answer questions but my time is up. Thanks.


<P>
(Applause.)


<P>
MR. DORSEN: Thank you Ruti. One way we are going to disappoint
you is that you will not be able to answer questions, nor will
the other panelists, because there will not be time for questions
since both our panel and the previous panel, I am advised by the
highest sources imaginable, Barry Steinhardt, went overtime, so
we will just wind up with Steve Shapiro, who you all know.


<P>
Take it away.


<P>
MR. SHAPIRO: Well, I don't know if your family is like my family,
but in my family periodically we have these dinner parties, invite
the people over for dinner, and at the 11th hour decide we don't
have enough food to share with everybody. So we say FHB, meaning
family hold back. As a member of the family, at five to 4:00,
my role is to hold back here and simply stand up and say, I agree
with everything that's been said and send you off to your coffee,
and that is largely what I am going to do.


<P>
I promised Barry that I would speak for no more than three minutes,
which is a system I have developed in 20 years of being in the
ACLU, often having to follow Ira at the podium.


<P>
Let me just say three things, none of which are particularly connected.
It would be more eloquent if I had 15 minutes, but in three minutes
I will say three quick things.


<P>
One was that I had an interesting experience the other day, which
is I got a fax message, really unexpected. It just arrived at
my office the other day, it arrived without an explanation, and
what it was was an official proclamation by the governor of South
Carolina, official state stationery, with the seal on the top,
declaring the last week in May, I believe it was, to be March
for Jesus Week in South Carolina, and it was a four-paragraph
state proclamation that began by reciting from one of the apostles,
I forget which one, and ended up by calling on all people of faith
in South Carolina to march with Jesus.


<P>
One of the advantages of being in the national office is I get
to put this in a fax machine, send this down to South Carolina
and say, what are you doing about this, and I get back very, very
promptly an article from the, from one of the South Carolina newspapers,
with the headline that says &quot;ACLU Fumes.&quot; I thought
to myself, I am proud to belong to an organization that fumes.


<P>
The second sort of unrelated, a totally unrelated story, has to
do with the comment that Ruti made about school vouchers, and
it relates, in fact, to a comment that John Siegenthaler made
about public education, its relationship to religious education.


<P>
I think many of us, myself included, think that school vouchers
are really what the game is all about and that we are soon heading
toward a major legal battle over the constitutionality of school
vouchers, and I agree that it is going to be a difficult legal
battle, which was Ruti's assessment as well. I am not quite as
convinced -- I can't be, I couldn't do my job if I were quite
as convinced -- that it is a battle that we cannot win, but I
am sure that it is a battle that we will wage and there is, in
fact, a school voucher bill that is on the verge of being passed
in the State of Wisconsin, and the Wisconsin affiliate and the
national office, I hope, are already gearing up to challenge that
law, and so we will be there, and we will be in there fighting.


<P>
The last comment I want to make and then I will really send you
off to the coffee break, and this is what I was going to talk
about if we had more time, was what I see as a very difficult
issue in this area, of the ACLU. When we talk about school vouchers,
school prayer, those are difficult legal battles, and the lawyers
have troubles when they get into court because the Supreme Court
is not as sympathetic as it once was, but we know the arguments
we will make, how to frame them, we go in and do our best.


<P>
There is somewhat shifting terrain in this area, though, that
has to do with another legal development, and that is the religious
right, and not by coincidence the Supreme Court, in recent years,
I think, has discovered the free speech clause, and they have
discovered the free speech clause as a way to promote religion,
and they have increasingly begun to recharacterize what formerly
would have been religion claims as free speech claims. That is
what the graduation prayer cases are about, that is what the Klan
cross case is about that Ruti talked about, that is what the Rosenberger
case is all about, which has to do with funding from the state
university to support a religious student journal.


<P>
Those are the issues that put the ACLU in a much more difficult
position because, after all, we do generally believe in free speech
and we do generally take the position that the government cannot
discriminate against speakers based upon the viewpoint of their
speech, and it is not implausible when religion speakers come
in and say my religion is a viewpoint, and why can't I express
my viewpoint when others can express their viewpoint and isn't
that the type of hostility that the First Amendment is meant to
protect.


<P>
Within the context of the religion clauses, it is easy to say,
aha, there is an establishment clause, but as the ground has shifted
and it is increasingly being fought out in the grounds of the
free speech clause, it is still possible to say, aha, there is
an establishment clause. But the legal arguments get a little
more difficult, the policy arguments get a little more difficult
and it is frankly an issue that we as an organization are still
grappling with, trying to find out where the fault lines are and
find out exactly where the right position is.


<P>
I will tell you as a matter of information, if you don't know
this, the two cases Ruti talked about, the Klan cross case, and
the religious journal case at the University of Virginia, in the
Klan cross case, the national office supported the right of the
Klan to place their cross in the public park on the grounds that
a public forum was a public forum, this was a form of speech,
and in the case with the University of Virginia, we took the stand
is what the university could not fund the journal, even though
it was simultaneously funding secular journals, because funding
for religion was fundamentally different and funding for religion
that the establishment clause absolutely prohibited.


<P>
Both of the cases will be decided Monday or Wednesday of next
week. We will have a better sense of the way the Supreme Court
is heading, but I think from our own internal perspective, those
are issues that are going to continue to plague us in coming years.
We are going to have to think our way through some very knotty
problems, and having said that, I will now send everybody off
to the bar.


<P>
MR. DORSEN: We regret there is no time for questions but there
will be plenty of time for discussion later. Thank you very much.
</blockquote>


<P>




