<TITLE> Substantive Plenary VIII </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<blockquote>
<center><h1>Transcript of Substantive Plenary VII<br>
 Immigration and Xenophobia</center></h1>
              <STRONG>MS. RIPSTON:</STRONG>  Thank you, Wendy, and it's
   good to be here.  It is wonderful to be asked to
    sketch out the problems about zenophobia and
    immigration and then never really talk to anybody.
   This organization asks you to do something, and
    then nobody tells you exactly what to do.
<P>               In November of 1994, in a movement born
    of fiscal austerity and nativism, California voted
    three to two to deny undocumented people and their
   children education, health care and many other
   government benefits.  In the same election,
   Republicans gained control of Congress, after
   campaigning on the Contract with America's promise
   that more than $4 billion per year could be saved
   by barring legal immigrants from such programs as
   Medicaid, food stamps and welfare.
  <P>            Several years before these events,
   Arizona had passed an initiative barring employees
   in government offices, government agencies, from
   speaking any language other than English.
<P>              Both Proposition 187 and the Arizona
   initiative have not been implemented because of
   court orders, but the final fate of both is still
   up in the air.  Two of the most contested voting
   rights cases in recent years come from Los Angeles
    and Dade County, the counties leading the nation
    with the highest percentage of adult noncitizens.
    An important issue in each case is whether the
   principle of one person, one vote means local
    districts should contain equal number of persons,
  including citizens and noncitizens or only equal
   number of citizens.
<P>
              Excluding noncitizens from the local
   apportionment base means shifting the power away
   from areas with large populations of Latinos and
   other immigrant groups.  We won this issue then but
   can a move to exclude noncitizens from local
   apportionment bases be far behind now?  With the
   anti-immigration tide running higher than it has in
   decades, a prestigious federal commission headed by
   Barbara Jordan, who has generally been a friend of
   civil liberties and citizen rights, has called for
   a national identity card and a national employment
   registry.
<P>              Three weeks ago, the Bipartisan Federal
   Commission proposed that the United States slash
   legal immigration by one third and virtually close
   the nation's borders to extended family members of
   citizens.  The commission also suggested imposing a
   fee on employers who hire foreign professionals.
<P>
              The Judiciary Committee has decided that
   it is not enough to deny children education and
   health care, but that undocumented people should be
  punished just for actually being here in the United
   States.  In addition, they have suggested that
   there be a 14-mile wall between Mexico and the
   United States.
<P>              Immediately after the bombing of the
   federal building in Oklahoma, there was a rush to
   blame Arabs for that horrible deed.  No one even
   thought that possibly white males from middle
   America might be responsible.  Right after that,
   the counterterrorist bill passed the Senate.
<P>              Is there any doubt that America is in
   the throes of zenophobia and anti-immigration
   frenzy?  It is not the first time this has happened
   in our history.  In 1919 there were the infamous
   Palmer raids.  The ACLU was there then and we have
   been there throughout our 75-year history whenever
   there has been an attempt to subject vulnerable
   immigrants to a denial of civil liberties, and we
   must be there again.  In times of economic
   difficulty or fear about national security,
   newcomers become the scapegoat for our economic and
   political problems.
  <P>           We know that the story of prejudices
   about race has been permitted to substitute for
   genuine responses to social and political and
   economic problems.  We somehow have to help shape
   the debate to make people understand that
   immigration has been and remains vital to a growing
   economy, that immigrants contribute more to this
   community than they take out.  People must be made
   to understand that the impact of policies like
   those included in Prop. 187 on public health and
  safety, have a grave, grave effect on innocent
  people and children.  And above all, we must be
  unified in our commitment to respond affirmatively
  to the denial of rights to immigrants.
<P>              Yesterday at the session on racial
   equality, there was a plea from all three
   participants for unity.  So in closing, I would
   like to make that same plea.  That immigration and
   zenophobia become one of the very important issues
   to the American Civil Liberties Union.
<P>              I know that it affects some of us more
   than others, that some states have a higher number
   of people who are noncitizens than other states,
   but we have to talk about people, and this
   organization must be there and we must be unified
   about it.
<P>              You know, when we in Los Angeles wanted
   to reform the Los Angeles Police Department, we
    formed a coalition.  Most of the members of that
    coalition turned out to be African-Americans,
    because it was the Los Angeles Police Department
    which policed African-American neighborhoods.  When
    we turned our attention to the sheriff's department
    and we formed another coalition, we had mostly
   Latinos, because the sheriff's department polices
   mostly Latino neighborhoods.  When we put a 187
   coalition together, we mostly had Latinos.
              We must all come together on these
   problems.  We must fight together because
   otherwise, we will all be lost.
<P>
              Ira?
<P>
              <STRONG>MR. GLASSER:</STRONG>  This is Peter Brimlow's
   book.  I carry it with me all the time when I need
   a rush of adrenalin, and it works so well so I am
   always afraid I am going to be arrested for
   possession of an illegal drug.
<P>              This is Peter Brimlow's nightmare.  This
   shirt has "Children of the World" on it and I stole
   it from my wife this morning when she wasn't
   looking.  This is a picture of children from all
   over the world, different faces and colors and
   hairdos and clothes, and that issue of race, I
    think, as we hope to demonstrate, is really at the
    bottom of what the politics of this issue is about
    and why it is so core, so much of a core ACLU
    issue.
 <P>              Immigration is not, by itself, a civil
    liberties issue, and it ought not to be thought of
    as something marginal or something new.  As Ramona
   said, we have been involved in these issues from
   the very earliest years of the ACLU's history, and
   basically, what you have in the area of immigration
   are at least three core civil liberties issues, which
   are taking place in the context of immigration.
<P>              It is not that immigration is a civil
   liberties issue, it is that race is a civil
   liberties issue and discrimination on the basis of
   national origin is a civil liberties issue.  That
   would be a civil liberties issue whether it was
   taking place in the context of employment, in
   education, in the context of police abuse or in the
   context of immigration.
<P>              The First Amendment, is a core civil
   liberties issue and many of our core positions on
   political asylum flow from providing relief to
   victims of political persecution in their own
   countries.  That has been an issue we have been
    involved in from the very beginning, it is a core
    civil liberties issue that takes place in the
    context of immigration.  Due process is a core
    civil liberties issue and our concern for fair
    procedures in deportation hearings and in all sorts
    of procedures that relate to the determination of
    asyum status and things like that are core civil
   liberties concerns taking place in the context of
   immigration.
<P>              So it is a mistake, I think, to think of
   immigration as something new to the ACLU, as
   something marginal, as a kind of an add-on issue.
   It is simply a setting in which all of our core
   concerns are implicated.
<P>              Now, you know, that isn't always the way
   it is discussed in public, and I want to try to put
   aside some of the issues that often get talked
   about when this issue is debated.  This is not
   about numbers.  We have about a million immigrants
   a year coming into the country now, including
   illegals.  That's about the same amount that came
   in annually between 1901 and 1910, when the
   population was much smaller.  In 1910, when we had
   about a million immigrants a year, the population
   was 90 million.  We were looking at something like
   14, 15 percent of the population was foreign born
   at that time.
<P>              Today about 8 percent of the population
   is foreign-born and the million who are coming in
    each year are a million against a population of 250
    million.  The truth is, the numbers are not
    significant.  It is not difficult to absorb.  The
   fact that they are concentrated in a few places
   creates special problems, but certainly New York is
   one of the major areas of in-migration still, and
   it is nothing like it was in 1890, in 1905, and in
   1910.
<P>              The fact is the numbers are not a
   serious issue.  You can debate about whether it is
   800,000, 700,000, a million or one.  That is not
   really important to the issue.  It should not be
   taken seriously.
<P>              The skills are not an issue.  Julius
   Simon wrote the Economic Consequences of
   Immigration, a leading columnist, he publishes in
   places like The National Review, has said
   explicitly, that the level of skills, the level of
   education is going up, not down, in terms of the
   average of immigrants coming in, for the most part.
               The skill level is a marginal issue in
    some places, sometimes, for some people, but the
    skill level question is not a serious issue.  We
    would not be having a major divisive public debate
    about this problem if we were just talking about
    skill levels.
<P>            Economics is not an issue.  The effects
   are marginal.  There is very little doubt -- Simon
   again says that every time immigrant comes in,
   natives become richer, and every time we keep an
   immigrant from coming in, the natives become
   poorer.  By and large, the economic consequences
   are good and the wealth that immigrants produce
   over their lifetime is more than what immigrants
   cost over their lifetime.
<P>              There may be disconnects between what
   the federal government collects in taxes and what
   local governments bear in costs, but those kinds of
   issues are federal issues to be worked out not at
   the expense of immigrants, but between federal
   governments and state governments.
<P>              If New York and California, Texas and
   Florida need to have different kinds of
   income-sharing between the federal government and
   the state governments because of who collects the
   taxes and who pays for the cost of local services,
    that is an issue that needs to be addressed.  So
    economics is not an issue.
 <P>              If you look at the statistics of whether
    or not the taxes that immigrants produce are
    outweighed by the services and the benefits they
    get, the most anti-immigration economist calculates
    that $42 billion, that it is $42 billion more in
   costs than in taxes, and he is not counting Social
   Security taxes.  If he counts Social Security
   taxes, then it's a wash.
<P>              The range of economics, of economic
   estimates of whether taxes outweigh benefits or the
   other way around, range from about $25 million more
   taxes produced by immigrants than the cost of
   services to them, to $42 billion of more cost of
   services than taxes produce.  The whole range is
   trivial compared to $6 trillion of national income
   that this country realizes at this time.  It simply
   is not a serious issue, and even George Borhaus,
   the most anti-immigration economist, the one most
   often cited by our opponents said, "economic
   arguments simply are not decisive."  It is not a
   serious issue.
<P>              So what is a serious issue?  Welfare.
   Well, that is also not a serious issue.  Basically,
    immigrant families, by and large, use welfare at
    about the same rate, a little more or a little less
    from time to time, from place to place, not
    significantly different from the rate at which
    native families use welfare, and the welfare people
    I am talking about, ADC and food stamps, most
    immigrants are not even eligible for a period of
   three to five years.  The really large welfare
   programs, income tax programs, Social Security and
   Medicare, few of them get them, very few are
   elderly.  So that is not an issue.  What is?
<P>              What is, inescapably, is race and
   national origin.  This has always been the true
   American politics from the very beginning.  The
   notion that today that something different is going
   on, as Brimlow and others argue, because in the old
   days, the immigrants, they were the good
   immigrants, they came from what he calls a common
   European heritage.  Well, the common European
   heritage wasn't thought to be so common back when
   it mattered.  In 1835, there was a whole lot of
   writing about Catholics taking over America and
   being alien to the American tradition.  In 1856,
   almost every encyclopedia published made distinct
    racial categories among Swedes, Finns, Greeks,
    Hungarians, Russians, Jews, Irish, Germans.  They
   were all distinct races, they described them
    differently in the way they looked, the way they
    thought, what their generic heritage was.
 <P>              Around 1850, a leading book on
    immigration said, "while the rich Irish brogue and
    heavy German accent supplants the American idiom,
   while aliens scorn our laws or customs and our
   religion."  There was a great concern about
   bilingualism, though they didn't use that word.
<P>              In 1914, Slavs were regarded as
   nonwhites, people with, "crooked faces, coarse
   mouths, heavy jaws, and low foreheads."  What
   common European heritage?
<P>              In 1890, there were writings about the
   naturally violent Italian race.  In 1911 there was
   a federal commission that reported that new
   immigrants were less skilled, less educated, slower
   to learn English, not likely to be assimilated.  It
   wasn't true then, it isn't true now.
<P>              In 1924, following the Palmer raids,
   from which alien subversives were deported without
   trial, the view grew overwhelmingly that Eastern
   and Southern Europeans were a genetically inferior,
   culturally incompatible, not Anglo-Saxon, that
    would threaten, "the America as we know it."  So
    they passed the 1924 Act.  It was a racist act
    passed at a racist time.  It basically limited
    immigration to North and Western Europe or skewed
    the quotas to that.  Immigration plummeted, the
    source of immigration changed.
<P>               It was a racist act which was not
   changed until 1965 when another civil rights act
   was passed.  It was called the Immigration Act, but
   it was a civil rights act, passed at the peak of
   the civil rights movement, a year after the Civil
   Rights Act of '64, and the same year that the
  Voting Rights Act was passed, and it repealed all
   of the racial and national origin exclusion quotas
   of 1924, created quotas on a per-country basis
   without regard to nation or skin color or anything
   else.
<P>              That is the act that is driving the
   opposition today.  That is the act they hate and
   they hate it for the same reason that they hate
   affirmative action.  They hate it not because of
   the numbers of the people coming in but because of
   the sources of the numbers of people.  They hate it
   because they hate the skin color, the language, the
    style, the cultural incompatibility with dominant
    American life, which is to say white middle class
    American life.  When you get beneath all of the
    objections, that's what you are talking about.
 <P>              This guy Brimlow says it far better than
    I could, and if you want ammunition to support the
    racial basis for this argument, do yourself a favor
    and read this book, but not if you have high blood
   pressure.
<P>              The favor this book has done us is that
   he has come out of the closet.  Many of the
   immigrants, the anti-immigration forces, will deny
   all of that and they would like to talk about
   numbers, economics, and welfare and bilingualism.
<P>              It is all a smoke screen.  Those
   arguments need to be set aside because they are not
   significant.  What is significant is that this is a
   civil rights issue taking place in the context of
   immigration against people who are terribly
   vulnerable because they are not citizens.  It
   behooves us to do as we have always done and to be
   strong in our dense of people who are themselves
   defenseless on those grounds.  Thank you.
              (Applause.)
<P>
              <STRONG>MS. RIPSTON:</STRONG>  Valerie Small-Navaro, from
    California.<P>
               <STRONG>MS. SMALL-NAVARO:</STRONG>  First of all, I want
    to make sure that everyone can hear me.  Yes?
    Okay.  Very good.
<P>               Well, Lucas gave me the easy task, and
    that was to explain why the ACLU doesn't buy into
    the distinction between legal and illegal
    immigrants when it comes to fighting for their
   civil rights.  Before I actually get into this
   discussion, I want to make sure that everyone
   knows, if we don't already know, that the ACLU does
   not advocate for open borders.  Some of us
   privately might do so, but that is not the position
   of the ACLU.
<P>              Now, before I go out every morning into
   Sacramento to do my job as a lobbyist there, I take
   a quick look at something that's on my
   refrigerator, and that is a one-line letter from
   The Los Angeles Times.  That letter says -- and
   this happened at the height of Proposition 187 --
   who cost Orange County -- the county which is now
   in bankruptcy, as you probably all know -- more:
   A, undocumented immigrants, or, B, greedy white
   men?
<P>     
               Now, I am not saying this to sort of
    exacerbate the racial issues that Ira brought up
    but rather to try and contextualize some of this
    discussion, and I want to just quickly run through
    some of the facts on illegal immigration before I
    get into the discussion about why the ACLU doesn't
    buy into this distinction between illegal and legal
    immigrants.
<P>               Now, I guess that I want to think about
   politics.  As we all know, issues in the past have
   been very colorful.  I don't think, when we say the
   words welfare queen, we don't think about the white
   woman sitting at home with her mother.  That is not
   the image we come up with, right?  When we talk
   about Willie Horton, who are we talking about?
   When we are talking about illegal immigrants, who
   are we talking about?
<P>              I always ask myself, why is it that two
   guys from Kentucky and Wyoming, Mr. Mazoli and
   Mr. Simpson, have made their political careers
   based on the issue of illegal immigration, and I
   also ask myself who or whom, if I feel in that
   mood, whom do they blame in their states for the
   economic recession or for the recession of the
   country?  Who do they blame?
<P>    

               Let me just turn and give you some quick
    facts.  I know you are getting tired and this is
    the end of the whole biennial, but we are looking
    at 1.5 percent of the total population of this
    country is here illegally.  1. percent.  Now, does
    that justify a national ID card?  Does that justify
    Diane Feinstein wanting to put fingerprints or
    retinal scans on this national ID card?  No.
    Okay.  Thank you.
<P>              Now, if you ask me, it -- and this is
   something that someone else said, but it really
   rings home true.  This is like using an atomic bomb
   to kill a mosquito.  Why are we looking at national
   ID cards, national registry systems?
<P>              In California, where the problem is
   supposed to be so God-awful and we have supposedly
   42 percent of the undocumented, that only
   represents approximately 5 percent of our total
   population.  Now, is that a justification for
   Proposition 187, 5 percent of our total
   population?  Does that justify the "Son of
   Proposition 187," which happens to be a move to put
   an initiative on the ballot that would take away
   the right of children born in the United States to
   U.S. citizenship.  That was something given to us
 by the 14th Amendment.
<P>               To talk about race, I mean, we just have
    to look at why the 14th Amendment was put in
    place.
<P>               Now, the real problem -- and I sort of
    feel like deja vu.  When we talk about immigrants,
    illegal immigrants, it is sort of easy to dig our
    heels in on those issues, but what are the real
    problems?
<P>              I think that everyone knows that the
   country is in a recession, but what people don't
   know, for example, in California, that the state
   commission on finance said that in the fiscal year
   1993-1994, that revenues to the State of California
   would have been $13 billion, with a B, dollars
   higher, but for the recession, that our state and
   local revenues are declining as a percentage of our
   personal income taxes.  So from 1978 until 1990, we
   saw a 25 percent drop in that revenue.
<P>              So it's too easy to look at those brown
   and yellow and black hordes and blame our problems
   on them than looking and trying to address the real
   economic situation, and again, I ask you, who or
   whom are they blaming in Kentucky and Wyoming?
   It's a real big question.
<P>         

               I want to shift a little bit now and
    talk about refugees and Haitians in particular.
    All of the screaming in the newspapers about
    Haitian refugees.  How many people do you think we
    are talking about?  You would think we were talking
    about hundreds of thousands of people to come
    over.  It was 35,000 people.  I don't know how many
    pages of The New York Times, the LA Times, all of
    the newspapers out there took up on this issue.  It
   was 35,000 people.
<P>              So I think about -- I like to think
   about refugees in sort of a bigger context in the
   world.  The UN high commissioner for refugees has
   told us there are 18 million refugees out in the
   world, 18 million.  How many do you think we let
   into the country a year here in the United States?
<P>
   What portion of that 18 million do you think we
   could absorb reasonably?  Well, it's only 120,000,
   okay?  120,000 of a total population of 18
   million.
<P>              So just having given you a little bit of
   background on this issue, I wanted to turn now
   specifically to why the ACLU cannot fall into the
   same pattern as other civil rights organizations
   have when they start talking about, well, there is
    good immigrants and bad immigrants, ones that come
    here legally and ones that come here illegally, and
    I want to remind you that a boatload of Jews were
    turned away not only from one port but two ports
    when they came during World War II, that we
    experienced the internment of Americans,
    Japanese-Americans, here in the United States.
<P>            Unless we think the civil rights
    movement or the ACLU was above this, I want to
   remind you that it caused great consternation
   within the movement at large and within the ACLU
   when we decided to represent Mr. Koramatsu.  So
   please don't fall into the too easy thing, yeah, we
   support them.  It is a big question that the ACLU
   needs to look at, why we support illegal as well as
   legal immigrants, and I hate using that term.
   Undocumented is what we usually say, use that
   term.  But it is about basic human rights.  Basic
   human rights cannot be forsaken because of
   arbitrary human distinctions.
<P>              Until all of people in this country have
   the right to assert their rights as employees,
   rights as victims of crimes, rights to attend
   school, our streets, our working places, our
   schools, will not be safe for all Americans, all of
    us, all of the residents of this country, and I
    think that it's important that the ACLU take,
    continues to take the leadership position that it
    has always taken, but recognizing that we can't
    fall into this false dilemma.  Thank you.<P>
               <STRONG>(Applause.)</STRONG><P>
               <STRONG>MS. RIPSTON: </STRONG> Now Lucas Guttentag, from
    New York and California.<P>
              <STRONG> MR. GUTTENTAG:</STRONG>  Thank you very much.
   The threat to immigrants' rights right now is
   enormous, but that's nothing new, and it is not a
   lost cause.  We have seen this throughout our
   history, we have had spasms of anti-immigrant
   hysteria before and right now we are in the midst
   of a major challenge, and whenever immigrants are
   under attack, as I think Ira, Ramona and Valerie
   pointed out, whenever immigrants are under attack,
   that becomes a vehicle for those who oppose all
   kinds of individual liberties and civil rights.
<P>              That's their way, that's the way to get
   the foot in the door:  Attack the immigrants,
   because they are the ones most vulnerable, they are
   the ones with the smallest political voice, they
   are the ones with the fewest constitutional
   rights.
         
<P>
               But the very breadth of the attack is
    also the opportunity to mobilize other communities
    and other constituencies who don't always see
    immigration or immigrants' rights as an issue
    affecting them, but it is, because as we know, and
    as Ira said, and I think as everybody is beginning
    to see, immigration, attacks on immigrants is a
    vehicle for racism, but it is not just racism, it
    is homophobia, it's restrictions on free speech, it
   is a way to diminish the due process rights of
   people accused of crimes, it is a way to dilute the
   protections of the 4th Amendment, it is all those
   things.
<P>              Let me just give you one example of the
   racism front, and just these two headlines, one of
   which was just called to my attention this morning,
   and keep in mind that Canadians are the fourth
   largest undocumented population in the United
   States.  Here is one headline from a newspaper in
   Utah that ran shortly after the Immigration Service
   conducted a series of raids against employers in
   Utah.  What's the headline say?  It says, "Hiring
   Hispanics?  Watch out."
<P>              And then at the same time, while we were
   talking about building walls and ditches and
    militarizing our southern border to keep out
    Mexicans, here is the other headline, from The New
    York Times-Associated Press Wire Service on
    building express lanes into and out of Canada.  Is
    that a concern about immigration or is that a
    concern about the color of the skin of the persons
    who are coming?
<P>               And let's recall that until 1990,
    persons were denied visas solely because of their
   sexual orientation.  Under the law, homosexuality,
   as the law called it, was a form of mental disease
   or defect, and the basis for denying their visa,
   and today, being HIV-positive is a ground for
   denying protection to refugees, to people fleeing
   persecution, denying reunification of families, and
   it was the policy that caused the Clinton
   Administration, and the Bush Administration, to
   imprison over 300 Haitian refugees at an HIV prison
   camp at Guantanamo for over two years, until a
   courageous federal judge ordered them to be
   released.
<P>              Proposals in Congress call right now for
   deporting persons merely because of their
   membership in a group that the President or the
   Secretary of State designates as terrorist, even
    though that membership would be protected under the
    First Amendment, if it was a United States
    citizen.
<P>               Proposals in Congress to discriminate
    against naturalized citizens, as opposed to
    citizens born in the United States, eligibility for
    federal benefits, proposals in Congress that
    discriminate against legal permanent residents in
    state benefit programs, even though the Supreme
   Court held almost 20 years ago that that's a
   violation of equal protection and due process.
<P>              Proposals in Congress to deny birth
   right citizenship, as Valerie pointed out, to
   children because of the status of their parents,
   mothers.
<P>              Proposals to eliminate judicial review
   so that no court could review the acts of the
   Immigration Service, even though it is one of the
   most arbitrary, the most error-prone, and one of
   the most discriminatory agencies we have in the
   federal government, to prohibit any Federal Court
   from reviewing the actions of that agency.  That's
   what we are facing.
<P>              But as I said, I think there is reason
   for hope because these kinds of proposals always
    occur when the population of the immigrants
    changes, when the people are perceived as different
    from those who came before, when the economy is
    bad, when we are afraid, when people are afraid of
    conditions in our own country.
<P>               I think, quite frankly, that most of the
    anti-immigrant hysteria, if you will, is coming
    from two places: Washington, D.C., and the State of
    California.  It is being used and exploited by
   politicans, by Governor Wilson to resurrect his
   gubernatorial campaign, now by Senator Diane
   Feinstein, and others.
<P>              And it is a good question.  Why is
   Senator Simpson, from Wyoming, the most powerful
   politician about immigration in the United States?
   Wyoming is a place that has fewer immigrants in its
   entire state than work in a single hospital or
   hotel or day care center in the City of New York or
   Los Angeles or Chicago, or most other major cities
   in this country.  He can do it but he shouldn't be
   able to, to run these kind of anti-immigrant
   campaigns, to propose these kinds of anti-immigrant
   restrictions.  But they can do it because
   immigrants do not have a political voice and too
   often others don't realize what is at stake, other
    groups, other constituencies.  But when they do,
    the dynamic changes, and I think the most striking
    recent example of that is our policy towards
    Haitian refugees, because three administrations,
    the Reagan Administration, the Bush Administration,
    and the Clinton Administration, were forcibly
    repatriating Haitian refugees to what was one of
    the worst human rights abusers in the world, in
    violation of U.S. and international law.
<P>              We fought the case in the Supreme Court
   and we lost, the Supreme Court disagreed with us
   about U.S. law and the impact and force of
   international law.  But when Randall Robinson and
   the Congressional Black Caucus took up the cause
   and called that policy what it was, namely racist,
   that policy changed.  And right now, we have a
   refugee policy that admits about 125,000 people per
   year, although there are proposals to cut that
   down, but of that 125,000 refugees that we have
   been letting in each year, how many do we admit
   from Africa?  7,000 out of 125,000.  How many do we
   admit from Latin America?  3,500 out of 125,000,
   and I think if the Congressional Black Caucus,
   Hispanic Caucus and other civil rights
   organizations looked at that and saw those kinds of
    policies, those too would change.
<P>               Now we have some interesting allies on
    the immigration issue.  Sometimes they are unusual,
    sometimes they are even bizarre.  The majority
    leader, Dick Armey, has been criticized in his own
    party for the position that others have proposed
    for immigration restrictions.  William Bennett and
    Jack Kemp oppose Proposition 187 in California, and
    they don't believe in blaming immigrants for the
   problems that are going on.  Mayor Giuliani, a
   Republican and Governor Cuomo, until recently the
   Governor of New York, said that all immigrants,
   legal and illegal immigrants, were welcome in New
   York City and New York State because they saw them
   as a strength, part of what makes New York City and
   New York State great.  On the national I.D. card,
   the Cato Institute, William Crystal, Phyllis
   Schaffley, Gary Bauer, Milton Friedman, they have
   all criticized the proposal and said, you are
   right, but this is the wrong way, this is the wrong
   route to go.
<P>              And I think one other thing happened in
   the 187 campaign in California.  We saw that, the
   opposition to that proposal, to that proposition,
   mobilize an entirely new population of students.
<P>         

    They got mobilized, activated, they saw Proposition
    187 for what it was, a racist attack on certain
    communities, and I don't know how many times I have
    heard people say from California, we don't care if
    they are legal or illegal, the problem in
    California is there are too many Mexicans.  That
    was what people said.  That's what's been going
    on.
<P>               The new generation of students got
   active, got involved, got mobilized, and they
   started getting active because of opposition to
   Proposition 187.  That is another opportunity we
   have as a result of what is a going on, through
   immigration.
<P>              There are a lot of states in which
   immigration is not yet the political hot potato
   that it is.  I think one of the critical things is
   that if you live in one of those states, yours are
   the members of Congress that we can get to.  Yours
   are the ones we can reach out to.  They are not the
   ones facing the kind of hostility that is rampant
   in California and a few other places.  There is an
   opportunity there to say to members of Congress
   from those states like Wyoming and others, we don't
   want those politicans jumping on this bandwagon, we
    don't want them pandering to the racist instincts
    that drive a lot of this, we don't want them
    attacking civil rights and civil liberties in the
    guise of immigration reform, as it is always
    called.
<P>               So I think we can take this threat that
    we have, and there is no doubt about it, but we can
    use it to build a broad coalition, and it is
    beginning to happen.  I think we have to work hard
   at it, but it is an opportunity, and I think that,
   just in closing, I think it is always useful,
   though, perhaps somewhat hackneyed, to remind
   ourselves that today's immigrants, regardless of
   their status, are tomorrow's poets, sports heroes,
   Nobel laureates --
<P>              <STRONG>VOICE:</STRONG>  Civil libertarians.<P>
              <STRONG>MR. GUTTENTAG:</STRONG>  -- civil libertarians,
   that's right.  Every immigrant group that comes to
   this country changes this country and is, in turn,
   changed by the country, and the results of
   immigration we are experiencing now is something we
   should celebrate, not be afraid of.
<P>              Immigration is a dynamic process, it is
   ongoing, continuing, it is not an historical
   artifact we look back at and see it as happening
    sometime back in the past, and in common times, as
    a country, we always look back and everybody looks
    back and said, oh, it was wrong to intern the
    Japanese-Americans, it was wrong not to accept Jews
    fleeing the Holocaust, it was wrong to repatriate
    Haitian refugees, it was wrong to deport persons
    because of their political beliefs.  But it is
    always after the fact.
<P>               In the meantime, when the policies are
   ongoing and happening, we have done untold damage
   to people's, lives, constitutional principles and
   our values as a nation.
<P>              I think the challenge for each of us is
   to recognize these policies as they are occurring,
   not after the fact.  That's what the ACLU has been
   doing for 75 years, that's what we have to continue
   to do in every state, in every capital, and in
   every community throughout the country.  Thank
   you.
<P>             <STRONG> (Applause.)</STRONG><P>
              <STRONG>MS. RIPSTON</STRONG>:  Because everyone on this
   panel stayed within the allotted time given to each
   of us, we have time, we do have time, if there are
   any, for several questions.
<P>              <STRONG>VOICE:</STRONG>  Thank you very much to members
    of the panel.  I have to say at the outset, as a
    personal matter, as a matter of policy, I would
    accept open borders, so that is the spirit from
    which this question comes.
<P>               Valerie, I did not understand the civil
    liberties rationale for the ACLU opposing the
    distinction between legal and illegal immigrants,
    and it would be very helpful to me in my advocacy
    efforts if either you or Ira also emphasize that
   our advocacy has to be in the framework of civil
   liberties, if you could articulate that.
<P>             <STRONG> MS. SMALL-NAVARO:</STRONG>  I will give it a
   shot.  I think Ira did it best when he started his
   talk, and I think that it is that immigration is
   just the context within which we fight for civil
   liberties or that those civil liberties are being
   attacked.  So it's the First Amendment, when we
   throw people out of the country for having
   political opinions that we don't agree with.  You
   know, it's those kinds of things.  It is the
   context within which the civil liberties come up.
<P>              <STRONG>VOICE:</STRONG>  The fact that somebody has
   committed a crime would be relevant in the First
   Amendment analysis, wouldn't it?  I am asking you
   why we don't buy into the distinction between legal
    or illegal, or documented or undocumented.
<P>               <STRONG>MS. SMALL-NAVARO:</STRONG>  Maybe I should back
    up on immigration law, and I don't know if Ira
    wants to answer, but just jump in here.
<P>               Coming to the country illegally, when
 you are passing over the border, that's a crime.
    Once you are in this country, that is not a crime,
    that's a civil wrong.  That's why we don't have
    police officers enforcing our immigration laws.  It
   is a civil problem.  So why do I say undocumented
   people are entitled to civil liberties?  That is
   because I am taking the point of view that human
   rights are civil liberties, or maybe I should say
   that the other way around.  And that's why, I
   think, it's so important that we don't allow civil
   liberties of individuals to be addressed
   differently just because of their immigration
   status.
<P>              Does somebody want to take a stab at
   that?  That's how I look at it.  I don't know if I
   am articulating a greater vision, but that's what I
   am seeing.
<P>              <STRONG>MR. GUTTENTAG: </STRONG> Let me just add one
   thing to that, and that is, what we are talking
   about is the Constitution, and remember what the
    Constitution talks about is persons.  When we talk
    about defending civil liberties and civil rights,
    we are talking about persons, all persons,
    regardless of immigration status, and that is
    really the principle that is at issue here, if
    somebody because of their status can be made a
    nonperson under the law, and that's what a lot of
    these proposals talk about, to render a person less
    than a full person because of their immigration
   status.
<P>              Can they be deported if they are
   undocumented?  Of course they can.  There is a
   procedure for doing that.  But that procedure has
   to be fair, it has to be performed with due
   process, it cannot be discriminatory, when the
   Immigration Service arrests people, they have to
   comply with the same principle as any other
   agency.  These are the constitutional principles
   that are no different.  The fact that a person is
   at the border of the United States should not allow
   Congress to say, therefore, they are not here,
   technically, and we can do anything we want with
   them.  We have had people in jails and prisons in
   this country for over 10 years because they are
   treated as nonpersons under the law, because the
    Supreme Court has said, well, they were arrested
    when they arrived, and they have never entered, so
    therefore, they have no rights at all.
<P>               Those are the kinds of issues that we
    have to focus on.
<P>               <STRONG>MR. GLASSER:</STRONG>  Let me just add one more
    concrete way of looking at this.
<P>               We believe, as a matter of civil
    liberties, that the Bill of Rights is a limit on
   the government's power.  This is irrespective of
   the target of that power.  We would not want to
   take the position that if somebody is arrested, if
   somebody is occupying an apartment -- and the
   question arises as to whether or not a cop can
   enter that apartment with or without probable
   cause, with or without a search warrant, that that
   has to depend on what the immigration status is,
   or, for example, what the parole status is.  There
   have been -- we have litigated that very kind of
   issue with respect to people on parole.
<P>              The question has to be that the cop
   cannot decide whether or not he can enter that
   apartment without a warrant, as a violation of the
   14th Amendment unless somebody first shows papers
   that they are a citizen.  Once they are here, how
    they got here has to become irrelevant, or else
    cops get to beat people on the street if they are
    not citizens in a way they cannot if they are
    citizens.  I think if somebody is arrested for
    distributing a leaflet, is the First Amendment less
    powerful than the --
<P>               <STRONG>VOICE:</STRONG>  I am sorry, I was not clear, I
    totally agree with you.  The welfare benefits, that
    we don't have a right to welfare benefits, so if
   the government uses as a cut-off that you have
   violated the law for entering the country, what is
   the civil liberties reason for saying that is not a
   valid distinction?
<P>             <STRONG> MR. GLASSER:</STRONG>  Because violating the law
   is not part of the eligibility requirements.  We do
   not argue that people have a right, even as
   citizens, we don't argue that citizens have a
   constitutional right to welfare.  We don't argue
   that citizens have a constitutional right to
   Medicaid.
   <P>           But we do argue that once the government
   establishes those programs, it may not distinguish
   between who gets them and who doesn't get them by
   irrelevant and suspect categories.  If somebody
   commits a crime, if somebody commits a crime in one
    area, it does not mean they lose their
    constitutional rights in the other area.  We have
    resisted that all through our existence.
<P>               I don't think the question of welfare,
    which I think, as I said, is a very tiny question,
    ought to drive the general debate, in any case, of
    whether or not people who are here without citizen
    status or green card status, have any fewer rights
    against government power than otherwise.  The
   Constitution gets muddy when you talk about
   welfare, but if somebody had the right, for
   example, to medical treatment, would you not pick
   them up off the street if they were bleeding until
   you saw their papers?  It is simply as a way of
   practice.  What would happen if anything contrary
   to that developed?
<P>              It is the same thing that happens in
   employment.  People would be denied services
   because of a Spanish surname, people would be
   denied of services because of the way they look,
   and because of practice, the government official
   would have no way to tell, and it would necessarily
   be overboard.  The distinction cannot exist because
   the distinction cannot easily be made, and that is
   part of the problem.
<P>         

               <STRONG>MS. RIPSTON:</STRONG>  I would also like to add,
    that while it only pertained to children and
    education, in Iowa, the United States Supreme Court
    did recognize that undocumented children are
    entitled to some rights.  If there were a different
    Supreme Court, it might be willing to expand on
    that a little.
 <P>              <STRONG>VOICE:</STRONG>  Well, this -- Ira sort of
    covered a lot of my point, I was going to address
   Nadine's point.  I was going to add that the 14th
   Amendment clearly states once you are within the
   jurisdiction of the state, any person within that
   jurisdiction is afforded the protections of that
   state under the law.
<P>              I also think Nadine's question brings up
   a serious point.  In California, about a year
   before the 187 debacle started to brew up, we ran
   an article in our newsletter about immigrants and
   about how they are becoming the official scapegoat
   in the State of California, and we got a
   significant amount of mail, a significant amount of
   angry mail from our own members saying, how can you
   take this position, and illegal immigrants are
   criminals, et cetera.
<P>              And I think this point really needs to
    be stressed to the membership of every affiliate.
    We are here and this is a very good time to reach
    out to all of the members and do some serious
    education on this point, because it is a
    distinction that is often blurred, often fudged
    over, saying, we don't support that, we only
    support legal immigrants.  I think, as an
    organization, we need to take a very strong stand
    along those lines.
<P>             <STRONG> MS. RIPSTON:</STRONG>  I want to thank you all
   for coming to this plenary.
<P>              <STRONG>VOICE:</STRONG>  One more observation.  I should
   point out that our enemies are having no trouble
   not making that distinction.  They are in the
   process of taking benefits away from all
   immigrants, legal or illegal, and I don't see any
   reason why we need to observe a distinction without
   a difference of that nature.
<P>              <STRONG>MS. RIPSTON: </STRONG> Thank you all for coming
   to this last plenary.  We are going to take a
   two-minute stretch.
</blockquote>
        


