<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>75th Anniversary</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<center><h1>Joycelyn Elders' Speech<br></h1>
<h2>"Nothing Kills Lies Faster Than the Truth"</center></h2>
<blockquote>
From the Madison (WI) Times<br>
  July 6, 1995<br>
  Joycelyn Elders to ACLU Assembly:<br>
  "Nothing Kills Lies Faster than the Truth"
<p>
  By John Quinlan
<p>
  New York--Speaking to hundreds of activists from around the country at the
75th   Anniversary Biennial Conference of the American Civil Liberties Union
in late June,   Former U.S. Surgeon General Joycelyn Elders was emphatic in
defending her record in   the face of the right-wing critics who had
succeeded in driving her from office.   "I loved   being your surgeon
general, and ... I did the very best job that I knew how to do.  And I   want
to tell you that if I had it to do all over again, knowing everything I know,
starting   today, I would do exactly the same things."
<p>
  At hearing this, the crowd, which included about a dozen representatives
from Wisconsin,   rose to its feet with applause and shouts of affirmation.
In an interview for the Madison   Times that followed her speech, Elders, who
had been forced out of office last December   allegedly because of remarks
that advocated masturbation as an acceptable sexual outlet   for teens,
exuded optimism despite the challenges presented by the current political
climate.
<p>
  "I think we have to have optimism," Dr. Elders said.  "We'll be moving
ahead again as   soon as we make the American society understand what the
problems are.  We are letting   the politicians draw the boundaries now...." 
<p>
  "As soon as we allow all of our people to understand what the whole of the
issues are,   rather than just understanding what the politicians want them
to know, then I think that   we'll be looking at a very different society,"
she said.  "You see, the politicians take the   facts that they want to use
to make them look good, to benefit themselves, and that's what   they use.
Whereas, if you're a scientist or a physician like myself, you have to use
all of   the facts."
<p>
  "I think that the people who are doing this know that they are stretching
the truth," she   added.  "And one of the things that we have to know is that
if we keep speaking the truth,   nothing kills lies faster than the truth." 
<p>
  When asked to respond to the assertions of her critics that her stands on
civil rights and   family planning issues are somehow immoral and
anti-religious, she was unequivocal.  "I   feel that I'm very much a person
of faith," she said.  "And I feel that many of the people   who are saying
that they are people of faith, they are actually the same people who were
very much involved against Blacks, they are the most  homophobic--they are
against gays   and lesbians--they believe that men are the heads of their
households and that women   have no rights.  They're the same people who have
used religion to justify these views all   through history..."
<p>
  "I think that most people who really are true believers in faith believe in
the civil liberties   of others and that God loves all of us equally," she
added.  "He didn't give one special   privileges and take away those
privileges from others.  I really feel that with many of   these people, it's
not about God, I feel that they're 'religious economists.'  They are really
using religion to raise money.  And that's what it's about--other agendas." 
<p>
  Asked specifically about critics who claimed late last year that she was
advocating   detailed "how-to" courses on masturbation and other sexual
practices in the public   schools, Dr. Elders reiterated her belief that her
critics don't have the first idea what   health and sex education are all
about.  "I don't think it's necessarily important to be that   explicit.  I
feel that God gave us the know-how and desires and all of that.  And nobody
needs to be taught how-to courses.  That's not what it's about."
<p>
  "What it's really about is being able to have the facts and being able to
make the   judgements and make the decisions," she said.  "That's what
sexuality is all about.  More   goes on above the neck than goes on below the
belt.  And so we can get off into all of   these details about how-to, but
that is never a part of the human sexuality courses that are   being taught.
Nobody needs to be taught how-to."
<p>
  Given the rising rates of pregnancy and incidence of sexually transmitted
diseases,   teenagers need to hear frank discussions about sexual outlets
that are alternatives to   intercourse, she said.  And masturbation is one of
those options.
<p>
  "I think that America was talking more about masturbation in December of
1994 than   they ever talked about masturbation before, and that now it's all
right to say masturbation,   and before we didn't know that it was all
right," she said.
<p>
  "It is an alternative.  Now teenagers know that they're not going to go
blind, they're not   going to go crazy.  Hair's not going to grow on their
hands.  We need to just stop lying to   our children."
<p>
  In her speech, Elders drove home repeatedly the notion that those who label
themselves   as pro-family, who preach about the need for welfare reform and
who oppose a woman's   right to choose,  seldom have a record of working to
improve the lives of the nation's   children in poor families.
<p>
   "We know in our society that 60 per cent of the children born in America
are   unplanned," she said.  "We have the resources, we have the know-how to
make a   difference.  But we've not yet made a commitment to get it done.  We
have allowed those   men in Washington to use women's uteruses to get
elected.  So let's stop letting them hide   behind our uteruses.  You know
and I know that they aren't concerned about poor   children. All these rules
and all these laws that are curbing welfare and in terms of   medicare.  Who
do you think they're affecting?"
<p>
  "If any of you in this room wanted to get an abortion, you might have to do
without a new   coat this winter, but you could get it.  They affect the
young, the poor, and the   uneducated."
<p>
  "And if we are going to try to make a difference, we have got to be the
power brokers for   the powerless."
<p>
  These so-called pro-family politicians must be made accountable for their
scuttling of   health care reform, she asserted.  "We are one of two
industrialized countries that do not   have health care for all--universal
access to health care--the United States and South   Africa.  We spend 14 per
cent of our gross domestic product on health care.  The problem   is we don't
spend it on health care, we spend it on very expensive sick care."
<p>
  "We spend less than one per cent of our health care budget on keeping
people healthy--things like immunization, like pre-natal care.  But these
have all been defined as 'women's   issues.'  How many men do you know who
feel they have a stake in good pre-natal care?"
<p>
  "We have a health illiterate society.  People say, well let the parents
teach it.  But the   parents don't know how to teach it.  Forty-five per cent
of our fifth and sixth graders say   that there is more fat in watermelon
than there is in cheese.  And so we're putting all of   these labels on food,
but if we don't know what they mean, what good are they?"
<p>
  "And we feel that we don't want to educate our society, because if we start
educating our   children (about health issues), then we might teach them
something about sex.  Well   somebody needs to teach them something about
sex."  The crowd rose once again to its   feet to applaud.
<p>
  "When you have the highest teenage birth rate, pregnancy rate, and abortion
rate in the   industrialized world, we need to prevent unplanned pregnancy.
It's not about 'reforming'   welfare systems, which really means finding ways
not to care for unplanned children.  If   we began to put good health
education in place, if we began to put good services for    young people in
place, well then we can talk about reforming welfare."
<p>
  "We need to make every child born in America a planned and wanted child."
<p>
  "And about abortion--I've never been about abortion.  I support a woman's
right to choice.    I don't know anybody who knows enough to define for
another woman--I don't know   anybody who's good enough even if they knew
enough to make that choice for her....  It's   a decision between a woman,
her doctor, her significant other, and her God.  And it's not   for the
politicians in Washington to decide."
<p>
  Elders returned to her criticism of people who are anti-abortion but show
little evidence   of working to improve the lives of unwanted children.  "If
you're going to have a love   affair with the fetus, then you'd better be out
there fighting for programs for children.    Have you heard these people
fighting for real reform in welfare?  Have you seen them out   there fighting
for health care?  Have you seen them out there fighting for early childhood
education for all children?  Maybe they do it in your state, they don't do it
in mine." 
<p>
  Too often, the challenge is expressed in terms of  single teenage mothers.
Young men   must also be educated about their responsibilities, she said. "We
must teach our young   men to be responsible," she said.  Elders advocated
putting the child's father's social   security number on their child's birth
certificate, and automatically taking at least17 per   cent of any of their
earnings for the benefit of their child.  "I say that two parents are
responsible, not just one."
<p>
  Elders says that when she becomes discouraged, she remembers a woman from
Alaska   who offered these words of encouragement: "One woman with courage
can make a   difference."
<p>
  And, in noting the longterm nature of the battle for civil rights, she
related the advice her   bishop once gave her. "The things that you're
fighting for are like dancing with a bear,"   he told her.  "And when you're
dancing with a bear, you can't get tired and sit down.  You   have to wait
until the bear gets tired.  And then...you sit down."
<p>
  Throughout her speech, Elders--who has been ubiquitous in the national
media in recent   weeks in rallying people behind the cause of civil
rights--made it clear that she isn't about   to stop dancing with the bear.
As to what the future holds for her, however, Elders, who   never sought the
limelight, paints a picture of a much simpler existence.
<p>
   "I'll probably be home in a garden raising flowers five years from now,"
she said.  "I now   look forward to going home and doing just that."
<p>
 This article's author, John Quinlan, is a free-lance journalist and
community activist who   is a member of the Wisconsin ACLU board of Trustees.
He was a delegate to the ACLU   Biennial Conference in New York City in late
June.  Quinlan can be reached at   JLQuinlan@aol.com.
</blockquote>


