<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACLU in the Courts: Voting Rights Project 1996 Report</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><IMG SRC="/graphics/courthdr.gif"></P>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">ACLU FOUNDATION, INC.<BR>SOUTHERN REGIONAL OFFICE<BR>REPORT,
DECEMBER, 1996</H2>
<P>An equal opportunity for all to vote and hold office is crucial to our
democracy.  Yet many minority Americans are denied that opportunity.  The ACLU's
Voting Rights Project is committed to making the promise of equal voting rights
a reality -- despite obstacles that, in recent years, have made the struggle to
keep that committment increasingly difficult.  This report summarizes the work
of the Voting Rights Project during 1996.</P>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="#I">I.  Meeting the Challenge of <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I></A></DT>
<DD><A HREF="#IA">A.  The Role of the Voting Rights Project</A></DD>
<DD><A HREF="#IB">B.  Exercising Damage Control</A></DD>
<DD><A HREF="#IC">C.  Are Majority Minority Districts Still Needed?</A></DD>
<DT><A HREF="#II">II.  Section 2 and Constitutional Litigation </A></DT>
<DD><A HREF="#IIA">A.  Motor Voter</A></DD>
<DD><A HREF="#IIB">B.  Other Litigation</A></DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="I"></A>I.  Meeting the Challenge of <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I></H3>
<P>A major task of the ACLU's Voting Rights Project over the past year was
responding to the crises created by the Supreme Court in <I>Shaw v. Reno</I>
(1993) and <I>Miller v. Johnson</I> (1995).  <I>Shaw</I> held for the first
time that white residents could challenge a redistricting plan under the
Fourteenth Amendment on the grounds that a district's shape was so bizarre that
it could only be understood as an attempt to segregate voters on the basis of
race.  Prior to <I>Shaw</I>, the Court had held that a compact district shape,
while frequently required by state law, was not an independent federal
constitutional requirement.</P>
<P>Two years later in <I>Miller</I> the Court went far beyond what it had said
in <I>Shaw</I>, i.e., that only bizarrely shaped districts were problematical,
and held that a district could be challenged, regardless of its shape, if race
was the predominant factor in the redistricting process and if the jurisdiction
subordinated its traditional districting principles to race.  </P>
<P><I>Shaw</I> and <I>Miller</I> have spawned a host of lawsuits challenging
majority minority districts.  At the congressional level, <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I>
challenges have been filed in North Carolina, Georgia, Virginia, Texas,
Louisiana, Florida, New York, Illinois, and South Carolina.  Thus far, majority
minority congressional districts have been invalidated in North Carolina (2),
Georgia (2), Texas (3), Louisiana (1), and Florida (1).  <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I>
challenges have also been made to a number of legislative and local
redistricting plans, including in South Carolina, Georgia, Florida, Louisiana,
Mississippi, Colorado, California, and Alabama.    </P>
<P>In <I>Thornburg v. Gingles</I> (1986), the Supreme Court established a
three part test for determining when the Voting Rights Act required the creation
of majority minority districts.  Plaintiffs were normally entitled to relief if
they established that the minority was geographically compact, i.e., that it
could constitute a majority in one or more districts, that it was politically
cohesive, i.e., that it voted as a bloc, and that the majority voted
sufficiently as a bloc usually to defeat the candidates favored by the minority.
 The essence of the ruling in <I>Gingles</I> was that majority minority
districts were necessary where racial bloc voting by whites effectively deprived
blacks and other minorities of an equal opportunity to elect candidates of their
choice.</P>
<P>Under the guiding principles of <I>Gingles</I> and the Section 5
preclearance process, the 1990 redistricting, from the point of view of
minorities, was the most successful in the Nation's history.  Sixteen new
majority minority congressional districts were created in Virginia, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia, Florida, Alabama, Maryland, New York,
Pennsylvania, Louisiana, and Texas.  There were similar increases in the number
of majority minority districts for the election of state senators, house
members, county commissioners, school board members, and city council members. 
 </P>
<P>The destruction of majority minority districts under the new rules
established by <I>Shaw</I> and <I>Miller</I> threatens to roll back the gains
in minority office holding accumulated over the past 30 years since passage of
the Voting Rights Act.  Prior to passage of the Act in 1965, there were fewer
than one hundred black elected officials in the seven Deep South states targeted
by the special preclearance provisions found in Section 5 of the Act.  Today,
the number of black elected officials in these states is more than 4,000.  There
is a general consensus that this dramatic increase in minority office holding is
linked directly to the increase in the number of majority minority electoral
districts created as a result of the Voting Rights Act.  Prior to the 1996
elections, for example, only one black had ever been elected to Congress from
the Deep South states from a majority white district.  Andrew Young was elected
in 1972 from the Fifth Congressional District in Georgia, which had a 44% black
voting age population.  Still, voting was racially polarized and he got only 25%
of the white vote.  When he ran for mayor of Atlanta in 1981 he got only 9% of
the white vote.  In 1990 he ran for governor, getting about a quarter of the
white vote, and was defeated.  Even for a candidate with extraordinary
qualifications, such as Young, racial bloc voting is a political fact of life. 
 </P>
<H3><A NAME="IA"></A>A.  The Role of the Voting Rights Project</H3>
<P>The Voting Rights Project has sought to represent citizen intervenors in as
many of the <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I> challenges as its resources have
permitted.  Such intervention is crucial, for the Southern states, as noted
below, cannot be counted on vigorously to defend the Voting Rights Act or the
plans they adopted after the 1990 census.</P>
<P>In Georgia, we have represented a group of black and white voters in the
ongoing challenge to the state's congressional redistricting (<I>Miller v.
Johnson</I>).  On remand from the Supreme Court, the district court allowed the
plaintiffs to amend their complaint to challenge the constitutionality of
Georgia's majority black Second Congressional District.  The state did not
attempt to defend the district but conceded that it was unconstitutional.</P>
<P>The governor called the general assembly into special session to adopt a new
plan, but it was unable to do so.  Accordingly, the district court adopted a
plan, which was used in the 1996 election.  Although the first plan enacted by
the state prior to any involvement by the Department of Justice contained two
majority black districts, the plan drawn by the district court contained only
one such district, the Fifth District in the Atlanta metropolitan area
represented by John Lewis.  </P>
<P>The state declined to appeal the decision of the district court, despite the
fact that the court's plan abolished two of the three majority black districts
drawn by the state in 1992.  The intervenors (including the United States)
appealed.  In a total reversal of roles, the state joined the plaintiffs and
have opposed the appeal.</P>
<P>We contend that the district court's plan violates the Voting Rights Act and
that the court abused its powers by ignoring the state's policy choices for the
location and racial composition of the Eleventh District.  The Supreme Court
heard oral argument on December 9, 1996 (<I>Abrams v. Johnson</I>).</P>
<P>We also represent intervenors in a <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I> challenge to
house and senate redistricting in Georgia (<I>Johnson III</I>).  The three
judge court granted the plaintiffs partial relief following a trial on
plaintiffs' motion for preliminary injunction.  Since then we have had several
settlement discussions with the plaintiffs and there is a possibility that we
can settle all or most of the litigation in a way that minimizes the destruction
of majority black house and senate districts.      </P>
<P>We represent black intervenors in <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I> challenges to
house and senate redistricting in South Carolina (<I>Smith v. Beasley</I>; <I>Able

v. Wilkins</I>).  The plaintiffs challenged nine house districts and three
senate districts.  The court invalidated six of the nine house districts and in
a split decision all three of the senate districts.  However, the court gave the
legislature an opportunity to redraw the lines, and it is possible that some or
most of the districts will be redrawn as majority black districts and in a
manner that is acceptable to our clients.</P>
<P>Although we hope that an appeal will ultimately be unnecessary, the
intervenors filed a protective notice of appeal.  We have also asked the Supreme
Court to delay consideration of the appeal until after the state adopts new
plans.  As in Georgia, the state declined to appeal the decision of the district
court.    </P>
<P>In a recent development, a <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I> challenge was filed
in early December, 1996 against the sole majority black congressional district
in South Carolina, currently represented by James Clyburn (<I>Leonard v.
Beasley</I>).  We have been asked to represent minority intervenors who wish to
defend the district, and will file the necessary intervention papers within the
next few weeks.  Clyburn is the only black in modern times to be elected to
Congress from South Carolina.  Given the levels of racial bloc voting in the
state, the creation of all majority white congressional districts would almost
certainly eventually lead to an all white congressional delegation. </P>
<P>As a footnote, the house, senate, and congressional districts in South
Carolina that are now under challenge were created as a result of litigation
brought by the Voting Rights Project in 1991 (<I>SRAC v. Campbell</I>; <I>SRAC
v. Theodore</I>).  The Republican Party brought a similar suit and the two cases
were consolidated for trial.  Thus, we have an added incentive to defend the
challenged plans in South Carolina.   </P>
<P>We are also representing intervenors in a <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I>
challenge to congressional redistricting in Virginia (<I>Moon v. Meadows</I>). 
The case has been tried and we are awaiting a decision.  Even if the court
invalidates the existing district, there is a chance that it would be redrawn to
save it as a majority black district.  In any event, the incumbent Bobby Scott
would probably survive under any likely remedial scenario.  The bigger question,
of course, is the probability of a non-incumbent black being elected in a
reconfigured district. </P>
<P>We have also defended three consent decrees we entered into against <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I>
challenges.  We were able to postpone the challenge in Perry County, Mississippi
(<I>McCarty v. Board of Supervisors</I>) until after the next census.  Another
challenge in St. Francisville, Louisiana (<I>Wilson v. Mayor and Board of
Aldermen</I>) we won after a trial on the merits.  The court invalidated the
challenged district as bizarre but implemented as a court ordered plan the
majority black district our expert had originally drawn.  The court ordered
district is actually a stronger black district than the one contained in the
consent order.  </P>
<P>The third consent decree involves residents of the Ute Mountain Ute Indian
Reservation in Colorado (<I>Cuthair v. Montezuma-Cortez</I>).  The district
court rejected the <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I> challenge filed by the defendant
school board to a decree creating a majority Indian district on the grounds that
the district was regular in shape and did not subordinate traditional
redistricting principles.  (We argued that <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I> did not
apply to Native Americans in the first place since &quot;Indian,&quot; for
purposes of the Fourteenth Amendment, is a political rather than a racial
category.)  The court, however, set aside the consent decree (wrongly in our
view) on other unrelated grounds and has set the case for a trial on the merits
in May, 1997.</P>
<P>In addition to direct representation, we have filed amicus briefs in the
Supreme Court in support of the minority intervenors and the United States in
other <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I> cases, i.e., <I>Shaw v. Hunt</I> (North
Carolina congressional), and <I>United States v. Hays</I> (Louisiana
congressional).  The director of the Voting Rights Project has also written
several articles as part of an ongoing public education campaign, and to address
and hopefully dispel some of the misconceptions surrounding redistricting and
minority voting rights.  See, L. McDonald, &quot;Can Minority Voting Rights
Survive <I>Miller v. Johnson</I>?&quot; 1 Mich. J. R &amp; L 1190 (1996); L.
McDonald, &quot;The Counterrevolution in Minority Voting Rights,&quot; 65 Miss.
L. J. 271 (1995); L. McDonald, &quot;<I>Holder v. Hall</I>: Blinking at
Minority Voting Rights,&quot; 3 D.C. L. Rev. 61 (1995); L. McDonald, &quot;This
Way?  Voting Rights at a Crossroads,&quot; 1 Civ. R. J. 36 (1995).</P>
<H3><A NAME="IB"></A>B.  Exercising Damage Control</H3>
<P>Given the hostility of the Court to all forms of perceived affirmative
action, the Voting Rights Project has tried to exercise as much damage control
as possible and defend the gains of the 1990 redistricting process.  We (and the
civil rights community in general) have been fairly successful thus far in
stemming the erosion of minority office holders.  At the congressional level,
despite the invalidation of redistricting plans in Georgia, North Carolina,
Florida, Texas, and Louisiana, all the black incumbents, with the exception of
Cleo Fields who did not seek reelection, were returned to office.  </P>
<P>We still don't know the impact of <I>Shaw</I>/<I>Miller</I> on legislative
redistricting in South Carolina and Georgia, but thus far no black incumbents
have lost their seats as a result of the litigation.  We certainly lost some of
the legal battles during the past year, and the work of the project has been
made more difficult as a result.  But the worst predictions of &quot;political
ethnic cleansing&quot; have not yet come to pass.  </P>
<H3><A NAME="IC"></A>C.  Are Majority Minority Districts Still Needed?</H3>
<P>With the election of Cynthia McKinney and Sanford Bishop to Congress in 1996
from Georgia in newly configured majority white districts, some critics have
argued that majority black districts are no longer needed.  Of course, similar
arguments were made in 1972 after Andy Young was elected.  Whether or not
minorities have equal electoral opportunities cannot, however, be determined on
the basis of one or a few elections.  The exceptions cannot be used to establish
the rule.  Instead, voting patterns over time have to be examined to determine
whether minorities in fact have the equal opportunity to elect candidates of
their choice.  </P>
<P>McKinney and Bishop were able to win in large measure because they ran with
the advantages of incumbency.  And they were incumbents because they were
elected in the first place in majority black districts.  They were therefore
able to establish track records of service to both their white and black
constituents.  By contrast, non-incumbent blacks who ran for Congress in 1996 in
majority white districts in Arkansas, Texas, and Mississippi all lost.</P>
<P>The voting in Georgia in the 1996 elections was still considerably
polarized.  In the 1996 Democratic primary, McKinney got only 13% of the white
vote.  She won the nomination because she got almost all the black vote and
whites mainly stayed home or voted in the Republican primary.  White turnout was
only 11% of registered voters compared to 31% for blacks.  As a consequence, the
electorate in the primary was actually substantially majority black.  In the
general election, running in a heavily Democratic district she increased her
percentage of the white vote, but voting was still along racial lines--100% of
blacks voted for McKinney while 69% of whites voted for her white opponent. 
</P>
<P>The real test of the new majority white districts, such as the Fourth
represented by McKinney, will come when non-incumbent blacks run for office. 
Hopefully, McKinney's election is a bellwether of a gradual change in voter
attitudes.  But in the meantime, the notion that racial bloc voting does not
exist should be seen for what it is, a myth.  </P>
<P>If the electorate were truly color blind we would expect to see a few black
governors, U.S. Senators, secretaries of state, commissioners of agriculture,
etc.  In fact, except for judicial office, not a single black holds a statewide
elected position in any of the southern states.  </P>
<P>The critics have charged that majority minority districts were &quot;segregated,&quot;
and would polarize the electorate and create racial tensions.  To the contrary,
the majority minority districts created after the 1990 census were the most
integrated districts in the country, containing an average of 45% of white
voters.  </P>
<P>As for polarization and racial tensions, the 1996 elections do not support
the critics' dire predictions.  The election returns show that the highly
integrated majority minority districts have helped break down to some extent
racial polarization.  Far from balkanizing the electorate, they have helped
reduce harmful stereotyping of minority candidates and reassured white voters
that their interests could be adequately represented by black office holders. 
Highly integrated majority minority districts have benefitted voters of all
races.   </P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="II"></A>II.  Section 2 and Constitutional Litigation </H3>
<P>A judicial backlash in the area of voting following <I>Shaw</I> and <I>Miller</I>
is undeniable.  Following a trial this summer, the court ruled against us on our
claim that Georgia's majority vote law was enacted in 1964 to discriminate
against blacks (<I>Brooks v. Miller</I>).  The court simply &quot;found&quot;
the evidence against us.  The court also rejected our Section 2 challenge to
at-large elections in Rome, Georgia despite strong evidence of vote dilution (<I>Askew
v. Rome</I>).  The court of appeals affirmed the granting of summary judgment to
the defendants in Alamance, North Carolina and adopted a new rule that
black/white contests are not controlling and that blacks would enjoy equal
political opportunities even if the only candidates they could elect were white
(<I>Lewis v. Board of Commissioner</I>). </P>
<P>In spite of these setbacks -- all of which we are appealing -- we have been
able to make progress on a number of fronts.</P>
<H3><A NAME="IIA"></A>A.  Motor Voter</H3>
<P>Our motor voter litigation in Kansas (<I>League of Women Voters v. Graves</I>),
Louisiana (<I>ACORN v. Fowler</I>), Virginia (<I>Richmond Crusade for Voters
v. Allen</I>), and South Carolina (<I>Grass Roots Leadership v. Beasley</I>),
was all resolved satisfactorily on the merits.  As a result, thousands of new
voters have been added to the voter rolls in the affected states.</P>
<P>The NVRA litigation in Mississippi (<I>Young v. Fordice</I>), which we are
participating in with the Lawyers' Committee, is ongoing.  The issue is whether
the state's attempt to revert to a dual system of registration, requiring
separate registration for state and federal elections, is subject to
preclearance under Section 5.  If we prevail on this issue and the changes are
submitted, we believe they would violate the retrogression principle of Section
5.  Minorities would be clearly worse off having to register twice, once to vote
in state elections and again to vote in federal elections.  Aside from the
expense of maintaining dual registration, such a system would create voter
confusion and inevitably depress minority political participation. </P>
<P>The Supreme Court has agreed to hear our appeal in this case.  No date has
yet been set for oral argument.</P>
<H3><A NAME="IIB"></A>B.  Other Litigation</H3>
<P>We prevailed in a number of cases brought to enforce one person-one vote,
the results (or racial fairness) standard of Section 2, and the preclearance
requirement of Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act.  </P>
<P>We won (for the second time) our challenge to at-large elections for judges
in Hamilton County, Tennessee (<I>Cousin v. McWherter</I>).  As a remedy, the
court implemented a system of cumulative voting.  The state has appealed; the
case has been briefed and is awaiting oral argument.   </P>
<P>We succeeded in changing the discriminatory annexation policy of Foley,
Alabama (<I>Dillard v. City of Foley</I>).  We prevailed in separate law suits
to require Hemingway, South Carolina and Douglasville, Georgia to submit for
Section 5 preclearance their annexations of predominantly white residential
areas (<I>NAACP v. Hemingway</I>; <I>Simpson v. City of Douglasville</I>).  
</P>
<P>We won a one person, one vote challenge in Cook County, Georgia that
resulted in the adoption of a new plan containing a majority black district and
a second strong minority &quot;influence&quot; district (<I>Jones v. Cook
County</I>).  A successful Section 2 law suit in Worcester County, Maryland
produced a new majority black district for the county commission (<I>Cane v.
Worcester County, Maryland</I>).  </P>
<P>Our Section 2 challenge in Thurston County, Nebraska resulted in the
creation of an additional majority Indian district for the county board of
supervisors (<I>Stabler v. County of Thurston</I>).  A similar suit in
Washington County, North Carolina produced two majority black districts for the
board of county commissioners (<I>Wilkins v. Board of Commissioners</I>).</P>
<P>One of the more imaginative consent decrees was entered in  the case
involving the board of education of Person County, North Carolina (<I>Webster
v. Board of Education</I>).  The parties agreed to adopt a system of plurality
voting to replace a staggered terms/majority vote method of elections.  The new
system will allow minorities to single shot vote (vote for less that all five
seats) and thus enhance their ability to elect candidates of their choice.  The
consent decree further provides that if minorities are unsuccessful in the 1996,
1998, and 2000 elections either party may apply to the court for further relief.
 The defendants agreed that under such circumstances they would not contest the
claim that the pre-existing at-large system violates Section 2.</P>
<P>We are awaiting a decision in our case challenging the county legislative
delegation system of county government in South Carolina (<I>Vander Linden v.
Campbell</I>).  The county legislative delegations, which have general powers of
county governance, are composed of members of the house and senate who have any
part of a county in their electoral districts.  As a result of having to split
counties to comply with one person-one vote in reapportioning the general
assembly, the delegations qua county governments are severely malapportioned. 
Some delegation members represent only a few county residents while other
members represent thousands of county residents.  </P>
<P>The district court has already granted our motion for a preliminary
injunction.  If we prevail on the merits, the state will have to restructure the
county legislative delegations to comply with equal population requirements, or
transfer the powers of the delegations to local governing bodies.  In either
case, county residents would have an equal voice in the election of public
officials.</P>
<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG
SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0"></A>
<P>    
</P>
