HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 11:46:04 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 07-Jan-97 20:55:36 GMT
Content-length: 9097
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SoftQuad//DTD draft HTML 3.2 + extensions for HoTMetaL PRO 3.0 19960923//EN"
>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Holiday Collection</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffffff">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%" BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD COLSPAN="2">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><BR><IMG SRC="/graphics/religion.gif"></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">The ACLU Celebrates Religious Liberty<BR></H1></TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR></P>
<H2>Protecting the Freedom to Believe</H2>
<P>Can a town council place a menorah display in the courthouse square?  Should
schools be allowed to hold Christmas parties that exclude children of other
faiths?  More widely, should our government directly fund religious
institutions, including parochial schools, or sponsor school prayer?   </P>
<P>The approaching holiday season, and the perennial controversy it stirs up
about the role of religion in public life, provides a good occasion to reflect
on these questions and on how the Constitution and Bill of Rights protects the
rights of all religions.</P>
<P>The ACLU believes that religious liberty -- the right of each and every
American to practice his or her own religion, or no religion at all -- is among
the most fundamental of the freedoms guaranteed by the Bill of Rights.</P>
<P>Americans enjoy a degree of religious freedom unknown in most of the rest of
the world, and they take full advantage it: The United States is home to more
than 1,500 different religious bodies (including 75 varieties of Baptists) and
360,000 churches, synagogues and mosques. Ninety per cent of Americans believe
in God; more than half say they pray at least once a day, and church membership
has remained at the same level -- 63 percent of the population, according to the
Census Bureau -- for more than thirty years.  </P>
<P>Yet assaults on the freedom to believe continue, both in Washington and in
state legislatures around the country.  While the 104th Congress was
unsuccessful in fulfilling its pledge to the Christian Coalition and others to
introduce constitutional amendments that would overturn the religion clauses of
the Bill of Rights, we can expect to see a renewed push for these initiatives in
the New Year.  </P>
<P>The 105th Congress is expected to introduce of a number of bills early in
1997, including constitutional amendments allowing school prayer and direct
government funding of religious institutions.  A constitutional amendment must
pass both Houses of Congress by a two-thirds majority in order to be sent to the
states for ratification, and a vote will likely come down to the wire in both
Houses.  The newly configured Senate, more conservative than in recent years,
cannot be counted on to head off the attack.  In fact, one new Senator, Jeff
Sessions of Alabama, has pledged to make the dismantling of church-state
separation his top priority. </P>
<P>Also in 1997, lawmakers will attempt to chip away at the separation of
church and state through the passage of statutes.  The most notorious of these
is the &quot;Community Renewal Act&quot; (CRA), a two-pronged attack on the
First Amendment.  </P>
<P>The so-called renewal act would rewrite our nation's laws on substance abuse
treatment to permit government- funded proselytizing and religious
indoctrination in substance abuse programs.  In other words, if a person seeks
treatment for a drug problem through a government program, he or she could be
sent to a religious program which could explicitly require the person to engage
in religious worship &#150; all with government dollars!  The bill would also
mandate a parochial school voucher scheme in 100 communities across the country,
and condition community funding on the institution of a program to funnel
taxpayer dollars for tuition to parochial schools.  Speaker Gingrich has
promised a vote on the CRA early in the 105th Congress.  </P>
<P>The ACLU will continue working to ensure that religious liberty is protected
by keeping the government out of the religion business.  Be sure to visit the
ACLU in Congress section this January: Our online voter's guide will provide
instant civil liberties ratings on key Congressional votes,  as well as
legislative alerts and a daily report from Washington when Congress is in
session.</P>
<P>In the meantime, take the religious liberty quiz at right to determine your
LQ (Liberty Quotient).  You might want to do some quick cramming first -- read
the ACLU's collection on religious liberty, including major Supreme Court
opinions and a joint statement on current law. </P>
<HR>
<P>Week of December 12th on
<A

HREF="http://www.intellectualcapital.com/library/issues/ic121296/icissue.html">IntellectualCapital.com</A>:
 the ACLU's
<A HREF="http://www.intellectualcapital.com/library/issues/ic121296/iccon.html">Loren
Siegel</A> and the Family Research Council's
<A HREF="http://www.intellectualcapital.com/library/issues/ic121296/icpro.html">Gary
Bauer</A> on Religion in Public Schools.</P>
<P>Ira Glasser's Visions of Liberty Column<BR><A
HREF="http://www.aclu.org/library/vision10.html">September 8, 1996: School
Vouchers and False Promises</A> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE></TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR></P>
<H2>Resources &amp; Features</H2>
<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><A HREF="rlquiz.html">Test your knowledge</A> of religious
liberty by taking our quiz</FONT></P>
<P><A HREF="relig7.html"><FONT SIZE="+1">Religion in  the Schools, A Joint
Statement of Current Law</FONT></A><BR>This statement, signed by dozens of
organizations concerned with religious liberty, including both the ACLU and the
Christian Coalition, offers a &quot;statement of consensus on      current law
as an aid to parents, educators and students.&quot;   Both Secretary of
Education Richard Riley and President Clinton have endorsed these guidelines for
schools.</P>
<P><A HREF="pr3.html"><FONT SIZE="+1">The Establishment Clause and the
Schools: A Legal Bulletin</FONT></A><BR>This earlier ACLU publication covers
school practices where differences persist among  advocacy groups, and among
people generally.  Includes guidelines on <A HREF="pr3.html#holiday">holiday
parties.</A></P>
