<HEAD>
<TITLE>Religious Liberty Quiz</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=FFFFFF>


<CENTER><img src="/graphics/religion.gif"></CENTER>
<p>
<CENTER><H3>Religious Liberty Quiz</H3></CENTER>
How much do you know about the religious liberty guarantees contained in the First Amendment to the
U.S. Constitution?  Take this quiz and find out.<P>

<FORM METHOD="POST" ACTION ="/cgi-bin/quiz.pl">
<INPUT TYPE="hidden" VALUE="aclu/rl.cf" NAME="cf">
<INPUT TYPE="hidden" NAME="order" VALUE="one:two:three:four:five:six:seven:eight:nine:ten">


<OL>

<LI> The two religion clauses in the First Amendment are called:<P>
         <input type="radio" name="one" value="The Establishment Clause and the Due Process Clause"> The Establishment Clause and the Due Process Clause<BR>
         <input type="radio" name="one" value="The Free Exercise Clause and the Establishment Clause"> The Free Exercise Clause and the Establishment Clause<BR>
         <input type="radio" name="one" value="The Free Exercise Clause and the Free Association Clause"> The Free Execise Clause and the Free Association Clause<P>

<LI> In 1925 the State of Tennessee prosecuted John Scopes for<P>
          <input type="radio" name="two" value="Advocating the violent overthrow of the government">Advocating the violent overthrow of the government<BR>
          <input type="radio" name="two" value="Refusing to pledge allegiance to the flag">Refusing to pledge allegiance to the flag<BR>
          <input type="radio" name="two" value="Teaching evolution">Teaching evolution<P>

<LI> The person who coined the phrase:  "a wall of separation between church and state" was<P>
          <input type="radio" name="three" value="Thomas Jefferson">Thomas Jefferson<BR>
          <input type="radio" name="three" value="John F. Kennedy">John F. Kennedy<BR>
          <input type="radio" name="three" value="Madeline Murray O'Hare">Madeline Murray O'Hare<P>

<LI> The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that the following governmental practice is unconstitutional:<P>
         <input type="radio" name="four" value="Punishing adherents of the Native American Church for using peyote for ceremonial purposes"> Punishing adherents of the Native American Church for using peyote for ceremonial purposes<BR>
          <input type="radio" name="four" value="Hiring a chaplain to open daily sessions of the state legislature with a prayer"> Hiring a chaplain to open daily sessions of the state legislature with a prayer<BR>
          <input type="radio" name="four" value="Having a religious leader deliver a prayer at a public school graduation ceremony"> Having a religious leader deliver a prayer at a public school graduation ceremony<BR>
          <BR>

<LI> An example of a constitutional accomodation to someone's religious beliefs is<P>
           <input type="radio" name="five" value="Allowing Amish children to drop out of school in 8th grade">Allowing Amish children to drop out of school in 8th grade<BR>
          <input type="radio" name="five" value="Granting conscientious objector status to members of pacifist religions">Granting conscientious objector status to members of pacifist religions<BR>
          <input type="radio" name="five" value="Allowing members of the Santeria Church to practice animal sacrifice">Allowing members of the Santeria Church to practice animal sacrifice <BR>
          <input type="radio" name="five" value="All of the above">All of the above<P>



<LI> In 1984 Congress passed a law to protect the right of secondary students to hold after-school religious club meetings if other, nonreligious clubs, were allowed to meet.  That law is called<P>

      <input type="radio" name="six" value="The Religious Freedom Restoration Act">The Religious Freedom Restoration Act<BR>
      <input type="radio" name="six" value="The School Prayer Act">The School Prayer Act<BR>
      <input type="radio" name="six" value="The Equal Access Act">The Equal Access Act <P>

<LI> The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that Establishment Clause is not violated when a teacher leads a public school class in prayer so long as the students are participating on a voluntary basis.<P>
 
      <input type="radio" name="seven" value="True">True<BR>
      <input type="radio" name="seven" value="False">False<P>

<LI> The Supreme Court's three-pronged test for determining whether a law or practice violates the Establishment Clause is called <P>

      <input type="radio" name="eight" value="The Establishment Test">The Establishment Test<BR>
      <input type="radio" name="eight" value="The Lemon Test">The Lemon Test<BR>
      <input type="radio" name="eight" value="The Vitale Test">The Vitale Test<P>

 <LI> In its 1984  ruling in Lynch v. Donnelly, the Supreme Court held that<P>
      <input type="radio" name="nine" value="All government-sponsored Nativity displays violate the Constitution"> All government-sponsored Nativity displays violate the Constitution<BR>
      <input type="radio" name="nine" value="A government-sponsored Nativity display is not unconstitutional if it is included in a larger display of secular Christmas imagery"> A government-sponsored Nativity display is not unconstitutional if it is incl
uded in a larger display of secular Christmas imagery<BR>
      <input type="radio" name="nine" value="A government-sponsored Nativity display is not unconsitutional if it is in a privately-owned park."> A government-sponsored Nativity display is not unconsitutional if it is in a privately-owned park.<P>

<LI> Under current law, public school students are never permitted to pray during school hours.<P>
      <input type="radio" name="ten" value="True"> True<BR>
      <input type="radio" name="ten" value="False"> False

</OL>

