HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 14:06:01 GMT
Last-modified: Wednesday, 25-Sep-96 19:07:56 GMT
Content-length: 10951
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 + all extensions//EN" "hmpro3.dtd">
<HTML>
	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>
		</TITLE>
	</HEAD>
	<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
		<P ALIGN="CENTER">
			<IMG SRC="/graphics/bbw.gif">
		</P>
		<BLOCKQUOTE>
			<CENTER>
				<H3>
					Order Banned Books an Materials on Censorship
				</H3>
			</CENTER>
		<H3><A HREF="http://www.aclu.org/store/store.html">Available from the ACLU</A></H3><P>
				<BLOCKQUOTE><b>An ACLU Banned Books Poster</b>
				<BR>
				 Which one has been <FONT COLOR="#FF0000">CENSORED?</FONT> -- All of Them<BR> Full color -- displays ten popular works censored in the United States, from Little Red Riding Hood to Webster's Dictionary to Playboy. (37" x 24") <B>Item #8010</B>
			<P>
			<B>ACLU Books and Authors</B><P>
			<P><I>Defending Pornography: Free Speech, Sex and the Fight for Women's Rights</I> by Nadine Strossen<BR>
(Scribner, 1995, 320 pp.) <B>Item #7086</B> $9.95 + shipping
			
			<P>
			<I>Sex, Sin  and Blasphemy: A Guide to  America's Censorship Wars</I>
                           by Marjorie Heins<br>
                           (The New Press, 1993, 210 pp.)
                           <B>Item #7070</B>
                           $11.95 + shipping 
             <P>
            <I> The Rights of Authors, Artists, and
                    Other Creative People </I><br>(1992)
                    <B>Item #1020</B>
                    $8.95 + shipping 
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<H3>Order Banned Books from Amazon.Com</H3>
			
			<A HREF="amazon.html"><IMG SRC="/graphics/amazon.gif" BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="60" alt="Amazon.Com"></A>
			Would be censors have tried to block access to these books, but we have arranged a way for you to order them online. You can follow these links to purchase banned books from Amazon.Com booksellers. If you purchase books by following the links on this page, the ACLU will get a percentage of the price of the book. If you want to order multiple books from this list, hit the back button on your browser and return to this page. Amazon.Com will keep track of the books you have ordered even if you return to this page between selections, and that way the ACLU will still receive a percentage.
			
			
			<P><BR CLEAR=ALL>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0684823527/acluA/">
				Boston Women's Health Collective
				<BR>
				Our Bodies, Ourselves
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				This highly respected women's health manual has been removed from school libraries on numerous occasions. Reasons vary, but it has been called "pornographic" and "filthy," and was removed from the public library in Three Rivers, Michigan because "it promotes homosexuality and perversion."
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0140184643/acluA/">
				Edgar Rice Burroughs
				<BR>
				Tarzan of the Apes
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				This classic story of a man raised in the wild, that later became the basis for a comic book series and many movies, was removed from the Los Angeles Public Library because Tarzan was "living in sin" with Jane.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0140432493/acluA/">
				John Cleland
				<BR>
				Fanny Hill (Memoirs of a Woman of Pleasure)
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				This 1748 best-seller about a prostitute was probably read and enjoyed by many of our Constitution's framers. But in 1821 it was banned in Massachusetts in what was the first known U.S. obscenity case. The U.S Supreme Court finally cleared it of obscenity charges in 1966.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0553268880/acluA/">
				Pat Conroy
				<BR>
				Prince of Tides
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				First a best-selling novel, and later a successful film, Pat Conroy's novel about a southern family was removed as a reading assignment from an English class in South Carolina. The reason? It was "trashy pulp pornography."
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<P>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D067973225X/acluA/">
				William Faulkner
				<BR>
				As I Lay Dying
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				This stream of consciousness novel, considered a literary masterpiece by one of America's most gifted writers, was banned from the Graves County, Kentucky school district in September 1986 on the grounds that it made reference to God and abortion in way that some people might find offensive.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
						<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0064406601/acluA/">
				Louise Fitzhugh
				<BR>
				Harriet the Spy
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				While Harriet the Spy is a favorite of many, it was challenged in the Xenia, Ohio school libraries in 1983 because the book "teaches children to lie, spy, back-talk and curse."
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0553296981/acluA/">
				Anne Frank
				<BR>
				Anne Frank: Diary of a Young Girl
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				Various reasons have been used to justify a number of attempts to ban Anne Frank's diary. In one 1983 incident, four members of the Alabama State Textbook Committee called for its rejection because it was a "real downer."
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN=1564022285/acluA/">
				Martin Hanford
				<BR>
				Where's Waldo?
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				The goal in this ubiquitous children's picture book is to find Waldo in a crowd of tiny, colorful figures. While some people may have trouble finding Waldo, others think they've found something else. In 1989 the book was attacked in the Saginaw, Michigan libraries because "on some of the pages there are dirty things."
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0060809833/acluA/">
				Aldus Huxley
				<BR>
				Brave New World
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				In this classic satire of a future world, all problems are solved through the use of "Soma," a fictional narcotic. Huxley's book was called anti-family and anti-Christian and was also challenged because of "language and moral content."
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0679722769/acluA/%0D">
				James Joyce
				<BR>
				Ulysses
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				James Joyce's presentation of a day in the internal and external life of an average Dubliner is now known to be a classic, but the U.S. Custom Service banned its importation into this country for 15 years on the grounds that it was obscene. In 1933 the ACLU won a major legal victory that forced the U.S. Customs Service to lift its ban.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0451524985/acluA/">
				D.H. Lawrence<BR>
				Lady Chatterley's Lover<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				D.H. Lawrence's classic work about a married woman's affair was declared an "obscene and filthy work" that could not be sent through the mail by the U.S. Postmaster General in 1959. The courts disagreed, and it can now be shipped freely.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0877797099/acluA/">
				Merriam-Webster Editorial Staff
				<BR>
				Webster's Ninth New Collegiate Dictionary
			</A>
			<P>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				Dictionaries get banned too! Webster's Ninth New Collegiate Dictionary was removed from classrooms in Carlsbad, N.M. because it defines "obscene" words.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0553278355/acluA/">
				Sylvia Plath
				<BR>
				The Bell Jar
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				This autobiograpical work eloquently tracks the author's descent into madness. Residents of Evansville, Il. challenged its use in school because it contains sexual material and advocates an "objectionable" philosophy.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0316769487/acluA/">
				J.D. Salinger
				<BR>
				Catcher in the Rye
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				The story of a young man's expulsion from school and subsequent nervous breakdown is a censor's favorite. It has been banned many times for reasons ranging from "profanity" and "sexual references" to charges of blasphemy and the claim that it "undermines morality." One 1983 attempt to ban the book simply gave "the book's contents" as the reason.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0140042393/acluA/">
				John Steinbeck
				<BR>
				The Grapes of Wrath
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				An epic novel of life during the Depression, The Grapes of Wrath has been censored countless times. First burned by the St. Louis public library in 1939, it was challenged again in 1989 in an 11th-grade English class in Westwood, California.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0440194784/acluA/">
				Kurt Vonnegut
				<BR>
				Welcome to the Monkey House
				<P>
			</A>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				An Alabama teacher was dismissed in 1970 for assigning this collection of short stories to her 11th grade English class, because the book promoted "the killing off of elderly people and free sex."
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0060812508/acluA/">
				Richard Wright
				<BR>
				Black Boy
			</A>
			<P>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				Richard Wright's pathbreaking book about the black experience in the U.S. was removed, along with nine other titles, by Island Trees, NY schools in 1976. The books were considered "immoral, anti-American, anti-Christian, or just plain filthy." The restriction was lifted by a ruling from the U.S. Supreme Court in 1982.
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
			<P>
			<P>
			<A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ISBN%3D0888992262/acluA/">
				Little Red Riding Hood
			</A>
			<P>
			<P>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
				A traditional version of this children's folk tale was removed from schools in Empire, CA in 1990 because Little Red Riding Hood brought a bottle of wine to her grandmother. Authorities claimed the story "condones the use of alcohol."
				<P>
			</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER>	<FONT SIZE="-1">[ <A HREF="bbwind.html">Banned Books Week Top Page</A> | <A HREF="howmany.html">Have you Read?</A> |  <A HREF="bbwmatch.html">Banned Books Quiz</A> |  <A HREF="order.html">Order Banned Books</A> |  <A HREF="bbwlinks.html">Other Resources</A> ] </FONT>
</CENTER>		</BLOCKQUOTE>
		<CENTER>
			<A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map">
				<IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP="ISMAP" BORDER="0">
			</A>
			<P>
		</P>
		<H6>
			<I>
				Copyright 1996, The American Civil Liberties Union
			</I>
		</H6>
