<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>AOL Transcript 1/25/96 Mike Farrell </h1>
<h5>Copyright 1996 America Online, Inc.</h5>
<p><b> 
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Welcome Mike!
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Can you tell us some more about your activism?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Thanks very much, K, nice to be here.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Sure.  I have opposed the death penalty for as long as I can
remember, but became much more active in my work against it during the late
'70s, when the return of executions in this country post-Furman was feared.
 From that point I've done a lot of speaking around the country, and have
been involved with the cases of a number of individuals on death row.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> We are also joined by David Riley an ACLU host and a
co-moderator for our vigil tonight.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Say hi, David.
 <p> <b>
 Driley7     :</b> ::bows : :  :)
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Audience members, you may send your questions and comments to
David. You should also know that we may be bringing people up on stage to
talk one-on-one to Mike Farrell. But, let's get to the questions.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> The first comes from ToddS67 who asks..
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> what motivated you to get involved in this issue?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Well, as I indicated, I've always felt killing people was
immoral.  The killing of people by the state seems to me to be just as
immoral as that done in the heat of passion, if not more so.  More than
that, it seems to me that state killing teaches people that the answer to
violence is violence, and that will get us nowhere fast.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Okay, the next question comes from Pgacds and asks a tough
question.
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b>  how would you deal with habitual offenders?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Clearly, some people, by their actions, indicate that they are
incapable of behaving in an appropriate manner.  That being so, I think they
have to be separated from society for as long as is necessary in order for
them to be rehabilitated.  In some, very sad, cases, that may mean for the
rest of their lives.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Thanks, Mike.  I have a question.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Sure.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> How does all this publicity-mongering around the execution
reflect on us?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Well, I guess that depends upon what you mean.  If you are
asking about how it makes us look to the rest of the world, I'd say it
paints a very sad picture. Even here at home, I think the sensationalism
around death-dealing creates an atmosphere of violence. 
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Okay, next comment from Wiredwill who writes
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> People are going to die anyway. The point is to fill life with
compassion, not aggression. More sticks don't put out the fire. Way to go Mike.
 <p> <b>
KeenanCLU   :</b> Not quite a question, but the encouragement is appreciated.
<p> <b> 
 MikefDPF    :</b> Thanks very much.  I agree that what we need is more
understanding and more thoughtful interaction.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Here's sort of an odd question, but I'm curious to hear your
reply.
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> Not that it matters much, but WHY would someone choose the
firing squad over lethal injection?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Of course it's not possible to get into the head of one in the
incredibly stressful situation that is death row, but I think we first of
all have to understand that that situation produces inappropriate behavior
in and of itself.  In this case, as Utah law allows the condemned person
that choice, and as I think he's aware of the furor that is likely to result
from what is obviously a barbaric response on the part of this government,
it may be that he wants to make a statement in his choice.  Either way I
think we have to understand that this is state-assisted suicide.  Nothing
more, nothing less.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> I don't think that is the sort of business we ought to be in
as a civilized country.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> The next question is from Highland who is concerned about his
taxes...
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> What about people like Charles Manson, who has made it clear
that if let out would kill again? Why should taxpayers pay for the upkeep of
such criminals? 
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> What the questioner needs to understand is that keeping a
hopelessly wounded (psychically) person in prison for life is much cheaper
than executing him or her.  Studies show that it costs three to four times
as much to execute as it does to imprison for life.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Then there is the question of the moral price that we as a
society pay for doing murder.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> We'll be looking to bring some folks up on stage soon.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Happy to meet them.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> In the meantime, Mike, tell us a little bit about the details
of the execution. 
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> What I understand,  at least in this case, is that he will be
strapped into a chair with a wall behind it and a tray beneath it (for the
blood).  A wall  before him will have holes in it for the shooters to aim
their weapons through.  All but one of the shooters will have live
ammunition - one will have a blank cartridge.  No one will know who had the
blank. I think that fact alone suggests an awareness, perhaps unconscious,
of the wrongness of the act. 
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b>  At the order, all will fire at a designated spot on Mr.
Taylor's chest - over his heart.  One study showed that death by firing
squad in Utah has historically taken between a few seconds and 27 minutes to
cause the death of the individual.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Here's an interesting one...
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> Isn't it (the firing squad) at least more honest?  It doesn't
sanitize the killing.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> I agree that it doesn't sanitize the killing.  that also
doesn't make it right.  It is a throwback to an earlier time in our country,
I think, but it causes the same result.  It's not an &quot;honesty&quot; that I
appreciate, frankly.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Okay, we are inviting the staff attorney for the ACLU of Utah
on stage now. Perhaps she can give us an update on the goings-on there and
on the rally which took place today.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> She should be here any moment.  In the meantime, let's take
another question..
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> Can you explain that answer better...re :  cheaper to keep
alive in prison than execute?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Sure.  the Supreme Court has said that &quot;death is different.&quot;
As a result of that fact and the fear of doing wrong by executing innocent
people, they have instituted certain required procedures in capital cases.
Bifurcated trials, for instance, which means a two-part trial - one part to
determine guilt and one part to determine sentence.  All of this, plus the
required appeals that must be allowed by law (hopefully to ferret out the
mistaken convictions) make the process very lengthy and very expensive.
Life in prison, on the other hand, requires only a simple trial and, if
found guilty, the sentence to be carried out, without many of the appeals.
It is infinitely less expensive.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Okay, we now have Jensie Anderson, the staff attorney for the
ACLU of Utah on stage with us.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Welcome Jensie! Do you have an update for us?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Actually, let me add, that in California alone, we would save
between $90 and $120,000,000 per year by simply eliminating the death penalty.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> Thank you.  An honor to be here.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> John Taylor is still committed to going through with his
execution despite the best efforts of myself and other attorneys and
abolitionists. At this point, it is unlikely that a last minute appeal will
be filed.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> What does that mean then, Jensie?  What will be happening
between now and midnight your time? 
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> At this point, they are preparing for the execution. His
attorneys are still with him in hopes of a last minute appeal. However, John
is determined to end his life this evening.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Jensie, has he said why he has elected the firing squad?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> For several reasons.  First, I think he wanted to bring some
attention to his case, particularly to draw attention to the barbaric
conditions at the prison here. It was also a method he chose when he was
sentenced six years ago.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Jensie, is it true John Albert Taylor converted to Catholicism
last week?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> He has been studying Catholicism for over a year, and was
baptized last week.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> How does religion play into this whole story?  what's the
feeling in Utah?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> Historically, the firing squad was used for &quot;blood atonement&quot;
which is of religious significance in Utah.  It involves the spilling of
blood in repentance for the crime of murder
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Taylor was a Mormon, is that correct?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> however, for John, there is no religious significance.  He is
focusing on the hereafter with his priest.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> He was a mormon, but was excommunicated when he was convicted.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> However, we should say that many Mormons are very horrified by
this execution by firing squad as well.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> Yes, they are.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Mike or Jensie, how do most religious organizations come out
on the death penalty?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> All the mainstream religious organizations are opposed to the
death penalty.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> The Catholic diocese here in Utah has actively participated in
the abolitionist movement.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Jensie, hang on with us here a little longer.  We're going to
take another question for Mike.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> The US Bishops conference recently took a very strong stand
against the death penalty, as did the Pope
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> Mike, I was pro-death penalty until Nebraska recently executed
a confessed killer. Unfortunately the entire episode turned into a political
carnival.  After the execution was completed, people were dancing and
cheering in Lincoln.  Yet my original question remains.  Why not work to
stop abortion which is claiming a much higher toll? 
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> i think it's a different question.  You certainly have every
right to work against abortion, and many, as you know, do.  the killing of
living, already born, human beings is a sign of total barbarism, in my view,
and one I choose to stand against.  The other question is a private one, in
my view, between a woman and her doctor.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Let's take another question.
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> Mike - Don't you find it ironic that one blank will be fired,
so that each shooter may feel that they weren't part of the execution - in
so far as that is an acknowledgement that there is something inherently
wrong *with* the execution?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Yes, I agree totally.  I think it's a confession, of sorts,
that they are aware of the wrongheadedness of what they're doing.  I only
wish they'd accept that and move to a better place.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> If you are just joining us, you are at the ACLU's online vigil
for John Albert Taylor who is to be executed at midnight in Utah. 
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Mike Farrell, actor and activist is on stage with us for the
duration of the vigil. We will be here from 12-3 a.m. EST.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> We are also joined by the ACLU of Utah's staff attorney,
Jensie Anderson.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Our co-moderator David Riley is taking your questions and
comments and will be inviting members of the audience on stage to talk with
Mike and Jensie. In the meantime, let's get back to your questions and comments.
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> What did this person do to get this type of sentence?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Perhaps Jensie can better answer.  As I understand it, he was
convicted of murdering a young girl. There may have been sexual acts
involved as well.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> He was convicted of the murder of a young girl.  He maintains
his innocence.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Is there any reason to believe he is innocent?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> The trial was handled very poorly.  No jury and his attorneys
had never handled a capitol case before.  No experts or witnesses were
brought on his behalf. He has very good issues should he choose to continue
his appeals.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> You see, this is the problem with the whole issue.  WE find
time after time that those convicted had lousy representation, or none at
all, and no way to actually know if the party is guilty of the act.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> But, at this time, he won't be doing that?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> Even prison guards, who are generally pro death penalty, feel
this is wrong. The prison has had to offer psychological counseling for the
staff as a result.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> No, he has chosen to stop the appeals process.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> We have with us now an audience participant who may not feel
the same as all you liberals! Howdy SSI, do you have some comments?
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> Isn't the death penalty more for the victim than society?
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Mike?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> I don't understand the question.
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> We are not try for rehabilitation, we are extracting justice.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Justice is intended to be fair and appropriate.  What you're
talking about is vengeance.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> What is the harm in trying to rehabilitate someone who has
gone wrong?
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> Retribution or vengeance is the whole reason for the death
penalty, it is designed to prevent future acts of extreme violence.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> If I may, the victim does not benefit from the death of the
accused.  Indeed, in this case the mother of the victim does not support the
death of John Taylor.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> The notion of killing to prevent future acts of violence on
the part of an individual is tantamount to suggesting that we can pick out
personality types that are likely to do crimes and eliminate them in
advance. What kind of society does that?
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> In Vietnam I was forced to kill, I didn't like it, but it did
keep friends alive. What is the difference? 
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Vietnam was a war.  People were, at least in theory, shooting
at you.  What you did was to defend yourself and/or your friends.  this is
not the same.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Is that the case here, though, SSI? 
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> Yes, by executing this man we are defending my daughter.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> This is taking a human being, caging him, telling him we're
going to kill him, torturing him with that knowledge and going through the
ritual of pre-execution activities until we have assuaged our consciences
enough to feel we've done all we can. Then we kill.  How does that help your
daughter?
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> What did he do to that 11 year year old?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> If you were listening, he says he didn't do anything to that
11 year old.  but even if he did, how is she served by doing a form of the
same thing to him?
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> It keeps him from being like the case in Texas where the man
escaped and killed again.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> Are other children served by seeing society kill? 
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> I know of no such case in Texas.  The idea of killers escaping
comes from too much bad fiction.
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> I believe they could be served by seeing it instead of hiding
it from the press.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> How would they be served?
 <p> <b>
 SSIMAGIC    :</b> No sir, He was even on America's most wanted, captured him
from a tip
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> If what you say is true, and I'm not sure it is, does one
anomalous incident justify our killing the 3000 people we have on our death
rows today?  Some of them are innocent, some are mentally retarded, most are
mentally damaged in one form or another.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> What time is it in Utah, Jensie?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> 11 :05
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Where exactly is the execution to take place?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> It will take place at the prison, in a specially prepared
warehouse. John is currently in a death watch cell.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Folks, you are at the ACLU's online vigil for John Albert
Taylor who is sentenced to be executed in one hour by firing squad.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> We are joined by MASH's Mike Farrell, actor and activist.  And
by Jensie Anderson, ACLU staff attorney in Utah. 
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Mike, this isn't the first unique execution this week, is it?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> As I understand it, a man was hanged in Delaware this week.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Jensie, are folks commenting on that execution in Utah?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> There is a lot of discussion here.The legislature is
considering a bill to eliminate the firing squad.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Perhaps replacing it with stoning?
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Is it likely to pass?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> Actually, it is wallowing, presumably because of its religious
significance
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Let's take an interesting question...
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> Do you believe  MASH was too violent and changed peoples views
on death?
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> I believe that one is for Mike. Sorry, Jensie.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> No, I think MASH was reflective of the situation of a war and
showed people trying to lend a helping healing hand in that situation. I'm
not sure what you mean about changing people's views on death.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU :</b> The next question is  from Dewdropper, who comments..
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> I know that the death penalty is rather cruel and unusual,
however, what other deterrent should our government use to make criminals
respect the law?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Life in prison is one possibility.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> There are a multitude of options.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Having elected officials respect the law is another.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Mike and Jensie, here's a particularly interesting question
from AABrewer...
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> I was in UT a couple of years ago when Warren Andrews was put
to death. He wasn't merely martyred, he was made out to be a hero. Some
forgot completely about the crimes he committed, and lost sight of the issue
at hand. How do we keep that from happening?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> First of all, it was William Andrews.  I know of no one who
wanted to make him a hero, but I know many who felt that the punishment did
not fit the crime. You may be aware of the fact that Mr. Andrews was not in
the room when the people in question were killed.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> I agree with you that it's important to not lose sight of the
issue at hand.  But I think the issue at hand is our humanity.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Mike, here's one..
 <p> <b>
 Question    :</b> Is this an act visited upon whites in Utah more than people of
color?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Jensie?
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> More than 2,800 men and women were imprisoned on death rows in
the U.S by mid-1994.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> I can tell you that it is visited on people of color in the
country in numbers disproportionate to their percentage in the population.
 <p> <b>
 Jensieclu   :</b> Whites represent 35 percent of murder victims, but the
overwhelming majority, 85%, were convicted of killing whites. Whites have
rarely been sentenced to death for killing blacks.  Indeed, since the death
penalty was reinstated in 1977 only one white has died for killing a black.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> We have with us on stage, KateHM.  Kate do you have questions
or comments?
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Kate, don't be afraid to speak up.  We're going to take
another question in the meantime.
  <p> <b>
KeenanCLU   :</b> Sorry for the blank air there folks.  AOL.. you understand
<p> <b> 
 Question    :</b> Would you have this much compassion for those on death row if
one of your family members was a victim?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Of course, if one of my family members was a victim I'd be
angry and want to tear the individual apart but the reason we have a system
of justice is to separate our personal emotional response from the
imposition of justice.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Murder Victim's Families for Reconciliation is an organization
made up of victim's families and they all know there is no value in
continuing the spiral of violence.
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> Many of the members of Death Penalty Focus have lost family
members to violence.  They maintain that the death penalty lowers us all to
the level of the original perpetrator of the violent act.
 <p> <b>
 KeenanCLU   :</b> Mike, what is this thing people sign saying they do not want
anyone executed because of them? That is, if they or their family members
are killed by someone?
 <p> <b>
 MikefDPF    :</b> There is a pledge, made up by a group of religious women in
