<head>
<title>Transcript 12/20/95 Roberta Richman</title>
</head>
<body>
<blockquote>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>AOL Transcript 12/20/95 Roberta Richman</h1>
<h5>Copyright 1995 America Online, Inc.</h5>
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Evening everyone. I'm Phil Gutis, the ACLU's media relations
director and slightly flustered host of our CenterStage series. I'm having some silly
technical woes tonight, but let's see how this goes.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Tonight, we're continuing our discussion about the nation's penal
system. Our guest is Roberta Richman, Warden of the Rhode Island Women's Prison. Let me say
a couple of words about Warden Richman and then we'll try to take your questions.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Roberta Richman is currently the Warden of Women's Facilities at the
Rhode Island Department of Corrections. She is a consistently progressive voice on female
offender issues. For Richman, an ideal alternative to incarceration of women
criminals would be placement in a community home or a safe, controlled environment that
would foster a healthy re-entry into society.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Warden Richman, let me open with the first question if I may. How
did you get involved in corrections in the first place?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    I began working at the prison in 1979. My first job was as the coordinator of a
prison arts program, and I got it indirectly through doing volunteer work.  My previous
experience had been as a working artist and an instructor at the Univ. of Rhode  Island of
Fine Arts. The prison was looking someone to coordinate programs in the arts, and I was looking
for a full-time job.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  We're talking with Warden Roberta Richman. I've got my system
working again and our next question comes from Mike97ADA.
<p><b>
Question:</b> what kind of crimes are most women in for in Rhode Island?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    Variety of crime...about 33% are serving sentences for drug
related offences.  We have people who are serving sentences for prostitution, shop lifting...the
majority...about 75%, not only in Rhode Island, but nationwide, are serving relatively shot
sentences for non-violent crimes.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  We're talking with Warden Roberta Richman of Rhode Island. Our next
question comes from Driley7.
<p><b>
Question:</b> Many people view prisons as places of punishment, others hope they
are places of rehabilitation. Can they be both? Should they be either?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    To my way of thinking, the punishment is the incarceration itself... that is
separating a woman from her family and her community is the punishment. Once she's in jail, we
should be preparing her to rethink her life and gain the skills she will need to become a
responsible citizen.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Let me ask the next question: To what do you attribute the current
anger or meanspiritness that seems to be sweeping America when it comes to criminal justice?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    That's a very troubling issue for me. The climate, in general, is, I think, a reaction
to growing violence in the community and pervasive fear. I think people are simply fearful of
offenders on the street, and see prison as an answer. Those of us working in system understand
all to well that simply putting a violent offender will not solve the problem. People fail to realize
that most offenders are in prison for a relatively short period of time.  The average length of
sentence is approximately 2-1/2 years. If we fail to provide an opportunity for prisoners while
they are institutionalized to rehabilitate themselves, they will emerge even more violent.
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    I'm not sure that we can ever make the public truly understand that.  The level of
their anger presently is just to deep.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Warden Roberta Richman comes from Gumby1618
and is a follow up.
<p><b>
Question:</b> What form of education or work training do you offer the inmates
for when they are released so they can have a more productive life?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    Every prison does different kinds of programs. Most prisons now do offer
educational opportunities and some job training, recognizing that lack of skills in those areas is a
root cause of crime. Prisoners in general have usually not completed a high-school education. 
About 22% of them are functionally illiterate and in the case of female offenders, the vast
majority have never held meaningful jobs. We do a variety of basic education programs,
including basic literacy, high-school equivalency, English as a second language, special ed. and
some college classes.
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    We also do job training and job preparation, computer literacy, and preparation
for job interviewing.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Warden Richman comes from Britron.
<p><b>
Question:</b> Roberta, I worked Atlanta Pre-trial detention center and I found
that many of those women are cold and hard and don't accept rehab.  Some do.  But by
softening sentences, don't you agree that we give carte-blanche to additional criminal
behavior??? 
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    I don't think you can generalize. It is very difficult to measure when a woman is
truly ready for treatment. I don't believe in softening sentences, but it's important to define what
you mean by softening. I support sentences that involve high structured treatment, to include
substance abuse, mental health counseling, academic and job training.
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    The length of a woman's sentence is not as critical as is what she does while she's
incarcerated. I don't think any sentence is soft. The restriction of freedom, and the separation,
usually from children, in my mind, can never be soft.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question comes from SocWorker.
<p><b>
Question:</b> Would you say that the sentences for women are more or less severe
for women than men?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    The length of the sentences and the number of women incarcerated, during the
decade of the '80's and into the 90's, increased about 300%, which exceeded the increase for
males. It's hard to say whether that increase is a reflection of equality or harsher treatment.  I
think women are receiving more or less similar sentences then men, but are committing, for the
most part, less serious and less violent crimes, so it may appear as though they are getting less
harsh sentences.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Warden Roberta Richman comes from Edelmaus.
<p><b>
Question:</b> What is your reaction to people who claim that prisoners live lives of "luxury"
with amenities such as "cable tv and weight rooms"?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    I find that whole sentiment to be absurd. Prison environments are very difficult to
manage, and having worked for 12 years in a male maximum security prison, I had many
opportunities to understand fully how important it is to allow inmates to be physically active and
occupy idle time in a positive way. Inmates who are watching TV or working out in a weight
room are far less likely to be involved in negative behavior. Although the public perceives those
activities as coddling, prison administrators and correctional officers understand how important
they are to institution management.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question comes from Geomandel and is a follow up to the earlier
question about job training and educational opportunity.
<p><b>
Question:</b> do any of these inmates recognize the courses as major opportunities?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    You can't generalize.  Inmates are people. Some of them sincerely appreciate the
opportunities we provide, and others see it as a way to pass time, or please the parol board. It's
difficult to know what motivates inmates. My general philosophy is regardless of why a woman
chooses to participate in a program, if, as a result her skills are enhanced, and she takes
something away with her, we have all benefited.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Another question from Edelmaus for Warden Roberta Richman.
<p><b>
Question:</b> Is there any evidence that the death penalty deters crime, either
in its present form, or in the "swifter, more efficient" form currently being proposed by
the far right?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    I am against the death penalty. I don't believe it serves as a deterrent, and am
grateful that we don't have it in Rhode Island. I don't believe that there is any evidence that it
serves any good purpose.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  An interesting question from SocWorker.
<p><b>
Question:</b> Do you believe that legalizing prostitution would help to relieve
prison crowding and that regulating it as a business would help to protect women?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    This is an unpopular position I take, but as is the case in many countries around
the world, where prostitution is not considered a crime, and where it is controlled it works well.
The most frustrating aspect of criminalizing prostitution is that only the female is punished.  The
"John" goes home to his family, and generally pays no price. Given today's high risk behavior
around HIV and AIDS, a sensible public policy around this issue is essential. 
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    I've never met a prostitute that told me she likes the work. For most of them, it's a
means to an end.  They do it because it's the only skill they have. 
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  And I'll jump in with the next question: Where do you see the criminal justice
system headed? Chain gangs, stripped privileges? Is another Attica far away?
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    I guess that will depend on who sets public policy, and given the direction many
prisons are headed in, it's a frightening prospect. Whenever I have opportunity to shape opinion
on this question, I stress the need for intermediate sanctions. While I do believe there is a need
to incarcerate the most violent of our offenders, the majority, and in particular the majority of
female offenders, should be in settings other then the institution.  I think this is the case for both
male and female inmates who have committed non-violent crimes. I don't think we can afford,
either morally or fiscally, to incarcerate every offender.
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    We would all be so much better off if we could separate out those who are ready
for and capable of restarting their lives by placing them in environments in the community
and helping them to reintegrate in a responsible fashion.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Our last question for Warden Roberta Richman comes from Edelmaus.
<p><b>
Question:</b> What is your experience with groups like Colson's "Prison Fellowship"? Do you
find such conservative Christian groups to be helpful or harmful? 
<p><b>
RbrtaRchmn:</b>    We have an extensive chaplaincy program representing many faiths. The "Prison
Fellowship" program is not represented in our prison, so I'm not very familiar with it. However
I'm a strong supporter of any force that serves to give the offender hope for his or her future. If
the "Prison Fellowship" does that, then it may be serving some good for some people.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Please join me in thanking Warden Roberta Richman for sharing her
perspective on this critically important topic. And remember, please join us in the ACLU's Free
Speech Zone at any time day or night to discuss criminal justice or anything else on your mind.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>  Goodnight everyone. Have a merry or happy!
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
