http://www.aclu.org:80/about/transcripts/chse1205.html 204.243.96.55 19970213142940 text/html 13417
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 13-Feb-97 14:28:23 GMT
Last-modified: Saturday, 27-Jan-96 17:51:48 GMT
Content-length: 13229
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>AOL Transcript Chase Riveland</title>
</head>
<body>
<blockquote>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>AOL Transcript Chase Riveland</h1>
<h5>Copyright 1995 America Online, Inc.</h5>
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Good evening everyone. After a little bit of confusion, we're ready
to start our event tonight. I'm Phil Gutis, the host of the ACLU CenterStage events and
the ACLU's Media Relations Director. We have a special -- and some would say
unexpected -- guest tonight: Chase Riveland, the Secretary of the Washington Stage Department
of Corrections. 
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Riveland has been involved in corrections for more than 30 years,
holding a variety of positions in Wisconsin, Colorado and Washington. He has also served as a
probation and parole agent.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  I'd like to start the questions tonight, if I may: Secretary
Riveland, how would you characterize the current atmosphere regarding our penal system in
America?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     In a short term I think its "cranky." Unfortunately as people struggle to find
solutions for drugs violence and crime, they've settled on incarceration as the singular solution and
have failed to address severe problems in our communities that could lead to real solutions. The
net effect is to burden our justice system at all levels to put our states and local jurisdictions in a
situation of investing massive amounts of money in prisons that could be well directed toward
other social, environmental, and educational uses.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  We're talking about prisons and prisoners rights with the Secretary of Corrections
of Washington State, Chase Riveland. The next question comes from DWhite1974.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Chase, doesn't the "lock 'em up and throw away the key" approach -- the kind
advocated by pandering politicians today -- just make criminals slicker and more bitter when they
re-enter society?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     In many cases that's true. However, we all need to take some responsibility for the
present environment.  We have allowed the political environment to become one that doesn't
allow even thoughtful politicians the opportunity to develop constructive policies around crime,
drugs, and violence. We all need to help level the playing field so that the thoughtful
officials can take that risk.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Our topic tonight is the nation's penal system. Our guest is Chase
Riveland, Secretary of  Corrections of Washington State. The next question comes from
SterlingEE.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Chase,  what will be the effect on the number of Blacks under
correctional control if we spend $10 billion more to construct prisons in the next 5 years as
the GOP proposes?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     It is my belief it will simply be a continuation of the trend we've seen over the last
few years. I believe the bureau of Justice Statistics report recently released indicated that for the
first time in this countries history, blacks in prisons and jails country wide now out number whites.
As long as we continue to incarcerate drug offenders at the rates we are and depend upon
incarceration for all of our justice problems that trend will  only get worse. The $10 billion could
be used to provide opportunities in our inner cities, significant amounts of drug treatment, and
educational and vocational opportunities that would have some chance of mitigating our crime
problem. Unfortunately, congress seems to be headed in exactly the opposite direction
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Chase Riveland of the Washington State Department of
Corrections comes from Mrs. OwlW and is, in some ways, a follow up.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> How are we supposed to deal with the real issues when Congress and
state legislatures keep cutting programs that may actually help?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     It is my opinion that as we have taken the path of incarcerating so many people so
long, that our state legislators have been shocked at the money being diverted from other major
needs such as higher education and K- 12. Their response has been to cut traditional programs in
our correctional facilities and to create such noble statements as having inmates pay for everything
from recreation to health care despite the fact that few inmates have money. The net effect, I fear,
is we may return to the early era of prisons of the late 70's in which over crowded institutions
with little activity resulted in at best federal court intervention and at worst disturbances and riots.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Secretary Chase Riveland of Washington State
comes from Hyperkat.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Would you turn violent people lose on the population at large?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     Absolutely not. One of the things that a professionally operated prison can do best
is incapacitate predatory, violent and dangerous offenders. I have known many offenders over the
years that simply never should be returned to the community. My argument is not about those.
My argument is about young, nonviolent offenders, people who's major problem is addiction,
people who's major problem is the absence of opportunity. We need be prudent and selective on
our use of incarceration.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Raven 472 has the next question for Chase Riveland, Secretary of
Corrections in Washington State.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> With the overpopulation of prisons, do you think drugs should be legalized, since
most of the prison population is incarcerated on drug related offences?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     Certainly the country needs to look at all options in dealing with crime and drugs. I
suspect our solutions are somewhere between legalization and over incarceration. I am not
personally a proponent of legalization of all drugs, however my response to addiction, possession
and the accompanying problems should be something much different then today.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Here's an interesting question from Ahvienda for Chase Riveland of
Washington state that gets to the heart of the penal vs. corrections system.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> So, Mr. Riveland, are you suggesting that these criminals may be
"curable" to use a medical description?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     I am not suggesting that all criminals can be "treated." However a great body of
research suggests to us that in the singular area of substance addiction we can, with adequate
resources be quite successful in treating people in the community. Today, particularly at the state
level, we are incarcerating predominantly users and people who sell because they use, not the big
drug dealer. It is that group of people that I'm referencing.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Secretary Chase Riveland of the Washington
State Department of Corrections comes from Jimeo 722.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Most think prisons are too luxurious, with cable and golf courses.
In your experience, are they too comfortable to constitute punishment?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     Absolutely not. Certainly there have been vignettes of instances of what would
appear to be overindulgence. However people are sent to prison as punishment not for
punishment. People who are involving themselves in recreational programs, including weight
lifting frequently maintain much healthier lifestyles in prison and are less of a drain on health care
costs. More importantly we in the correctional field know that if we cannot maintain high levels of
activity to include TV in our over crowded facilities we are looking at a bleak future.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Secretary Chase Riveland comes from TurnkeyDM.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Mr. Riveland, would you agree that if public new the types of
behavior that your staff  has to deal with on daily basis that they would not only be appalled but
would require more restriction on inmates rights?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     I believe that for the most part the inmates in our system have daily behavior that is
appropriate and is goal oriented. Like any community we have people who are trouble makers,
who act out, who are assaultive and abusive. Like in our own communities we isolate and
penalize them. I believe if I could better portray to the general public what life in prison really is
like they would be willing to dedicate more resources to the correctional system. Unfortunately
do to the closed nature of prisons combined with the need of the media to only display the worst
of situations we are unable to fairly represent what prison life is like.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  JoanBeth has the next question for Washington's Secretary of Corrections Chase
Riveland.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Please comment on privatization of prisons.
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     Privatization from time to time has been characterized, particularly in state
legislatures as a silver bullet that will help us run things more cheaply. There are instances around
the country where that has been true and there are instances when it has been a disaster. In
looking at the issue of cost, in my opinion, it is simply playing around the fringes. The real issue
and the real point of discussion should not be who can lock people up the cheapest but rather
should be locking up so many people with the accompanying high cost at all.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Let me ask the next question of Secretary Riveland: What do you
think of Congress's so-called STOP legislation?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     I have for some time been a member of the group called STOP STOP. To much
attention originally was given by Congress, the media, and some attorney generals to the frivolous
inmate suit portion of the legislation. Most destructive in my opinion are the limitations put on
jurisdictions to fashion meaningful consent decrees, the limitations on attorney's fees, and the
other portions of the STOP legislation that limit reasonable and responsible federal court
intervention
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Secretary Chase Riveland comes from SlvrStorm.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Instead of low activity, how do you feel about going back to the
chain gangs?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     In my opinion we are reintroducing a strong image of slavery and
brutality. I told my legislators and governor that I wouldn't do chain gangs for 2 reasons. First, the
inmates on my work crews work to hard to slow them down with chains. Secondly, Alabama and
Arizona bought all the chain.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Our next question for Chase Riveland comes from Iridium1.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Can you offer advice on how to convince the average person -- those
enraged with the notion that prisoners should be treated humanely -- that our system
is in desperate need of reformation, for our own benefit?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     I think many of us do a poor job, myself included in doing appropriate education.
The persons who are encouraging "tough on crime" through more incarceration and tougher
conditions use images of Willie Horton, and crying victims relatives as their symbols. Many of us
talk about hundreds of thousands of people being incarcerated and millions of dollars being spent.
Those large figures have little meaning the average person and do not draw the emotional
response of the former. We must learn better techniques for getting our citizens emotionally and
intellectually involved in this quest for solutions for crime and violence. If not we'll continue to
have only an irrational debate with irrational solutions.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Our last question for Secretary Riveland comes from LFGH.
<p>
<b>Question:</b> Isn't England trying a new system.  50% serving time/25% rehab/25%
aftercare.  They said they was seeing a small decline.  Has America checked this out?
<p>
<b>RivelandC:</b>     I think there are many things we should be looking at around the
country. Some states are experimenting with restorative justice. Some are doing a better job of
providing community drug treatment. There are many successful drug courts. The key is not to
find singular solutions in my opinion. We must first determine that incarceration should be used
only for those people the community must be protected from. We then should tailor solutions or
punishments for the rest in some manner that encourages or demands that our citizens and
communities must be responsible and involved.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  Please join me in thanking Secretary Chase Riveland of the Washington State
Department of Corrections for joining our forum tonight. We plan on continuing this discussion
over the next couple of months as the country struggles to find a balance between punishment and
rehabilitation.
<p>
<b>PhilCLU:</b>  On Thursday at 7 P.M. Eastern, we'll be exploring a related topic --
the nation's drug policy -- with Eric Sterling. And, of course, please join us at any time in the
ACLU's Free Speech Zone to debate this issue or any other!
<p>
</blockquote>


<CENTER><A HREF="/graphics/toolbar.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/toolbar.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A><P>
