<head>
<title>AOL Transcript 9/26/95 Laura Murphy</title>
</head>
<body>
<blockquote>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>AOL Transcript 9/26/95 Laura Murphy</h1>
<h5>Copyright 1995 America Online, Inc.</h5>
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Evening everyone. Welcome to the joint online appearance by the ACLU
and the NRA to discuss our 24-point plan to address federal law enforcement that
will be announced tomorrow at a Washington news conference.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Joining us tonight on the Stage are Tanya K. Metaksa, the Executive
Director of the NRA Institute for Legislative Action. And Laura W. Murphy, the Director of the ACLU's National Washington office.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Let's open it up with opening statements, if we may. Laura. Anything
to start with?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	 I am overjoyed at the prospect of widening the coalition in favor
of greater accountability in federal law enforcement efforts.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Tanya, anything to start off with?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	The problems we are focusing upon today are not the problems of
individual law enforcement agents, but problems of policy and leadership.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Okay, we're talking with Tanya Metaksa of the NRA and Laura Murphy
of the ACLU. The first question comes from CBurgL.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Is it the ACLU's position that civil rights violations occured at
Ruby Ridge?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	We have not independently analyzed the events at Ruby Ridge, but we believe that there was lack of sufficient supervision, and a tendancy to make up rules
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	in mid-course, during the stand-off, which lead to tragic consequences.
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	The Department of Justice's report indicated that civil rights
violations occurred. For the first time in our history, you've seen five federal law
enforcement agents take the Fifth in testimony before Congress.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking about Federal Law Enforcement with Tanya Metaksa of
the NRA and Laura Murphy of the ACLU. The next question comes from DWhite1974
and is addressed to the NRA.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Tanya, a lot of us civil libertarians are wary of the NRA because
it seems to ignore nine of the ten Amendments that make up the Bill of Rights. Where is the
NRA's committment to due process, fair trial, etc?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	We support the entire Bill of Rights, from the First through the
Tenth amendments, but we focus on the Second. That doesn't mean that due process, fair
trial, and the Fourth Amendment are not important. Just because we support strong
punishment for people convicted of violent crimes doesn't mean we would have criminals
punished in violation of any part of the Constitution.
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	The ACLU and the NRA have very different agendas , but we agree on
several important issues having to do with greater accountability for federal law
enforcement procedures. I think that our organizations both agree that no new powers should
be given to federal law enfocement agencies (of which there are over 100) until we can
be sure that procedures are in place that safeguard the constitutional rights of all.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking about federal law enforcement and other issues with
the NRA and the ACLU. The next question comes from XPhileAmy.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Would banning guns disrupt the balance of powers that our nation is
famous for?
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Tanya?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	"Banning guns" is not the issue we are here to discuss.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Laura, anything to add?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	The balance of powers that our government is known for has little
or nothing to do with banning guns, but more to do with the seperation of powers and the checks and balances that they give to the legislative, executive and judicial branches.
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	We are concerned about powers granted to federal law enforcement
agencies that are being misused.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking about federal law enforcement with Tanya Metaksa of
the NRA and Laura rphy of the ACLU. The next question comes from RonaldCor and is
addressed to Laura.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	LWM:  What does ACLU mean by "acountability in law enforcement"?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	What we mean is that law enforcement operates by commonly
understood rules that comport with the bill of rights and Constitution. For example, we would not expect a federal law enforcement official to enter someone's home without securing a valid warrant, because to do otherwise would violate the Fourth Amendment.  this may seem like a simple proposition, when in fact, we have uncovered numerous allegations of warrantless searches on the part of federal officials.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>Tanya, anything to add? What is the NRA's definition?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	We believe that federal agents must be held to the same standards
as all other law enforcement officers and other citizens.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking with Tanya Metaksa of the NRA and Laura Murphy of the
ACLU. The next question comes from Zarrdoz.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	This is for either participant: Do you see the ACLU and the NRA
working together on any other projects in the future?
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Tanya? You first?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	This project has been on-going since Jan. 1993, and since that time
Pres. Clinton has not responded to our calls for a commission to study the abuses by
federal law enforcement agencies. Until this project is completed, NRA will continue to pursue this agenda. However, we will always try to work with the ACLU in civil rights matters.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Laura?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	I would hope that the ACLU and the NRA would not only continue to
work on the commission but would also work to assure that Congress does not enact poorly
crafted crime and counter-terrorism proposals that expand federal investigatory
powers with no safe guards.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	The next question for Laura Murphy of the ACLU and Tanya Metaksa of
the NRA comes from KYBillG.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Why is Clinton so ready to go for the increased powers.  Is he
getting bad advice.  Has he ever been a civil libertarian?
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Laura?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	HE WAS A CONSTITUTIONAL LAW PROFESSOR AT ONE POINT IN HIS
CAREER!!!!! But I think he feels that it is politically safer to sound tough on crime and hope that his friends in Congress and constituents don't read the fine print.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Tanya? Why do you think the President keeps pushing for expanded
powers?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	It appears that Pres. Clinton wants to appease those in the Dept.
of Justice who are interested in trying to continue the war on drugs, which is taking
increasing amounts of money and other resources to win. They have all forgotten in their
zeal, that it s more important to safeguard the rights of citizens than to catch the drug-runners.
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	Way to go Tanya!
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking with Laura Murphy of the ACLU and Tanya Metaksa of the
NRA. The next question comes from BuyingTim.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	While rushing to reform FBI rules of engagement (which should be),
I believe there is an even more sinister aspect to address:  Law enforcement's increasing
pressure on citizens to become enformants.  That, after all, was the real prime mover, in
Ruby Ridge, for instance. Comments from either Laura or Tayna please?
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Tanya?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	I believe that BATF's attempt to turn Randy Weaver into an informer
was the catalyst for the whole sad episode. The idea of entrapping honest citizens into
informing is obscene.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Laura?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	Informants are notoriously unreliable.  It is not a sound way to
investigate illegal activity because the informant has a motivation to deliver
"something" in order to get paid.
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	IT is important to remember that a federal judge accused BATF of
entrapping Weaver
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Our next question for Tanya Metaksa of the NRA and Laura Murphy of
the ACLU comes from Edie88.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Why are Civil Lib. under such attack from both right and left at
this time?
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Laura?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	Because of the end of the cold war, and increasing political
isolationist policies in the international arena, Americans are being pitted against one
another.  We must avoid the temptations to scapegoat vulnerable groups within our own
borders--an idea fueled by elected officials who are looking to divide and conquer.  If you
villify enough groups frequently, then you create a climate where people feel justified
in denying the targeted groups rights whether we are talking about members of militias or
immigrants.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Tanya, any thoughts?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	 People reach for a safety net when they feel threatened by crime
and criminals. They then prefer the safety of Big Brother telling them what to do
rather than the freedom of self determination.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Our next question comes from Motorman6.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Do either of you think that the American public might be somewhat
paranoid about the powers of the Federal Government?
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Tanya?
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	No. They are not frightened enough of the possibility of some
agency of government into their homes without a warrant, to investigate non-existent
criminal behavior.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Laura?
<p><b>
LWMURPHY:</b>	I believe that the American people are ambivilent.  One one hand
they support simple sounding solutions like more police.  On the other hand I think there is
general concern about things like IRS employees snooping into tax records and illegally
distributing that information to businesses as was the case in the Atlanta IRS field office.  As
long as more powers help in the short run, few think of the long term consequences of
expanded powers being mishandled.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We have time for one more question. It comes from LucyGee and is for
the NRA.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Why doesn't the NRA just come out and say that the 2nd Amend is for
protection against oppressive government?  It has nothing to do with hunting.
<p><b>
Tmetaksa:</b>	We are on record more times than I count, pointing out that the
purpose of the amendment is to guarantee the American people their right to possess the
means with which they can protect life and liberty, that it is not about hunting or any other
sport, such as target shooting.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	I want to thank Tanya Metaksa of the NRA and Laura Murphy of the
ACLU for joining us tonight. Check back in Constitution Hall tomorrow for the
24-point joint plan we'll be releasing tomorrow to the media at a news conference in DC.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Thanks again. And goodnight.


</blockquote>

