<head>
<title>AOL Transcript 10/31/95 Marc Mauer</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff><blockquote>
<h1>AOL Transcript 10/31/95 Marc Mauer</h1>

<h5>Copyright 1995 America Online, Inc.</h5>
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Good evening everyone. I'm Phil Gutis, the ACLU's media director and
our ever welcoming host of our AOL forum. Tonight I'm delighted to welcome to our
CenterStage Marc Mauer for a discussion about our nation's criminal justice
system. 
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Let me take a few moments to introduce our Halloween guest and then
we'll get started with your questions. Remember, to ask questions, use the
Interact icon at the top of your screen.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Marc Mauer is the Assistant Director of The Sentencing Project. He
has directed programs on criminal justice reform for twenty years. He is the
author of some of the most widely cited reports in the field of criminal justice,
including Young Black Men and the Criminal Justice System and the Americans Behind Bars
series.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Marc has served as a consultant to the Bureau of Justice Assistance
and the Office of National Drug Control Policy.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Please join me in welcoming Marc to AOL. And Marc, let me ask the
first question: It seems that every day we are hearing more and more about the idea
that our criminal justice system is indeed racist. Do you believe it to be so?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	I think that there is often a debate about whether criminal justice
policies are consciencely racist. I am more concerned with the outcomes of policies rather
than their intent. For example, I don't know what is in the minds of the members of
Congress when they passed crack cocaine laws in 1986 and 1988 but what we do
know now is that those laws have clearly had a racist effect. And therefore by not acting to change those laws at this point that clearly seems to me to be a racist action.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking with Marc Mauer of The Sentencing Project, which has
become one national leaders in the search for reform of our national criminal
justice policy. Let me ask a followup. Were you suprised to see President Clinton's
speedy signature on the Congressional crack bill?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	Historically after the Sentencing Commission made its
recommendations, the Justice Department made clear its opposition to those
recommendations. Once that decision was made it would have been very difficult politically for President Clinton to support the Sentencing Commission.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking tonight with Marc Mauer, a twenty-year expert on
criminal justice. Our next question comes from RAArehart.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	you are using the word "racist" in different ways - are you
implying that a statistical imbalance implies racism?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	No. I think a statistical imbalance is racist though if it fails to
achieve a policy objective that could be accomplished through other means that would not
aggravate those racial disparities. In the crack cocaine case for example, there has been very little impact on drug abuse that can be credited to the policy. But the harm that has been caused is substantial.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking with Marc Mauer of The Sentencing Project. Our next
question comes from Plang0012 who would like to know, and I'll paraphrase here for
reasons of technical ease, whether you feel the system makes it "easier to put a black man
away."
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	I think what we see in the criminal justice system a combination of
race and class effect that is blacks are not necessarily always more likely to be sentenced
to prison for being black but just as much for being disproportionately low-income. The OJ Simpson Trial is obviously the best example of this where the wealth of a black defendent was much more significant than his race.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking with Marc Mauer, a longtime analyst of our nation's
criminal justice policy. The next question comes from Ken a h.
<p><b>
Comment:</b>	how do you explain 60-70% of all prisoners - are Black - you suggest
the entire US sends Blacks to prison for the hell of it.... No, they commit 60-70% of
the crime, and they are only 15% of the population, that is the racism here.
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	Blacks do not commit  60 to 70 percent of crime although they do
commit a disproportionate share of some crimes. For example, blacks represent about forty-five percent of all arrests for violent crime. Studies have shown that for violent crimes blacks are incarcerated at roughly the same proportion of which they commmit crimes. But for drug offenses in particular blacks are incarcerated in greater numbers than they use drugs or are arrested for drug offfenses.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking with Marc Mauer of the Sentencing Project. The next
question comes from Aerospace.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Isn't it true that the law abiding citizens who live in the inner
cities and have to tolerate drug dealers want tougher laws and penalties to protect
their families/children?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	People in all communities whether rich or poor want safe communities.
The communities that are the safest have not become that way because they have the
toughest laws or the most police. Instead they are safe because  they have strong
families and communities and many resources to draw upon. I think that in low income communities we should supply not only appropriate law enforcement but also try to bring additional resources such as prevention, treatment and economic development into those communities as well.
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	That is what I hear people in low income communities asking for to help solve their problems.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Our next question for Marc Mauer comes from EAnder135.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	In a presumedly color-blind system, does the presence of racists
condemn the entire system?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	I don't know anyone in the year 1995 who still thinks we have a
color-blind system this doesn't mean that every institution is completely racist but
that racism is still prevelent in our society in general.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Our next question for Marc Mauer comes from JLong6302.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	You can make anything in the world a race issue.  How about just
making it a responsibility issue?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	All of us, regardless of our circumstances, are responsible for our
actions but we don't all begin life with the same amount of resources or support. Therefore, it's easier for some of us to act in a way that is viewed as responsible than for others. Understanding this doesn't condone criminal behavior but it allows us to try to understand where that behavior comes from and how we as a society should respond to it.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	We're talking with Marc Mauer of The Sentencing Project. The next
question comes from MumB
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Would you disagree that crack causes more violence than powder
cocaine, fries the brain much quicker, is addictive virtually the first time you use it and
causes such inexcusable harm to children that that is perhaps why the penalties for it are
stiffer.
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	Most of the research on crack cocaine shows us that the violence
associated with the drug is primarily due to the drug trade itself. That is, the violence
that occurs between rival drug dealers who are heavily armed and fighting battles over
drug distribution territories. There are already sufficient laws in place to punish drug dealers who
engage in violence. We don't need harsh mandatory minimum sentences for the people at the
bottom of the drug trade who are using drugs or selling drugs to support their own
drug addiction.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Marc, let me ask the next question: Your recent report on the number
of young black men under the jurisdiction of the criminal justice system created quite
a stir. What is that you are trying to say with the report?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	I think it is important to call attention to the dramatic numbers of young black men in the system. I think it is particularly important for two reasons: First, because the policies that have created these numbers have not succeeded in having a significant impact on crime. Second, the long-term consequences of these policies for the black community and particularly the next generation of black children will be devastating
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Our next question for Marc Mauer comes from Boo Ahhhh.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Hi...how do you feel about the new codes passed in Pasadena that
deal with gang members and how police are going to be able to deal with them?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	I am not familiar with that code.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Our next question for Marc Mauer comes from PtsBeyond.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Maybe this was covered--but were all the other recommendations put
into effect tomorrow, i.e. the marijuana growing sentencing changes from 1000 to 100
grams.  And so the mandantory minimums still apply?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	I don't understand the question.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Okay, I'm afraid I don't understand it enough to explain it either,
so let's move on. The next question comes from NAC5.
<p><b>
Question:</b>	Why not advocate stiffer penalties for powder cocaine also?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	Because the penalties for powder cocaine are already stiff enough. There is also very little research that shows us that merely increasing the harshness of penalties has any significant impact on criminal behavior.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Let me ask the last question, Marc. Are you optimistic for the
future? Your most recent report suggested a very bleak outlook.
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	In general I am not optimistic in the short run. But I have been very encouraged about the increased level of discussion of issues of race and the criminal justice system in recent months. I hope that we can take the anger that has been generated due to the
Congressional votes on crack and other recent events to work towards some
constructive changes in the months ahead.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Actually, Marc, I just remembered one more question that I wanted to
explore with you: Both Houses of Congress have passed the STOP bill. Do you see this
leading to more Atticas?
<p><b>
MauerM:</b>	It certainly won't help. While I can't predict the whole impact of this legislation
it is a sad commentary on the state of civil liberties and our sense of compassion these days.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	I'm afraid that we've run out of time. Please join me in thanking
Marc Mauer for tonight's discussion. I'm sure this is an issue we'll be exploring
repeatedly over the coming months. And remember, please join us in the ACLU's Free
Speech Zone anytime night or day to talk about the criminal justice system or
any other topic that suits your fancy.
<p><b>
PhilCLU:</b>	Good night everyone.
</blockquote>
</head>

